<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MCCURRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCURRY ADMITS `DOUBTS' ABOUT CLINTON 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH LYALL  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Michael D. McCurry, the former White House press
secretary, said Friday that he had ``enormous doubts'' about
President Clinton. Speaking on the BBC public affairs program
``Newsnight,'' McCurry said that although he respected Clinton's
professional ability, he had serious concerns about his
``incredibly bizarre personal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he had confidence in the president, McCurry
said: ``I have enormous doubts because of the recklessness of his
behavior. The immorality is troublesome to me, but one can sort of
understand how an adult male gets in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry left his job in October after months of deflecting
questions about the Monica Lewinsky affair. ``But there's something
beyond that, the nature of this particular affair and the way in
which he did conceal it really does raise some profoundly troubling
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of Clinton's behavior, ``It's surely reckless, contrary
to the way you'd expect a rational human being to behave.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had believed Clinton was telling the truth when he
denied having a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, and felt
aggrieved that he had had to spend so many months trying to
``wiggle through'' questions put to him by the news media.
</P>
<P>
   While the president never ordered anyone to lie, McCurry said,
he allowed ``the deception to go on, knowing the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the president would not consider resigning
from office unless he was sure the country would be damaged too
severely otherwise. ``He can't suffer any more personal
embarrassment than he's already suffered,'' McCurry said. ``The
question is, how much do we all have to suffer through at this
point?''
</P>
</TEXT>
