<HEADER>
A8179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GADEL19-COX     12-19 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GADEL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians in House split on party lines
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One called on President Clinton to resign. Another
attacked his Republican foes. A third called for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the historic vote on whether to impeach the
president, members of the Georgia congressional delegation spoke
out on the floor of the House as they were poised to cast their
votes down party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ending months of fence-sitting, Rep. Sanford Bishop came out
Friday against impeachment. Bishop's conservative southwest Georgia
constituents have flooded his office with calls urging him to vote
to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I cannot defend the president's conduct, it is my solemn
duty to defend the Constitution,'' Bishop said. ``Even if true, the
president's actions do not rise to the high level of `high crimes
and misdemeanors.'''
</P>
<P>
   The other two Democrats in the Georgia delegation, Cynthia
McKinney and John Lewis, had long been on the record opposing
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   All eight Republicans said they would vote to impeach the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) took an active role in steering more than
12 hours of debate, spending most of the day at the equivalent of
the prosecution's table.
</P>
<P>
   One of a handful of Republicans charged with responding to
points of law raised by the Democrats, Barr took the House
microphone repeatedly to differ with Democrats' interpretation of
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as entrapment for perjury,'' he shouted
in response to suggestions that independent counsel Ken Starr had
set up Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 hours of debate to fill, however, nearly every member of
Georgia's delegation became players in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is sick. Her heart is heavy,'' said Rep. John Lewis
(D-Ga.), the Democrats' chief deputy whip in an appeal for
reconciliation. ``Her soul is aching and her spirit is low. Today
our nation stands at a crossroads, at the intersection of
participatory democracy and the politics of personal destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people elected Bill Clinton president of the United States
and they want him to remain president of the United States,'' Lewis
said. ``Some ... have never accepted the verdict of the people ...
Instead they embarked on a crusade of personal destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) said he was dismayed to see the House
chambers half-empty, but he said it showed that the public seemed
resigned at the notion that the House would vote to impeach the
president for the second time in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a degree of sadness, a high degree of sobriety,''
Kingston said. But it does not take away from the evidence,
evidence that makes Kingston believe the president ought to be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston noted that the Democrats argued it is wrong to debate
the impeachment vote when American forces have been sent to attack
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But Kingston said there were 62,000 troops on the ground in
Vietnam when three resolutions were presented in the House to
impeach President Nixon on May 18, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Those articles called for Nixon's impeachment based on military
action in Indochina, not the Watergate matter.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.) went further, asking for the
president to resign and spare the country the spectacle of a trial
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of pages of material that have not been made
public in the House that would be in a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country does not need that,'' Norwood said. ``Clinton
doesn't know how to be straight, and that scares the bejesus out of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican members say this is not about sex, the
Democrats say it is just that.
</P>
<P>
   They portrayed the GOP as a party obsessed with removing the
president at any cost, including the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is a sad day for our republic,'' said Rep. Cynthia
McKinney (D-Ga.). ``The Republican leaders have chosen to trample
the Constitution with partisan arrogance in order to strike a
political blow against President Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The American people clearly oppose impeachment, McKinney said,
but that won't stop lawmakers like Barr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican leaders, blinded by their own sanctimonious piety
and hypocrisy, have chosen to push our nation to the brink of a
constitutional crisis for their own petty, political benefit,''
McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
