<HEADLINE>
IRAQI LEADERSHIP DEFIANT AS ATTACKS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Corrects day of week throughout to Saturday)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ The US and British missile attacks on Iraq intensified
before dawn Saturday, pounding the heart of Saddam Hussein's
regime, leaving a trail of destruction at southern positions of the
Republican Guard, oil refineries in Basra, TV transmitters near
Baghdad, and presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
   After three straight days of missile strikes, Iraq held out hope
that the bombing would end with the dawn, which the nation marks as
the start of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   But as morning neared, the skies lit up in fiery nighttime
finale. One cruise missile tracked through the night sky over
Baghdad, passed unscathed through a short barage of Iraqi
antiaircraft fire, and detonated in a direct hit on a large
government building.
</P>
<P>
   Two more cruise missiles then hammered the building, bursting
into mushroom clouds of fire. The building spewed acrid smoke into
the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   In and around Baghdad, the continued pounding of cruise missiles
could be heard and flames from destroyed buildings shot lit up the
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   It ended just before 5 a.m. as, following the sudden silence, a
slow, melancholy morning call to prayer came from a downtown
mosque.
</P>
<P>
   The sustained strikes prompted an angry and besieged Iraqi
leadership to respond by sharply redrawing diplomatic lines, and
making it apparent that the UN weapons inspectors would not return
to Iraq unless harsh economic sanctions were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   A defiant Hussein appeared in a taped statement Friday night
aired on a Qatar-based television network, telling the Iraqi
people, ``You must thank God for your success, and continue
resistance. We are the people of good morality. We are not going to
compromise to the other side of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the words of defiance, Pentagon officials said they have
been struck by the lack of military resistance from Iraqi forces.
The United States denied Iraqi assertions that more than 77 US
cruise missiles had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   The streaking red tracers and rattle of Iraqi antiaircraft fire
over Baghdad in the predawn hours Saturday were noticeably
shortlived compared to the resistance offered in the previous two
days of US missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Following through on President Clinton's promise to step up a
campaign aimed at toppling Hussein, US jets also dropped leaflets
on Iraqi forces in southern Iraq telling them not to worry about
being targeted unless they are defending what they referred to as
``the Baghdad regime,'' according to Voice of America broadcasts
heard in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Already more US cruise missiles have been launched in Operation
Desert Fox, as the attacks have been dubbed, than the 289 fired at
Iraq in the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Baghdad, Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz said that chief UN weapons inspector Richard Butler
``has killed his job'' by ``preparing the grounds for this
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said that the US and British attacks were orchestrated
through Butler via a report to the UN Security Council that, Aziz
asserted, falsely accused Iraq of not cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq will not tolerate UNSCOM and sanctions at the same
time,'' said Aziz. ``If they want to keep the sanctions, let them
leave UNSCOM in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz stressed that Iraq fulfilled its responsibility in
accordance with the spirit of the letter it sent to the UN
secretary-general on Nov. 14 and that UNSCOM has carried out
hundreds of inspections since then.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz also expressed anger that the United States and Britain
have attacked targets that have wounded civilians in Iraq. He
described sustained missile strikes causing vast damage.
</P>
<P>
   A warehouse belonging to the Ministry of Trade was hit. Four
warehouses in Baghdad holding 1,000 tons of cotton were destroyed
by a cruise missile, he said. The targets also included an oil
refinery in the southern port city of Basra and the old Ministry of
Defense building in downtown Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The targets seem aimed at degrading Hussein's military machinery
as well as his grip on the civilian society.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said attacks on civilian targets were ``sinister.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The collateral damage on the Ministry of Defense led to the
nearby destruction of hospitals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Saturday were taken to see the hospital, which had
blown out windows and moderate damage from the nearby attack. But
there were no reports of injuries to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi Health Ministry announced Thursday that at least 25
people have died during the attacks and 75 have been wounded in
Baghdad, but a complete casualty toll has not been announced. The
bombings in the southern cities of Basra and Hussein's hometown of
Tikrit were certain to have caused some casualties but Iraqi
officials offered no official accounting of dead or wounded.
</P>
<P>
   At the Al Yarmouk Hospital, among Iraq's largest hospitals and
located in the Western part of the city, officials said they had
received approximately 13 people who were dead when they arrived at
the hospital during the first two days of attacks. They said they
had treated a total of 34 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital was once a crown jewel in Iraq's formerly advanced
and now crippled medical infrastructure. The hospitals are hard hit
by the crushing economic sanctions imposed in the aftermath of the
1991 Gulf War. At the entrance there are large painted signs that
read, ``Down, Down, USA.''
</P>
<P>
   In the emergency and surgical wards, those wounded lay in
rusting cots amid bleak conditions. Among them was Muhsin Hadi, 20,
who said he was walking home from his job selling cigarettes on
Thursday night when US cruise missiles pounded a seven-story
military industrial building in the heart of downtown Baghdad. The
blast blew him off his feet, he said, and sent shrapnel into his
abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can America do this?'' he asked. ``They say they hit only
military targets, but they hit people too.''
</P>
<P>
   In the surgical ward, Jasem Zubati, 41, was listed in serious
but stable condition with head wounds and a fractured vertebra.
With bandages wrapped around his head and in obvious pain, he
described how his home in the Al Adel section of Baghdad was hit by
a missile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crashed through the back of our house, right into the
kitchen,'' said Zubati, a well-to-do engineer who has profited from
an import business under the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter visited the home, and saw the evidence of the damage.
There was a crater in the rear of the house, and broken kitchen
appliances were stacked in the front of the house. Zubati said his
injuries came in the collapse of the roof of his home, where he
lived with his wife and three children. He has a 3-week-old son.
Two older children were injured slightly and hospitalized, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is my house a secret, military location? Have I done anything
to America?'' he asked, shaking with anger and pain. ``I will
avenge myself if it takes 40 years. I will ask Saddam to take
revenge. I have great hatred for your government.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained difficult for reporters to assess the full extent of
the damage. The Ministry of Information forbids reporters from
traveling without a government ``minder'' accompanying them, and no
reporters have been permitted to travel outside Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that the attacks seemed aimed directly the heart of the
Iraqi leader's personal power base, Aziz said virtually all of the
sites had been inspected and heavily monitored by UN arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They attack presidential sites, they are guest houses built by
the Iraqis, they are fine buildings, they just want to destroy
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz made repeated references to the impeachment proceedings
engulfing Clinton's presidency and fixating both the American and
Iraqi people. He said that Clinton ``lied to his own people'' and
that he was now ``lying about Iraq to justify this aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can the American people believe a man who has lied to his
own people, to the Congress. He lies to his nation and tells the
truth about Iraq? How can that be? How can we swallow that? These
are lies, cheap lies,'' Aziz said.
</P>
