<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA READY FOR FINE-TUNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maryland, Kentucky and Oklahoma State are in the
rear-view mirror. Arizona and Stanford arrive in a few weeks. But
tonight, against Cal State Northridge, the Bruins (5-2) begin the
critical three-game transition portion of their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   They've tested themselves against three ranked teams and
compiled a lengthy list of deficiencies, ranging from inexperience
and impatience to floor balance and transition defense.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge, American University (Dec. 23) and Loyola Marymount
(Dec. 29) provide three opportunities to smooth those glitches
before Pacific-10 play begins Jan. 2 against unbeaten Arizona. The
Bruins play at Oregon the following week, then host Stanford and
Cal. There won't be much chance for introspection or correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we'd have a high level (of competition) in Puerto Rico
. . . so we tried to find a nice mix,'' coach Steve Lavin said.
``Obviously, it worked out ideally.
</P>
<P>
   ``(These) are games where we can get a look at more players.
They're at home, and they can build confidence. We thought it was a
nice blend.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is 6-3 and lost its most recent game, at Brigham Young.
American, which plays USC on Monday, is 3-6 and Loyola Marymount
4-4.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dawn patrol: Because of exams, the Bruins practiced at dawn
this week for 90 minutes or two hours. Although short, the workouts
were productive. UCLA held three formal scrimmages, complete with
the scoreboard, uniforms and Pac-10 officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make it as close to game conditions as we could,''
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lending a hand: Guard Ray Young and walk-on forward Sean
Farnham continue to provide brief but significant contributions in
limited playing time _ Young with his defense and athleticism,
Farnham with his spirit and physicality.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, they're averaging four points and three rebounds in 12
minutes.``From where I've been, it's just nice to make a
contribution,'' Farnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a McDonald's All-American who had trouble adjusting to
college life and practice length, is UCLA's most improved player
since Oct. 17. But he might be limited tonight because of a
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a quantum leap,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stat of the month: The Bruins held Nevada-Las Vegas to one
field goal in the final 13 minutes, their best defensive stretch of
the early season.
</P>
<P>
   Through seven games, opponents are shooting 39.6 percent from
the field and 34.7 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quote of the month: Perhaps it was subconscious; perhaps it
was lingering frustration. But Lavin appeared to take a subtle dig
at Jelani McCoy, Kris Johnson, Toby Bailey and J.R. Henderson when
he said of the current roster:
</P>
<P>
   ``They're low-maintenance. They're all well-adjusted kids. There
are no dysfunctional personalities in the group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
