<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STEELE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARS BEGIN ERA OF STEELE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Addressing an enthusiastic audience at a Baylor
news conference yesterday, new Bears football coach Kevin Steele
was reminded of a recent public appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure you all came here today to hear what I sound like,''
he said. ``Because after last Sunday, you all know what I look
like.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a day before he interviewed for the Baylor job,
Steele _ an assistant with the Carolina Panthers _ became the star
of the highlight films after being attacked on the sideline by one
of his own linebackers, Kevin Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The green-and-gold crowd roared with laughter, and thus was born
the Steele era at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very exciting,'' said linebacker Fred Rogers. ``This
program is in the basement right now, and there's nowhere to go but
up. I think we have a guy now who is a good coach and very
intelligent, and he can take us up.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he would begin immediately with the task of
rebuilding the Bears _ 2-9 each of the last two years under Dave
Roberts _ Steele promised the crowd that ``we will soon be
competitive in the Big Eight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, excuse me,'' he said, quickly, ``I meant Big 12. I was
thinking about when I used to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, 40, was formerly an assistant at Oklahoma State
(1984-86), and Nebraska (1989-94), before the league expanded. This
is his first head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be competitive here _ I know that because of that man
right there,'' Steele said, pointing at former Baylor coach Grant
Teaff. ``He proved Baylor can win, and along with Tom Osborne at
Nebraska, he was one of those I always looked to as a mentor _ even
though he never knew I was looking. He laid the foundation here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steele, who was linebackers coach at Carolina for the past
four years, said he still has a commitment to the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will finish out the season with them, but only on Sundays,''
he said. ``The rest of the time I will be here _ but I'll be going
back to coach in each game the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL was a great experience _ I got a doctorate in Xs and
Os _ but I really missed college coaching. When I took the job, I
told \RPanthers owner\S Jerry Richardson that my dream had always
been to be a college head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very understanding, and when this came up, he told me
to go after it and not worry about the remaining games on the
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a late start, Steele said he was eager to begin
recruiting, ``because Texas has the best high school players in the
country, and we plan to get our share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, recruiting is my golf game _ it's what I do for fun.
I know that sounds sick, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his plans for a staff, Steele said that he would
``look first at the present staff, then after that look at anyone
who has Baylor ties. After that we will look for Texas ties \Rthe
state, not the Longhorns\S, and if there's anything left we'll look
at people noted for great offensive or defensive schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   After introducing his wife, Linda, he said, ``We also have a
12-year-old son, Gordon, who is ecstatic about being a Baylor Bear,
and a nine-year-old daughter Caroline, who is like her dad _ up for
any challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that sounded pretty good to safety Curtis Henderson, who
said, ``I'm excited. Coach Osborne spoke highly of this man, did
you see that? If that's what Coach Osborne thinks, it's good enough
for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of talent here, and next year's schedule isn't
as bad as this year's was. This team can go a long way up in one
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting Steele's commitment to Christian values and education,
Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton called him ``the cornerstone
of the future,'' saying, ``He's the right man at the right time for
the right university.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is who we are at Baylor University.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
