<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-KATY-DISQUALIFICATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATY FLAGS ITSELF, VACATES 5A FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ San Antonio MacArthur lost to Katy in a
Class 5A Division II semifinal last week, but at 12:06 this
afternoon at Texas Stadium, MacArthur will be on the field playing
in the state championship game. With a half-day of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Katy withdrew from the state high school football playoffs
yesterday morning after learning Thursday night that a player who
participated in three plays in the playoffs had falsified grade
reports and forged a teacher's signature. That sent MacArthur, a
14-6 loser to Katy in the semifinals at the Alamodome last weekend,
against Midland Lee in the title game today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no options,'' University Interscholastic League
athletic director Charles Breithaupt said. ``Katy self-reported and
took themselves out of the playoffs. They did the thing that they
had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday at MacArthur High School, school officials knew what
to do first _ post somebody at the front desk to answer the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pandemonium,'' said defensive coordinator Cade King, who
drew the assignment to answer the phones after the school learned
it was back in the playoffs. The announcement drew TV crews,
newspaper reporters, photographers, fans and parents to the school,
which hadn't gotten as far as the semifinal round in the playoffs
since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a pretty sketchy playoff history around here, so
this is big,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Breithaupt said there was no discussion about delaying the game
to give the teams a better chance to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair to Midland Lee on one side, but MacArthur is not
prepared at all,'' Breithaupt said. ``It's going to be difficult to
get their folks together and get there.''
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur made plans quickly. The UIL called at noon, and by
1:30 p.m., athletic officials were meeting, parents and players
were being notified, and coaches were pulling out helmets, shoulder
pads and uniforms that had been stored on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By 2:30, travel arrangements were complete: two Southwest
Airlines flights, leaving at 8 p.m. and 9 p.m. and reservations at
a Dallas hotel. Coaches planned for an early film-watching session
today and a walk-through at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In Midland, Lee was changing its plans, too. The Rebels had
scheduled a leisurely bus trip, leaving Midland around 3 p.m., with
dinner along the way, then a short meeting or two upon arrival.
Those plans were scrapped when UIL officials called at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were basically ready to get on the bus and go,'' Midland
schools athletic director Tim Whalen said. ``Now, a week of
teaching has disappeared. Our focus has to change. Teaching-wise,
it's going to be a level playing field. But emotion-wise, MacArthur
can go wide open now _ they have nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Breithaupt said the UIL has no lesser punishment for Katy's
violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have debated in our meetings about what to do about a kid
that makes an insignificant contribution,'' Breithaupt said. ``But
then you have to decide what is insignificant. If a player is
ineligible, this is the minimum penalty. We have to do what the
schools have told us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy Principal Robert Blankenship said the school learned late
Thursday that a player falsified grades and forged a signature on a
three-week grade report the week after Thanksgiving, violating the
state's no-pass, no-play rules. School officials declined to
identify the player, saying only that he was a 17-year old senior.
\Nshirt:This report contains material from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
