<HEADER>
A8190 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-BRILES-STEPHENVIL     12-19 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-BRILES-STEPHENVILLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSFUL COACH IS TALK OF THE TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ If it were not for La Marque's run of
playing in six consecutive championship games, the Stephenville
Yellow Jackets and coach Art Briles would reign as the undisputed
kings of Class 4A football this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Around town these days, it's hard to believe things were ever
different. Aside from periodic winning seasons, football in
Stephenville never did much to grab the community's imagination.
Before Briles came in 1988, Stephenville last made the playoffs in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``My senior year in 1985 we had a perfect record _ 0-10,'' said
Stephenville native Robert ``Boots'' Elliott Jr., president of
Stephenville's local radio station, KSTV, the home of Jackets
broadcasts. ``No one really came to the games except the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott probably has enjoyed the closest view of the coach, a
man whose success and style has mystified out-of-town fans and
coaches. Briles joins Elliott every Friday in the NationsBank lobby
for a half-hour radio talk show. Yesterday's show focused on one
topic: Stephenville's attempt to secure its third Class 4A state
championship in six years. The Yellow Jackets face three-time
defending champion La Marque today in the Division II title game at
4 p.m. at Texas Stadium. More than ]half the town, a projected
10,000 fans, will be in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, just getting Briles to talk about his team for 30 minutes
on the air can be a feat in itself, although not as difficult as in
his earlier coaching days, Elliott said. Briles relies on his
119-27-2 record at Stephenville and multiple title runs to speak
for his success. Briles prefers not to get introspective toward his
program. After victories, he is the first off the field so his
players receive the attention. He will always defer success onto
others. Briles prefers to remain behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in West Texas, Briles is somewhat of a homebody. He'd
rather be with his family than out fishing or hunting. When he's
not at practice or a game, he'll be at home, relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have no hobbies,'' Briles said. ``I try not to get
too tight as to have to unwind. I enjoy being around the high
school, the coaches and the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than his family, the only thing Briles seems to consume
himself with is coaching the Yellow Jackets and concocting one of
the most dynamic offenses in the state. Opposing coaches accuse him
of using all of his free time drawing up plays in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   He despises talking about anything that can be construed
negatively, such as his coaching salary and other benefits like his
radio show, for which he receives financial compensation. He makes
no excuses for his pay, one of the top coaching salaries in the
state, in the mid-$80's, but refuses to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've developed one of the most dominant programs in the
state,'' Briles said. ``We had to make them \Rthe players\S believe
they could be winners. Once they got that, it goes to work ethic.
Once you win, people see results of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the community there are few complaints about his salary.
Winning, apparently, is well worth the price. Plus, Briles'
off-the-field character is worth a portion of his salary, some fans
say. The husband of 20 years and father of three embodies the
community's dearest traits. His yes-ma'am, no-sir,
see-you-in-church-on-Sunday character fits this conservative, Bible
Belt town to a T.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has all the Southern mannerisms,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with championships, Briles has become the Tom Landry of
Stephenville. Sellouts of 6,500 at Tarleton State's Memorial
Stadium are the norm. To get season tickets you first have to get
on a waiting list. Briles and his team have grown into almost
mythical proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is just a lot better than losing,'' said Betsy
Chambers, a booster-club member who remembers watching two stepsons
play in the days before Briles. ``It just gives you so much pride.
It goes beyond football, it seeps into the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there's something to talk about, something other than
rodeo and world champion Ty Murray to get excited about.
Stephenville football requires wearing your emotions on your
sleeve. In the semi-rural setting, free from the distractions of
the big city, high school football can help bring back those
simpler days the town covets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that worth? Those who haven't seen it don't know. I've
been there. I've seen what it's meant to a town,'' said W.T.
Stapler, a revered high school coach who became Briles' mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The retired Stapler hired Briles as an assistant at Sweetwater,
leading to Briles' first head coaching job at tiny Hamlin. His next
stop was Georgetown. When the Stephenville administration called on
Stapler to coach its program in 1988, Stapler chose to remain at
Andrews and sent Stephenville after Briles.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a two-way love affair ever since.
</P>
<P>
   He led Stephenville to the playoffs in 1989 and won the district
title in 1990. Stephenville hasn't missed the playoffs since. In
1993 and '94, the Yellow Jackets steamrolled to back-to-back titles
and a 32-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate we haven't just fallen on our face,'' said
Briles, who owns a 28-3 playoff record since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows how much longer Briles will stick around.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities at college jobs have and will continue to come his
way. He professes his love for the town and the school. His wife,
Jane, teaches third grade. Two daughters, ages 18 and 12, are
enrolled in Stephenville schools. His son, Kendal, likely will be
the starting quarterback the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculate he will move on once Kendal graduates. Others
think he could remain for years, eventually compiling a career that
will rival legendary former Brownwood coach Gordon Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Few like to wonder what life after Briles would be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be tough,'' Betsy Chambers said. ``It would be
tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
