<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-CLEMENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYSTERY CLAUSE' LEAVES BLUE JAYS WITHOUT A CLUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Just when you thought the Roger Clemens
`It's A Wonderful Life'' Sweepstakes had become as (pick one)
wearying, unseemly, extravagant or nauseatingly greedy as the law
allows, yet-another plot twist has taken root.
</P>
<P>
   As originally reported in the ``Toronto Star'', Clemens'
arrangement with the Blue Jays allegedly contains a ``separate
addendum'' that would make the five-time Cy Young Award winner a
free agent if he's not traded by March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about it,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said yesterday. ``I've heard rumors that it's a handshake or
a side agreement or even that he could be a free agent. But it's
all speculation at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear all that. But we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What Melvin has seen is Clemens' current, binding Toronto
contract. ``And it's not in there,'' Melvin said of the mystery
clause.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash said that he had no
discussions with any teams yesterday on a possible trade for
Clemens. It would not be a long stretch to conclude that the lull
is being caused, in part, by Major League Baseball officials
looking into these possible new revelations about the
Clemens-Toronto arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The importance for the Rangers would be twofold. If Clemens does
have a 90-day, must-trade clause, major-league teams could ignore
the Blue Jays' trade offers and allow The Rocket to become a
free-agent on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   But, on the other hand, that could be expensive, in that it
would wipe out the two remaining years on Clemens' existing
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that makes him attractive is that his salary
would be $8 million for the next two years,'' Melvin said. ``The
point that doesn't make him attractive is that you might end up
having to pay him $15 million each year for the next four or five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The alleged addendum comes across as contract roulette. The Blue
Jays would be compelled to make a deal by the 90-day deadline, or
get nothing in return for Clemens. The teams that want the pitcher,
on the other hand, would have two choices:
</P>
<P>
   Surrender players in a trade to Toronto by the deadline, and
then assume Clemens' contract with its reported new, third-year,
$27-million extension. Or allow the deadline to pass, trade no
players, and otherwise hand Clemens the checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   Is any of it legal?
</P>
<P>
   We might never know. The man who orchestrated the original deal
in Toronto was then-club president Paul Beeston. He now serves as
president and chief operating officer of Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   According to Melvin, whose family recently vacationed with the
Ash family, ``Gord wasn't really aware of it, from what I
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day addendum smacks of being unethical, at best, or
simple blackmail. But who was the victim here?
</P>
<P>
   Both the mystery clause and the one invoked by Clemens' agents
on Dec. 2, allowing him to demand a trade, obviously were designed
to give The Rocket his freedom. Without the escape clauses, Clemens
might not have stunned the baseball world and signed with Toronto
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays had to realize that retaining Clemens beyond two
years was a longshot. They received two seasons of Cy Young
Award-winning service from Roger.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' probable intent, if not the letter, of the original
agreement was fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped the Blue Jays from trying to squeeze
compensation for what, in essence, was a flawed deal, a deal they
willingly made.
</P>
<P>
   Once a team agrees to a must-trade clause, it deserves to
forfeit all leverage. And without leverage, how can Toronto expect
a Rick Helling, an Andy Pettitte or a Derek Bell?
</P>
<P>
   Ash expects a pitcher in return for any deal involving Clemens.
My suggestion would be that, instead, he goes to the VCR and looks
at those two years of Roger Clemens highlights. They'll never ride
a cheaper Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Bud Selig. If the commissioner upholds the mystery
addendum, he probably adds another expensive chapter to baseball's
current spending frenzy. Clemens is going to want five years, $75
million and all the hotel suites that Kevin Brown doesn't already
have booked.
</P>
<P>
   But if Selig tosses out the 90-day addendum, he's legitimized
what was, from the start, a flawed baseball deal.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto got its two Cy Young years. Anything it's allowed to
squeeze out of teams beyond that should be considered an undeserved
bonus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
