</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE EXPECTED TO RISE ABOVE FRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It turned out to be one of the most intensely
partisan debates in memory, split almost precisely down party
lines.
</P>
<P>
   And if it continues to unfold that way, impeachment is not more
likely, but less, and for an important historical reason: The
founding fathers intentionally made the Senate a brake on one-sided
efforts to remove a president from office.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's impeachment authority over the House avoids
``making the same persons both accusers and judges, and guards
against the danger of persecution from the prevalence of a factious
spirit,'' wrote Alexander Hamilton in 1787.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even when the House is full of fury, the Senate
is expected to rise above the fray and adopt a broad view.
</P>
<P>
   While the House requires a simple majority vote to pass
impeachment, the Senate mandates a two-thirds vote. The founding
fathers believed the Senate could afford to be somewhat detached
from their constituents' passions because they face the voters
every six years, compared with every two years in the House.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the House impeachment debate was at times raw and
emotional, just as the drafters of the Constitution might have
predicted. With the House poised to endorse impeachment articles
against President Clinton, the president's supporters may have
taken a small degree of comfort in Hamilton's words.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate trial would likely begin in January on any impeachment
article approved by the House. On most legislation _ not just
impeachment _ the Senate tends to move more deliberately than the
House, in part because its rules give members more stratagems for
bottling up bills they don't like than are available to their
counterparts in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 1996 GOP presidential candidate Bob Dole is urging his
former colleagues to forgo a trial and agree instead to a harsh
condemnation of the president. It's far from certain that the
Republican-controlled Senate will go along with the plan, which
would require Clinton's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., pledged to keep the process as free from partisan strife as
possible. He said the founding fathers intended it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's efforts notwithstanding, Friday's debate was full of
bitterness and angry words from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., said the impeachment effort was
characterized by ``unbridled hatred and meanness.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans countered that they were following the ``rule of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere likely will be cooler in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the senators feel any less strongly about the
issue than their House colleagues. Rather, the Senate knows that
the Constitution confers upon it the burden of being the last fire
wall separating a chief executive from impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were expected to be a more mature, deliberative body,''
said constitutional scholar Alan Hirsch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
