<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RHODES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP'S JOHN RHODES FAVORS CENSURE, BUT NOT IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former House Minority Leader John Rhodes of Arizona, who played
a key role in persuading Richard Nixon to resign the presidency,
says President Clinton should be censured, not impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have impeached him,'' Rhodes, 82, said Friday. ``I
was one of the first that I know of who talked about censure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes, who lives in the East Valley, said he has expressed
those sentiments in letters to House Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde, Rep. Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the Constitution that says you have to
impeach him,'' Rhodes, an elder statesman of the Arizona Republican
Party, said. ``There are a lot of ways the House could have brought
this up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes also denied that an incident about him recounted on the
House floor during Friday morning's debate ever took place.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., in responding to
demands by Democrats that they be allowed to vote for censure
rather than impeachment, said that in 1974, John Rhodes, then House
minority leader for the Republicans, approached Speaker Tip O'Neill
and asked that Republicans be permitted a censure vote as an
alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill turned down the request, Solomon said, adding that
today's Democrats ought to heed the word of their late leader.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, Rhodes told ``The Republic'' that the incident
never happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nixon-Watergate era it was Rhodes, along with the late
Sen. Barry Goldwater, who met with Nixon two days before he became
the only U.S. president to resign from office, on Aug. 9, 1974.
They told Nixon that impeachment was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was a dramatic moment in history that Rhodes
recalled in ``The Arizona Republic'' recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry and I had campaigned and worked with Richard Nixon for
years. The whole Watergate thing practically broke our hearts, yet
we had to tell this man whom we had trusted that his presidency
would be ended. It was indeed a very bad day for us,'' Rhodes
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview Friday that Clinton should be punished.
Congress, he said, ``couldn't let the people of the country think
morals were no longer important.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rhodes said he's not sure that independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's case ``should go all the way to the point of impeachment,
and removal from office.''
</P>
<P>
   A key difference in Clinton's case, Rhodes said, is that Nixon's
resignation opened the door for Gerald Ford to become president.
``There was a wide amount of trust and respect for Gerald Ford,''
Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, he added, ``ain't no Gerald Ford.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
