u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SHOE-DEALS-700&AMP;AD     12-19 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHOE-DEALS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIKE WITHHOLDING PAYMENTS TO LOCKED-OUT PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BKN-NBA-PLAYERS) 
(mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   National Basketball Association players who were expecting Nike
to supplement their income during the lockout may have to start
searching their couch cushions and car ashtrays for loose change.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 100 players with deals to wear the swoosh
have discovered language in their contracts that gives Nike the
right to withhold payment because of a work stoppage. With the
exception of a few signature clients _ like Michael Jordan and
Anfernee Hardaway _ agents say that most players under contract did
not find a quarterly check in the mail on Tuesday. No games, no
visibility, no pay.
</P>
<P>
   While other shoe companies, like Reebok and Adidas, are paying
their endorsers during the nearly six-month-old lockout, no other
company has the number of clients Nike has. Combined, Reebok and
Adidas account for fewer than 20 players, a number that reflects a
troubled industry that has been forced to downsize its marketing
budgets in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Although sports marketing firms have watched various national
advertisers pull deals off the table because of a hostile lockout
that has left product visibility impossible and players' images
stained, Nike's actions constitute a noticeable hit. While a
handful of charismatic stars have soft drink and fast-food deals, a
quarter of the league's 400-plus players have Nike contracts that
industry analysts say pay middle-range players approximately
$100,000 a year and an all-star anywhere from $250,000 to $1
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike's explanation for this is that they want to see how this
whole thing plays out,'' said Eric Fleischer, an agent who
represents several top players, including Kevin Garnett. ``I'm
obviously very disturbed by it. I find it amazing that a company
that was started by athletes for athletes has taken a position
which, for all practical purposes, is choosing sides. If they are
prorating their sponsorship agreements with the league, it would be
different. But I haven't been told that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike officials maintain that their contracts with players, teams
and the league are confidential, but they said the company is
reassessing the value of its investments in the NBA across the
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anyone to assume that we are taking sides based on our
actions, or that we are doing one thing to one party and not
another, is inaccurate,'' said Vizhier Mooney, a Nike
representative. ``We stand firm in choosing to not take a side.
This issue is between the players and the league. We owe it to our
employees to be fiscally responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Nike, the world's top athletic shoe and apparel
seller, announced that second-quarter earnings were off 51 percent.
The soles of the shoemaker, once filled with air, have gone flat,
and chairman Phil Knight placed part of the blame for the company's
recent earnings decline on the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the right way to look at it, if we were a fashion
house, they've taken away one of our critical runways,'' Knight
told reporters on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of television spots that poke fun at the
lockout _ like the Sprite ads with Grant Hill and Tim Duncan _ the
lockout has also eliminated the showroom floor for companies beyond
the shoe industry. Many advertisers are treating the lockout as a
burning house, standing a safe distance away while waiting to see
what is left amid the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the season is canceled or the lockout ends, advertisers
who once gladly invested in the stars who pushed the NBA atop the
pop charts will keep an eye on fan reaction in an effort to gauge
the feel-good meter concerning the sport. Throughout the lockout,
players have done little to endear themselves to fans by making
comments that are perceived to be greedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have done themselves tremendous harm here,'' said
Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports, a company that matches
athletes with advertisers. ``Leverage could have been generated
with the players keeping their mouths shut, which would have
created an image of being locked out. That has gotten lost in the
process. The players want to play. That message comes out once in a
while but it gets squashed by, `Well, poor me, I'm going to have to
sell one of my eight cars.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some players are more savvy than others. A select few have
remained noticeably silent during the lockout. Although his
commercials are broadcast, Hill has stepped into the background and
declined interview requests concerning lockout issues. While he has
drawn some criticism for not being a vocal member of the union, he
has also kept his wholesome image intact by not joining the ugly
word fray.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Bonham, of the Bonham group, a sports marketing firm in
Denver, said: ``The players that are taking the position that I'm
going to sit by and let the union represent me and work it out, and
I'm not going to make a public case about why I'm economically
disadvantaged, that's smart. The players that are keeping a low
profile are the ones conscientious of the importance of maintaining
a positive image with the fans. Those who are complaining about
things and bringing up the race issue and how they are being
treated, they are not making friends with the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps players feel that the public fight for a deal at the
bargaining table is more important than the falloff in advertising
dollars. After all, only the telegenic elite, such as Jordan, Hill,
Dennis Rodman and Scottie Pippen, can match their on-court earnings
with their off-court endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if endorsement opportunities decline further as a result
of the lockout, there will be less visibility for the players and
less saturation for a league that found its niche based on the
celebrity of its players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA is much more of a celebrity-driven league than the NFL
or baseball or the NHL,'' Bonham said. ``The word celebrity is used
because the NBA is as much entertainment as it is sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league will have to use other strategies to keep
their visibility up if, in fact, this trend continues to go down
the path it's traveling now,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   This path was unthinkable six or seven years ago, when shoe
companies drove the market. At the time, Nike was hip and cool and
omnipresent in every school. Nike Airs were selling, and the
competition was at Knight's mercy. At the time, rivalries were
created that had nothing to do with the game as shoe companies
raced to sign rookies to seven-figure shoe deals.
</P>
<P>
   As the industry has struggled, so have the players. Off-court
issues have companies severing their shoe deals with players.
Still, plenty have found that a shoe deal makes a nice supplement
to their incomes, a source some Nike endorsers have discovered is
not going to soothe any pinch caused by the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone takes a hit in this situation,'' said the agent Mark
Bartlestein. ``This is just another issue the players have to deal
with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
