<HEADLINE>
BELCHER JOINS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ He's not exactly Randy Johnson or Kevin
Brown, but Tim Belcher will have to do for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels announced Friday they have signed Belcher, 37, to a
two-year, $10.2 million contract with a club option for a third
year. Belcher will make $4.6 million a season in 1999 and 2000. The
option year is worth $5.1 million with a $1 million buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was the Kansas City Royals' win leader in each of the
past three seasons, including a 14-14 record with a 4.27 ERA in
1998 while being tied for second in the American League with 34
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said the signing was
important not only because the Angels got much-needed pitching help
but because the club was able to acquire a starting pitcher without
having to give up a player in return _ namely, Jim Edmonds or
Garret Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to the winter meetings, we really got a bad
feeling for how other people were looking at our club,'' Bavasi
said. ``They were thinking, `They got Mo (Vaughn), they have to
trade one of their outfielders for some pitching.' Well, we don't
have to. We were dealing with clubs that were thinking it was
possible to steal our gold in exchange for brass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts us in a better position. It helps us relax because
we don't have to make a deal. But if we can make a good deal, we
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who is a native of Ohio and still lives there, said
going to a team with a chance to win was his top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I was looking at it was that this could possibly be my
last contract,'' Belcher said. ``I came in a winner in '88 with the
Dodgers, my first full year. I'd like nothing more than over the
next two or three years to go out a winner with the Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher has a career record of 136-127 in 12 major-league
seasons playing for six teams _ the Dodgers, Reds, White Sox,
Tigers, Mariners and Royals. Three times he has won 15 games in a
season and he has averaged more than 200 innings per season for his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the most durable guy out there,'' Bavasi said. ``And
maybe sometimes we look too much at the durability and overlook the
fact that he's a good pitcher. It was a chance to get a quality guy
with a quality arm. He's a good fit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said he's not the same pitcher he was 10 years ago. But
then again, nobody is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you hang around in this game, you have to adjust,''
Belcher said. ``You'll have your freaks, like Nolan Ryan, who stick
around until they're 62, so you have to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm still a power pitcher. I won't blow the ball by people
like I did seven or eight years ago, but I still throw primarily
fastballs. I'm not looking for a strikeout like a young guy, I'm
looking to make a guy make weak contact as early in the count as I
can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher joins a starting rotation that will include Chuck Finley
and Ken Hill. Those who will compete for the final two spots in the
rotation are Omar Olivares, Steve Sparks, Jarrod Washburn, Jason
Dickson and Mark Petkovsek.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: The Angels will not tender contract offers to
infielder Paco Martin or pitcher Allen Watson. . . . To complete
the trade for pitcher Petkovsek, the Angels sent minor-league
catcher Matt Garrick to the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
