<SLUG> BC-BOX-TUA-RAHMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR CHANCE AT IBF HEAVYWEIGHT CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ David Tua and Hasim Rahman are in the no man's land of
boxing's heavyweight division. They are young, they hit hard and no
one who has a world title or who has designs on winning a world
championship wants to fight them.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck in this predicament, the only way out is to fight each
other. That's what they will do when they square off in a 12-round
International Boxing Federation elimination bout here on Saturday
night. The bout is on the undercard of a 12-round title match
between Floyd Mayweather Jr., the World Boxing Council
super-featherweight champion, and Angel Manfredy, and it will be
broadcast on HBO's ``World Championship Boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tua and Rahman are in a group of heavyweights that could be
referred to as the young and the fightless. That group includes
Michael Grant, who many believe is the next heavyweight superstar,
Chris Byrd, Ike Ibeabuchi and Larry Donald.
</P>
<P>
   They have not had a fight against Evander Holyfield, Mike Tyson
or George Foreman, and they usually do not fight each other.
Ibeabuchi did score a controversial decision over Tua last year.
Shannon Briggs and Lou Savarese are supposed to fight on Feb. 27,
so things are getting better in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The division is better than most people are giving it credit
for,'' said Lou DiBella, HBO/TVKO's senior vice president for
programming. ``If you want to have a legitimate top 10, there are
enough good young heavyweights out there to do it. It's a pretty
healthy division. This is probably the best talent pool in the
heavyweight division in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tua-Rahman bout is one of the most compelling heavyweight
fights of the year, because it pits two boxers in their prime and
the winner will be the IBF's No. 1 contender, becoming the
mandatory opponent for whoever wins the March 13 heavyweight
unification bout between Holyfield and Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Botha, who was the IBF's No. 1 contender, took himself
out of the loop by agreeing to fight Mike Tyson on Jan. 16. Rahman
(29-0) is the IBF's No. 3 contender and Tua (32-1) is not ranked in
the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is the last time two guys have fought to be the mandatory
for the heavyweight championship?'' said Tua's promoter, Dino Duva
of Main Events. ``It hasn't happened in a while. But this new rule
that Bob Lee and the IBF have instituted that you have to fight to
be the No. 1 contender is one of the best things that has happened
to this sport. The winner will be No. 1 and will fight for the
title. That is how Fernando Vargas earned his right to be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas defeated Yory Boy Campas last Saturday for the IBF
junior-middleweight title.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Tua-Rahman bout will have to wait before
receiving a crack at the world championship, because Henry
Akinwande, the World Boxing Association's No. 1 contender, has the
first shot, if he is free of hepatitis B.
</P>
<P>
   Tua and Rahman were scheduled to fight on Sept. 26 on the
undercard of Lewis' title defense against Zeljko Mavrovic. Rahman
pulled out of the fight, because he had signed an agreement with
the promoter Don King, and King had advised him against fighting
Tua.
</P>
<P>
   Rahman also was under contract with the promoter Cedric Kushner
when he entered the agreement with King. Kushner has filed a $12
million lawsuit against King for violating his contract with
Rahman, and Rahman has returned to Kushner.
</P>
<P>
   Tua fought on the undercard of that Lewis-Mavrovic card,
stopping Eric Curry on a first-round technical knockout. The last
time Tua fought in the Miami area, he scored a knockout 19 seconds
into the first round against Darroll Wilson in Miami Beach. That
solidified him as one of the hardest-hitting young heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he wants to take that next step, he will have to take
out Rahman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
