<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOZLOV COULD FACE FUTURE PENALTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Colin Campbell, the NHL director of operations and
chief disciplinarian, was on hand last night when Red Wings winger
Slava Kozlov laid out Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk with an elbow to
the chin at the 18:12 mark of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlov received a five-minute major penalty, meaning an
automatic review by Campbell, who is in charge of suspending
players for those types of infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who took over for Brian Burke, already has handed out
18 suspensions in his first season on the job _ a product of the
league's desire to crack down on hits that lead to head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While Campbell wouldn't comment on whether there would be a
suspension, he did say the hit was ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stupid elbow that was thrown at a time of the game
when it shouldn't have been thrown,'' Campbell said. ``The game was
out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk, who had just turned up ice in his own zone and had
passed the puck, was hit squarely across the jaw by Kozlov, who
doesn't have a history of cheap shots. Nieuwendyk was helped off
the ice, but was fine in the locker room after the game. CHAMBERS
PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers last night returned from injured
reserve after missing seven games with a broken index finger on his
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers wore a hard cast on his right hand and played a regular
shift with defensive partner Craig Ludwig.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little sore when I have to check and the cast is
awkward if the puck is at my feet and I'm trying to use my stick,''
Chambers said. ``But I'll live with it.'' BIG D
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings defenseman Larry Murphy and Stars defenseman Darryl
Sydor rank first and second, respectively, in the NHL in defensemen
scoring. Sydor assisted on Jere Lehtinen's second-period power-play
goal and has 23 points (eight goals, 15 assists). Murphy assisted
on Kozlov's third-period goal and has 24 points (4, 20).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Stars and Red Wings have the top two teams in the
NHL in defenseman scoring. The Stars have 65 points among their
defensemen, while the Red Wings have 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a conscious effort to get our D-man more
offensively involved this season,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``They've got the green light.'' NEXT CLAUDE?
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Dam Keczmer, who bloodied the face of Red Wings
captain Steve Yzerman the last time the two teams played in
Detroit, has been dubbed the new Claude Lemieux by Red Wings fans.
Lemieux is the Colorado Avalanche winger who started a bloody
rivalry between the Red Wings when his check in 1996 broke the jaw
of Red Wings forward Kris Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends are giving me a hard time,'' said Keczmer, who grew
up in Mount Clemens, Mich. ``C'mon, though, Claude Lemieux. That
guy has a history. I'm not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman said he felt the hit was clean. Keczmer was mostly left
alone last night. THREE STARS
</P>
<P>
   1. Jere Lehtinen, Stars _ Hard-working defense from the league's
top defensive forward and the back-breaking goal.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ed Belfour, Stars _ Despite losing the shutout, he was steely
calm when game was 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mike Keane, Stars _ Set up first goal and was a burr in the
saddle of Red Wings all night. X-FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Stars defensemen Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk were
dominating in front of the net. The Red Wings were impressive in
the neutral zone and on the perimeter, but they struggled to get to
rebounds. Hatcher and Matvichuk wouldn't let them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
