<HEADER>
A8205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITS-NYT &LR;      12-19 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWARD CHALK, 76, FORMER AD EXECUTIVE  
 WILLIAM BOX COOK, 48, MUSEUM OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Wash., Calif.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howard Wolfe Chalk, an advertising executive, died on Dec. 12 at
Phelps Memorial Hospital Center in Tarrytown, N.Y. Chalk, a
resident of Cortlandt Manor, N.Y., was 76.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was lung cancer, his daughter, Robin Chalk
Levy, said.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk's clients were mostly fashion accounts, and included
Spring Mills, After Six, Pierre Cardin and British Knights. He
started several advertising agencies, beginning with Chalk, Nissen,
Hanft in 1968. He left that company when it was acquired in 1986,
and started Chalk &AMP; Partners. In 1995, he closed Chalk &AMP; Partners
and started Aerie Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk attended New York University, and served in the Army in
World War II. After the war, he joined Sterling Advertising. In
1955, he was hired by Altman Stoller as an account executive and
eventually became a partner. He left what was then called Altman,
Stoller, Chalk to start Chalk, Nissen, Hanft.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk is survived by his wife, Shirley, of Cortlandt Manor; a
daughter, Robin, of Chappaqua, N.Y.; a son, Russell, of Austin,
Texas, and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM BOX COOK, 48, MUSEUM OFFICIAL
</P>
<P>
   William Box Cook, associate director of the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Chicago, died on Tuesday at his home in
Chicago. He was 48.
</P>
<P>
   He had a heart attack in the lobby of his apartment building, a
spokeswoman at the museum said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook joined the museum in September after serving as executive
director of the Cunningham Dance Foundation in New York City for
four years. Cook also supervised the activities of the Merce
Cunningham Dance Company, producing annual seasons in New York,
London, Paris and California and coordinating Cunningham's
collaborations with Roy Lichtenstein, Rei Kawakubo, Brian Eno and
others.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his father and stepmother, Box and Maxine Cook
of Port Townsend, Wash.; three brothers, Stephen and Michael, of
Sacramento, Calif., and Richard, of Carlisle, Pa.; and a sister,
Karen, of Whidbey Island, Wash.
</P>
</TEXT>
