<SLUG> BC-BKC-LIU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 STRUGGLING LONG ISLAND UNIVERSITY SEEKS NEW IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are struggling to learn a new offense. They shoot free
throws as if the ball was a boulder. And the electricity that had
surrounded them the past two seasons has fizzled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island University Blackbirds (1-6, 1-3 Northeast
Conference) are not in the ideal position to play a difficult
stretch on the road against Florida on Sunday, South Florida on
Tuesday and Georgia on Dec. 28. But Ray Martin, the first-year
coach, is keeping his team's plight in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody died,'' he said earlier this week. ``We're going into
these three games as a challenge for us to get better. Now, getting
better may not necessarily mean we're going to win all three
games.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to his native New York from an assistant's post
at Miami of Ohio, Martin knew that the Blackbirds had lost the
nation's leading scorer, Charles Jones, and his sidekick, forward
Mike Campbell. He knew that his predecessor, Ray Haskins, had left
him with just one new player, the Monroe Community College transfer
Virgil Smiley (9.9 points, 5.1 rebounds), because Haskins' other
recruits failed to qualify academically. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a proponent of the halfcourt game, also knew that most
of what the Blackbirds did under Haskins was run and gun. And they
ran successfully, compiling a record of 42-20 the previous two
years while reaching the National Collegiate Athletic Association
Tournament in 1997 and National Invitation Tournament last season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of their high-flying, high-scoring act, the Blackbirds
developed a mystique. They packed the Schwartz Center and attracted
the curious on the road. Haskins' success was a return to coach
Claire Bee's teams in the 1940s, before a point-shaving scandal
killed the program from 1951 to 1957.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the team is losing and attendance is dipping. Martin did not
anticipate how slowly the Blackbirds would adapt to a disciplined
offense. He wants them to focus on working the ball inside, then
resorting to the perimeter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us are not accustomed to playing that style, but
we're learning,'' guard Issiah Francis said. ``When we run the
plays through, they work.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, the Blackbirds, who are averaging 19 turnovers a game,
sometimes do not get through the plays. Martin believes the
mistakes stem from carelessness, and from front-line players not
being used to handling the ball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been times when you look out there and you say, `Does
anybody know how to play this game?''' Martin said. ``But there's
been times when it looks beautiful, too, and the guys are moving
the ball and getting good-percentage shots.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Blackbirds beat a Northeast Conference team, Robert Morris,
by 71-59 on Dec. 7 to give Martin his first victory, but they have
lost two since.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin has players pointing toward the end of the season,
especially the conference tournament, to give them time to adjust
to his controlled tempo. In the frenetic pace of the Jones/Haskins
era, players rarely worried about contesting shots and denying
offensive rebounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing regular basketball, but that's what they would
have to do with the talent they have,'' said Wagner coach Tim
Capstraw, whose Seahawks defeated LIU by 82-72 on Dec. 5. ``They
can do well in the Northeast Conference.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
