A8209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MURDERS-SENTENCE-5     12-19 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDERS-SENTENCE-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY REJECTS DEATH PENALTY FOR MURDERER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After deliberating for three days, a Queens jury on
Friday spared the life of a 26-year-old man who was convicted of
murdering three women and trying to kill two others.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing the decision, the defendant, James Allen Gordon,
shook the hands of his lawyers and thanked them for persuading the
jury that there were sufficient mitigating factors in his
background to permit a sentence of life imprisonment without parole
instead of death by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was overcome by relief,'' said Christopher Renfroe, one of
Gordon's three lawyers. ``Few people experience a moment when
people are announcing whether you live or die.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had represented himself, with his lawyers acting as
advisers, during the first portion of the trial, at which he was
convicted. He was the first person in the state to defend himself
in a capital case since the death penalty was reinstated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dock Johnson and his wife, Eurilee, the parents of one
of the murder victims, left the courtroom with differing views. ``I
am opposed to the death penalty and I am satisfied and happy with
the verdict,'' said Johnson, assistant pastor of the Community
Baptist Church in South Ozone Park, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Johnson, whose eyes were damp with tears, said the
decision had dishonored the memories of her daughter, Darlene
Johnson, 28, and her daughter-in-law, Mary Mouzon, 33.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who lived across the street from Darlene Johnson in
Jamaica, Queens, was convicted in state Supreme Court in Queens on
Dec. 3 of invading Ms. Johnson's house in July 1996 and raping,
sodomizing and fatally shooting her, and stabbing and shooting to
death Mrs. Mouzon. He was also found guilty of killing Hadiyah
Holliman, 18, who was in the house, and of attempting to murder her
sister, Zakkiyah, and another person, Latisha Crite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darlene and Mary pleaded for their lives while he tortured
them,'' Mrs. Johnson said. ``If someone is found guilty of
committing such gruesome crimes and still escapes the death
penalty, then what sense does it make to have capital punishment?''
</P>
<P>
   In the punishment phase of the trial, Gordon's lawyers provided
a portrait of him as an abused, unwanted child. They said he was
born to a 14-year-old mother who was addicted to alcohol and drugs.
The jury was told that he grew up watching his mother inject heroin
and that he was beaten frequently by her.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives testified that Gordon's mother left him dirty, unkempt
and unfed and that he was forced to beg for scraps of food from
neighbors and strangers. The lawyers said that at the age of 7, he
tried to help his mother and two younger siblings by loading bags
at a supermarket and using the tips to buy groceries for the
family.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, in cross-examining Gordon's witnesses, noted that
his siblings, despite growing up in the same environment, turned
out differently, and are leading responsible lives.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brown, the Queens district attorney, whose office
prosecuted Gordon, said the unanimous decision by the jury of eight
women and four men not to impose the death penalty was ``made after
much deliberation and soul searching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept the jury's decision,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Unlike many states in which murder victims' relatives are
allowed to testify about their own suffering, New York prohibits
the presentation of sentiments by families affected by the crime.
In calling for the death penalty, New York prosecutors may only
cite ``aggravating factors'' and remind jurors of the circumstances
of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Renfroe, the defense lawyer, said that he and two other lawyers,
Russell Morea and and Susan Johnson, met briefly with Gordon before
he was returned to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan gave him a kiss on the cheek and we promised him we
would visit him in prison,'' said Renfroe. ``We all know that 20
years from now we can look back and say we were successful in
saving a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Johnson said that after the decision they laid
flowers at the grave of their daughter at a cemetery in Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went with tears flowing from my eyes to tell my daughter how
disappointed I am by the decision,'' Mrs. Johnson said. ``He had no
mercy for my daughter and my daughter-in-law and I can never
forgive him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
