<SLUG> BC-NY-FATAL-FIRE-VICTIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES, FRIENDS MOURN; PROFILES OF THE FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-FATAL-FIRE-SCENE) 
(rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Cavalieri
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One by one, they walked out onto the porch of Lt.
Joseph Cavalieri's home in Malverne, on Long Island, tugged at
their caps and wiped a hand across their contorted faces as if it
was some sort of rite.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family who streamed into the home of his widow,
Deborah, Friday afternoon in this community several miles east of
his Brooklyn firehouse said that Cavalieri was a man of action, a
firefighter who had requested a busy assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they never planned to bury him this young. He was 42.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani spoke of Cavalieri in a subdued tone
Friday during his weekly radio show when he took a call from Pat
McDonald. She is the wife of police officer Steven McDonald, who
was left a quadriplegic in 1986 after he was shot in the neck in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieutenant Cavalieri is not only one of the city's heroes, but
he is also a good friend of ours,'' Mrs. McDonald, who also lives
in Malverne, said.
</P>
<P>
   Others remembered Cavalieri, a 15-year veteran of the fire
department who stood a rugged 6 feet 5 inches tall, as a father of
two who placed God before family, and then family above all else.
He was also active in the community and a hero who died so others
would not, his mourners said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Cavalieri grew up in nearby Valley Stream and married
Deborah, his high-school sweetheart, 20 years ago. They brought up
two daughters in their Cape Cod home; one is now a 19-year-old
Fordham student and the other a 13-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He started his career in the Bronx, spent a decade at Ladder
Company 150 in Hollis, Queens, then moved to Ladder Company 170 in
Canarsie two years ago after being promoted to lieutenant, said his
friend, Michael Farrell, a fire marshal.
</P>
<P>
   As ashen-faced firefighters were bringing supper and soda and
beer into Mrs. Cavalieri's home, Farrell stood on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a hell of a Christmas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Bopp
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Bopp loved being a firefighter, friends and family
said, and he could barely contain his excitement about the prospect
of soon becoming a father. Friday, instead of coming together to
share in his good fortune, friends and relatives gathered at his
home in Midwood, Brooklyn, to mourn his loss and to try to help his
wife, Cori, face a future without him.
</P>
<P>
   Bopp lived just a few blocks from his childhood home and clearly
had earned the love and respect of his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best guy that you could ever meet,'' said Ed
Gleason, 73, a neighbor and a friend, who said Bopp helped him
shovel snow and with other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Gleason added that Bopp was good with children and was looking
forward to the birth of his first child, in July. He said that the
27-year-old firefighter always had time to ``talk hockey'' with
Gleason's 15-year-old grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Bopp's brother, John, said Christopher seemed to have found his
true calling when he became a firefighter three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved what he was doing and he loved the guys he did it
with,'' John Bopp said. ``He was one of the happiest men I ever
met.''
</P>
<P>
   James Bohan
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors on the street in Middle Village, Queens, where James
Bohan grew up and still lived with his parents remembered the
25-year-old firefighter as a polite boy who was inseparable from
his older brother, Maurice, and who grew up to be a thoughtful and
helpful neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time he was a boy, he was a real gentleman,'' said
Ann Jelley, who lived down the street from the Bohans until
recently and who frequently invited the two young brothers over to
play in her back yard with her granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jelley said that as a teen-ager and young adult, James
Bohan often made repairs at the homes of elderly neighbors. ``He
would go out of his way to help, painting and other repair work,
especially with neighbors where there was no man around the
house,'' she said. ``He and his brother both were good, good boys
for this day and age.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, other firefighters and friends and relatives
filed into the modest two-story attached brick house to pay their
respects to Bohan's family, some openly weeping.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Moreano, the Bohans' next-door neighbor, said James Bohan's
parents, John and Margaret, were devastated by their son's death.
``Especially his mother, she's having a hard time dealing with
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Conte, another neighbor, said the Bohans were a
close-knit and devout Irish Catholic family. ``Every Sunday, it was
like seeing the mother duck and the father duck with two baby ducks
walking in front of them and they would all head off to church
together,'' she said. ``And the boys did this even as adults. It
was wonderful to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
