<HEADER>
A8218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      12-19 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: IOC BEGINS MENDING A POSSIBLE TEAR IN INTEGRITY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There long have been allegations, suggestions and assumptions of
corruption among the International Olympic Committee, whose
oligarchic, undemocratic structure and penchant for choosing the
host city's finest hotel hardly has helped discourage such chatter.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, after all, is one of the world's most exclusive and
visible clubs, and exclusive clubs have a habit of fostering
jealousy, even animosity among nonmembers. All the more reason for
the fortunate few to be above reproach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask athletes to compete with integrity, and we ask members
of the IOC to act the same way,'' said Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice
president from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Not all athletes have answered the call, and neither have all
the members, which is no surprise in light of human nature but
certainly no excuse. The difference this time is that there appears
to be proof in the form of a scholarship and training-assistance
fund created by the bid committee from Salt Lake City that
benefited at least six relatives of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, and I expect I speak for a huge majority of IOC
members, I don't like this to be out there but I'm glad it is,''
IOC Vice President Dick Pound had said last week. ``Because it
gives us an opportunity to look into it, and hopefully that
opportunity will put a chapter that appears to be somewhat
disagreeable behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound, a potential candidate for the IOC presidency if Juan
Antonio Samaranch ever sees fit to vacate the post, has a major
role to play in the weeks ahead as head of the special commission
appointed to investigate the scholarship fund and, more important,
its beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is the members,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   While it is somewhat reassuring that the IOC has appointed a
special commission brimming with lawyers, it would have been much
more reassuring if the IOC had uncovered the fund's existence on
its own, instead of relying on the journalistic work of a Salt Lake
City television station.
</P>
<P>
   That the IOC has found nothing rotten with the state of Olympic
bidding until now means that it could not have been searching hard
enough or sending the proper signals to candidate cities about the
benefits of candor. Yes, the IOC has changed its system, removing
some of the dining and wining and waste by having an evaluation
commission pare down the lists of candidates and by strictly
defining gift limits. Yes, the IOC has debriefed bidding teams
after votes in an attempt to monitor the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that information is limited,'' said Marc
Hodler, the Swiss IOC member who has alleged that corruption in the
bidding process is hardly confined to Salt Lake City and its
scholarship fund. He said winners never say anything because they
have a ``bad conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The losers only give information if they have decided never to
run again,'' Hodler had added.
</P>
<P>
   This, Pound insists, is the first time the IOC has a paper
trail. If the committee does not take full advantage, it will risk
doing further damage to the credibility of an organization that
will pick another Olympic city next June in Seoul when it votes for
the host of the 2006 Winter Games. Any reform in the electoral
process will come too late for that vote.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner is Sion, Switzerland: a bid that Hodler
supports but did not necessarily help with his meandering, not
terribly cogent description of Gianni Agnelli's decision to give
Fiats to national federations during Sestrieres' successful bid to
host the 1997 Alpine Ski Championships.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Hodler seemed to be citing the gifts as a cautionary
tale, but he then shifted gears and began thanking Agnelli for
helping him combat the insidious influence of a Luxembourg-based
agent who was trying to sell blocks of votes to a rival bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Agnelli family essentially built Sestrieres, and Turin, the
Italian city which is one of Sion's leading rivals in the 2006
Olympic bidding is another Agnelli fief. Hodler insists that his
comments were never meant to sway votes for Sion.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler also was not maladroit on all counts in Lausanne. The
mystery is that he waited until after his 80th birthday to begin
speaking openly about his belief that corruption exists in the IOC.
He was president of the International Ski Federation for 47 years
without ever being quite so provocative. Hodler, who is now
president of the IOC coordination committee for the 2002 Games,
explained Monday that he spoke out because a recent conversation
with a friend made him realize that outsiders had begun to question
his own integrity and because he did not want Salt Lake City to
take all the blame when it was hardly alone and had been so quick
to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Where that cooperation leads or does not lead will be
fascinating to track, and the IOC surely must realize that if it
cannot police itself, outsiders will try to take over the policing.
Pound said that his committee hopes to complete its work by the end
of January. Then the executive board meets before a world
conference on doping begins in Lausanne. The timetable is
appropriate _ addressing one major problem in the Olympic movement
before moving on to the biggest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
