<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAVIAR-COPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COPS ON THE CAVIAR BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: With NY-CAVIAR-RING) (DW) 
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Special Agent 523 from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service flashed his gold badge at a security agent and wheeled his
dark blue Ford into the Northwest Airlines cargo area at Kennedy
International Airport. More than a thousand pounds of caviar
awaited his scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Inspector 248, his partner on a recent afternoon,
Special Agent 523 could barely contain his excitement. It was as if
their briefcases _ packed with test tubes, sample bags and latex
gloves _ were instead filled with mother-of-pearl spoons and the
duo were headed toward a caviar bacchanal.
</P>
<P>
   But their enthusiasm was purely scientific. The two are among
the force of caviar cops, so to speak, who monitor the rich supply
coming into New York City. The team, using DNA testing to determine
the origin of the eggs, was set up to enforce the tough new
international standards that now regulate caviar importing.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted by the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species of Wild Fauna and Flora, known as Cites, the regulations
seek to protect the dwindling supplies of sturgeon from the Caspian
Sea and elsewhere. The Fish and Wildlife Service of the Department
of the Interior is responsible for enforcing these standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two tons of imported caviar is now being held in the New
York region by the wildlife service. Some of it has flunked its DNA
testing and will be destroyed. Other shipments are waiting for the
results of DNA tests to verify that the fish eggs are, in fact,
what their traveling papers say they are _ for example, that a tin
labeled ``Caspian Sea Beluga'' really contains that premium grade.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector 248, Robert Rothe, who is 28 years old and has a
degree in wildlife biology, is like a patrolman on the beat. He
wears the department's uniform _ beige trousers, brown turtleneck
and brown fleece jacket stitched with a patch of the agency's seal.
He does not carry a gun.
</P>
<P>
   He carefully studies shipments of caviar in cold storage hangars
at the airport as well as in the suitcases of passengers on flights
from Russia, Eastern Europe and Scandinavia. On Oct. 28, Rothe
assisted Customs agents in discovering nearly 1,000 pounds of
caviar in the baggage of seven passengers on a Finnair flight from
Poland. In the case that developed from this finding, three people
were indicted Friday on smuggling charges in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent 523, Edward Grace, is more like a detective. It
was Grace, for instance, who worked nearly 600 hours in the last
two months to connect the smuggled caviar to a supplier in
Connecticut _ and discovered at least four other instances of
caviar smuggling that the supplier has been charged with.
</P>
<P>
   In his green tweed L. L. Bean jacket, a .40-caliber SIG Sauer
pistol tucked into the band of his chinos, Grace sounds like an
assistant biology professor, which, with his master's degree in
biology, he could be.
</P>
<P>
   Sliding open the door of the Northwest Airlines 50-by-50-foot
cold storage unit last week, Grace and Rothe opened the airline
container and freed a cardboard box.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first big shipment from China,'' said Grace, who
describes himself ``as the voice of the sturgeon which has no other
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Rothe sliced open the box. The cans of caviar inside were
pristine, each bearing a hologram of all the information required
by the international regulations. Grace opened six tins. He used a
tongue depressor to remove a dab of caviar from one tin and gently
slide the sample into a clear plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs were taken throughout the process, a total of six
snapshots per sample. The process took about 90 minutes. The
samples were sent to a laboratory in Ashland, Ore., for DNA
testing. The results would be ready in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The tests have not yet been completed, but neither Grace nor
Rothe expected any problems in the case of the Chinese eggs. Its
papers were in perfect order. Its contents smelled fresh. Fish eggs
from the Amur River on the border of China and Russia are sold as
keluga or as ossetra caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these Chinese sturgeon eggs are comparable to the
ossetra caviar harvested in the Caspian Sea is not something Rothe
or Grace would know.
</P>
<P>
   Grace does not like caviar. Rothe has never tasted the stuff.
``The more I see, the less I'm tempted,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
