<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KATY-DISQUALIFIED     12-19 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KATY-DISQUALIFIED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Player ruled ineligible on eve of contest
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BRIAN McTAGGART &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KATY _ One day before it was scheduled to play for the Class 5A
Division II state championship, Katy High School's football team
was disqualified Friday for using an ineligible player in its
victory over Clear Brook two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, imposed by University Interscholastic League
officials in Austin, came after Katy school officials reported that
a reserve player falsified grades so he could remain eligible
during the Tigers' bid for a second consecutive 5A title.
</P>
<P>
   With Katy's disqualification under the no-pass, no-play rule,
San Antonio MacArthur, which lost to the Tigers 14-6 in last week's
semifinals, now will play Midland Lee at noon today at Texas
Stadium in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a UIL rule is violated, sometimes there is a range of
penalties that can be involved,'' said Charles Breithaupt, the
UIL's athletic director. ``But when you're talking about no-pass,
no-play, there is no range, there is no interpretation, there is no
leeway.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy coach Mike Johnston, one year removed from a raucous
celebration of the Tigers' 1997 Division I state title, was somber
and shaken when he announced Katy's dreams of a repeat championship
would not come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, my feelings are for the seniors on the team,'' he
said. ``For this to finish our season is certainly the roughest
road I've ever traveled on as a coach. Our players are totally
dumbfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   The team was scheduled to leave for Irving at 10:15 a.m. Friday
and had boarded buses as the band played the school fight song when
Johnston received word of the UIL ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought they would let us play and then slap us hard for
next year,'' Johnston said. ``But the UIL told us that what had
happened was a violation of state law (the no-pass, no-play rule)
and that the UIL had to enforce state law.''
</P>
<P>
   The players were ushered from the buses to the field house where
they were informed by Johnston that their season was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the door slammed in your face at the threshold of a
state championship game, I don't know of anything tougher,''
Johnston said. ``When you have a group of guys who don't know
anything but to do the very best, it no doubt hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Midland Lee scrambled to prepare for a new opponent,
MacArthur coaches reissued equipment before the team caught a
flight late Friday for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' MacArthur linebacker Joey Johnson
said. ``I still can't believe it. I was getting ready to watch the
game on TV and thinking about how that could've been us, and here
we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Katy's players were left to wonder what could have
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we ended practice (Thursday) at Rhodes Stadium, we had a
little deal with the seniors because that was the last time we were
going to be on that field in pads,'' said team captain Trey Moebes.
``It was sort of sad, because for most of the guys this was going
to be their last chance to play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now our season's ended without us having a chance to do
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy Principal Robert Blankinship said the school learned late
Thursday that a player falsified grades and forged a signature on a
three-week progress report the week after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The player, a senior whose name was not released, participated
in the final three plays of Katy's 40-0 win over Clear Brook but
sat out the Tigers' victory over MacArthur last week.
</P>
<P>
   UIL rules state the minimum penalty of forfeiture must apply if
a student is ruled ineligible under no-pass, no-play.
</P>
<P>
   The forgery came to light when a teacher of one of the two
classes the player was failing noticed he was preparing to make the
trip to Irving with the team. The teacher told an assistant
principal, who notified Blankinship, who informed the UIL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was passing, and I had the progress report in
front of me,'' Johnston said. ``These kids want to be Katy Tigers
in the worst way, and it's unfortunate when they have to do some
things to stay on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to pass judgment (on the player). It's not the
makeup of our football team, not the way they were brought up and
not the way I was brought up. We just have to hope for
forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the third time in a little more than two months that
Katy has been thrust into the spotlight over eligibility concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Katy's troubles began Oct. 9 when Johnston reported to the UIL
that the Tigers had used an ineligible player in the final seconds
of a 28-14 win over Fort Bend Austin on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Katy was ordered by the District 19-5A executive committee to
forfeit four more games Oct. 22 for violations of the UIL amateur
rule after players received free meals and a free T-shirt from a
parent group.
</P>
<P>
   The State Executive Committee restored the victories Oct. 27,
but not before issuing Katy a public reprimand and one year on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Katy could find itself subject to further punishment from the
UIL for violating its probation. Penalties include disqualification
from next year's playoffs or a full-fledged suspension of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said he understood the UIL's decision in this case, but
thinks the rule should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our understanding if a student forges grades it's a
violation of state law, and the UIL doesn't have any flexibility,''
he said. ``They have to enforce the state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope in the future they review this in fairness to the team
and make adjustments so nothing like this happens to anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, who is president of the Texas High School Coaches
Association, said he wasn't concerned about his program possibly
getting a bad image statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot I can do for what people on the
outside think,'' he said. ``Everything we've done this year has
been the right thing to do by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't hesitate to turn ourselves in the two times before
and we didn't hesitate this time. Right now the system is unfair to
disqualify a whole football team for the actions of one person.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy school Superintendent Leonard Merrell said he wasn't sure
what punishment, if any, the player would suffer for falsifying his
grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern as far as he's concerned is his emotional
well-being and making sure he has the help he needs to make it
through this,'' he said. ``The young man worked hard to be on the
team. He made a mistake, and many others will suffer from that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope nobody does anything mean to him,'' Johnston said.
``He's not a bad kid. Being a part of this team was one of the most
important things in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Katy's campus was quiet Friday as students were released early
for winter break. Around town, signs proclaiming ``Paw is law'' and
``All the way to state'' remained intact even as the Tigers' season
was ripped to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the opportunity to live in this community 19 years
and have been involved in lots of things outside of school,''
Johnston said. ``I have a good handle on the spirit of the
community, and football has a lot to do with that spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have already come and shown support at a very difficult
time for the community. I feel they'll respond like our football
team does _ like champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporters Scott Kaiser, Sarah Hornaday and David
Barron contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
