<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STEELE-HNS     12-19 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-STEELE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baylor
</P>
<P>
   Man of Steele flying high
</P>
<P>
   Ecstatic coach calls new Baylor home `perfect fit'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ After he was introduced Friday as the new football coach at
Baylor, Kevin Steele couldn't help but reflect on what likely had
been the most emotional and dramatic week of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, sports fans across America saw TV replays of one
of the lowest moments in his 17-year coaching career. As the
linebackers coach for the Carolina Panthers, Steele was attacked by
Carolina linebacker Kevin Greene in a brief altercation on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   What no one knew at the time was Steele was about to get on a
plane headed for Waco to interview for a job and a chance he had
dreamed about most of this life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an amazing week,'' Steele said. ``Make no mistake
about it, (Sunday's incident) was a disappointing thing. Nobody
likes for that to happen. But three hours later, I was on an
airplane headed for what was the greatest opportunity of my
coaching career. I went from pretty frustrated to an ultimate
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele found out four days later he was Baylor's choice to
replace Dave Roberts, who was reassigned Dec. 6 after back-to-back
2-9 seasons. Steele, 40, has reached his longtime goal of becoming
a head coach for a major-college program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful time in my life,'' Steele told a gathering
of Baylor alumni Friday morning. ``The values this university has
in higher Christian education is conducive to the way Kevin Steele
tries to coach football and live his life. It was a perfect fit for
me and all the things I envision about being a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all of you are here today to hear what I have to say,
because after (last) Sunday, you all know what I look like.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident wasn't an accurate representation of what Steele is
like or how players feel about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, that issue was put to rest three minutes after
it happened,'' Steele said. ``You didn't see that on camera, but
Kevin Greene and I hugged each other's neck right after it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Respect of the men who play for him, ability to communicate with
people, a deep religious commitment and a firm belief in discipline
are some of the characteristics that enabled Steele to beat out the
other candidates for the Baylor job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is the right man at the right time for the right
university,'' Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton said. ``Kevin is
a professional with integrity. He has a brilliant football mind,
and he represents and stands for the things Baylor stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton admitted Steele became a front-runner for the job after
he interviewed with the advisory committee. When Gene Stallings
backed out Wednesday night, Steele was the man Baylor wanted.
</P>
<P>
   `We saw in him an outstanding individual and a man with
tremendous integrity,'' Stanton said. ``When you talk to Kevin, you
can't help but feel his commitment and his depth as an individual.
When the group saw Kevin's football knowledge and his charisma,
there was no doubt this was the man to lead our football program in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. was on the advisory committee.
Steele spent Thursday in Houston with McLane at the Astros offices
in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a communicator, which was the greatest asset I saw in
(Astros manager) Larry Dierker,'' McLane said. ``Larry knows how to
get his ideas over to the players, and Kevin will do that, also. He
spoke to (Astros president) Tal Smith for about 15 minutes, and Tal
told me Kevin was one of the most impressive sports people he had
ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, who played linebacker at Tennessee, has been an
assistant coach at Nebraska, Tennessee, New Mexico State and
Oklahoma State, along with four seasons in the NFL. But he never
has been a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no concern whatsoever about that,'' Stanton said.
``Kevin is the son of a coach and has worked under some outstanding
mentors. Kevin is a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Commitment is important to Steele, which is why he will do his
job for the Panthers in the last two games for the team this
season. Steele will be in Waco during the week, but join the team
on Sunday for its final two games. He said his top two priorities
are to start recruiting and fill his coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I will do is talk to the coaches here and see
if they fit into what we are trying to do,'' Steele said. ``Then we
want to look for coaches with Baylor ties that understand the
unique qualities of this university and have played at this school.
We also will look for coaches with Texas ties.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to indicate Highland Park High School coach
Scott Smith has a good chance of coming to Baylor. Smith, a former
Baylor player and assistant coach under Grant Teaff, was
interviewed for the head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, an avid runner, talked about the type of offense and
defense he wants to employ, saying he likes an aggressive 4-3
defense and a power-I offense with ``quick-strike'' passing
capabilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
