<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      12-19 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   A solution &QL; 
the problem &QL; 
for Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Numerous factors &QL; 
contribute to letdown
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with the Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's easier to start with what's right.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys still need only one win or an Arizona loss to clinch
the NFC East title and have two of the losingest teams in the
league remaining on their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback/punt returner Deion Sanders could return this week.
The Cowboys' 0-6 record with him out (over two years) should be all
the explanation necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith could return at cornerback this week. And though he
was an easy scapegoat early in the season, the alternatives have
been worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys scored a combined 65 points against these two
opponents in the previous meetings. The Eagles and Redskins got
into Dallas' end zone once.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys finish up at home and have a chance to go 8-0
within their division for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been what's wrong that has stood out in recent weeks,
and it's the reason the Cowboys need to worry about the last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a combination of both mental and physical,''
offensive lineman Mike Kiselak said. ``We have to come in wanting
it a little bit more and push a little harder through.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 22-3 drubbing by the New Orleans Saints, the Cowboys
spent a painful morning reliving the game film, but they thought
they figured out some things. It was the Saints' blitz that shut
down the Cowboys' ground game and stymied the once-potent air
attack. It was the Saints' quickness that led to so many
three-and-outs by Dallas that the Cowboys finished the game with a
season-low eight yards rushing and 128 yards overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any major problem,'' Kiselak said. ``We
just have to get together as a team and work a little harder, a
little longer at staying on our blocks and pushing that extra half
a step.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were prepared to protect against the blitz in the
Kansas City game, but they found the Chiefs to be more troublesome
in other areas. The Chiefs' defense took away the quick-passing
routes. The offense proved even more troublesome as brawny running
back Bam Morris shrugged off tackles to gain 134 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in too many of his highlight films,'' Cowboys safety
Charlie Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The explanations are many. There have been injuries galore. The
three biggest offseason acquisitions were running back Chris
Warren, offensive lineman Everett McIver and wide receiver Ernie
Mills. The latter two are on injured reserve. Warren has spent his
share of the games on the sidelines nursing ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders can take away half the field from opponents who
generally try to stay as far away as possible from the seven-time
Pro Bowl selection. With Sanders gone for the past three weeks, and
Smith and even backup Kevin Mathis gone at times, offenses have had
a field day with the decimated Dallas secondary.
</P>
<P>
   But recognizing the problems doesn't seem to have escaped
Dallas' grasp. Just reacting and adjusting. The Cowboys overcame a
three-quarter drought and the loss of receiver Michael Irvin to
score two late touchdowns last week against the Chiefs. But two
weren't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith had rushed for 100 yards or more in
three of the last five leading up to the New Orleans game. He
gained 50 in the last two games combined and 92 total in the past
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, everybody was gung-ho,'' Smith said. ``Now,
everybody's looking for answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Larry Allen, who will make his fourth trip to
the Pro Bowl this year, has been uncharacteristically manhandled at
times the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to a point in a season where you think that all the
other linemen are scared of you,'' Allen said. ``Then they start
doing different things than they did on the tape. That's what I
have to expect from here on out. I can't expect them to do what
they did on film the week before. I just have to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The run should again be the biggest factor Sunday. The Cowboys
put themselves in too many third-down situations last week,
converting only 9-of-27. The absence of solid runs on first and
second downs is largely to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just vital, especially in the NFC, that we get a running
game going,'' guard Nate Newton said. ``That helps keep the
pressure off Troy (Aikman). We've just got to work harder and
concentrate a little better and execute.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good formula, but the same one they spouted before the
Kansas City game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was one thing, you'd feel much better about it and
trying to work it out,'' coach Chan Gailey said. ``But it's a
combination of two or three things. In this game, you can never sit
down and fix one thing and then everything is OK. It doesn't work
that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 0142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8230 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXECS-CHARITY-LISTING     12-19 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECS-CHARITY-LISTINGS-$ADV20-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 EXECUTIVES' CHARITY LISTINGS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass., Fla., Texas, Calif., R.I., Tenn., Ga., Va.,
Conn.)  (EDS: Sidebar with EXECS-CHARITY) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he has been the honorary chairman of a number of
fund-raising benefits in the last several years, Michael D. Eisner,
who has been on the Forbes list of the wealthiest Americans since
1993, has not been known for megagifts to charity.
</P>
<P>
   That is likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Eisner reaped a stock-option windfall. He had 21.9
million options that were worth $460.8 million at the end of
Disney's fiscal year in September 1997. When he cashed them in late
that year, they were worth $550 million.
</P>
<P>
   During 1997, Eisner also put Disney shares worth about $116
million into his personal foundation. For Eisner, as for any donor
in his situation, the donation had two tax advantages: It reduced
his taxable income, perhaps by the full $116 million, and he did
not have to pay capital gains taxes on the donated shares.
</P>
<P>
   For the charitable world, the donation created an important new
benefactor. Like all foundations, his must give away about 5
percent of its net asset value annually _ millions of dollars, in
this case.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner has said his foundation would help needy children and
children with learning disabilities. No details of its giving are
yet known, but there are clues to the Eisner family's interests.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, Eisner's wife, Jane, has been on the board
of the American Foundation for AIDS Research. ``They have always
taken the position that what they give is anonymous,'' said Jerome
Radwin, executive vice president of the organization. Eisner also
has contributed more than $1 million to Georgetown University, his
son's alma mater. The school's president, the Rev. Leo J.
O'Donovan, is on Disney's board.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner is president of Disney's foundation, but its giving does
not reflect a personal point of view. A company spokesman said:
``It gives in communities where we are physically located. We want
to be good neighbors.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sanford I. Weill thinks about charity in the same way he thinks
about mergers: big.
</P>
<P>
   This year, big meant $100 million to Cornell University, which
renamed its medical school the Joan and Sanford I. Weill Medical
College and Graduate School of Medical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Weill has been extremely coy about revealing the number
of years over which he is giving his money away, making the real
value of his gift hard to figure.
</P>
<P>
   Weill has been chairman of the board of overseers of the medical
school since 1996 _ and last year was an opportune year for giving.
Weill exercised stock options for a gain of $220 million. Giving
away $100 million or some portion of that figure in the same year
could have helped him reduce his taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, the day he announced his gift to the medical
school, shares of Travelers, where he was then chairman, were
selling at $61.1875. ``When the market is up, you feel good about
giving,'' &UR;  &LR; Weill said. Five months later, the price had plummeted
to $31.75. On Friday, stock in Citigroup, the company formed from
the merger of Citicorp and Travelers, closed at $49.875.
</P>
<P>
   Weill has long been aware of the value of the corporate purse.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, he helped found the National Academy Foundation,
based in New York, a group that trains high school students for
jobs in the financial industry. American Express, where Weill was
then an executive, assisted with $100,000 to start the program. In
1996, when Weill was chief executive of Travelers Group, its
foundation gave the program $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Travelers foundation also gave to the Cornell medical school
and to Carnegie Hall, where the recital hall is named for Weill
because of a gift he made in 1983 and where he is chairman of the
board. Last year, Carnegie Hall was the site of the Travelers
annual meeting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eugene M. Isenberg doesn't believe that his company should have
a corporate foundation. ``Basically, I think it is the
shareholders' money,'' Isenberg said. ``It's not for the executives
to make the decision. They should give the money to the
shareholders and let them make it.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Isenberg himself donate last year? A total of $2.5
million, he said, well above his usual giving of about $500,000
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Isenberg's prime cause is education, and the major beneficiary
has been his alma mater, the University of Massachusetts. Last
year, he pledged $6 million over five years, giving $2 million of
that sum in 1997. Separately, he gives $90,000 annually for
scholarships at the university in mathematics, engineering,
computer science and business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to give something back to education,'' Isenberg
said. ``I could afford to do it, and I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Isenberg lives in Palm Beach, Fla., where he makes some
donations to the Palm Beach Opera and to a home for abused
children. He is sponsoring a fellowship in stroke prevention at the
Intercoastal Health Foundation in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Isenberg family also supports New York's Parkside School for
children with learning challenges. This year, Isenberg pledged to
give $750,000 if the school could raise an additional $500,000.
``The headmistress is my daughter's best friend,'' Isenberg said.
``They came to me 10 years ago. I helped them do a business
plan.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard Pfeiffer has been in Houston for just eight years, but
he is already a familiar figure at charitable events, where gossip
columns record his attendance at A-list functions, escorting the
socialite Caroline Farb.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that as one of Houston's most prominent
businessmen, he would be invited to join his adopted city's most
prominent boards, including those of the Houston Symphony, the
Greater Houston Partnership and the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center. He
is also on the board of Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But Pfeiffer, who was born in Germany and spent most of his
working life in Europe, does not appear to have embraced big-ticket
American philanthropy. Pfeiffer has not established a personal
foundation, so there is no public record of his giving, and he
declined to comment on his donations.
</P>
<P>
   Symphony officials confirmed that he gives to that organization
in the range of $7,500 to $10,000 a year, and Compaq says he is a
member of the Alexis de Toqueville Society of the United Way, which
requires a minimum gift of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's corporate giving is being reassessed as the company
absorbs recent acquisitions: the Digital Equipment Corp. and Tandem
Computer. It gave away $4.2 million last year, primarily to
education, health, social services and arts programs, mainly in
Houston. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Mark is a company man, having worked for
Colgate-Palmolive since he graduated from the Harvard Business
School in 1963. He became chief executive in 1984 and has grown
wealthy along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Mark declined to comment on his giving. But his philanthropic
interests seem to focus on education.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mark and his wife, Arlene, served a few years ago as
trustees of the I Have a Dream program. In that organization,
founded by Eugene Lang, a New York industrialist, benefactors adopt
classes of primary school students, work with them through junior
high and high school and then help them get into college.
</P>
<P>
   The project generally involves a financial commitment of
$500,000 to $1 million over seven years for each benefactor, and a
large commitment of personal time.
</P>
<P>
   Mark formerly was a trustee of Bank Street College of Education
in New York and is a director of New Visions for Public Schools,
which uses private funds to establish small new schools in the
city. Colgate-Palmolive is a corporate contributor to the program. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eli Broad does not shirk the philanthropic limelight; he is
eager to talk about both his views on philanthropy and the size of
his gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Los Angeles we don't have a tradition of philanthropy,''
Broad said in a telephone interview. ``I don't mind being out
front, and hopefully others will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The single largest beneficiaries of Broad's giving last year
were Pitzer College in Claremont, Calif., at $1.6 million; Michigan
State University, $1 million, and the new Disney Hall concert
facility in Los Angeles, also $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also give to United Jewish Appeal,'' Broad said. ``But I am
more interested in the community. Some people fault me for it. They
say how can you give to Michigan State and not to some Jewish
hospital? But I tell them that you have to do your own thing. I am
more a citizen of the city than I am of the Jewish community.''
</P>
<P>
   His giving is clearly structured with taxes in mind. Last year,
he said, his adjusted gross income was $38 million, between pay
from SunAmerica and investment income. Broad said he gave away
$11.6 million, or 30 percent of his adjusted gross income _ the
maximum a donor can deduct.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, an art collector, put $8 million of that sum into two
family foundations: one that provides grants for art students and
one that buys art and lends it to museums for exhibits. The two
foundations gave away $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   SunAmerica's corporate foundation, he said, gives primarily to
charities in the Los Angeles area, like the United Way, and makes
grants to local artists. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a fire badly damaged Central Synagogue in Manhattan last
September, Charles A. Heimbold Jr. quickly wrote a personal check
for $25,000 to help with restoration. Though Heimbold is Roman
Catholic, a spokesman for Bristol-Myers Squibb explained that he
``wanted to be a good neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be interviewed about his giving, but a
surprisingly eclectic collection of charities benefited from the $5
million Heimbold &UR;  &LR; donated last year, primarily through his personal
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gift was $2 million to the University of
Pennsylvania Law School, where Heimbold worked on the Law Review in
1960. Others were $1 million to Villanova University, where he
received his bachelor's degree; $500,000 to Phoenix House, a drug
treatment network, and $100,000 to the American Museum of Natural
History.
</P>
<P>
   Heimbold's wife, Monica, a social worker, is a trustee of the
American Scandinavian Foundation, and the Heimbolds have given
$500,000 toward the group's Child Center. They also gave $250,000
to a library in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The Bristol-Myers foundation gave about $28 million last year to
organizations aimed at furthering science, education and child
care. But a spokesman said Heimbold was careful that the
foundation's giving not mirror his own. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the gifts made last year by the personal charitable
foundation of John F. Welch Jr., his philanthropic passions are
education, religion and the United Way.
</P>
<P>
   The largest single gift from the $6.2 million foundation was
$25,000 to the Sankaty Head Foundation, which provides college
scholarships for young people who caddie at the Sankaty Head Golf
Club on Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the foundation gave away $134,156 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Welch also makes gifts other than those reported through records
of the foundation, but he does not like to talk about them, a GE
spokeswoman said. ``He does believe in charitable giving, but he
feels it is a private matter and he is not going to discuss it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Welch foundation gave $19,381 to the Inner City Foundation
in Bridgeport, Conn. ``Jack Welch has been the guiding light behind
it for seven years, and his wife, Jane, is on the board,'' said
Bishop Edward M. Egan, president of the Inner City Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's foundation also gave $15,000 to the Tri-State United
Way; $7,500 to his alma mater, the University of Massachusetts, and
$5,000 to the Bridgeport Hospital Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   GE's corporate foundation gave away about $40 million last year,
primarily to educational institutions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is chairman of an Atlanta company, but Summerfield K.
Johnston Jr. has his heart and heritage in Chattanooga, Tenn.,
where his family's century-old bottling business was based before
it was bought by Coca-Cola Enterprises in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was chief executive of the Atlanta company for seven
years before easing into his current job last April, he ``is a real
mystery'' on the Atlanta charity scene, according to an executive
active in giving there who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston does serve on the board of the Morehouse School of
Medicine in Atlanta and has made contributions to the school and to
Spelman College, also in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In Chattanooga, he is on the board of the University of
Chattanooga Foundation and has given grants for research on the
blighted American chestnut tree and to endow professorships.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his foundation also gave $50,000 to the Baylor
School, a Chattanooga preparatory school &UR;  &LR; that he, his father and
his son all attended.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the foundation, which had assets of $23 million in 1997,
gave away $1 million last year. Other beneficiaries included a
community foundation in Sheridan, Wyo., near where he has a home;
and his alma mater, Vanderbilt University. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some people want to change the world; Stephen M. Case wants to
connect it to the Internet. A founder of America Online, he now
hopes to use some of the same techniques in philanthropy that he
uses in business.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is entrepreneurship. In 1996, Case and his wife,
Jean, started the Computer Learning Center to put computers in
low-income housing projects in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise,'' Case said, ``kids go home from school and don't
have access to computers.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to enlist others to start similar centers elsewhere.
``This is the same way venture capitalists help create new
companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, of course, have made it possible for Case to become a
philanthropist. Six years ago, all of America Online was worth $70
million. Last year, his total pay, including unexercised options,
was more than $119 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1997, Case established a personal foundation with a
donation of America Online stock worth $981,250. His subsequent
contributions _ and the run-up in Internet stocks _ have increased
its assets to $50 million, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   America Online started a corporate foundation last year, as
well, dedicated to helping the Internet have a positive impact on
society. The foundation gave away $400,000 in its first year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that few chief executives have such large private
organizations to support as Lawrence A. Bossidy, the father of 9
and the grandfather of 20.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bossidy gives money to a number of institutions in which
he is personally involved, including religious and alumni groups.
</P>
<P>
   Bossidy worked at General Electric for 34 years, and, to an
extent, his giving mirrors that of his former boss, John F. Welch
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gift last year from Bossidy's personal foundation,
which has $3.7 million in assets, was $50,914 to Faith in
the &UR;  &LR; Future, a Bridgeport, Conn., group that is headed by Bishop
Edward M. Egan and helps Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Sankaty Head Foundation, which gives scholarships for
caddies at a Nantucket golf club and is a favorite charity of
Welch, received $10,000 of the $206,962 that Bossidy's foundation
gave away. Bossidy also gave $40,000 to St. Mary's Roman Catholic
Church in Ridgefield, Conn., near his home, and $19,950 to the
Tri-State United Way.
</P>
<P>
   A Colgate University alumnus, Bossidy has been a steady
contributor to the school; last year, his foundation gave it
$24,590.
</P>
<P>
   Bossidy declined to be interviewed; Bishop Egan said he was very
generous, and another associate added that he sometimes preferred
to be quiet about his giving. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Louis V. Gerstner Jr. has long been a champion of education. And
while much of his philanthropy was financed until recently from the
corporate coffers of IBM, he has begun to make big gifts of his own
as his personal wealth has soared. This year, he has given away $2
million, partly through his personal foundation, according to an
IBM executive.
</P>
<P>
   Among the gifts were $1 million to Bishop Edward M. Egan's Faith
in the Future campaign for Catholic schools, for which he has
established a distinguished scholars program; $500,000 to the
Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons, and
$300,000 to Chaminade High School, the Catholic school he attended
in Mineola, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Gerstner gave his foundation $1.1 million and it made
gifts totaling $118,000, including $34,460 to Faith in the Future;
$15,000 to the United Way of Greenwich, Conn., and smaller amounts
to various community, educational and religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
   IBMs corporate giving ``mirrors Gerstner's own commitments,''
according to Stanley Litow, a company vice president. IBM makes
grants to schools and state education departments to foster the use
of technology in the classroom. It donated $26.6 million cash and
$70.2 million in computers last year, about two-thirds to
educational projects. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
