 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RDP (Washington) _ On the third day of the air assault on
Iraq, the Pentagon said Friday that it was able to confirm that
only 18 of its 89 targets had been severely damaged or destroyed,
despite waves of bombers and more laser-guided cruise missiles than
were hurled at Iraq during the gulf war in 1991. Saddam Hussein
showed defiance toward the United States in his first televised
address since the attacks began, calling his attackers ``the agents
of Satan.'' Ledeall. By Philip Shenon. (With photo and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SOLDIERS (Fort Steward, Ga.) _ Here at Fort Stewart,
headquarters for the Third Division's Second Brigade, President
Bill Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq has canceled the homecomings
of many, and will probably cause others to be shipped out to the
Persian Gulf over the next few days or weeks. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RUSSIA (Washington) _ Despite Russia's anger over the
bombing of Iraq and the recall of its ambassador from Washington,
Moscow's private conversations with U.S. officials reflect a desire
to preserve and protect the U.S.-Russian relationship, senior U.S.
officials said Friday. Officials noted that the most positive
conversation yet occurred Friday morning between Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECT (United Nations) _ If Saddam Hussein is still in
control of Iraq when the bombing ends, arms-control experts say,
the Security Council should not abandon arms inspections but should
quickly reimpose rigorous monitoring in every area of weapons
development. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-MILITARY (Washington) _ As U.S. and British forces struck
Iraq for a third day, senior defense officials said the attack was
simply working its way through a ``tightly drawn'' list of military
and industrial targets. The strikes would end, they said, when the
cruise missiles and jets reached the end of the list. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SAUDIS (Manama, Bahrain) _ More than half of the U.S.
strike aircraft in the Persian Gulf region have been kept out of
the attack on Iraq because of objections from Saudi Arabia, Western
military officers said Friday. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RAMADAN (Undated) _ Ramadan, the holy month of dawn-to-dusk
fasting in the Islamic calendar, begins this weekend for Muslims
around the world. Its start depends on the sighting of the new
crescent moon. (No byline)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ For the first time since Feb. 24, 1868,
three years after the United States emerged from an awful Civil
War, the House of Representatives debated the impeachment of a
president Friday. It scheduled for Saturday a vote on four articles
of impeachment ``for high crimes and misdemeanors'' against William
Jefferson Clinton. By R.W. Apple Jr. (With photo and graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The strangest sound of all in the
debate to impeach President Clinton was the sudden roar of
shockingly bipartisan approval and applause erupting across the
House of Representatives when the plaintive cry came forth: ``The
politics of smear and slash-and-burn must end!'' For the briefest
moment in a day of bear-pit partisanship, Republicans and Democrats
cheered as one. The scene. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ Mindful as ever of his standing
in history, President Clinton is said by associates to feel
devastated about a scar he now regards as inevitable: a vote to
impeach him Saturday in the House of Representatives. But at the
same time, aides and friends of Clinton say, America's most tested
political fighter has steeled himself for the battle of his life.
By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-FLYNT (Los Angeles) _ It was, in some ways, inevitable
that Hustler publisher Larry Flynt would immerse himself in the
infidelities of President Clinton and other Washington politicians.
Raunchy, flamboyant, self-serving and defiant, Flynt was fully
enjoying his notoriety Friday just as he did more than 25 years ago
when he leveraged a string of Ohio strip clubs into the start of a
publishing empire that pushed _ and is still pushing _ the limits
of sexual tolerance. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RESIGN (Washington) _ The next battle the White House
will face is an anticipated campaign to pressure President Clinton
to resign. White House aides charge that Republicans are
orchestrating a resignation push, because House leaders expect
their impeachment drive to falter in the Senate. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MOOD (Washington) _ The president, some of his aides and
friends say, is devastated. He has withdrawn, they say, even
cutting off some of his usual circle of friends. One, who talked to
him daily, hasn't heard from him since Thanksgiving. Another tells
of calls among the inner circle about how to get Bill Clinton's
political fires burning again. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS (Washington) _ They are the lame ducks in the
House, 21 Republicans and 17 Democrats, not including two
Republicans and one Democrat who won election to Senate seats. And
as the House took up impeachment Friday, they streamed back into
the Capitol to deal with what for many is the most momentous issue
of their careers in public service, one they variously view as
unfortunately necessary or just unfortunate. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLL (Washington) _ The Republican Party's standing with
the public dropped significantly this week, tying its lowest rating
in the past 14 years, as the House moved toward a vote on
impeaching President Clinton even as the United States launched a
military attack on Iraq, the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll
shows. By Richard W. Stevenson. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ The television screen showed the
House of Representatives more than three-quarters empty. And if
Congress wasn't watching, why should we? The House floor was meant
to be the site of history-making drama, but the action Friday was
all off-stage. It was definitely on camera, though, captured in the
talk of reporters and commentators who helped shape the political
spin and strategies. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-VOICES (St. Louis) _ Back in the St. Louis suburbs to
talk to people about impeachment. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: As the acrid,
rueful and righteous debate went through the hours Friday, the
House stood poised to do what even some of its own Republican
leaders once considered unimaginable _ to impeach a Democratic
president on a near party line vote against the will of the people.
This was not the way something as momentous as impeachment was
supposed to take place. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CAVIAR-RING (New York) _ Uncovering what it called a black
market caviar scheme worth millions, the federal government
indicted three men who run a distributing company that supplies
much of the retail and restaurant market in New York City with the
precious fish eggs. The distributors were charged in federal court
with smuggling thousands of pounds of Russian sturgeon roe into the
United States from Poland. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLOON (Undated) _ The eternal quest to become the first
balloonist to circumnavigate the globe begins anew: The ICO Global
Challenge, a 160-foot-high balloon piloted by an all-star team of
long-distance balloonists, rose from its launching pad at
Marrakesh, Morocco, on Friday to begin a voyage the balloonists
hope will take them around the world in 10 days. By Malcolm W.
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-AIRLINES (Manila) _ With $2.2 billion in debt,
plunging revenues and losses of close to $1 million a day,
Philippine Airlines, Asia's oldest airline, is in desperate shape.
But Philippine Airlines is also the crown jewel in the empire of a
tycoon who is a leading supporter of the new president of the
Philippines. In the murky world of Asian business, where
friendships often count more than solvency, Philippine Airlines
would seem to be the classic candidate for a government bailout.
But that is not the case. By Mark Landler. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   ALLTEL-ALIANT (Undated) _ Alltel Corp., a telecommunications
company based in Little Rock, Ark., said Friday that it had agreed
to acquire Aliant Communications Inc., a midwestern telephone
company, for $1.5 billion in stock. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Surreal, unreal, mind-blowing: these are
words of the '60s, and it's no wonder they returned to vogue this
week. Not since a tottering presidency, a divisive war,
assassinations, civic unrest and bitter partisanship overloaded the
American psyche in 1968 has there been a spectacle to match this
moment. ``Split-screen America'' we call it now. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
30th anniversary of Special Olympics, which had a banquet Thursday
night that brought together the likes of David Stern and a few NBA
players. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SALT-LAKE-CITY (Salt Lake City) _ At a closed meeting room
at the Salt Lake Organizing Committee's headquarters, the
five-member SLOC Ethics Committee met to discuss the bribery
allegations. Likely to be on the agenda was a $400,000 scholarship
whose 13 beneficiaries included relatives of IOC members; why those
scholarships were not reflected on tax documents; and $28,000 in
free medical service provided to three IOC members. The payments
appear to violate IOC rules limiting the value of gifts to members
to $150. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIEWS-OF-NATURE (Undated) _ Nature is constantly being invoked
in moral crusades. Our views on nature are tied to our political
and cultural outlook. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPARENCY (Undated) _ The hot new word: Transparency is not
just for glass, water and lies anymore. There are transparent
cities, economies, countries, cosmology and more. By Barbara Boxer.
</P>
