<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON STORIES &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DC-LAWSUIT (Washington) _ The District of Columbia has requested
immediate action on a lawsuit against the federal government
seeking voting representation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPLANE-NOISE (Washington) _ Airplane noise has gotten a lot
softer, according to the Federal Aviation Administration, and a
10-year program with that in mind is approaching a pianissimo
finale. But some airlines will face a last-minute rush to fix or
retire old planes next year, and one, a cargo carrier in Miami,
will ground some planes in January, until they can be fixed. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRAQ &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RDP (Undated) _ Ledeall on assessment of third day of
airstrikes, plans for future attacks. By Philip Shenon and Steven
Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-POLICY (Undated) _ An inevitable price of the United
States' and Britain's use of force in Iraq is that it arouses
considerable unease around the world, especially if it fails.
Although only Russia has publicly vented irritation at the U.S.
decision to punish President Saddam Hussein, many another
government, especially in the Middle East, has watched the attacks
with consternation, either from uneasiness about any nation that
would take on itself the role of global policeman, or from concern
about local repercussions, or from unanswered questions about what
the United States is trying to achieve. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-HIDE (United Nations) _ Dazzling television images of
rocket attacks and satellite photographs of ruined Iraqi buildings
have yet to convince some experts, including U.N. weapons
inspectors, that President Saddam Hussein has been decisively
undercut in his ability to make new weapons of mass destruction. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ENTERPRISE (Aboard the USS Enterprise) _ The bombs may be
sophisticated, but the sentiments are not. Just below the flight
deck, in a newly-dubbed Bomb Farm, the high-tech weapons had been
scrawled with Magic Markers, in that time-tested way, to send crude
messages to Iraq of what sailors really think. ``To Sadam, Mery
X-Mas, '' one of them said. ``Hold Onto Yer Butt,'' read another,
``Die, You Magets,'' said another, and yet another read: ``This is
Gunna Hurt.'' By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CULTURE (Jerusalem) _ On city streets and in their living
rooms Israelis are awash in American popular culture. McDonald's
restaurants, Tower Records stores and Blockbuster Video shops dot
the urban landscape, and MTV and ``Seinfeld'' reruns are on cable
television. But the Israeli Parliament is trying to turn the
cultural tide. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-RUSSIANS (Geneva) _ Since the fall of Communism, rich
Russians have frequented this country's ski slopes and luxury
boutiques, welcomed as free-spending guests but otherwise
attracting little notice. But two recent events have begun to focus
Swiss attention on whether this banking redoubt is becoming a prime
place to stow ill-gotten cash from the former Soviet Union and a
comfortable haven for rich Russian undesirables. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA-SCANDAL (Oklahoma City) _ Far from the impeachment
battle engulfing the nation's capitol, Oklahoma's lieutenant
governor is discovering that the American Bible belt is hardly
immune to sex-fueled controversy. A divorce between Lt. Gov. Mary
Fallin, 43, and her estranged husband has eroded into accusations
of adultery that threaten to cripple her political future. The
attorney for Fallin's husband suggested in a Dec. 4 divorce hearing
that the lieutenant governor had had an affair with one of her
bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ATHEIST-AUCTION (Austin, Texas) _ The deepest secrets and
innermost thoughts of America's most famous atheist are for sale.
Madalyn Murray O'Hair, who founded the nation's leading atheist
group, American Atheists Inc., in the 1960s and vanished in 1995,
left behind a stack of diaries that will be sold next month to
satisfy a claim against her estate brought by the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DOWD-COLUMN _ A column on impeachment. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HERBERT-COLUMN _ A column on impeachment. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
