<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-DRUG-USE-NYT &LR;      12-19 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-DRUG-USE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE OF DRUGS BY TEEN-AGERS DECLINES SOME, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After rising since the early 1990s, the use of marijuana and
other drugs by teen-agers may be ebbing, however modestly,
according to a new survey that is considered the most reliable
gauge of substance abuse among secondary school students.
</P>
<P>
   The annual survey of nearly 50,000 students around the country,
titled Monitoring the Future, was conducted at the Institute for
Social Research at the University of Michigan and released on
Friday. Though the levels of drug and alcohol use remain higher
than they were several years ago, the survey reported, all grades
that were studied showed a slight but often statistically
significant drop in overall drug use in the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the institute's researchers found use of illicit
drugs declining only among eighth-graders. That trend continued
this year, and drug use declined slightly among 10th- and
12th-graders, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the best news we've had to bring the country
in some years,'' the principal researcher, Lloyd Johnston, said in
a telephone interview. ``Young people seem to be appreciating more
fully the dangers of various drugs, including alcohol and
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of adolescent drug use involves
marijuana, which remained widespread. This year, 49 percent of
12th-graders and 22 percent of eighth-graders sampled said that
they had tried marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of 12th-graders who smoked marijuana in the
previous month declined to 22.8 percent from 23.7 percent, while
the number of eighth-graders using it dropped to 9.7 percent from
10.2 percent. The decline in regular use was more noticeable among
10th-graders: 18.7 percent had smoked marijuana in the previous
month, compared with 20.5 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly are not back to levels at the beginning of the
'90s and it's too soon to trumpet victory,'' Johnston said, ``but
certainly it's very encouraging news that this upward trend has
finally begun to reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of harder drugs, notably heroin and cocaine, remained
statistically small and appeared to level off or decline for most
groups surveyed. Among high school seniors, 2 percent acknowledged
experimenting with heroin, marginally down from 2.1 percent a year
ago. But 9.3 percent said they had tried cocaine at some point,
compared with 8.7 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about their use in the previous 30 days, 2.4 percent of
the seniors said they had snorted or smoked cocaine, compared with
2.3 percent a year ago. And 0.5 percent said they had used heroin
in the previous month, a statistic unchanged from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol, primarily beer, remains the substance most frequently
abused by teen-agers, though even its use declined. Among
eighth-graders, 23 percent said they had drunk alcohol in the
previous month, compared with 24.5 percent last year. Among
10th-graders, monthly alcohol use dropped to 38.8 percent from 40.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But 8.2 percent of eighth-graders admitted getting drunk in the
previous month, a slight rise from the 8 percent who reported doing
so a year ago. Among high school seniors, 32.9 percent said they
had been drunk in the previous month, compared with 34.2 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed tobacco use down slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston and his fellow researchers, Jerald Bachman and Patrick
O'Malley, attributed the changes in drug-seeking behavior to a
reassessment by teen-agers of the risks and to stronger expressions
of concern by parents and other adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1112EST &QL; 
