<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-CULTURE-NYT &LR;      12-19 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CULTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL BATTLES NEW FOREIGN FOE: MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In city streets and in their living rooms Israelis
are awash in American popular culture. McDonald's restaurants,
Tower Records stores and Blockbuster Video shops dot the urban
landscape, and MTV and ``Seinfeld'' reruns are on cable television.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli Parliament is trying to turn the cultural tide.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote last month, lawmakers gave initial approval to a bill
that would require that half the songs on national radio stations
be in Hebrew, the official language. The vote, 36 to 0, which
crossed party lines, was the first of three votes necessary for
passage, and the bill seems assured of final approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting up a protective wall against the flood of
foreign culture'' said Yona Yahav, a sponsor of the bill from the
opposition Labor Party. ``The country is 50 years old. Its culture
has yet to be formed, and we thought it should be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill reflects the struggle here to mold the image of a
country whose culture is a work in progress. The legislation is
proceeding as cable television, the Internet and an increasingly
privatized economy are connecting Israelis more than ever to the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis listen avidly to American popular music, and
Israeli music itself is a melange of East and West, with heavy
Middle Eastern and Mediterranean influences that mix with
American-style rock. Immigrant groups like Russians and Ethiopians
listen to their own ethnic music.
</P>
<P>
   The two national, and most popular, radio networks, the Voice of
Israel and Army Radio, play foreign and Israeli songs. A host of
niche stations that have sprung up specialize in areas like
religious music or Arabic-style tunes by Sephardic Jewish singers.
</P>
<P>
   Yahav says his legislation is intended to promote original work
by Israelis and to counter the influence of foreign music on
teen-agers, many of whom are avid viewers of MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're part of the global village, and the minute you bring up
the younger generation to listen only to foreign music the youth
won't have any relationship to Israeli music,'' Yahav said. ``Part
of the essence of setting up an independent state was to establish
our own culture here. The bill is a cultural statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing similar legislation in France, where 40 percent of the
songs on the radio have to be in French, Shaikeh Levy, chairman of
the Israel Union of Performing Artists, said his group had pushed
for the bill partly to help the music industry. Demand for Hebrew
songs is rising, Levy said, and there is a need to preserve Israeli
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Americanization in Israel,'' Levy said. ``We want to
prevent our culture from getting lost among others and we want to
encourage local productions.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bill see it as a hopeless effort to legislate
cultural tastes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Thank God Israeli culture is still unformed, and God save us
from a situation in which laws will mold culture,'' said Michael
Handelzalts, a former culture editor at the newspaper Haaretz who
now edits its book-review supplement. ``Frightened countries build
protective walls. It's provincial and stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Israeli songwriter, Ehud Manor, said exposure to
foreign influences had enriched Israeli music. ``Israeli pop music
is not autonomous,'' he said. ``It is affected by what is happening
in the world, and I see that as a blessing. Trying to prevent
developments in the world from entering our cultural bloodstream is
a lost cause, and it will only spoil what is a natural process.''
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed requirement to broadcast Hebrew-language music
on the radio would not help artists who perform in languages like
Arabic, Yiddish or English. And the national networks have
responded in recent years to the demand for Israeli music. On Army
Radio, 60 percent of the songs are in Hebrew, and the Voice of
Israel has devoted one station entirely to Hebrew music.
</P>
<P>
   The Association for Civil Rights in Israel has criticized the
bill for Hebrew songs as infringing on the free speech guaranteed
under Israeli law. ``In matters of freedom of artistic expression
it is improper to intervene through legislation,'' said a lawyer
for the association, Anat Scolnicov.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to requiring Hebrew songs on national stations the
bill stipulates that licenses should be given to new local stations
``whose aim is to promote Israeli works and songs in the Hebrew
language.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of programming at Israel Radio, which specializes
in Hebrew songs, Menachem Granit, said he was against imposing such
music on other stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for foreign influence,'' Granit said. ``We can't stay
shut up in our own little world. We're living in the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
