<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8297 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-COOLING-LADN     12-19 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-COOLING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAGS CONTINUE TO DELAY SCHOOL AIR CONDITIONING IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With the fast-track installation of air
conditioning now stalled in court, Los Angeles school district
officials are considering hiring individual contractors to do the
work -- a method critics said has resulted in slow and shoddy work
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The district had hoped to have a single consortium of companies,
led by Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric, complete the 150-school, $155
million job.
</P>
<P>
   But that plan now faces a court challenge, potentially tying up
the program until after a March 26 hearing. Rather than delay and
let students swelter through another summer, several Board of
Education members said it may make more sense to hire separate
companies to begin the second phase of installation at 58 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the preference,'' board President Victoria
Castro said Friday. ``We don't want to wait until March.''
</P>
<P>
   The consortium would possibly be retained for the project's
third phase, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of using independent contractors strikes others as
an immense step backward. It was slipshod work by some contractors
on the first round of air-conditioning projects that drove board
members to give the job to the consortium, critics said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where we started. It was unacceptable then, and it's
unacceptable now,'' said Steven Soboroff, chairman of the
Proposition BB Oversight Committee, which pushed for the fast-track
process. Voters approved the $2.4 billion bond measure in 1997 to
fund renovations at the district's aging schools.
</P>
<P>
   Soboroff said that regardless of the legal questions, the Los
Angeles Unified School District should go ahead and sign the
contract hammered out with the consortium to start work
immediately. A spokeswoman for one of the consortium companies,
PG&AMP;E Energy Services, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in fact willing to sign the agreement, as currently
drafted, tomorrow if the district is willing to move forward with
it,'' said spokeswoman Diane Sable.
</P>
<P>
   But district officials counter that should the judge rule
against them, schools would be left with half-finished
air-conditioning systems as summer approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Board members initially picked the consortium for the $155
million job in July, but did not sign a contract, waiting instead
for a judge to rule on the legality of the way the consortium was
selected. Although the district had discussed the project with
several firms, it bypassed the regular bidding process to save
time.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, led a longtime district contractor, the H.A.
Nichols Construction Co., to challenge the selection process in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Board members point out that both possibilities have potential
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The district relied on individual contractors for the initial
round of air-conditioning work, and in the project's first 15
months, systems were installed in just 16 of the 150 schools
targeted. That phase of installation is now about 80 percent
complete.
</P>
<P>
   District spokesman Eric Nasarenko said if officials choose to go
with individual contractors again, they would avoid some of the
mistakes that happened last time. For example, the district would
likely buy the needed air-conditioning units up front and warehouse
them to make sure there were no delays in getting them to
individual schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, board member David Tokofsky said he worried about the
potential speed and quality of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's been stated to me that if the district takes on the
work, the students would have air conditioning before the Fourth of
July,'' said member David Tokofsky.
</P>
<P>
   If district officials sign a contract with the consortium to
begin the work, they risk having to stop in midstream if a judge
eventually rules against them in the court case. They would then
have to place the half-finished projects out to bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything would stop for six or eight weeks again while we
went out to bid,'' said board member Valerie Fields. ``It would be
a shame to give up on (the fast-track concept) -- I like the idea
-- but we've got to look at this unemotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Soboroff, however, argued that even such a worst-case scenario
carries little potential danger for the district. If the projects
were put back out to bid after the consortium already had ordered
equipment and started work, the consortium would logically be the
lowest bidder to complete installation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the risk to the district?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Board members said they hope to reach a decision on how to
proceed before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
