r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOOTHING-HOSPITAL-LAD     12-19 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOOTHING-HOSPITAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL PROVIDES SOOTHING SIGHTS, SOUNDS, SMELLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News.) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ITALICS ON)``It just makes sense to me. If I was a patient,
this is what I would want.'' -- Mitch Leichter, director of
recreational therapy for Sherman Oaks Hospital and Health
Center.(ITALICS OFF)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOS ANGELES -- Me, too. Although I think I'd trade in the classical
music for some Sinatra, and the flutist for a sax player.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, everything else in Mitch Leichter's magical rec
room is exactly what you'd want if you were a hospital patient in
recovery trying to keep your mind off the pain and hospital food.
</P>
<P>
   Saltwater aquariums with beautiful fish swimming around,
cascading waterfall fountains, soft classical music playing in the
background, and special aromas filling your nostrils to help take
your mind a thousand miles away from your ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Add a strolling violinist, flutist, Zen garden and some pets.
Even some kids from nearby Notre Dame High School stop by after
school to visit. With any luck, Leichter said, they'll remind some
of the elderly patients in recovery of their grandkids and help put
their minds in a good, warm place.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it's all there in Mitch Leichter's magical rec room -- all
except the standard hospital recreational stuff, like bingo, and
arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not feeling well, the last thing you want is someone
bouncing into your room like a cheerleader and telling you it's
time for bingo,'' Leichter said. ``This isn't a cruise ship.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's the transitional care unit at Sherman Oaks Hospital and
Health Center in suburban Sherman Oaks, Calif., where patients are
recovering from surgeries, hip replacements, pneumonia, respiratory
problems, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first people they meet waking up is Leichter, who
walks in their room for a quick assessment. He doesn't carry a
notebook or a clipboard, just the gift of gab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gently schmooze with them a little, ask them how they like
to spend their day and go from there,'' he said. ``A lot of them
are hurting and don't want to work hard at anything right now, so
you come up with a soft stimuli, something they can ease into.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to make it like taking them back to the favorite room
in their house. You don't feel compelled to do anything there, the
room does it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   For patients who miss their pets, Leichter brings in puppies and
kittens for them to hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty minutes of petting and stroking a puppy is 20 minutes
less they're thinking about and dealing with the pain,'' Leichter
said. ``It's a great diversion.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who love music, a violinist and flutist &UR;  &LR; come in a
few times a week and stroll the hallways of the facility in
Southern California's San Fernando Valley. Over the speakers, soft
classical music continually plays, as patients read the newspaper
or a book in front of cascading waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular form of this environmental therapy, as it's
called, is aromatherapy -- the smells and senses that bring back
better times than now. The smells of flower gardens, apple pies
baking in the stove, pine needles in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aromas allow the patients to reminisce and give them
smells other than hospital smells,'' he said. ``It gets their mind
off why they're here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way most patients describe it to me is like closing their
eyes and flying. And that's what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   From all the positive feedback, Joan Jessop, the hospital's
director of patient care, has been getting over Leichter's
environmental therapy, that's exactly what patients want in
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   To close their eyes and fly, but not on medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have patients who have been in surgery before who will
request aromatherapy in their recovery room, and go off the
medication,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been amazing to see, the power smells, music and pets
have on the minds and bodies of these patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, we had two 8-week-old puppies in, and an
elderly woman begged us to take them into her husband's recovery
room. He was having a tough time after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen them. They each had a puppy cuddled under
one arm and were lying together in the bed, smiling and playing
with the puppies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get any better therapy than that,'' Jessop said.
``The patients love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, because it makes sense and beats the heck out of bingo.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
