<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-RUSSIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS FEAR INFILTRATION BY RUSSIAN UNDESIRABLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Since the fall of communism, rich Russians have
frequented this country's ski slopes and luxury boutiques, welcomed
as free-spending guests but otherwise attracting little notice.
</P>
<P>
   But two recent events have begun to focus Swiss attention on
whether this banking redoubt is becoming a prime place to stow
ill-gotten cash from the former Soviet Union and a comfortable
haven for rich Russian undesirables. This month authorities
detained a former Ukrainian prime minister who entered Switzerland
on a Panamanian passport, and they tried a Russian accused as a
Moscow mob kingpin.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva prosecutors tried Sergei Mikhailov, reputed boss of a
major Moscow mafia family, on charges that he belonged to a
criminal organization. By Swiss standards the eight-day affair was
high-profile, complete with bulletproof vests in court. A former
FBI agent testified that Mikhailov was not the businessman he said
he was, but instead associated with a mafia group that had also
infiltrated the United States.
</P>
<P>
   What was even more disconcerting to some was the fact that
Mikhailov, 40, had settled quietly in a village outside Geneva. He
was living with his wife and two young daughters, and had gone
unnoticed until he was arrested at Geneva's airport. And all this
in a country that keeps careful tabs on foreigners, requiring them
to register and provide a valid reason for living and working here,
then renew the process annually for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   While the trial was going on, Swiss police arrested Ukraine's
former prime minister, Pavlo Lazarenko, who was then indicted on
money-laundering charges. During his leadership, from June 1996 to
June 1997, he was accused of corruption. Ukrainian news
organizations accused Lazarenko, 45, a well-known opposition member
of Parliament, of seeking to withdraw money from secret bank
accounts, but Geneva prosecutors then released him on nearly $3
million bail, which freed him to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, despite dramatic trial testimony, Mikhailov was
acquitted on grounds of insufficient evidence to convict him on
three counts, including unlawfully residing in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had been counting on a conviction, to send Russian
gangsters the message that Switzerland should not be their
preferred destination. A year ago the federal police department
warned that Russian organized crime was making headway here, not
only by stashing cash, but also by buying legitimate businesses and
property.
</P>
<P>
   There are no official figures, but authorities estimate that $40
million to $50 million in Russian capital has ended up in Swiss
banks. Federal police expect fresh figures and details on Russian
money stashes next year, said Folco Galli, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss federal prosecutor, Carla del Ponte, has expressed
concern about ``the penetration of our country's economy by dirty
Russian money.'' Last month she told a local newspaper she was
convinced that current inquiries into Russian mob influence ``were
only the tip of the iceberg.'' She visited Russia last spring to
strengthen ties between Swiss and Russian law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In their annual report last year, federal police noted that it
is simple to transfer money ``from murky sources from the east to
Switzerland.'' Police pointed out that the sheer number of visitors
or short-term residents makes laundering money easier, noting that
the number of visas granted to residents of the former Soviet Union
soared to 70,000 in 1996, from 4,000 in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   To guard against money laundering and support Switzerland's
reputation as a safe haven for funds, a law took effect last April
making it mandatory not only for banks but also for insurance
companies and lawyers to report suspicious transactions. Some
reported so far involved the use of dubious Russian money to set up
companies in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. del Ponte's office also reported that suspicious money has
been used in attempts to start up banks and tourist offices. Her
efforts to track dirty money across borders have been hampered, she
said, by neighboring countries including Germany and France, whose
laws are not as strict as Switzerland's.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Ukraine have both tried to seek out illegal funds
deposited in Switzerland. Last year Russia lodged requests for
legal assistance on 40 cases, Galli said. Ukraine entered 20 such
requests, although Lazarenko's name was not among those listed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland may have a tough time getting rid of unwelcome money
and its owners. Immediately after Mikhailov was acquitted, his
lawyers requested political asylum for him on grounds that he was
in danger in Russia. Swiss officials have yet to rule on that
request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
