<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HILLARY-505&AMP;A     12-19 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HILLARY-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY RENEWS ROLE AS HUSBAND'S DEFENDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-CENSURE,
IMPEACH-DEBATE, IMPEACH-MAVERICKS, IMPEACH-ROLLCALL.) 
(lb) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As defiant as on the day she blamed the Monica
Lewinsky scandal on a ``vast right-wing conspiracy,'' Hillary
Rodham Clinton went to Capitol Hill on Saturday morning and blasted
an unfair, politically motivated impeachment process that she said
the president would continue to fight.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed meeting with House Democrats, Mrs. Clinton said she
was there in part as ``a wife who loves and supports her husband,''
and charged that Republicans were impeaching her husband _
``hounding him out of office,'' she said _ because they opposed his
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said this is as much about ending his agenda on health
care and other things as about hounding him out of office,'' said
Rep. Bob Menendez of New Jersey. ``She said there would be no
resignation and we should not and cannot allow them to hound him
out of office.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is extremely popular among congressional Democrats
_ far more so than her husband _ and came to inoculate him against
the possibility that Democrats could be persuaded that resignation
might be best for the country. Two House Democrats, Rep. Louise
Slaughter of New York and Rep. William Lipinski of Illinois, had
already said they would urge resignation if he were impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was determined and defiant,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler of
New York. ``Her message was that they've been pursuing him since
the day he came into office.''
</P>
<P>
   In what several members called a ``pep rally,'' she thanked
Democrats for their support and asked them to keep it coming,
receiving half a dozen standing ovations. After the meeting,
members stood in line to give her a hug. And as they left, several
House Democrats referred at least obliquely to Mrs. Clinton's own
political prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's probably the most popular person in the country with
Democrats, period, and that's also true of us in the caucus,'' said
Rep. Eliot Engel of New York, where Mrs. Clinton has been mentioned
as someone with the potential to succeed Daniel Patrick Moynihan in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's continued support for her husband has been seen
as crucial to his popularity with the public, cited again and again
by those who say they will stick with him, too, in statements along
the order of ``If Hillary doesn't mind, why should I?'' or ``That's
between him, his God, and Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mrs. Clinton got generous credit for campaigning in
congressional races before the November elections, some Democrats
had still expressed nervousness that she had not offered fresh
support for the president in recent weeks. (Friends said she was
annoyed by the inference: Was she supposed to announce her
continued support every day? Or lobby Republicans who wince at the
mention of her name?)
</P>
<P>
   And her appearance on Saturday, following supportive remarks she
made on Friday, definitively ended a week of speculation that Mrs.
Clinton had decided to distance herself from her husband, in the
hour of his greatest political need, in order to keep her own
options open.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That the Clintons held hands rather less on their recent trip to
Israel than on earlier trips, and that Mrs. Clinton seemed to pull
away from her husband at one moment, were reported on CNN, NBC and
a number of newspapers as evidence that Mrs. Clinton was no longer
on the team. The headline on the page one story that ran in the
Washington Times on Wednesday was ``Hillary shows signs of
relinquishing role as the defender in chief for her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday she said she had come to the Hill as ``a wife
who loves and supports her husband,'' a Judiciary Committee staff
member during Watergate who knows firsthand how the process should
work, and an American who feels proud of the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Members said that the first lady's demeanor had been serious but
that she never stopped smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Kucinich of Ohio said he felt pumped up by the
meeting with Mrs. Clinton: ``It's a campaign all over again. This
needs to be a fight every step of the way, and we're going to wake
the town and tell the people.''
</P>
<P>
   And he suggested that at this late date, the two-for-one
presidency has new life: ``She's so terrific,'' he said. ``It's
lucky for America we have a woman with the strength to lead the
nation right now. And everybody understands she is one of the
leaders of the nation right now, as much as the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
