<HEADER>
A8358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-AUSCHWITZ-ART-     12-19 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-AUSCHWITZ-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLES AND JEWS FEUD ABOUT CROSSES AT AUSCHWITZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSCHWITZ, Poland _ Crosses large and small are mushrooming
outside the Auschwitz death camp, filling a field just beneath its
barbed-wire-topped wall and driving a new wedge between Poles and
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In light wood, in dark wood, some straight, some listing, the
240 crosses have been placed by Catholic zealots over the last five
months. They now form a spreading Christian sea overlooked by a
watchtower of the camp that formed the industrial nexus of the Nazi
attempt to annihilate European Jewry.
</P>
<P>
   The crosses have a self-styled guard, Kazimierz Switon. A former
member of Poland's Solidarity Union, he arrived here on June 14. In
a now squalid tent, he took up residence, declared he had come to
defend Polish soil against the Jews, planted a cross and _ with
conspicuous success _ invited sympathizers to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not tell the Jews what to do in their country, and they
have no right to tell us what to do on our Polish soil,'' said
Switon, 67. ``I will not leave until I have a written assurance
from the church that these crosses which pay tribute to the Polish
victims of Auschwitz will stand forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The adjacent camps of Auschwitz and Birkenau have been at the
center of repeated conflict in recent years as divergent Polish and
Jewish views of World War II have clashed, envenomed by each
people's sense of enormous _ even incomparable _ loss.
</P>
<P>
   But the forthright anti-Jewish oratory of Switon and his
vociferous followers appears to mark an escalation in an atmosphere
clouded by new Polish fears of Jewish claims for restitution of
property lost during the war.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the inability of the center-right Polish
government of Prime Minister Jerzy Burek to remove the crosses _ or
even to stop their proliferation _ has illustrated the enduring
sensitivity of religious and nationalist issues in a deeply
Catholic country still grappling with the divisive legacy of more
than 40 years of Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Switon represents a lunatic fringe, but perhaps not such a
narrow one,'' said Jerzy Ledlicki, a historian. ``The Communists
removed crosses from public places, so to remove a cross today is
to be an enemy of the nation. The government therefore finds itself
in a tight spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Burek has promised several times to remove the crosses, most
recently in a letter to Miles Lerman, chairman of the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Council.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, dated Nov. 30 and made available to The New York
Times, says that ``all new crosses'' will be removed and that ``the
government of Poland is determined to do it as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   However, up to now, as legal battles boil, no attempt has been
made to take the crosses down or to evict Switon. Even the Polish
episcopate's formal condemnation of the new crosses in August has
failed to break the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crosses are deeply offensive,'' said Kalman Sultanik, vice
president of the World Jewish Congress. ``For many Jews, they
symbolize persecution, and 90 percent of those murdered in
Auschwitz-Birkenau by the Germans were Jews. Why can the crosses
not be removed by police, and then let Switon fight the decision in
court if he wants?''
</P>
<P>
   There have been repeated provocative issues in recent years. A
26-foot-high so-called ``papal cross'' erected in 1989 and still
standing at the center of the new crosses, a Catholic convent that
abutted the camp until its Carmelite nuns left in 1993, and the
presence until their removal last year of crosses and Stars of
David near the Birkenau gas chambers have all caused bitter
exchanges between Polish authorities and Jewish groups.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of the friction lie starkly divergent senses of
history. Many people in Poland have the sense that the 3 million
non-Jewish Poles who died during the Nazi occupation, of whom close
to 100,000 were killed at Auschwitz, are somehow invisible to the
Jews because of the scale of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Jews, by contrast, see an unspeakable affront in the placing of
Christian symbols at the place that stood at the heart of the Nazi
extermination program, are troubled by enduring expressions of
anti-Semitism in Poland and point to the fact that more than 1
million of the victims of the Auschwitz-Birkenau complex were Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stop competing over suffering,'' said Wanda
Rapaczinski, a Warsaw newspaper publisher who is Jewish. ``And now,
with these American lawyers combing Europe chasing restitution
money for the Jews, and the fear that Jews may come back to Poland
to claim property, I feel a new tension in the air. The property
issue is explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, until the crosses began spreading, significant progress
appeared to have been made in Polish-Jewish relations through an
ongoing dialogue between the government and several Jewish groups,
including the American Jewish Committee, Yad Vashem and the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum.
</P>
<P>
   In November, under a government commitment to return communal
property to Poland's small remaining Jewish congregations (there
are no more than 20,000 Jews in Poland), three synagogues were
reopened in Wroclaw, Opole and the town of Oswiecim, adjacent to
the Auschwitz camp.
</P>
<P>
   But the spreading Auschwitz crosses have now become a stumbling
block to any further progress. ``The Jewish people want to abuse
us, they want to have power in Poland,'' Switon said, as he gazed
down on the crosses. ``But these Christian symbols show we will not
bow to their blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Switon has found critical local support from a wealthy
real-estate dealer and former Communist security services agent,
Zbigniew Janosz, who has veered from communism to nationalism since
1989, heads an association of Polish war victims and leased the
land on which the crosses now stand from the departing Carmelite
nuns in 1993. His lease runs until 2033.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is a legal one,'' said Agnieszka
Magdziak-Miszewska, the prime minister's special adviser on Jewish
issues. ``We have brought a court case against Janosz, but it could
drag on for a long time. And we cannot violate the laws of
Poland.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears certain that any government attempt to remove the
crosses by force without firm legal backing could provide much
ammunition for Switon's supporters _ essentially radical elements
in the Catholic Church whose mouthpiece is called ``Radio Maria,''
and Polish nationalists increasingly convinced of various Jewish
conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalists were already encouraged earlier this year when
Sultanik of the World Jewish Congress suggested during a visit to
Poland that Auschwitz should be made an ``extra-territorial''
entity to insure respect for the site. That term is explosive in
Poland because Hitler demanded an ``extra-territorial'' road link
from Berlin to Gdansk before invading in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   ``That comment was a disaster because it allowed Switon to
portray himself as a defender of Polish land against the ever
predatory Jews,'' said Mrs. Magdziak-Miszewska. Sultanik later
apologized and said he was misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   The Polish government has now drafted a law to be submitted to
Parliament in the next few weeks that would put all former
concentration and death camps and the land around them in the
control of the state. The law would override all previous property
claims; land would be bought out at market prices.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Magdziak-Miszewska said she expected the law to pass and
provide the basis for a resolution of the Auschwitz problem. ``The
new crosses will go, quite soon,'' she said. ``But the papal cross
is another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Polish officials say privately that the depth of national
feeling about the papal cross, which commemorates a papal Mass at
Auschwitz in 1979, is such that only a public request from the
pope, who is scheduled to visit Poland next summer, could open the
way for its removal.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fate of the 240 new crosses appears certain to be
bitterly contested. ``We gave up the Carmelite church and the Jews
still want more,'' said Witold Urbanski, 68, as he wandered in the
field of crosses. ``Not only Jews died in Auschwitz, and they have
to realize that we Catholics have the same rights as them.''
</P>
<P>
   Switon says the crosses will soon double in number. On many of
them, a slogan is written: ``Only under this cross, only under this
symbol, Poland is Poland and a Pole is a Pole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1346EST &QL; 
