<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DC-LAWSUIT-NYT     12-19 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DC-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA SEEKS ACTION ON SUIT FOR VOTE IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The District of Columbia has requested immediate
action on a lawsuit against the federal government seeking voting
representation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In September, 57 district residents and the district's Office of
Corporation Counsel filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court arguing
that they were being denied their constitutional right to vote in
elections for members of the House of Representatives and the
Senate. The district is represented in Congress by only a nonvoting
member of the House.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel consisting of a federal appeals court judge
and two district court judges was formed last month to hear the
case, but no hearing date was set. In its latest courting filing,
the district asks that the panel immediately rule in its favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a completely intolerable anomaly that must be dealt
with,'' said Eleanor Holmes Norton, the district's delegate in the
House and a constitutional lawyer. ``This is a serious challenge to
the purgatory status of our citizens, and I am focused on
maximizing representation and government. I'll never let up; it is
a clear case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norton noted that district residents voted overwhelmingly
for President Clinton, but were being denied the right to protect
that vote because they have no representative who can cast a ballot
in the House on articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation counsel, John Ferren, is a former judge on the
district of Columbia Court of Appeals who assumed the post last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress impacts community life in the district in myriad
ways,'' Ferren wrote in a 28-page brief filed in U.S. District
Court, ``through its control over the appropriation of local
revenues (which, in turn controls the activities and services of
district government); through its power to override locally enacted
laws, and through its power to legislate directly for the district.
Absent voting representation in Congress for district citizens, the
district as a community is subject to hardships and indignities at
the hands of the national government that no other represented
jurisdiction must endure.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress appointed a financial control board in 1995 to manage
the city's government. It recently passed laws requiring
congressional approval for all capital improvement projects as well
as locally financed health and welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   The district's City Council, encouraged by arguments developed
by Jamin Raskin, a professor of constitutional law at American
University's College of Law in Washington, in March unanimously
passed a resolution supporting litigation that would challenge the
constitutionality of denying voting representation in Congress for
district residents.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, the office of corporation counsel submitted a formal
petition of redress of grievances to Congress, thus invoking the
First Amendment right to petition the federal government for the
500,000 residents of the district.
</P>
<P>
   Congress handed down its response to the petition and to the
lawsuit in October by adopting a rider to the 1998 appropriations
bill prohibiting the district from using its money to pursue voting
representation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The rider, as understood by Ferren, requires lawyers for the
district to work on the lawsuit only outside normal working hours
and without the use of district resources _ no government supplies,
law books, computers, office space or telephones.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington law firm of Covington &AMP; Burling is representing
the district, taking on the considerable work load and costs
involved in developing and presenting the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a substantial legal effort,'' said Thomas Williamson,
a lawyer with Covington &AMP; Burling. ``It addresses the fundamental
right of citizens to be represented in a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting representation in Congress has long been sought by
residents in the district. Early residents of the city voted for
congressional representatives in Maryland and Virginia, from which
the district was carved, but around 1800 the states stopped this
practice, asserting that Congress had the responsibility of
representing the population. In 1875, residents of Washington won
the right to send a nonvoting delegate to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, 150 resolutions for fuller representation have
been introduced and all have failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1347EST &QL; 
