<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALTLAKECITY-NYT     12-19 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALTLAKECITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE CITY AND THE PRESSURE TO BE ACCOMMODATING 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ When this city lost by only four votes to
Nagano, Japan, to play host to the 1998 Winter Olympics, it became
a heavy favorite to win the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City's advantages were plentiful: it would be the
largest city to be host of a Winter Games. Many of its sports
facilities were already under construction. The airport was 15
minutes from downtown, and major highways would carry spectators to
every event in no more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, all the city had to do was protect a big lead.
</P>
<P>
   It did, winning in a landslide, but the manner of Salt Lake
City's victory has become the focus of an investigation into
charges of bribery and corruption that have further damaged the
credibility of an Olympic movement already staggered this year by
an unprecedented series of doping scandals.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City scandal has provided the most unsparing
glimpse yet of the tectonic grinding between purist ideals of the
Olympics and the economic reality that the Winter and Summer Games
are billion-dollar businesses. The 2002 Winter Games have an
operating budget of $1.45 billion and are expected to have an
economic impact of $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The process for obtaining an Olympics has been revealed in
great, troubling detail by the scandal. Attracting the Games
involves far more than simply building stadiums, hotels and
highways. It also involves the providing of lavish gifts and favors
to members of the International Olympic Committee and their
relatives, and the hiring of consultants to make introductions and
assert influence with IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   This process, according to Olympic officials, has frequently
extended beyond expensive wining and dining into a murky area where
the lines are blurred between proper hospitality and improper
inducements.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was the saying in Atlanta? `It's a dirty business, I hope
it all washes out after it's over,''' said John Ruger, a member of
the Salt Lake Olympic organizing committee's board of trustees and
a prominent member of the U.S. Olympic Committee. ``The process
needs to be cleaned up, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting on cities to host the Olympics is the most important
function for many of the IOC's 115 members. When they came to visit
Salt Lake before the 1995 vote that determined the host city for
the 2002 Winter Games, Salt Lake offered such gifts as shotguns and
skis, hunting trips, free medical care and college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Welch, who was president of the bid committee that won the
2002 Winter Games for Salt Lake City, said this courting of IOC
members was part of a necessary, long-established ritual to build
trust and friendship with people of varying cultures and
backgrounds. Salt Lake City spent $14 million in its attempts to
win the 1998 and 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not uncomfortable with the way we handled it,'' Welch
said. ``The process works.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Hodler of Switzerland, the second-most senior member of the
IOC, has another word for Salt Lake City's actions: bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Hodler made incendiary charges that vote-buying
had influenced the selection of Atlanta, Nagano and Salt Lake City
as Olympic cities, as well as Sydney, Australia, which will host
the 2000 Summer Games. Salt Lake officials have acknowledged
spending about $400,000 on scholarships and athletic training for
13 people, including six relatives of IOC members, most from
Africa. They have classified the spending as humanitarian aid, not
bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler has offered only hearsay, not proof, of his claims of
vote-buying, according to Dick Pound, the IOC member from Montreal
charged with investigating the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday night, Pound said that Hodler had
produced no direct evidence to support his contention that Salt
Lake City was the victim of extortion by so-called agents who offer
to deliver blocs of votes for up to $5 million and that as many as
25 IOC members sold their votes in various Olympic-city elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He offered no names, nothing, only what he heard other people
say,'' Pound said of Hodler, who could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in Salt Lake City have expressed shock and anger
upon learning that such extravagant _ some say inappropriate _
services must be performed to attract what is billed as the world's
most unsullied form of sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics have become a business,'' said Ken Bullock, a
populist member of the Salt Lake City organizing committee who has
often said that money spent on limousines would be much better
spent on youth programs. ``They're not about athletes and people.
It's an international business.''
</P>
<P>
   No city was more eager to attract the Olympics than Salt Lake
City. It had been seeking the Winter Games since 1966 as the most
persuasive way to demonstrate that great skiing existed in the
Rockies in places other than Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Because the European vote for 2002 would likely be divided
between Sion, Switzerland, and Ostersund, Sweden, Salt Lake
officials appear to have settled on a strategy of shoring up IOC
votes in Africa and South America. At that time, Africa accounted
for 17 of the IOC's approximately 110 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Favors to African officials included providing free treatment
for hepatitis to Jean-Claude Ganga, an influential IOC member from
Congo Republic, according to The Salt Lake Tribune. Richard
Anderson, a Salt Lake City plastic surgeon, told The Associated
Press that Welch had cajoled him into performing free cosmetic eye
surgery for another unnamed IOC member. Welch did not return a call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to sensationalize this and see it in black and
white, but it's more blurred than that,'' Charlie Battle, who
served as head of international relations for the Atlanta Olympic
organizing committee, said of providing gifts and favors to IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's great pressure to be accommodating,'' Battle said.
``I'm not talking about scholarships or envelopes of money, I'm
talking about being nice. Sometimes, with hospitality, you feel
like you're doing more than is necessary for something like this.
But you feel like you have to be as nice as you can. It's a
competitive situation, and you want to keep hanging in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Under these circumstances, a kind of ethical vertigo can occur,
Battle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you doing this for humanitarian reasons or are you doing
it to sway votes?'' Battle said. ``It becomes difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch said that no one had tried to extort him and that he did
not deal with agents who promised they could deliver votes.
However, the Salt Lake City bid committee paid an Egyptian native
living in Canada, Mahmoud Farnawani, $58,000 for consulting
services in 1994. He told The Toronto Sun in 1995 that he had
``assured'' the Arab vote to Salt Lake officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take this opportunity to clean house and recapture
the ground we hope to occupy,'' Pound said. ``We have to show that
we set a standard of conduct that is high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
