</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONUSES FOR BLOCKERS
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a great athlete and one of the nicest Jets
players, Curtis Martin is something else: a smart man. Why? He
takes care of his linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is continuing a tradition he started when he played for
the New England Patriots, financially rewarding his linemen for
opening up those large holes he rumbles through.
</P>
<P>
   Martin gives each lineman $100 after every game in which he
rushes for at least 100 yards. Before the game against the Buffalo
Bills Saturday, he had seven 100-yard games, which amounted to
$3,500 divided five ways. There is one more regular-season game and
the playoffs still to go, and he may also give the linemen some
sort of other gift at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offensive line is the key,'' Martin said earlier this
season. ``Those guys do a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has had a solid season. Entering the Bills game, he was
fourth in the American Football Conference in both rushing yardage
with 1,146 yards and in rushing touchdowns with eight. He came to
the Jets with a reputation as a player who often got hurt, and
though he missed some time this year with leg injuries, he spent
most of the year on the field and not in the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   What Martin has provided the Jets is an explosive running
threat. If opponents try to stop the passing game, he breaks loose.
If they use eight-man fronts to try and stop him, wide receivers
Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet have big days.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's running and pass blocking have helped quarterback Vinny
Testaverde have a great year. Testaverde had a gaudy quarterback
rating of 128.3 and had thrown 133 consecutive passes coming into
the Bills game without getting sacked. He was the only quarterback
in the NFL who had not thrown an interception on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Although the linemen have done a nice job of pass protecting and
run blocking, none of them will be starters in the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The linemen _ center Kevin Mawae, guards Todd Burger and Matt
O'Dwyer and tackles Jumbo Elliott and Jason Fabini _ enjoy blocking
for Martin because he is sincere in his appreciation of them. But
Martin remains a mystery in the locker room. Few players know him
well because he rarely opens up about himself to teammates. He is
not aloof, but is extremely quiet and private.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some running backs, however, Martin understands that a
handshake, a thank you and a little cash can go a long way.
</P>
<P>
   ON- AND OFF-FIELD REBELLION
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Panthers linebacker Kevin Greene shoved his assistant
coach on the sideline. Pittsburgh Steelers quarterback Kordell
Stewart screamed at Coach Bill Cowher. Ugly, ugly, ugly _ and these
incidents were just from last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans may not realize these kinds of incidents are common,
but most of them are not caught on tape.
</P>
<P>
   A more subtle form of disagreement also occurs: ignoring a play
that is called by the coaches. That happened during the Detroit
Lions' loss to the San Francisco 49ers Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, the Lions' coaches called a play that was
supposed to go to someone other than Herman Moore, the Pro Bowl
wide receiver, who has been frustrated this season by what he
perceives as a reduced role.
</P>
<P>
   Moore did not like the call. While in the huddle, according to
several Lions, Moore told quarterback Frank Reich, who was in for
the injured Charlie Batch, to ignore the called play and simply lob
the ball to him in the end zone. That was what Reich did, and the
Lions scored on a 24-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   Defying a called play would normally anger coaches. But when
Moore went to the sideline, he was congratulated for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   UNION SAVING FOR HARD TIMES
</P>
<P>
   What has made Gene Upshaw a respected union leader among NFL
players is that he is always prepared and a step ahead. That may be
why the union, spurred on by the NBA lockout, is taking steps to
guarantee that its players have a large financial war chest in case
there is labor strife when the collective bargaining agreement
expires in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, there is concern among players and agents that some
of the lower-paid players may be feeling a financial squeeze with
the lockout nearing its 200th day. The football union wants to make
sure at least some money is available for players if they too wind
up in a dispute.
</P>
<P>
   According to agents and union officials, most of the money being
invested for the players is coming from the union's licensing arm,
which earns millions each year from merchandise sales. Some agents
believe that by 2005 the union will have emergency funds of at
least several hundred million dollars, and maybe much more.
</P>
<P>
   Would that be enough to support each player for, say, one year
if there was a strike? Probably not, but it would help ease the
pain and give players some security and leverage.
</P>
<P>
   BRONCO BRAGGING
</P>
<P>
   Were the Denver Broncos too cocky before they lost to the Giants
last weekend? Some Giants believe they were.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are normally chatty, and it is not unusual for them
to talk trash to opponents during a game. That is what happened at
Giants Stadium. Tight end Shannon Sharpe, some Giants have said,
was screaming about how he could not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants took all the talk personally.
</P>
<P>
   Especially quarterback Kent Graham, who played one of the best
games of his career. Late in the final period, Broncos linebacker
Bill Romanowski, never afraid to do or say almost anything on the
field, told Graham to shut up when he was speaking to several
officials about a call. Graham, one of the classiest of players,
lost his temper and yelled a few choice words at Romanowski.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth seemed to energize Graham. Soon after the
exchange, he launched the game-winning bomb to wide receiver Amani
Toomer. Graham got the last word.
</P>
<P>
   AN UNFAIR ADVANTAGE?
</P>
<P>
   One reason the NFL's competition committee rejected instant
replay for the playoffs was because of possible unfairness.
Indianapolis Colts General Manager Bill Polian, among others,
believed coaching staffs who worked with replay when it was in use
from 1986 to 1991 would have had an advantage over the staffs that
did not. . . . Now that Denver quarterback John Elway has his Super
Bowl ring, who would he like to see win one? Miami quarterback Dan
Marino, whom Elway faces tomorrow night. ``If we can't get it this
year,'' Elway said, ``then I'd like to see him win one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
