<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV20 _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ The year is 1977,
when mood rings and platform shoes are hot, and a soft-spoken
president named Jimmy Carter signs two very controversial treaties
with his pistol-packing friend from Panama, Gen. Omar Torrijos. The
treaties are a milestone in U.S.-Latin American relations,
requiring the United States to relinquish control of the Panama
Canal _ long a symbol of American domination and Yankee ingenuity _
to Panama by high noon on Dec. 31, 1999. In 1977, the turn of the
century seemed eons away. But now the sun is finally setting on
this strategic outpost, a presence the United States has enjoyed
for 95 years. But like a husband and wife headed for an amicable
divorce, both sides are suffering a rush of last-minute doubts. In
the United States, there are misgivings over whether Panama, a
small country with no military and only 2.8 million people, can
successfully oversee one of the world's most valuable waterways.
(Emling, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CANAL-HISTORY-$ADV20 _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ A chronology of
events related to Panama and the Panama Canal. (Emling, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-MILITARY-$ADV20 _ BALBOA, Panama _ Sgt. Reginald Thomas
will sorely miss this place, with its barbecues, banyan trees, and
balmy weather. Over the past year, he has rarely ventured beyond
the comfortable confines of the U.S. Army base at Fort Clayton,
just north of this Pacific coastal city. And why should he? The
all-American enclave boasts nightlife, tennis courts, a movie
theater, a bowling alley, appealing housing _ even dirt-cheap boat
rentals. But the base's days are numbered and Thomas must steel
himself, like thousands of other Americans, for relocation to
another U.S. base next year outside of Panama. Under the Panama
Canal treaties signed in 1977, the United States promised a gradual
pullout from Panama, slowly relinquishing pieces of the Canal Zone
_ and eventually the canal itself _ by Dec. 31, 1999. (Emling, Cox
News Service) MOVED WITH
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-RIVALS-$ADV20 _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ With its
money-making ditch, Panama has long been the envy of its neighbors,
particularly Nicaragua. Nearly a century after French engineer
Philippe Bunau-Varilla frantically persuaded the United States to
take over a failed French attempt to build a canal in Panama,
Nicaragua's dreams for a canal of its own still haven't died. And
other countries, too, are offering fresh proposals to challenge the
Panama Canal. But whether any of them fly remains to be seen.
(Emling, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
