<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Hours after becoming the first
president of the 20th century to be impeached by the House,
President Clinton launched a fight to save his administration. In a
statement read at the White House while surrounded by his
Democratic supporters, Clinton was expected to ask the country to
put his misconduct behind it and mend the tears a year of scandal
and partisanship has ripped in the national fabric. (Deans, Cox
News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ Finally, a day for the history
books. It was supreme drama supercharged by shocking news. As if
impeaching a president were not awe-inspiring enough, the House on
Saturday presented the additional spectacles of a speaker-elect
resigning over past adultery, a mass Democratic walkout from the
chamber, and the president's wife making an emotional plea for his
political survival. (Dart, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKER _ WASHINGTON _ House Republicans meet following the
impeachment vote to discuss their leadership. It appears that Rep.
Dennis Hastert of Illinois has the inside track to become the next
speaker. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ Any candidate who wants to win
either major-party presidential nomination in 2000 will have to
raise $22 million to $25 million in 1999, leading campaign finance
experts tell us. That's more than $60,000 a day, 7 days a week. And
that's just the so-called ``hard'' money. Enforcement of federal
limits has become so haphazard that another expert says he can't
even guess at how much unregulated ``soft'' money will be raised
and spent. An explainer of why candidates must raise so much so
early, what the money is spent for, and which candidates are
favored in what pundits call ``the invisible primary.'' (Mollison,
Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
