<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-BAGHDAD-NYT &LR;      12-19 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BAGHDAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS OF BAHGDAD MAINTAIN ROUTINE DESPITE BOMBING ONSLAUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ Soon after the air raid sirens sounded, the
antiaircraft fire began booming Saturday evening from batteries
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Then, evidently in a sign of defiance, a small caravan of cars
drove down the main streets, honking horns, blaring music from
speakers mounted on their roofs and symbolically daring British and
American bombers to hit them.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter jets had reportedly taken off from a base near the
Iraqi border to carry out bombing missions, but by mid-evening none
had been heard over Baghdad and there had been no audible bombing
in or around the capital. The jets may have been striking targets
in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn Saturday, orange explosions lit up the sky over
Baghdad as targets here were hit. The series of explosions lasted
about 15 minutes, and afterward the wail of ambulance sirens could
be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during a daytime lull in the strikes, a somber procession
wound through the city. Cars and taxis bore the white-draped
coffins of 68 people whom the government said had been killed in
the first three nights of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Baghdad mourns 68 martyrs who fell due to the criminal
military action committed against our peaceful country,'' Sultan
al-Shawi, a member of Iraq's National Assembly, told several
hundred people gathered at a square where the procession ended.
</P>
<P>
   The government-controlled Iraqi press continued to call for
solidarity and resolution in the face of bomb attacks. One
newspaper quoted President Saddam Hussein as saying that the
attacks would not force Iraq to ``compromise or kneel.'' Another
reminded Iraqis that they are ``the people of a great
civilization'' and urged them to ``fight and resist the
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, the Iraqi vice president, Taka Yassin
Ramadan, asserted that his country was determined to ``fight until
the last citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you all that Iraq will continue to defend its land,
policy and dignity,'' Ramadan said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that ``the number of martyrs amongst civilians is
tens of times higher than that of military personnel,'' though he
gave no casualty figures. And he bristled at questions about
whether Iraq should take some initiative to end the raids. ``There
are no conditions,'' he said. ``We accept no conditions, and all
that was in the past is behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   For a city facing bombardment by some of the world's most
sophisticated missiles, Baghdad appeared remarkably calm. Auto
traffic was light but uninterrupted, and although most people chose
to remain inside after dark, those who walked the streets did not
seem concerned, even when air raid sirens blared.
</P>
<P>
   Street lights, as well as those in shops and homes, are burning
normally. An enormous statue of President Saddam Hussein in
downtown Baghdad remains brilliantly illuminated, towering more
than 50 feet above a park, an arm stretched high into the air as if
taunting the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe stores, supermarkets and clothing stores were open and
doing business Saturday evening, as were other establishments from
butchers to florists. As two barbers sat sipping tea and awaiting
customers, a young couple leaned against a car parked outside,
talking softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to it by now,'' said a building custodian,
shrugging as he went about his work after air raid sirens sounded
this evening. ``You cannot run away and hide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
