u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERRACE20-COX     12-19 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERRACE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moot or not, interracial marriage still an issue
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Next year's session of the Alabama Legislature may be
outlined in black and white as lawmakers debate whether to repeal a
97-year-old passage in the state constitution that bans interracial
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   While Article IV, Section 102 of the Alabama Constitution lacks
the force of law _ U.S. Supreme Court rulings have held states
cannot establish racial requirements for marriage _ some state
legislators still want the law repealed.
</P>
<P>
   The interracial marriage ban may be the nation's last of its
kind. In November, South Carolina voters agreed to delete a similar
prohibition from their constitution.
</P>
<P>
   When South Carolina's constitution was written in 1895, Gov. Ben
Tillman ran his administration based on the belief that white
people should keep control of state government.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, the current constitution was ratified in 1901. A
constitutional amendment requires a three-fifths vote by the state
House and Senate. It must then be approved by a majority of voters
in a statewide referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn University history Professor Wayne Flynt said the push
for a repeal will be backed by black legislators eager to remove a
symbol of racism and by business leaders who opposed the stubbornly
evangelical Christian stands of outgoing Republican Gov. Fob James.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the business community, not the Legislature, that
pulls the plug on this one,'' Flynt predicted. ``Alabama has been
embarrassed by four years of Jamesism.''
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional passage under scrutiny says, ``The
Legislature shall never pass any law to authorize or legalize any
marriage between any white person and a Negro, or a descendant of a
Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Alvin Holmes, a black Democrat from Montgomery, tried
last session to get the law repealed, but his bill was killed in
committee. He says he'll try again this session and predicts an
easier path after the November defeat of some incumbent
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, known to stir up racial politics in the state House,
helped get the Confederate flag removed from the Alabama Capitol.
In a state ``pregnant with racism,'' and one where only one-quarter
of the state representatives are black, Holmes said ``you have to
use all the pressure tactics you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes called the marriage prohibition ``a symbol of racism.''
He predicted many legislators wouldn't vote against it but
``they'll have to go to the restroom when it comes up for a vote.
That will be the same as voting against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two out of every three people polled by the Alabama
Education Association in November favored removing the ban against
interracial marriages. The survey of 569 registered voters showed
almost one in four respondents wanted the ban left in place.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 131 black poll respondents, 71 percent favored removing
the ban. Of the 405 whites surveyed, 62 percent favored ending the
interracial marriage ban.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Johnson, pollster for the Alabama Education Association,
said it was the first time the group had conducted a poll on
interracial marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect from that,'' Johnson said,
``since we've had such a long history of racial tensions of one
sort or another.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Chris Pringle, a Mobile Republican and former House
minority leader, said he gave Holmes the idea for the bill. ``I
drafted it last session but didn't put it in,'' Pringle said.
</P>
<P>
   Pringle doesn't see a problem with the bill passing out of the
House, and, in fact, may offer his own bill to repeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you defend something that is flagrantly
unconstitutional?'' Pringle said. ``Nearly every legislator I've
seen quoted on this said (a repeal) should be passed.''
</P>
<P>
   One colleague, though, appeared to favor the interracial ban
when first drawn into the debate during a radio interview but has
since clarified his stand.
</P>
<P>
   On the air with WTNM-AM, a Mobile news-talk station, state Rep.
Phil Crigler didn't bring up the topic but responded when asked
about his views on interracial marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``He argued against (interracial marriages) on a personal basis
for himself,'' said Chris Smith, the radio host who interviewed
Crigler. ``He didn't see it as taboo, and he didn't strongly oppose
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crigler, who originally appeared on the station to talk about
the November elections and the push for an Alabama lottery, was
invited back by Smith to clarify his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will support the effort to remove the ban even though it is
a moot point,'' Crigler said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an exercise in futility. What if it fails (in a
referendum)? That doesn't change the legality,'' he said, because
of U.S. Supreme Court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
