<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fall from grace
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Less than two years ago, Dom Capers took a fledgling
franchise to the brink of a Super Bowl, and the Carolina Panthers
coach was the toast of the NFL. Less than two weeks from now,
shortly after the Panthers conclude a season that has been a
disaster on and off the field, Capers instead will be roasted by
owner Jerry Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   The plunge from the penthouse to the outhouse for Capers, a
decent man whose early success raised the bar too high too fast in
Charlotte, is one of the most dramatic falls in the recent history
of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   That it could occur to Capers, a guy so meticulous he has
maintained a leather-bound journal every year of his coaching
career and can detail what he did every hour of every working day,
makes it all the more sobering.
</P>
<P>
   What has occurred since the Panthers lost to the Green Bay
Packers in the conference championship game Jan. 12, 1997, however,
lends a new connotation to the term Carolina Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Not since they defeated Dallas in the '96 NFC semifinal round
have the Panthers beaten a team with a winning record. And since
the middle of the '97 season, Carolina is 5-17 overall, the worst
mark in the NFL during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even watching if from afar, it's painful,'' said Athens native
Willie Green, the wideout who had such a key role in the Panthers'
meteoric rise and now plays in Denver. ``That it could all fall
apart so fast _ no one could have predicted that. From talking to
people there, hearing some things, it sure seems like it's a mess.
Someone will be a fall guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The fall guy will be Capers, given that the perception is he has
lost the respect of his players, as well as too many games. While
he could not have forgotten in two seasons how to coach, it would
take selective amnesia not to find Capers at least partly culpable
for his own demise.
</P>
<P>
   When general manager Bill Polian hied off to Indianapolis in the
spring, Capers demanded and was granted more control over
personnel. In an offseason when Richardson opened his checkbook
wide and set a league record for free-agent spending, Capers
lobbied hard for the acquisitions of defensive end Sean Gilbert and
cornerback Doug Evans.
</P>
<P>
   For their '98 investment of $11 million in Gilbert, the Panthers
have gotten 47 tackles and four sacks. Playing against Washington
last week, his previous employer and a club he harbors a grudge
against, Gilbert had zero tackles. Evans earned $9.5 million this
season, surrendered seven touchdown passes, had two interceptions,
then went on injured reserve at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, quarterback Kerry Collins decided that it wasn't
finer to be in Carolina. Tailback Fred Lane was suspended for a
game after making an obscene gesture to New York Jets fans.
Linebacker Kevin Greene tried to choke assistant coach Kevin
Steele.
</P>
<P>
   In a confrontation last Sunday that somehow escaped the cameras,
Winslow Oliver and special-teams coach Brad Seely had a heated
exchange on the sideline. That came after a holding penalty by
Oliver nullified a 97-yard kickoff return for a score by Michael
Bates. When it was suggested to Bates that the Panthers suddenly
looked like a team bankrupt of discipline, he indicted Capers,
saying, ``And where does that start?''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, there has been a disquieting unrest in the
Carolina locker room and, far worse, an apparent schism along
racial lines. Cornerback Eric Davis, one of the team's leaders and
normally a standup guy, claimed he had ``no opinion'' when asked if
Capers should be retained.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the Panthers were being hailed as the model franchise, a
paradigm for success that was the envy of long-suffering Atlanta
fans. Two years later, the Falcons are into the playoffs, and
Carolina is into the dumper. ``It can be,'' former Carolina safety
Pat Terrell said, ``a cruel league.''
</P>
<P>
   Dom Capers will second that motion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
