<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITS-GATECH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defense is Tech's biggest recruiting need
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a little more than six weeks left until national
signing day, Georgia Tech will use its final 10 football
scholarships to go after some of the top athletes in the South.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yellow Jackets are looking mainly at defense, as they
try to bring in the best recruiting class yet under fifth-year
coach George O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 commitments so far, recruiting analyst Jamie Newberg of
Border Wars magazine says Tech is well on its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're really doing well, especially in-state,''
Newberg said. ``(Pepperell running back) Sidney Ford is a great
player. (Stone Mountain defensive end) Leslie Williams is the best
commitment thus far, for the fact that they need defensive linemen.
That will be the key to the end of their class.''
</P>
<P>
   Two scholarships will count toward last year's total, O'Leary
said, so the Yellow Jackets can sign 27 players on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about needs to be filled, O'Leary mentioned tight
end first. ``They're all still out there (uncommitted),'' he said.
``A number of them are set for visits. Defensive end is still a
concern. We'd like to bring in another offensive lineman, a couple
defensive backs, linebackers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets are itching to get tight end Gary Godsey,
Tech backup quarterback George Godsey's younger brother, a 6-2,
245-pounder out of Jesuit High in Tampa. But if Godsey chooses Ohio
State or Notre Dame, then Eran Landry of Pass Christian (Miss.)
High is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   If Tech is able to sign the defensive linemen all giving Tech
serious consideration, the Yellow Jackets can feel good about
filling their most critical need, Newberg said. They are Campbell's
Shomari Chism, Greg Gathers out of East St. John's High (La.) and
Marist's Hugh Reilly, whom Newberg considers widely underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   The top defensive backs Tech has a good shot at, Newberg said,
include Parkview's Jeremy Muyres, who's brother Jon Muyres is a
receiver at Tech, and Cory Collins from Egg Harbor Township (NJ).
</P>
<P>
   Tech needs another kicker/punter in addition to Walton's Phillip
Newman, who has committed, and is eyeing Nick Setta of Lockport
(Ill.) Township High.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets are still in the running for Washington
quarterback Latrez Harrison, who is deciding between Tech and
Auburn, and Willie Simmons of Shanks (Fla.) High. To land either or
both of those, Newberg said would be ``icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech had 18 recruits on campus this weekend and expects another
18 the weekend of Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're well on our way to filling our needs,'' O'Leary said,
``but there are a lot of good players still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's accomplishments on the field this season should make
getting them easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, they've got in the final stages with some of the
special kids and lost them,'' Newberg said. ``When you go 9-2, beat
Georgia and make it to a major bowl to play Notre Dame, and
probably beat Notre Dame, that helps you. This year, they'll get
those kids instead of just missing out.''
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA TECH COMMITMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Name Pos. Ht. Wt. Hometown (High school)
</P>
<P>
   John Bennett OL 6-5 275 Woodstock (Etowah)
</P>
