<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITS-UGA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Running backs top Bulldogs' wish list
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ With more than a month to the national signing day
for college football, Georgia already has 17 commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs seem to have addressed two of their concerns _
secondary and wide receivers. But Georgia coach Jim Donnan still is
courting several players at his biggest need _ running back.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrange High running back Bruce Thornton, a preseason Super 11
choice by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, remains near the top of
Georgia's list. Thornton, 6-feet-2, 185 pounds, has scheduled four
official visits during January_ Georgia, Notre Dame, Florida and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Derrick Watson of Palmetto High in Williamston, S.C.,
the state's player of the year, also will visit Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who rushed for 2,534 yards and 44 touchdowns as a
senior, says he is wide open among Georgia, Tennessee, South
Carolina and Clemson. Watson has scheduled official visits to all
four schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs also are involved with Nick Maddox of A.L. Brown
High in Kannapolis, N.C., rated the No. 3 running back nationally
by SuperPrep. Maddox reportedly has Florida State, Florida and
Tennessee as his favorites, followed by Georgia and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia also is recruiting tailback Michael McConnell of
Adairsville, who reneged on a commitment to Michigan State, and
Shaud Williams of Andrews, Texas, who favors Texas Tech and the
Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville's DeJuan Green and Arkansas' Cedric Cobbs also are
possibilities for the Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan got four commitments after Georgia's biggest recruiting
weekend so far. Defensive backs Dantra Clements of East Coweta High
and Stanford Simmons of Hargrave Military in Virginia, wideout
Damien Gary of Clarke Central High and defensive end Johnathan
Sullivan of Griffin all chose the Dogs last week.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, a 6-foot-1, 195-pound cornerback, was a Parade
All-American in 1996 at Clay County High in Ashland, Ala. He signed
with Auburn each of the last two years but enrolled at Hargrave
after failing to academically qualify. Simmons is expected to
enroll at Georgia in January, along with former Carrollton
defensive back Jamie Henderson. Both could be eligible to
participate in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Edwards of Washington County and Reagan Torbert of
Peach County, both of whom signed with Georgia last February, also
are scheduled to enroll in January. Edwards already has joined the
Bulldogs' basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a 6-foot-4, 270-pound Super 11 choice, was perhaps the
state's most dominating lineman this season. He had 50 tackles, 47
assists and 13 sacks, leading Griffin to an 8-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good as advertised,'' LaGrange coach Steve Pardue
said. ``He could play for any team in the state right now, and that
includes Georgia Tech, Georgia and the Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA COMMITMENTS
</P>
