<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBACOLUMN20-COX     12-19 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBACOLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courting stress, NBA coaches get off lucky
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Falcons coach Dan Reeves underwent coronary
bypass surgery Monday, the news jolted his peers in the NFL and
sent a reminder to all the NBA coaches who are chafing to return to
the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Beware, the message said, stress can kill you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at what they do in football and, if anything, we have
more of it,'' the Hawks' Lenny Wilkens said. ``Maybe it helps that
we don't dwell on one game because there's always another one
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd have to say that as a group we've been very fortunate.
Thank God. I know the coaches in our sport are in pretty good
shape, but still we've been very fortunate it hasn't happened as
often with us as it seems in football.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few cases of heart trouble. Bill Fitch had
open-heart surgery during his tenure with the Los Angeles Clippers,
and Scottie Robertson and Johnny Bach had problems while working as
assistants. But NBA coaches have remained remarkably healthy given
the pace of the game on the court and the rigors of travel with
back-to-backs and sets of four games in five nights that require
irregular eating and sleeping patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said he learned to manage stress after being
hospitalized with a life-threatening blood clot following surgery
on his Achilles' tendon when he was in Cleveland in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clot had nothing to do with my overall health, but it made
me realize how vulnerable you can be,'' he said. ``When that
happened I came to realize that even though I will work as hard as
I can to get the job done, at the end of the day I've got to turn
things loose. That was a wake-up and it had nothing to do with
coaching, but something like that makes your realize your own
mortality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock says, ``I think coaching in
any sport at any level is stressful. But the stress in professional
sports is all relative. Real stress is having to pay the utility
bill, having to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks still generous
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when Hawks players would make a number
appearances on behalf of children. With the lockout in force, the
team's staff is picking up the slack. Babcock, Wilkens and others
will appear at CASA Kids, 52 Avondale Road, at noon today. Monday
evening, the staff will be hosts at Jocks and Jills, CNN Center,
for children of the Grace Home of Waiting Children of Georgia.
Wilkens will read ``Twas the Night Before Christmas.'' Tuesday
afternoon, the staff will make its annual visit to Scottish Rite
Children's Medical Center on Johnson Ferry Road. ... On Monday, the
Hawks will announce their gift of 2,300 uniforms to the city's 170
youth basketball teams. The scheduled Dec. 12 start of city leagues
for girls and boys was delayed by the city's dispute with a
sporting goods company.
</P>
<P>
   They also talk a lot
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardaway ripped Miami teammate Alonzo Mourning and the
Knicks' Patrick Ewing after they begged public sympathy by saying,
sure, NBA players make a lot of money, but they also spend a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have a gag order on some of our players,'' Hardaway
said. ``Some people are not saying the correct things. They're
blah, blah, blahing this out and that out and, man. ... They should
be quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Needy NBA players?
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams said he refused to be part of Saturday's
exhibition in Atlantic City until the players removed themselves
from the proceeds, belatedly agreeing to give all the money to
UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 5 percent of America makes $275,000 a year,'' Williams
noted. ``If you mismanage your money, you get a job. I'm not going
to hold a game for somebody making $275,000. For `needy' NBA
players? There's no such thing. When I found out (proceeds were)
going to charity, my marketing firm said OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has to wait
</P>
<P>
   It appears Antoine Walker will stay with the Celtics, because
his $100million contract demand will be stymied by any new working
agreement. When Walker hits the market next summer, the league says
the cap will be at $35million per team and a player with 0-to-six
years experience will be able to max out at an average of about
$11million per year for the six, with a 10 percent raise for the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlo on employees
</P>
<P>
   Former Hawk Craig Ehlo, who retired last season after 14 years
in the league, said current players have lost all proper
perspective of the game. ``I think the thing that we had going for
us was we understood that we were still an employee of an
employer,'' Ehlo said. ``I think they've lost that now. The players
think because of the way salaries are that they are the show. We
understood that there was an owner who put up all the risk for us
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
