<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hockey's huge deals go bust
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The number of $5 million-a-year NHL players doubled
this season from seven to 14. The average salary has jumped to $1.2
million _ from $271,000 in 1990-91. And Detroit forward Sergei
Federov ($14 million) earns more than the entire roster of the
expansion Nashville Predators ($13.6 million).
</P>
<P>
   As we enter the holiday season, several NHL executives are
learning the hard way that you can get burned for paying full
retail.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Blackhawks, who aren't close to competing for a
Stanley Cup, gave unrestricted free-agent forward Doug Gilmour a
three-year contract worth $18million. Through 29 games, Gilmour had
grossed $2,121,951, scored three goals and netted a rating of
minus-14.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other fizzled investments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Los Angeles, needing an offense-minded defenseman, gave Steve
Duchesne a three-year, $11.25million deal. Result: one goal, eight
assists.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Jose guaranteed defenseman Gary Suter $10million over
three seasons. The return has been one game and a torn triceps
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brett Hull, who signed for $17million over three years with
Dallas, has missed nine games because of injuries, pouted at times
over not getting enough ice time and scored eight goals and 17
points in 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carolina, which made a run at Federov last year, only to have
the Red Wings match the offer, this year settled on Pittsburgh
free-agent center Ron Francis for a staggering $20.8million over
four seasons. But Francis, who doesn't have nearly the supporting
cast with the Hurricanes that he did in Pittsburgh, has managed
only five goals and a rating of minus-seven in 29 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Toronto Maple Leafs can't complain about the four-year,
$24million deal they threw at goalie Curtis Joseph. Or can they?
Through 23 starts, Joseph was 12-9-2 with one shutout, a 2.64
goals-against average and .903 saves percentage. But Carolina
goalie Arturs Irbe, the free-agent bargain of the millennium at
$550,000, is 9-7-3 with three shutouts, a 1.95 GAA and .932 saves
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a risk signing one of these guys,'' Los Angeles
general manager Dave Taylor said. ``The majority of these players
don't reach unrestricted status until they're 31, 32, 33. And in
order to get these guys, you have to overpay, and you put too many
years on the contract, so you pay for it down the road. There's
competition for them, and teams feel if they don't sign one they're
going to fall behind.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL players cannot become unrestricted, or Group III, free
agents until they are 31 or have 10 years experience.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell agreed that ``age becomes
a big factor'' when pursuing unrestricted free agents, although he
doesn't support the contention of some that veterans let up after
landing a major deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like after they sign a contract that there's a lack
of effort,'' Waddell said. ``But there's so few real top guys who
become unrestricted free agents that they get a lot of attention.
Consequently, they make a lot of money, and the expectation level
is very high, maybe higher than it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing a goalie tends to be less risky, because they mature
later in their careers. Conversely, Gilmour is 35, missed 18 games
last year in New Jersey and has seen his production tail off. This
year, he plays for a team that can't get out of last place, despite
the presence of the NHL's top goal scorer, Tony Amonte.
</P>
<P>
   Amonte said he thinks ``it's been tough'' for Gilmore to live up
to the contract, although he added, ``I do think he's helped our
power play. We needed another centerman. His points are down a
little bit from when he was in his heyday in Toronto and Calgary.
But it's not just up to him. He has linemates and teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the results with Duchesne ``have not been what we
expected,'' but he attributed the player's struggles in part to the
absence of his defense partner Rob Blake, who has been injured most
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Next season's likely unrestricted free agents include goalies
Patrick Roy (Colorado) and Guy Hebert (Anaheim), forwards Theo
Fleury (Calgary) and Pat Verbeek (Dallas) and defenseman Brian
Leetch (N.Y. Rangers).
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will be marked down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
