A8438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLEAST20-COX     12-19 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Devils' good fortune starting to irk Gretzky
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Gretzky of the Rangers is starting to become
irritated with the New Jersey Devils' success this season, and for
good reason. When the Devils dumped their border rivals 6-3 the
other night, it extended their unbeaten streak over New York to 12
games (8-0-4). New Jersey also was unbeaten in eight overall
(6-0-2) going into Montreal on Saturday and was averaging 5.6 goals
per game in the previous five. This team used to be the master of
the 2-1 win under coach Jacques Lemaire but has become more wide
open under Robbie Ftorek. Goalie Martin Brodeur is not having a
great year, but says, ``I think I felt sorrier for myself when we
were only scoring one goal.'' Gretzky calls the Devils ``a good
team,'' but he did not want to go overboard in his praise.
``They're a solid team, the team we're all chasing at this point,''
he said. ``But I've been in this game a long time, and I've yet to
see a team win the Stanley Cup in December.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   This must go down as one of the all-time U-turns in the history
of negotiating contracts. Ziggy Palffy, a three-time 40-goal
scorer, finally came to terms with the New York Islanders on a
five-year, $24.8 million contract. He signed the deal just hours
before he was about to sign with a team in Slovakia. After coming
to terms, Palffy denied his comments from the week before, when he
said he would never play for the Islanders again and now wanted to
play for the Rangers. ``I always wanted to be a New York
Islander,'' he said. ``I want to make it clear that I didn't say I
wanted to be a New York Ranger. I said I wanted to beat the
Rangers.'' What Palffy really wanted, and received, is a $1 million
signing bonus and base salaries escalating from $3 million to $6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.:
</P>
<P>
   Felix Potvin remained a goalie without a team after trade talks
broke down between Toronto and Tampa Bay. The Lightning, which was
offering forward Mikael Renberg, gave up on the deal and sent
Renberg to Philadelphia, where he started his career. Renberg has
been reunited with linemates Eric Lindros and John LeClair. ...
Scalpers reportedly are getting as much as $3,500 for a ticket to
the final game at Maple Leaf Gardens, Feb. 13. Toronto is moving
into the new Air Canada Centre the following week. ... Although the
Southeast Division, future home of the Thrashers, remains weak,
Carolina went 6-1-2 after a 8-10-3 start to expand its first-place
lead over Florida. The streak included consecutive 3-0 wins over
Detroit and Edmonton. ... Nobody else has to say the Florida
Panthers are underachieving. Team captain Scott Mellanby will say
it for them. ``What we've got now is some guys who have to realize
that their skill isn't enough. You've got to work your tail off in
this league to score.'' ... Poor Washington. Already wracked by
injuries, the Capitals learned left wing Chris Simon will require
shoulder surgery, sidelining him for the season.
</P>
