<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The last laugh rests with Chicago's Amonte
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chicago forward Tony Amonte would like to believe it's
kismet that he's having one of his best seasons the same year
Vancouver coach Mike Keenan is desperate for a scorer. Amonte, who
scored a league-high 21 goals in the Blackhawks' first 29 games,
began his career with the New York Rangers and played for Keenan in
the 1993-94 season. But the two often feuded and Amonte was traded
in March of that year, missing the Rangers' Stanley Cup run. Amonte
had two 30-goal seasons before Keenan's arrival and scored 31, 41
and 31 in the last three years with the Blackhawks. But under
Keenan, he scored only 16 in 72 games. Keenan's Canucks are
averaging 2.8 goals per game. ``He didn't like me very much and I
didn't like him,'' Amonte said last week. ``I still don't like him.
He said (the trade) was just business at the time. He said I wasn't
any help to the club, and he had me believing I wasn't any help.
But as Mike Keenan says, that's life and life's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   No deal
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Keenan, his continued attempts to pressure general
manager Brian Burke into trading the rights to holdout Pavel Bure
have gone for naught. Los Angeles general manager Dave Taylor, who
resisted making trades and dealing young talent during the Kings'
awful start, said, ``We're not dealing with (Vancouver). I don't
expect anything to happen with Bure.'' The Kings and Rangers, two
big-market teams looking for scoring help, were believed to be the
likely candidates for a trade. The Rangers recently swung a trade
with Pittsburgh for another holdout, Petr Nedved, and might not be
as desperate. Bure, meanwhile, is spending Christmas in Moscow. His
current contract technically expires after this season, but agent
Mike Gillis can forget about any thoughts of claiming that his
client is an unrestricted free agent should Bure sit out the entire
year. Burke said he has been assured by league officials that Bure
would still owe the team one year. ``But I don't expect it to come
to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the eight wingers for the Dallas Stars are
right-handed, and some players have had difficulty getting shots
off in recent games. It remains to be seen if the situation will
require a trade a become a problem in the second half and during
the playoffs. ``The angles they approach passes and their
forechecks are different,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It's a big
adjustment, and it takes a smart player to play there.'' ...
Phoenix finally might be ready to land. After a 17-3-4 start, the
Coyotes were winless in their last three games, went 0-13 on the
power play during a four-game trip and lost center Keith Tkachuk to
a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
