<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTANDING THE INDEX FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Resending; please ignore any other file bearing this
slug.)  
 (For release Sunday, December 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. You mentioned that the average domestic stock fund had a
year-to-date gain of only 6.5 percent. This seems rather low. I
have one fund, Oppenheimer Growth, Class A, which has had a
year-to-date gain of only 7 percent and I consider that poor
performance. My other equity mutual funds range from 7.85 percent
to 26 percent year-to-date gains. Our total portfolio, which
includes several professionally managed investment accounts, has a
year-to-date gain of 15.3 percent, with an allocation of 62.6
percent in stocks, 30 percent in bonds and the rest in cash
equivalents. Since the stocks are mostly large cap companies and
the Standard and Poor's 500 has a year-to-date gain of 21.26
percent, this seems like a reasonable gain. So if the average
domestic stock fund has gained only 6.5 percent this year, I would
consider the average fund poorly managed. Is this correct?
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, things have improved a bit since I wrote that, with the
average domestic stock fund having a 7.20 percent year-to-date gain
as of Dec. 10. But when you look at such figures, you should
remember that many of the funds that go into the calculation are
required by their charters to operate in market segments that are
currently unpopular. Thus while growth funds showed the highest
year-to-date average, at 14.22 percent, the figure for all domestic
stock funds was dragged down by the 7.59 percent average loss for
small company growth funds, and the meager 2.65 percent gain for
mid-cap funds.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these statistical glitches, your point is well taken,
and it goes far to explain the mushroom popularity of index funds.
A lot of apologists for the mutual fund industry have spent a lot
of time explaining that the terrific performance of the big index
funds in the past few years will probably prove an anomaly over the
longer run -- that the past few years have seen the large-cap
stocks that dominate the indexes move ahead almost in lockstep,
thus driving the index funds to their strong results. I think this
is a reasonable argument to explain the dramatic outperformance of
the last three years, when the average domestic stock fund produced
average annual returns of 16.19 percent, compared to 25.98 percent
for the Standard and Poor's 500 Index. But note also that if you go
back a full decade, the average annual figure posted for the
average domestic stock fund was 14.34 percent, which compares to
17.87 percent for the S&AMP;P 500 (and 17.70 percent for the largest
S&AMP;P fund, Vanguard Index 500). Perhaps something in the
neighborhood of half of the difference between the S&AMP;P 500 results
and those of the average domestic stock fund can be ascribed to the
fees and expenses which mutual fund owners bear. An additional part
of the variance can, as above, be tied to results of some funds
which are required to be in a particular market segment, no matter
how unpopular it is. But in the end, I'm afraid, there's yet
another element, which is that some mutual fund managers seem to
try too hard; the competition for the investor's dollars lead some
mutual fund managers to turn their portfolios too often, and to
take some short-term risks, attempting to bump their star ratings
from Morningstar Mutual Funds. Morningstar, which supplied the
long-term figures I cited above, no longer uses categories such as
aggressive growth or capital appreciation. But Lipper Analytical
Services Inc. still uses the Capital Appreciation category to
denote funds which take the most aggressive investment stance. As
of Lipper's report of Dec. 3, for the last five years the Capital
Appreciation group average showed a 97.76 percent gain. In the more
sedate growth group, the average total return was 124.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But to complete the tortoise-and-hare portrait, in those same
five years the average growth and income fund posted 125.34 percent
returns, while the average S&AMP;P 500 fund posted a 171.57 percent
total return. During those five years, only the Science and
Technology and Financial Services segments topped those of the S&AMP;P
index funds, with figures of 178.16 percent and 177.95 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   So I think the answer to your question takes two parts. One,
obviously, is that you and your advisors have done a good job of
building your portfolio. But it also seems true that the portfolio
has been at the right place at the right time -- and if you don't
change your investment mix as the market focuses change, ultimately
the markets will focus in other segments than the large caps, and
you'll find the comparative results less attractive than you do
now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In September of 1997 my son invested an IRA account of
$90,000 in Vanguard funds, with 50 percent in Vanguard Index Value,
20 percent in Vanguard Specialized Health Care, and 15 percent each
in Vanguard International Growth and Vanguard International Value.
This IRA will have 23 years before he must make his initial minimum
withdrawal. While I am satisfied with the composition of the funds,
I wonder if he wouldn't be better off by using something more
aggressive -- such as Vanguard Index 500 or Vanguard Index Growth
-- instead of Index Value.
</P>
<P>
   H.N., Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, if your son were required to maintain the same
portfolio for 23 years, I would be inclined to agree with you. But
while I've never been much of a believer in market timing, I do
like the idea of periodically switching among Vanguard's three
funds that track the Standard and Poor's 500 Index and its subsets.
If you are willing to look at broad market trends and are confident
in your judgment of the status of market trends, you might decide
that you will hold Index 500 in a neutral market, use Index Growth
in a market with low PEs and high dividends, and use Index Value
when stocks are expensive and dividends low. If you're going to use
this approach, I don't advocate frequent switches, but rather
setting a schedule that requires a reassessment of the portfolio
allocation no more than once a year -- and perhaps even once every
other year.
</P>
<P>
   If your son were to adopt such a strategy, I think the current
market fully justifies holding the position in Index Value, so I
would make no change there right now -- or for the foreseeable
future.
</P>
<P>
   But I would suggest one fairly minor change. To achieve broader
market diversification, why not suggest your son reduce the
positions in International Growth and International Value by 5
percent each, putting the proceeds of those sales into Vanguard's
Small Cap Index fund?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
