<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFCNOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami hot for back
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson bypassed Randy Moss this
year because of off-field concerns, but his need for a big,
every-down tailback might force him to take a chance in the '99
draft. One player Miami scouts are monitoring closely is tailback
Cecil Collins, who over the last two seasons has been booted out of
LSU and McNeese State, played in only six games, undergone knee
surgery and tested positive for drugs. Collins, who had a great
season in '96 after replacing injured Kevin Faulk, currently is in
a halfway house in Baton Rouge. If ``The Diesel'' gets his life on
track, he will be a first-round choice. Blesto Scouting, which
assesses players for 12 teams, rates Collins the top player
available. The rest of the top five prospects, excluding
underclassmen: WR Torry Holt (North Carolina State), FB Ron Konrad
(Syrcuse), RB Ricky Williams (Texas) and QB Daunte Culpepper
(Central Florida). The Dolphins still like incumbents Karim
Abdul-Jabbar and John Avery, but short-yardage problems convinced
Johnson and coordinator Kippy Brown to get a bigger back.
</P>
<P>
   Back for more
</P>
<P>
   As predicted here last week, San Diego owner Alex Spanos granted
GM Bobby Beathard a two-year contract extension late Thursday
night. That move ensures the team will not pursue Green Bay's Mike
Holmgren and suggests San Diego will replace June Jones with a
college coach. Beathard desperately wants to retain the current
defensive staff _ Joe Pascale (coordinator), Wayne Nunnely (line),
Jim Vechiarella (linebackers) and Rod Perry (secondary) _ along
with offensive line coach Joe Bugel. Word is that Bugel has
informed Beathard he won't stick around if another Kevin
Gilbride-type is hired.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers stalled
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Bill Cowher's public criticism last week of
quarterback Kordell Stewart comes word the Pittsburgh coach has
been just as harsh in private with his first-year offensive
coordinator, Ray Sherman. The classy Sherman has been under
scrutiny since replacing Chan Gailey and he's had a tough year
trying to learn the offense, formulate game plans and refine
Stewart's techniques. Sherman has attempted to afford Stewart more
input into planning, seeking preferences for third-down calls, but
gotten nowhere with the young signal-caller. Stewart's ``crying
game'' last week, after being replaced by Mike Tomczak, could force
GM Tom Donahoe to seek an alternative. The team is said to be
enamored of UCLA's Cade McNown as a second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Miami vice
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins are apoplectic at having only one defender selected
to the AFC Pro Bowl squad. Coordinator George Hill is incredulous
that one player was tackle Tim Bowens. Scouts feel the Dolphins'
other tackle, Daryl Gardener, was superior. The selection earns
Bowens a $500,000 salary increase for '99, which doesn't thrill
Jimmy Johnson. The team feels middle linebacker Zach Thomas along
with cornerbacks Terrell Buckley and Sam Madison merited more
consideration. Free safety Brock Marion now has played 40 straight
games without an interception.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis leaving the building
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Kansas City quarterback Elvis Grbac winds
up in Cleveland in '99, reunited with fellow former 49ers Carmen
Policy and Dwight Clark. The Chiefs seem to be more sold now on
quarterback Rich Gannon, a potential free agent, and quietly have
talked to him about an extension. Dumping Grbac could save them as
much as $2 million on next year's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Etc
</P>
<P>
   Since corner Eric Allen was injured Nov. 15, the Oakland defense
has gone 18 quarters without an interception.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
