A8447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BOBBYROSS20-COX     12-19 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BOBBYROSS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite disappointing season, Bobby Ross' zeal to win burns in
Detroit
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Because the public persona reflects the gentility of
his Southern upbringing, the discipline of military education and
the rectitude of a church-goin' man whose Sunday mornings still
mean as much to him as his Sunday afternoons, Bobby Ross isn't
about to curse the darkness of the Detroit Lions soulless 1998
season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, unless Ross is operating in the
what-is-said-here-stays-here sanctuary of the locker room, the man
who led Georgia Tech to a share of the national title in 1990 isn't
about to curse at all. Ever in character, he will mumble the
trademark ``dad-gummed'' or ``gosh-dang'' for the benefit of
minicam jockeys paid to document the fact the man possesses passion
as well as a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   But if his guards have let him down this season (as have his
tackles and wide receivers and players at just about every other
position), Ross isn't about to let down his guard. The emotions
which so often and so obviously have simmered below the surface
after inexplicably shabby performances have yet to fully erupt for
public consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a time bomb ticking inside of him,'' said
defensive end Robert Porcher late last week, ``but it's only going
to blow up in front of us. Lately, you might have to say the
explosions resemble the last few nights in Baghdad. Given the
situation, they're justified. He's pretty (angry) and he's got a
right to be. I mean, it wasn't supposed to be this way, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the Lions host the Atlanta Falcons this afternoon,
the matchup has a definite role reversal feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   The people who sign Ross' paychecks, of course, moonlight by
building Ford trucks and automobiles. But instead of wheeling
around in an F-Series pickup in '98, the coach has been driving a
rusty old Edsel with a faulty transmission. Atlanta, conversely,
has traded in its Yugo traditions for a shiny stretch limousine.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, some will claim, is that Ross might have been
piloting this Falcons joy ride had he opted to return to the city
where he led one of the college game's best turnarounds of the past
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, when Ross and Falcons president Taylor Smith led
local media on a wild goose chase around the city in January of
'97, both men knew the courtship was merely a facade. Smith had all
but committed to Dan Reeves and Ross already had a handshake deal
with Lions owner William Clay Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ross may have conducted a mental inventory of the Falcons and,
as some front-office people from both sides suggested, decided the
club's talent did not compare favorably to that on the Detroit
assembly line. The prospect of trying to recreate the miracle of
The Flats in the precinct of Suwanee, though, never was seriously
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years later, neither regrets the staged mating dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both knew where things were headed,'' Ross said recently.
``Because of my respect for the Smith Family, and I'd like to think
their respect for me, we owed it to each other just to get
together. I'm sure they're thrilled with the way things turned out
and I'm happy for them. This is where I wanted to be and I'll never
second-guess myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly since his early-season switch of quarterbacks, from
nine-year veteran Scott Mitchell to rookie Charlie Batch, the fans,
some players and the media all have handled those second-guessing
chores for him.
</P>
<P>
   By his third season in San Diego (1994), Ross had taken a team
to the Super Bowl and similar results were expected with the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   Now some wonder if he'll survive more than three years with
Detroit, a team whose stars are on the downside of their careers.
The urgency expressed by veterans such as tailback Barry Sanders
and wide receiver Herman Moore hasn't carried over to the rest of
Ross' team and he has become the target for a group of players who
fear that their chances for winning a championship are running out.
</P>
<P>
   His critics emphasize that Ross, who was brought in to win
immediately, suddenly is enamored with rebuilding the club around
Batch and a younger talent pool that includes wideouts Johnnie
Morton and Germane Crowell, guard Jeff Harting, linebacker Stephen
Boyd, free safety Ron Rice and corners Bryant Westbrook, Terry Fair
and Kevin Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Team vice chairman William Clay Ford Jr. debunks the notion that
Ross' direction for the franchise has changed or that he has worn
on his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to win this year, next year, every year,'' Ford said.
``That's all that drives the man. It's all he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   With two games remaining this year, the Lions are just 14-16
(counting a '97 playoff defeat) under Ross' stewardship. Last
season's 9-7 performance was supposed to be a starting point and
not a high-water mark. Should the Lions drop both games left on the
schedule, this season would tie for the franchise's worst
performance since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Already the year represents an NFL low for Ross, who in six
previous pro campaigns never finished worse than .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I despise (losing),'' Ross said when asked how he has
reconciled this season. ``The grass doesn't look green, the sun
doesn't shine, all those things. It's bad. It's ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the notorious workaholic has extended his
already-torturous regimen. Ross has privately questioned his team's
heart, charged some with playing only for the paycheck following
one lethargic defeat, jabbed at the veteran leadership, cajoled and
criticized and juggled. The consummate coach has pored over hours
of videotape and, as is his wont, reviewed the schemes on both
sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The results, unfortunately, are hardly reflective of his efforts
and last Monday's loss at San Francisco was an embarrassment in
which it appeared the Lions had quit on him. In the wake of that
defeat some old charges that were raised in San Diego _ that Ross
is a coach eventually tuned out by his players _ again resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have switched to a different frequency, Ross allowed,
will find themselves in a different city next year. The turnaround
for the Lions, he said, begins today.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last two games are about establishing character,'' said
Ross, a man eminently familiar with that coveted commodity. ``All
of us, me included, are going to find out what we're all about
here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
