<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Raising the ante for Washington ownership
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The battle for ownership of the Washington Redskins
heated up last Wednesday when New York banker Howard Milstein and
Bethesda, Md., businessman Daniel Snyder bid a whopping $720
million for the club. That bid, which is 36 percent more than Al
Lerner paid for the Cleveland Browns expansion franchise, could
blow away team president John Kent Cooke, son of the late owner
Jack Kent Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   A clever element involved with the Milstein bid is that it is
only good through this Wednesday. The seven other suitors are to
submit binding bids by Tuesday. That means the seven trustees who
operate the team might have less than 24 hours to evaluate the
Milstein-Snyder bid against others before it disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke last week secured additional financing which enabled him
to raise his bid from $450 million to about $600 million. If he's
able to keep the Skins, look for Cooke to retain GM Charley
Casserly and coach Norv Turner for one more year. If the
Milstein-Snyder group prevails, it will pursue Green Bay coach Mike
Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   More green for Garrison
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco GM John McVay already has contacted agent Pat Dye
Jr. about a new deal for tailback Garrison Hearst. For practical
reasons, the former Georgia star deserves a contract upgrade. He
needs just 61 yards in the final two games to break Roger Craig's
single-season club rushing record and has been named to his first
Pro Bowl squad. But the Niners have pragmatic reasons as well for
wanting to renegotiate. The club already is $22 million over the
projected '99 salary cap and McVay certainly will need some of the
juggling skills of predecessor Carmen Policy to find a remedy. The
goal is to lower Hearst's 1999 cap figure from $2.65 million to
about $1.5 million by replacing base salary with signing bonus.
McVay desperately wants to retain young wideouts Terrell Owens and
J.J. Stokes. The former can become a restricted free agent next
spring and the latter an unrestricted player. Look for the 49ers to
get their annual cap relief from quarterback Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news Bears
</P>
<P>
   Although vice president Mark Hatley wants to give coach Dave
Wannstedt another year in Chicago, the decision will be made by
president Mike McCaskey. Since earning a wildcard berth in '94,
Wannstedt's second season, the Bears are 23-39. Chicago failed to
land a player in the Pro Bowl for the fifth straight season,
currently the longest such streak in the NFL. The team's last
players in the annual all-star game were defensive end Richard
Dent, corner Donell Woolford and free safety Mark Carrier in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Trent not entrenched
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty over ownership has kept the Redskins from making
a contract offer to quarterback Trent Green, who can become an
unrestricted free agent in February. In the seven games since the
Skins' bye on Oct. 25, Green has thrown for 1,675 yards and 14
touchdowns, with just two interceptions. Washington is 5-2 in that
stretch and Green, 28, has a passer rating of 89.6. ``The
indications are that their hands are tied for now because of the
question of ownership,'' agent Jim Steiner said. The Skins probably
will release quarterback Gus Frerotte after the season to avoid
paying him a $1.25 million roster bonus due on Feb. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia coach Ray Rhodes acknowledged last week he's going
to be fired, but he doesn't sound like a man worried about
employment. ``I had a job when I came here and I'll have a job when
I leave,'' Rhodes said. ... One scout's perspective on why Arizona
quarterback Jake Plummer has developed quicker than Pittsburgh's
Kordell Stewart: ``If Jake makes a mistake, he shrugs it off. Bad
plays seem to hang with Stewart longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
