<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-minute drill with John Elway
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Topic: His rivalry with Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Background: Elway and Marino entered the NFL as part of the
celebrated ``Class of '83,'' when a record six quarterbacks were
selected in the first round. Between them, the pair has thrown for
109,224 yards. But in 16 seasons, the two have played only once,
the Dolphins claiming a 30-26 victory in '85. On Monday night,
Marino and Elway match up for the second, and probably the final,
time in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has the Marino-versus-Elway debate affected your career?
</P>
<P>
   A: It seems like it's been there forever. Because we're the same
age, people compared us in high school, college and finally, the
NFL. Dan hit the ground running in the league, and I had to climb a
little more. But him being around, yeah, it's been an (incentive).
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have the one thing he doesn't have, a Super Bowl ring.
Have you two talked about that at all?
</P>
<P>
   A: It used to come up all the time when people pointed out no
one from that Class of '83 had one. It was like an asterisk after
our names. I'm sure Dan got tired of talking about it, just like I
did, so we stopped bringing it up when we got together.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it fair to say you're a fan of his?
</P>
<P>
   A: To do the things he's done and put up the numbers he has, how
could you not admire that? But what I admire most is how he loves
to compete. You still see that same look in his eyes every time
he's on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Spotlight on . . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Veteran: With two more wins, the Cardinals gain their first
playoff berth since '82. To get the first today, against New
Orleans, quarterback Jake Plummer must be very decisive against a
Saints defense that will bring plenty of pressure from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie: With Mark Brunell (ankle) and Jamie Martin (knee) both
out, Jacksonville will turn to rookie Jonathan Quinn as its
starter. A shaky performance by the third-rounder from Middle
Tennessee State could cost the Jaguars a first-week bye in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free agent: New England defensive tackle Chad Eaton flopped
with three teams before landing with the Patriots in '96. Over the
past three games, he has 32 tackles and three sacks and will have
to play stout if the Pats are to slow the 49ers' Garrison Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Miami coordinators Kippy Brown (offense) and George
Hill (defense) were outcoached badly by their New York Jets
counterparts last Sunday. The duo will need better game plans
against Denver on Monday for the Dolphins to have a chance for an
upset.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   The contract extension that has been on the desk of Green Bay
coach Mike Holmgren since August is worth much less than the $4
million per year that has been reported, and he has no intention of
signing it. Packers GM Ron Wolf quietly is solidifying his short
list of potential replacements. ... Former UCLA coach Terry Donahue
and San Diego State coach Ted Tollner are campaigning quietly for
the Chargers job. ... The first three coaches who will be
interviewed by Cleveland Browns president Carmen Policy are Denver
offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak, Green Bay quarterbacks coach
Andy Reid and Jacksonville offensive coordinator Chris Palmer. The
Browns probably will interview six to eight candidates. ... He has
yet to throw his first regular-season pass, but several teams
already are eyeing New York Giants No. 3 quarterback Mike Cherry,
who will be a restricted free agent in February. ... The Redskins
will expose tailback Terry Allen in the expansion draft. ... By
landing a spot on the NFC Pro Bowl team, New Orleans defensive end
Joe Johnson earned a $1 million bonus and voided the final season
of the five-year deal he signed in September. ... Look for
Minnesota offensive coordinator Brian Billick to emerge as the
leading candidate to succeed Ted Marchibroda in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up
</P>
<P>
   In a year when the ``zebras'' have come under fire, game
officials Jerry Markbreit, Johnny Grier, Phil Luckett, Ed Hochuli,
Gerry Austin and others donated time and money visiting children's
hospitals around the country for the holidays. The guys in stripes
deserve a nod for their generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   All six offensive tackles selected for the Pro Bowl _ Tony
Boselli (Jacksonville), Tony Jones (Denver), Jonathan Ogden
(Baltimore), Larry Allen (Dallas), William Roaf (New Orleans) and
Todd Stuessie (Minnesota) _ play the left side. The left and right
tackle spots have evolved into different positions and should be
voted as such.
</P>
<P>
   The list
</P>
<P>
   There are four new starting quarterbacks today _ Frank Reich
(Detroit), Steve Bono (St. Louis), Jonathan Quinn (Jacksonville)
and Scott Zolak (New England) _ raising to 62 the number who have
started at least one game in 1998. That number is believed to be
the most since the 1970 merger. The number of starting quarterbacks
for the rest of the '90s:
</P>
<P>
   Year Starters
</P>
<P>
   1990 50
</P>
<P>
   1991 50
</P>
<P>
   1992 58
</P>
<P>
   1993 57
</P>
<P>
   1994 53
</P>
<P>
   1995 50
</P>
<P>
   1996 54
</P>
<P>
   1997 58
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has lost three games in a row for the first time
since Bill Cowher became coach in 1992. The team has just two
offensive touchdowns in the last 18 quarters, a stretch of 52
possessions. Cornerback Dewayne Washington has as many TDs this
year (two) as tailback Jerome Bettis.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie on his Pro Bowl selection:
``It's kind of a feeling of acceptance. I'm no longer a novelty.
They actually take me seriously as a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
