<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-PROPAGANDA-1220-     12-19 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-PROPAGANDA-1220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOSING THE AIR(WAR), SADDAM EXPLOITS THE AIRWAVES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 450 words.
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1220.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saddam Hussein cannot stop the air strikes, but
some defense experts say he is scoring hits on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   With shrewd use of the news media, these experts said the Iraqi
president has tightly controlled the world's view of the nightly
pounding by American and British missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In a calculated bid for world sympathy following the first night
of bombing, his officials led foreign journalists to a bomb crater
in a residential street to counter the U.S. declaration that it
sought only to disable Iraq's weapon-making capabilities. Foreign
camera crews and reporters, who are not permitted to move without
government ``minders,'' have been taken to photograph and interview
wounded civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Saddam, who has remained in hiding, appeared on a
television broadcast to fire verbal assaults at the ``agents of
Satan,'' as he called the U.S. and British forces. In an appeal to
the Muslim world, he vowed Friday: ``We will fear nothing but God,
and we will not kneel except to the face of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Through such public relations offensives, the Iraqi leader has
placed blame for the suffering of the Iraqi people on the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an information war going on, there's no doubt about
it,'' said William J. Taylor Jr., international affairs specialist
at the Center for Strategic and International Studies in
Washington. ``And Saddam and his Revolutionary Command Council know
how to play this game very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme is, this is a horrible thing that's being done to
their people.''
</P>
<P>
   That message has touched a responsive chord on the streets of
cities in Arab countries, and even Palestinian-controlled Gaza,
where demonstrators have charged that President Clinton -- who only
Monday was cheered by Arabs for his trip to Gaza -- ordered the
strikes to divert the impeachment effort in the sex-and-cover-up
scandal involving former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the Egyptian capital of Cairo, protestors have carried signs
saying ``For Monica's sake, Iraqi children are dying'' and crowds
have chanted, ``Leaders of the country, let us go to holy war!''
the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Americans have also attempted to use the weapons
of public persuasion to help its cause. U.S. forces dumped leaflets
over southern Iraq to tell Saddam's troops that, if they stay put
and cause no trouble, they will not become the target of U.S.
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. officials have sought international backing for the
military action with some success. More than a dozen nations,
chiefly European, have issued statements of strong support.
However, Russia and China have both issued equally strong protests,
as have several Islamic nations.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional ad follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One problem for the United States is that its objective is not
clear yet, said John Bolton, who served as undersecretary of state
during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam's goals have been simpler, easier to define, and he's
been at them for a very long period of time,'' Bolton said. ``He
wants out from under the (United Nations) weapons inspections
regime and he wants out from under the (international) sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's stated goal, to ``degrade''
Saddam's weapons-making capacity, is too ambiguous and hardly a
rallying cry, Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Hanlon, a foreign policy specialist at the Brookings
Institution, echoed the concern that the lack of specific goals
could make problems for explaining the U.S. mission in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they've made a convincing case,'' he said of the
Clinton administration. ``So far, people are rallying around the
flag , but I think that over time people will see that this strike
didn't have tangible effect except to get the (U.N. weapons)
inspectors out (of Iraq) for good.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
