<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jets clinch division title, spot in playoffs
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In keeping with his track record, New York Jets coach
Bill Parcells has accomplished what three decades worth of
predecessors could not.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' 17-10 victory over the Buffalo Bills on Saturday
earned the team its first division title since 1969 and first-ever
AFC East championship. New York was the only team in the league at
the time of the 1970 NFL-AFL merger which had never claimed a
division crown.
</P>
<P>
   The winning score came on Dedric Ward's 71-yard touchdown
reception.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the third time in Parcells' 14-season career as a head
coach that he has taken a franchise to the playoffs in just his
second year on the job. The other occasions were with the New York
Giants and New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to say alive in the chase for the NFC's final
wildcard spot, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers faced the Washington
Redskins in a late afternoon game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the first home defeat for quarterback Doug Flutie in his
NFL and USFL career, the Bills still can secure a wildcard berth if
Tennessee loses at Green Bay today. With Saturday's results, three
of the six division championships have been decided and the other
three could be determined in today's action. The Atlanta Falcons,
Jacksonville Jaguars and Dallas Cowboys all can clinch division
crowns.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 12 playoff berths already are reserved. Pending the
outcome of the Tampa Bay-Washington game, it is possible for all of
the postseason spots to be filled by the time this week's schedule
is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
