<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRUMP-OPPONENTS-70     12-19 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRUMP-OPPONENTS-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SOME BIG NAMES MARSHAL FORCES AGAINST TRUMP'S LATEST TOWER
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donald Trump's plan to build what he calls the
tallest residential tower in the world across the street from the
United Nations is arousing the kind of opposition unknown since the
great real estate wars of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the area have complained that the slim bronze-glass
monolith will overwhelm the neighborhood and lord over its most
distinctive landmark _ the United Nations. But the hue and cry
raised by Seymour Flug, former chairman of Diners' Club, and Walter
Cronkite, former television news anchor, has spread from their
exclusive Beekman Place neighborhood near the United Nations to the
Upper West Side, Yorkville and the halls of the Municipal Art
Society.
</P>
<P>
   They have formed a coalition, hired lawyers, raised more than
$125,000 in a week and hired a public relations outfit to fight the
most media-conscious developer in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Trump has his permits and has begun demolition for the $360
million tower on First Avenue, between 47th and 48th streets, and
construction is expected to begin early next year. But a similar
alliance among neighborhood groups, civic organizations and
blue-bloods a decade ago brought another developer, Mortimer
Zuckerman, to his knees when his proposed 925-foot tower at
Columbus Circle threatened to cast long shadows across another
landmark, Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The groups have been largely quiet since the last great real
estate boom in the 1980s, when there were protests in neighborhoods
from the Upper East Side to TriBeCa against the demolition of town
houses, tenements, shoe repair stores and dry cleaners to make way
for more tall towers.
</P>
<P>
   But every full-color advertisement and brochure for what Trump
said would be his most luxurious tower has served as a clarion call
for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trump certainly has broadened his opposition with this
project,'' said Olive Freud, vice president of the Committee for
Environmentally Sound Development, a West Side neighborhood group
that continues the fight against another project at Columbus
Circle. ``Maybe a lot of people will understand what Trump's doing
to this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Flug, Cronkite and Ms. Freud are Genie Rice, president
of Civitas, an East Side planning group that won a five-year battle
to force a developer to lop 12 floors from his newly built 31-story
tower on East 96th Street because it failed to conform to local
zoning regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine Polayes, president of the Coalition for a Livable West
Side, which has tangled with Trump over his Trump Place project
between 59th and 72nd streets near the Hudson River, has also
joined the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Flug, who heads both the Beekman Hill Association and the newly
formed Coalition for Responsible Development, said: ``This is not
about a bunch of rich guys going after Donald Trump. This is a
grass-roots, community effort. It's about one of the most
irresponsible development projects we've ever seen. To drop this
into the middle of a residential area which has a great deal of
historical importance is about as offensive as anything anyone can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump is not as concerned with Ms. Polayes as he is with ``the
rich guys,'' many of whom he considers friends, he said. Flug's
comrades include William Donaldson, founder of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette Inc., an investment firm; Stanley Kaplan, chairman of the
test preparation company; David Koch, executive vice president of
Koch Industries, an oil and gas company, and Alberto Vilar, the
founder of Amerindo Investment Advisers, who recently donated $25
million to the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Trump project has grown in size with each telling of
the story. The developer himself and his glossy advertisements
describe it as a 90-story tower. Some opponents refer to it as a
looming 100-story behemoth. Truth be told, the building will have
only 72 floors. But at 861-feet, it will be the tallest residential
tower in the city, and possibly, the world. Trump World Tower would
soar 317 feet above the 39-story U.N. Secretariat and 11 feet above
the General Electric Building at Rockefeller Center to be the rough
equivalent in height of Citicorp Center on Lexington Avenue in
midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``People actually like the building,'' Trump said. ``They just
don't like the height. But the height is what gives it majesty.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Philip Howard, chairman of the Municipal Art Society, said he
did admire the ``simple and clean'' design of the tower by the
architect Costas Kondylis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reality is,'' Howard added, ``you shouldn't have a
building of this size in that neighborhood. It's twice as big as it
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite shares that view: ``This building overwhelms the
architectural features of the United Nations. The enormity of the
project is not in keeping with the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has also said the tower is too
tall and questioned its approval by the city, but Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has defended the approval process.
</P>
<P>
   If the project cannot be stopped for legal or environmental
reasons, Howard, Ms. Rice and the local community board will press
for changes in zoning regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The developer is not without supporters. Buyers love the
project, Trump said, adding that he sold 58 of the building's 376
apartments in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Newman, an insurance broker who lives nearby at 870 U.N.
Plaza, said she favored the tower because each of Trump's previous
projects was accompanied by a greater sense of security,
cleanliness and city services. ``I'm a proponent of change,'' Ms.
Newman said. ``I think it's going to be an improvement for the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, community groups from across Manhattan met to draw
up a battle plan to oppose the building. That evening, dozens of
local residents debated the project, including Ms. Newman and
Arthur Caliandro, senior minister of Marble Collegiate Church,
which happens to be the Trump family church. Caliandro said that a
Trump executive had encouraged him to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Although Trump's building would block his living room view of
the East River, the minister said he expected the tower to be
spectacular and, like the developer's other projects, an
improvement for the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Vasell, a management consultant, noted that much of the
opposition was centered at 860 and 870 U.N. Plaza, two towers that
obstructed the views of Beekman Place residents when they were
built in the 1960s. Nevertheless, Vasell said, Trump's building was
``totally out of scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump and his associates say they worked within the city's
zoning regulations. Local residents could easily have foiled any
plans for a tall tower by buying the air rights in the early 1990s,
after others considered building on the site, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Wallach of the Trump Organization said: ``You've got some
powerhouse people living over there. They could've maintained the
character of the area by buying up a sliver of air rights, which
would have negated any developer from building a tall tower.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump outbid a dozen other developers for the property nearly
two years ago, paying about $52 million. In an uncharacteristically
quiet manner, Trump then spent another $30 million buying up unused
development rights, or air rights, from nine of his neighbors on
the block, including the Japan Society and the Church of the Holy
Family. Those rights, along with a promise to build a public plaza,
enabled Trump to obtain construction permits to build an oversize
tower.
</P>
<P>
   Trump acknowledged that if he had bought the development rights
with his well-publicized style, his opponents ``probably would have
changed the zoning rules'' and prevented him from building.
</P>
</TEXT>
