</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-VIRTUAL-SAILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL SAILORS JOIN THE AROUND ALONE FLEET AS IT BRAVES THE
SOUTHERN SEA
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Calif., S.C.) 
 (nk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Rudiger, a champion ocean racer, is not one of the
competitors in the Around Alone race. But a computer game is
bringing him and thousands of other virtual sailors closer to the
action.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old Rudiger is one of 5,521 people who have signed
up on the Web site of the Around Alone (www.aroundalone.com) to
sail along with the 15 actual competitors in the 27,000-mile solo
race. The army of armchair sailors is currently navigating its
fictitious boats through Leg 2, a 6,884-mile trek from South Africa
to New Zealand that began Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty addictive,'' Rudiger said recently by telephone
from San Francisco. ``I get in on it at least a couple of times a
day. If I don't get on the Web for a stretch, I start worrying
about what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the virtual race, the site includes e-mail
dispatches from the real sailors, news updates and ``Rudiger's
Roundup,'' an audio commentary on the race which Rudiger provides
for the site's producer, Quokka Sports.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997-98 Whitbread Round the World Race, Rudiger was
actually racing. As navigator on EF Language, the 60-foot Swedish
sailboat that won the race, Rudiger found out what victory is like.
But in the virtual Around Alone, he is struggling to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, his entry, named Team Rudiger, was among the top
100 boats. But by the end of last week, his standing had dropped to
333rd. Part of the problem, he said, was a computer game hiccup
that caused a small portion of the cyberspace fleet to look as if
it was going backward through the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Distressing, yes. But mild by comparison to the rerouting
experienced by many of the real Around Alone sailors last week. The
15 competitors had agreed at sea, by e-mail, to head north around
the mid-ocean Kerguelen Islands to avoid a severe storm to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the new routing affected them all differently.
Mike Golding, the English sailor who had won Leg 1 from Charleston,
S.C., to Cape Town, was blindsided with a 30-knot breeze and huge
ocean swells from the distant storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, a succession of waves arrived with a squall, and we
were off,'' Golding said in an e-mail last Monday. ``At first I
thought it was fun sailing at 26-28 knots. Then the fun turned to
fear when I realized I was on an unstoppable ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Golding said that his sailboat, the 60-foot Team
Group 4, accelerated down a huge wave in a near vertical drop. ``A
split-second later, she hit the bottom of the wave,'' he added. ``A
veritable wall of water engulfed the boat from stem to stern, then
threw the boat on its side causing an instant jibe and knockdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Golding was able to bring the boat back under control 30 minutes
later. By late last week, he was in third place with fewer than
3,500 miles to go to Auckland, New Zealand. In first place, about
100 miles ahead of Golding, was Giovanni Soldini, the Italian
skipper of Fila.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle Autissier, the French sailor who was leading early last
week, was forced on Thursday to seek calmer waters by heading
north. She dropped out to fix a jam in her boat's mainsail track,
and is unlikely now to have a chance at winning.
</P>
<P>
   The on-line competitors choose one of three boat designs and
then make decisions about how much food to take, how many calories
to expend each day and when to eat and sleep. The same weather
reports sent by satellite to race competitors are shared by at-home
sailors. The multitude of information requires difficult decisions,
whether a person is at sea or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finding that more factors come into play with one person
sailing the boat than with the 10 or 12 people per boat in the
Whitbread,'' said Frank Tulp, a former equity trader from San
Francisco. ``For one thing, you have to take into account the extra
time needed to fix something.''
</P>
<P>
   Quokka Sports says the average number of visits to the Around
Alone home page is about 12,000 a day, compared to about 66,000
visits a day at its 1997-98 Whitbread site. But the Around Alone
visits have been longer, averaging 15 minutes compared to 9 minutes
for the Whitbread site.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know when the solo sailor sleeps,'' said Susan
Daly, vice president of sailing for Quokka Sports. ``We tell them,
on and off for a few minutes at a time, 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Participation in the current virtual race is closed to new
entrants for the remainder of Leg 2. But people interested in
joining for Leg 3 can register on the site in mid-January.
</P>
</TEXT>
