<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers keep chipping away at negotiations for practice rink
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lest there were any doubts that the Thrashers'
negotiations to build a practice facility at the Cooler ice rink in
Alpharetta, Ga., are on a respirator, the team is in the middle of
serious talks with a facility in Duluth. The Ice Forum is
interested in helping build the team's permanent complex adjacent
to its existing skating rink. The Ice Forum has one sheet of ice
but owns several acres that could be used to build a second rink
and a separate building for team offices, training equipment and
locker facilities. Thrashers general manager Don Waddell has met
with architects and is convinced that a new building could be
completed in time for the team's inaugural season. The only
alternative is to rent ice next year and maintain offices downtown
at CNN Center while a deal is worked out. Blueprints have been
drawn detailing the proposed practice facility at the Ice Forum.
... Waddell has been named to a staff of NHL general managers that
will help select players for the United States to compete in
hockey's World Championship, which takes place every spring in
non-Olympic years. Next year's championship will be held May 1-16
in Oslo, Norway. ... The Thrashers' advertising has spread to a new
outlet. A 30-second pre-show commercial began appearing in several
movie theaters Friday. The idea is to take advantage of the
increase in moviegoing during the holiday season. ... Team
officials held a dinner for several former Atlanta Flames last
week, including Tom Lysiak, Curt Bennett and Tim Ecclestone. ...
Waddell, marketing director Derek Schiller and other members of the
front office held the first in a series of breakfast study groups
last week with a dozen season-ticket holders, hoping to gauge the
success of marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   FACEOFF: RAY BOURQUE
</P>
<P>
   Team: Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Defender.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 38.
</P>
<P>
   Update: His 20 years with the Bruins represent the longest
tenure by any active player in the four major sports. He has played
in 16 All-Star games and his 1,425 career points at the start of
the week rank 11th on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   On making the roster as an 18-year-old: ``Back then, the
expectations weren't as high and the money issue wasn't as big. Now
they're making the big bucks right off the bat, and they're
expected to deliver earlier than I did. I came into a good
situation with a veteran team. But now, kids are picked first by
the worst teams in the league, and they're being expected to make
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   On his longevity: ``Sometimes I think about how fortunate I've
been. But I intend to keep on trucking as long as my body and mind
hold up. Sometimes I think: When will it end? I guess when I start
falling apart. But hopefully, that won't happen. I want to be out
of the game before I start sliding.''
</P>
<P>
   On whether he will slide into coaching: ``I definitely see
myself in hockey. But I'm not too sure about coaching. The travel
gets old after a while. One thing I'd like to do is slow down and
spend more time at home.''
</P>
<P>
   On the highlight of his career: ``I hope it hasn't yet come. I
still see myself skating around the ice with the (Stanley) Cup one
day. I've had so many great moments _ going to two finals, the
All-Star game in Boston when I scored with under a minute left, my
first game in Boston Garden in 1979. But if I ever win a Cup, that
would be the special time.''
</P>
<P>
   FIT TO BE TIED
</P>
<P>
   Although it remains to be seen if any rule changes will be
implemented, league officials continue to study ways to minimize
tie games in the regular season, and here's why. The percentage of
games that remain tied after overtime has been on the rise in the
last three years. Here is a 10-season breakdown of total games
played, overtime games and completed ties.
</P>
<P>
   Season Games OT Ties Pct.
</P>
<P>
   1989-90 840 155 100 64.5
</P>
<P>
   1990-91 840 166 112 67.5
</P>
<P>
   1991-92 880 169 117 69.2
</P>
<P>
   1992-93 1008 165 100 60.1
</P>
<P>
   1993-94 1092 214 140 65.4
</P>
<P>
   1994-95 624 101 75 74.3
</P>
<P>
   1995-96 1066 201 137 68.2
</P>
<P>
   1996-97 1066 214 144 67.3
</P>
<P>
   1997-98 1066 219 165 75.3
</P>
<P>
   1998-99 373 72 56 77.8
</P>
<P>
   (Through Tuesday's games)
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE/UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a seven-hour bus trip (from Chicago) to Cincinnati. It
was the longest airport runway of my life. You couldn't get NHL
scores on the out-of-town scoreboard _ just the Federal League (of
`Slapshot' fame).''
</P>
<P>
   _ Toronto goalie Glenn Healy on his two months in the minor
leagues.
</P>
