<HEADLINE>
NO PROHIBITION AGAINST WAR DURING RAMADAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite President Clinton's desire not to launch attacks on Iraq
during Ramadan, there is nothing in Islamic law that prohibits
warfare during Islam's holiest month, some religious scholars said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue about not attacking during Ramadan is only
important in the administration's mind, because there's absolutely
nothing in Islam that says you can't have a war during Ramadan,''
said Yvonee Haddad, a professor of the history of Islam and
Christian-Muslim relations at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan, which begins this weekend, celebrates the divine
revelation of the opening sections of the Koran, Islam's sacred
text, to the prophet Mohammed. Fasting from dawn to sunset during
the month-long observance is one of the five pillars, or
obligations, of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Along with fasting, the world's 1 billion Muslims are also
required to observe the holy month by abstaining from smoking,
liquids, and sex from dawn to dusk as a sign of purification and
sacrifice. Ramadan ends with Id al-Fitr, the feast of the breaking
of the fast, one of the biggest Muslim celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ramadan's special significance _ it is specifically
mentioned in the Koran _ Haddad noted that, Iran and Iraq, two
predominantly Muslim nations, waged war in the 1980s during the
month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   But other Islamic specialists said that even if it is not
forbidden by religious law, bombing Iraq on Ramadan could still be
regarded by Muslims as being highly disrespectful because it is
considered an especially sacred period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention, the effort, and energy of Muslims is very much
directed toward Ramadan,'' said Denis Sullivan, an associate
professor of political science and a Middle East specialist at
Northeastern University. ``To have that experience of faith
violated by non-Muslims, especially by the United States, is really
a complete and total denigration of that month.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Muslim organizations in the United States, while not
necessarily supportive of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein, have been
critical, for political and not religious reasons, of the US
assault on Iraq .
</P>
<P>
   ``This assault does not lend credibility to undermining the
Iraqi regime's perceived threat to its neighboring states as well
as the world community,'' said a statement released Saturday by the
Washington-based American Muslim Council.
</P>
<P>
   Another Washington-based group, the Council on American-Islamic
Relations, said the bombings along with the continuing US economic
sanctions against Iraq will exacerbate a ``humanitarian disaster
that includes vastly increased rates of malnutrition, disease, and
infant deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Islam follows the lunar calendar, which is shorter than
the solar calendar, the dates of Ramadan change every year. The
start of Ramadan depends on the date of the new moon, based on
stringent Islamic astrological guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim countries begin and end the month on a different day,
based on when their clerics determine a new moon to be sighted. In
the Boston area, Muslims are expected to begin their Ramadan fast
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to some misconceptions, the majority of the world's
Muslims are not in the Middle East and are not Arab. According to
Muslim scholars, the country with the largest number of Muslims is
Indonesia, followed by Pakistan, Bangladesh, and India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
