u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-US-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      12-19 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-US-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR US TROOPS, FAMILIAR GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOHA, Kuwait _ As they quick-stepped into the staging area, the
soldiers of Charlie Company gave roar to that durable Army marching
chant: ``Here we go _ again! Here we go _ again!''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Kurt Antoine was surely going again. Saturday marked
his fourth rapid deployment to Kuwait since the 1991 Persian Gulf
War. The sands of the emirate were becoming as familiar as the
sands of his native Asbury Park, N.J. ``Saddam Hussein keeps
jerking Americans back here, and it's getting pretty tiresome,'' he
said. ``If the orders come, we're ready to head across that border
and start killing bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Overhanging the operation, however, was the ongoing impeachment
crisis enwrapping Bill Clinton, commander-and-chief of these
fighters. For some, it plainly whittled away the edges of their
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What should really be a political sideshow for Americans has
become the whole show, and I guess there is a feeling that we're
here, willing to put our lives on the line, but no one at home is
paying attention except as it plays out as part of the scandal,''
said Spec. Derrin Brown, 21, of Taunton, Mass. ``This deployment is
our reality. But it doesn't seem to register at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fliers were back in the air, delivering death and
destruction at supersonic speed. American F-16 fighters and A-10
``tank busters'' thundered again Saturday night from Navy carriers
and desert air bases.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, the US troops still pouring into the Gulf were
wondering if maybe, just maybe, their time might be next.
</P>
<P>
   It's a prospect they weigh with equal parts anxiety and
anticipation. ``No one really wants to go into combat,'' said
Specialist Kevin McKoon, 20, of Rindge, N.H. ``But the bottom line
is, that's what we're trained for.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely an hour after being disgorged from the air transport that
carried them from their home base of Fort Stewart, Ga., the
bleary-eyed soldiers of Charlie Company, 3rd Battalion, 15th
Regiment, 3rd Infantry Division were hurriedly drawing ammunition
and field rations, then readying their Bradley fighting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our soldiers are moving at speed. It's 12 hours from the
moment they hit the ground to the time they take up fighting
positions out in the desert,'' said Col. Ron Williams, chief
spokesman for US ground forces in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Company was just one of scores of combat units airlifted
or landed by sea into Kuwait over the past several weeks, bringing
total American ground forces in the emirate to over 5,000 Army
troops and Marines, a number increasing almost by the hour in an
operation that has gone nearly unnoticed as the bombs crash down on
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The company's staging ground was a forlorn strip of asphalt
whipped by wind-blown sand. The cold darkness of early morning was
harshly illuminated by batteries of diesel generator-fired
floodlights.
</P>
<P>
   There came the oily purr of turrets swiveling as gunners
performed battle readiness checks on 25mm ``chain guns'' capable of
chewing an ordinary car into metal confetti in two blinks of the
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeants bawled orders; officers pored over maps; lowlier ranks
manhandled crates of Meals-Ready-to-Eat, drinking water and ammo
into the dun-colored armored vehicles. Each Bradley carries three
crew members -- gunner, driver, commander -- along with six
infantrymen, plus the hundreds of pounds of gear and supplies
needed to sustain them.
</P>
<P>
   As the troopers of Charlie Company prepped as if for war, the
31st Marine Expeditionary Unit -- ``a thousand trigger-pullers
strong,'' in the words of Lt. Kristen A. Lasica -- were digging
into a rocky ridge not far from the Iraq border.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines had shoved ashore on landing vessels after a rushed
ocean passage from a training mission in Okinawa. Now, as first
light paled the eastern sky, the Marines were hacking foxholes into
the barren ground, sweat streaking the sand plastered to their
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an adventure, only not a lot of fun,'' said Cpl.
Sean Walsh, 21, of Worcester, Mass., mechanic on an amphibious
assault vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Marines were dug in, there was little to do but listen
to the desert wind moan and watch a camel caravan plod across the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Most US troops interviewed had little inkling of world events,
so cut off are they from the news; none had any notion of how their
commander-in-chief was faring in his fight for political survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got no TV, got no radio, but that's fine, that's cool,'' said
Cpl. Joshua Ridley, 20, of La Grande, Ore. ``We're not here to be
public commentators. We're here to do whatever our country asks us
to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
