<HEADER>
A8515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-BLAIR-BOS &LR;      12-19 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BLAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT LEAVES BLAIR AN UNLIKELY HAWK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With President Bill Clinton undermined and effectively
silenced by his impeachment, an unlikely chief cheerleader of the
Anglo-American assault on Iraq has emerged: British Prime Minister
Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unaccustomed position for Blair, who is more
comfortable extolling the virtues of his post-empire vision of
``Cool Britannia'' than sabre rattling.
</P>
<P>
   But with the American commander-in-chief being impeached even as
US forces are in combat, it has been left to Blair to be the
standard bearer for Britain and America.
</P>
<P>
   Telegenic and an accomplished speaker, Blair has impressed even
his political enemies by forcefully articulating the Anglo-American
case for striking at Saddam Hussein's regime.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, some observers in London were stunned by the
hard-line rhetoric Blair used. He talked of keeping ``Saddam in his
cage, because if he is allowed out of his cage he is a danger to
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's choice of words was even more striking because the most
vocal critics of the Anglo-American attacks on Iraq are members of
his traditionally left-wing Labor Party, which last year broke an
18-year hold on power by the Conservatives in winning the biggest
parliamentary majority in nearly two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Clinton, Blair moved his party away from ideologically
held positions to the center in a calculated move to gain power.
And like Clinton, Blair has emerged as an unlikely hawk in the
campaign against Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Blair stepped up the war of words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is without any doubt at all our desire to see the end of
Saddam Hussein,'' Blair said at a news conference here. ``As well
as the military dimension, we are already in discussion with our
colleagues and allies and partners around the world as to how we
then adopt a forward strategy to make sure there is stability and
containment in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has an ever-decreasing credibility with many of
those European allies, it will be left to Blair to mend fences with
the major powers, especially France, which has joined Russia and
China in opposing the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, with the president preoccupied, the case
to be made for bombing Iraq has been left mostly to Defense
Secretary William Cohen, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, and
General Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
Similarly, the British have used Foreign Minister Robin Cook and
Defense Minister George Robertson to argue their case.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who despise the Blair administration, viewing it
as arrogant and self-righteous, acknowledge that it is Blair
himself who has made the most compelling case for bombing Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan support here has been made easier by Blair's public
speeches. The opposition Tories find themselves handcuffed, unable
to repudiate Blair's hard-line rhetoric because they agree with it
wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Letts, who covers the House of Commons for The Daily
Telegraph, the voice of the Conservative establishment, conceded
that Blair's speech to Parliament on Thursday defending the attacks
on Iraq was impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Letts and others feel uncomfortable giving too much credit
to the leader of a party whose backbenchers were describing the
bombings as a violation of international law. Conservatives are
suspicious of Blair's motives and think his Commons speech on
Thursday was inconsistent with the pacifist stance of Blair's Labor
Party predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though one hesitates to say this,'' said Letts, ``he (Blair)
seemed almost to be enjoying his opportunity. . ., rejoicing in it,
even.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday night, as the first bombs were
dropping on Iraq, Blair's foreign secretary, Cook, chuckled when
asked if his boss was acting tough.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair, he said, is much tougher than his critics give him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
