<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-PARK-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 TRYING TO MAKE A BLEAK WATERFRONT INTO A HARLEM RIVER PARK
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The elegant Robert F. Wagner Jr. esplanade along the
Harlem River stops cold at 125th Street _ no more antique lights,
no railing, no benches. What relentlessly unfolds as one keeps
walking north is an almost surreal industrial wasteland. An
enormous pile of road salt gives way to an abandoned concrete plant
surrounded by hundreds of tons of asphalt chunks.
</P>
<P>
   The dreary riverfront is littered with burned-out automobiles,
rusted oil drums and empty bottles. There is a small encampment of
homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   In place of this desolation, people have long imagined a
waterfront park beside the river from 125th to 145th streets. A
plan was actually drawn up in 1991 at the behest of Ruth Messinger,
then the Manhattan borough president. But administrations changed,
and other projects claimed priority.
</P>
<P>
   Now the plan, with a price estimated at $15 million, is
resurfacing _ albeit slowly and in smaller stages. The City Parks
and Recreation Department has assembled $1.9 million, including
$1.1 million in federal transportation funds, to build a segment of
the park from 135th to 139th streets and is completing final plans.
It is also applying for more money to build the segment between
139th and 142nd streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be done; the question is, when?'' Parks Commissioner
Henry Stern said. ``Why not do it sooner, rather than later?''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he has been fighting for a Harlem River park since
the 1960s, when, as assistant to the Manhattan borough president,
he urged the city to forbid the construction of a concrete plant
between 128th and 131st Streets.
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason to be optimistic about the area's chances
for renewal, despite its desolation, Stern said. Unlike many other
suggested sites for city parks, he said, this stretch of the Harlem
River has no developers clamoring for it. He added that the City
Sanitation and Transportation Departments were willing to remove
the piles of salt and asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   But finding almost $15 million to build the entire park remains
a major stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, a variety of conservation and civic organizations
are urging the state to pick up at least part of the tab under the
1996 environmental bond act.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To demonstrate their concern, members of the Audubon Society,
the Parks Council and Civitas, an Upper East Side community
organization, marched through steady rain on Thursday morning .
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can attract some bond act money, we can cobble together
more funding from other sources,'' said Linda Davidoff, executive
director of the League of Conservation Voters, which organized the
march.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates want the revived park plan to be something like
the original design. The 1991 plan envisioned features like
crescent-shaped concrete beaches with beach chairs, barbecue areas
and green shade structures. Swimming would not be permitted, though
sprinklers would spray cool water.
</P>
<P>
   An esplanade would separate the beaches from the river. It would
be designed to look like a tidal zone, with rounded rocks, pebbles
and tidal pools. A trail for jogging and bicycling would run the
length of the park. Tall beacons would mark the end points of the
avenues that end at the water.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Laird, planning director for the parks department, said
the department was trying to do just that. C. Virginia Fields, the
Manhattan borough president, has met with Stern to discuss the
park, Laird said.
</P>
<P>
   Laird said the current approach was a no-frills version of the
1991 design, delaying features like the beaches. A major goal will
be to construct the bikeway along the full length of the park as
early as possible, to establish a constituency and identity for the
park, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said it was time to begin developing parks on the east
side of Manhattan. New parks have been built around Battery Park
City on the Hudson, and the huge new Hudson River Park is under
construction. ``We want to do as much for the waterfront facing the
Bronx as we've done for the one facing New Jersey,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
