<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE20-COX     12-19 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DAY FOR THE HISTORY BOOKS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Robert Hurt drove 32 straight hours with his
pregnant wife and their 10 children to see the House impeach
President Clinton on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a historic moment,'' explained Hurt, who is from near
Kerrville in southwestern Texas. ``We're conservative, and this is
the answer to a lot of prayers and hard work. We feel like it's the
fruit of our labors.''
</P>
<P>
   In triumph or in tears, hundreds flocked to the Capitol on a
raw, gray day to witness the first impeachment of an elected
president since the nation's founding 222 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the drama lived up to expectations. This truly was a
day for the history books.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the House was gaveled to order at 9 a.m., first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton made an emotional visit to Capitol Hill to
rally Democratic House members.
</P>
<P>
   ``She talked about the fact that she believed we were all
American citizens, and that as citizens we live in a constitutional
country, and that the process should be done right and that up to
now it has not been,'' House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of
Missouri said after the closed session.
</P>
<P>
   For any who may have wondered how the sex scandal had affected
her marriage, she had an answer: ``I love and care deeply about my
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   But as events unfolded, Mrs. Clinton's visit soon became a
footnote.
</P>
<P>
   For once, members filled the House chamber beneath the skylight
emblazoned with an American eagle and the motto ``E Pluribus Unum''
_ ``Out of Many, One.'' But contrary to that spirit, partisanship
reigned on this day.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats quickly set the tone by demanding a roll call vote on
the approval of the previous day's journal, a procedural annoyance
often employed by a piqued minority.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was already dark when Speaker-designate Bob Livingston
strode to the well to speak for impeachment. The room was hushed,
for everyone wanted to know what the lanky Republican leader from
Louisiana would say about his own recent confession to marital
infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Near the conclusion of his speech, Livingston urged the
president to spare the country the anguish of a Senate trial. ``I
say that you have the power to terminate that damage and heal the
wounds that you have created,'' he said. ``You sir, may resign your
post.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were ready with a response. ``No. No. No,'' they
chanted. ``You resign. You resign. You resign.''
</P>
<P>
   And to the shock of the assemblage, that's what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only challenge you in such fashion that I am willing to
heed my own words,'' Livingston continued. ``I must set the example
that I hope President Clinton will follow. I will not stand for
speaker of the House ...''
</P>
<P>
   First there was silence. Then Democrats and Republicans rose as
one with respectful applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very dramatic. It was very shocking. It brought tears
to my eyes,'' said Marian Hunter of Richmond, Va., watched from the
visitors gallery. ``It took me a moment to grasp what he was
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Other spectators said the man who won't be speaker had made his
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think President Clinton should follow Bob Livingston's
example,'' said Christian Adams of Columbia, S.C. ``Bob Livingston
has honor. Bill Clinton has none.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the final House votes on Clinton's fate could begin,
however, the Republicans needed to defeat a Democratic attempt to
substitute a censure motion for the four articles of impeachment.
When they did, the Democrats stood and walked out in an
orchestrated protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats straggled down the east steps of the Capitol and
then assembled behind their leaders like a high school band trying
to get into formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are deeply offended by this process,'' Gephardt began,
before being drowned out by catcalls by pro-impeachment protestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back in and do your job,'' shouted one.
</P>
<P>
   And within eight minutes, they did return to the House chamber
to vote on the first impeachment article. It was approved, 228-206,
and President Clinton had been impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, people listened on transistor radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sad for the country,'' said Molly Jones of
Washington. ``I hope and pray the president won't think of
resigning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Curtis Stafford of Woodbridge, Va., thought differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came for the historic vote today,'' he said. ``I think they
did the right thing and I'm glad they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike O'Grady had come from Arlington, Va., to show his support
for Clinton. On his shoulders rode his 4-year-old daughter,
Kaitlin, wearing a Santa hat and waving an American flag. He pushed
Brittany, 2, in a stroller.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the Capitol, O'Grady sighed at the events of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish they'd focus on some issues that would help my
kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
