<HEADLINE>
H.S. RUNNERS CHRISTEN NEW INDOOR TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Will be led; meet is running behind schedule.) 
 (nk) 
 By WILLIAM J. MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 4,000 boys and girls from 181 Eastern high
schools christened the newly &UR;  &LR; installed $600,000 Mondo 200-meter
banked indoor track on Saturday at the Armory Track and Field
Center in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan. The occasion
was the 45th annual Bishop Loughlin Games, said to be the largest
high school indoor track meet in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Norb Sander, who has spearheaded the drive to make the
former National Guard Armory the Mecca of indoor track in the East,
regarded Saturday's meet as a good test of what he and its Italian
builders claim will be ``the world's fastest indoor track.''
</P>
<P>
   It is constructed with an Olympic-quality Super X surface with
banked turns laid down on the former flat Mondo track at the Armory
with 11 inches of wood beneath it all, Sander said. Most indoor
tracks, according to the builder, are placed on concrete floors or
hard floors.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the track a new Finish Lynx computerized scoring
system has been installed, allowing spectators to view results
immediately after the completion of each event. There are more than
60 meets scheduled for the center in 1998-1999, ranging from Police
Athletic League competition to the New York Sports Museum
Collegiate Invitational on Jan. 16 with entries from Ohio State,
Villanova, Oklahoma and George Mason.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's competition the huge fields in each event caused
the meet to be two hours behind schedule in the boys division alone
with the girls events to follow. The meet was originally scheduled
to be conducted over a 10-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   In early boys events, Ali Abiola of St. Peter's in Staten
Island, nipped his senior teammate Rolondo Ortiz at the finish in
the 1,000-meter run and posted a meet record of 2 minutes 31.07
seconds. Ortiz, who led from the start with a fast 2:02.4 first 800
meters, also topped the previous record of 2:32.4 in finishing
second in 2:31.09.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Morgan, a senior from Lawrence on Long Island, also
registered a fast time over the new track in the 600-meter run,
which he won easily in 1:21.50; Joshua Wilson of Brooklyn's Boys
and Girls was runner-up in 1:23.50. Morgan missed the meet mark set
last year by Sean Jeffers of Boys and Girls by only two-tenths of a
second. Noel Parnell of Philadelphia's Roman Catholic sprinted to a
55-meter dash victory in 6.54 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
