<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-PENTAGON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON UPGRADES SUCCESS RATE OF ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon Saturday sharply upgraded its estimate
of how much damage US-led air strikes have inflicted on Saddam
Hussein's military power, leaving open the possibility that the
bombing might soon stop.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, though, many targets _ including those related to
Hussein's nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons program _ have
been only lightly damaged, and several others have not been
attacked at all.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said Saturday at the
Pentagon's daily news conference, that the impeachment vote in the
House would have no effect on the operation. ``He's still the
commander-in-chief,'' Cohen said. ``We're going to continue to act
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fourth night of bombing got under way, Cohen claimed the
attacks have ``substantially degraded'' the Iraqi leader's ability
to wage war.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry H. Shelton, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
declared himself ``very pleased with the results'' and noted
``significant success.''
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat words were explicitly meant to reverse the glum
impression of Friday's news briefing, when Cohen said he was merely
``satisfied'' and Shelton allowed that ``not all'' the strikes had
``gone according to plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the brighter picture, other officers said, was due to
the results of Friday night's ferocious barrage of bombs and cruise
missiles, some of which re-struck targets that they had missed or
just lightly damaged before.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was also due to revisions by intelligence analysts,
who, one day earlier, had not had time to examine spy-satellite
photos of all the targets.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday morning, US and British bombs and missiles had
attacked a total of 97 targets and done at least some damage to all
of them.
</P>
<P>
   This marked an advance over the day before, when a total of 89
targets had been attacked, of which 12 received no damage.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 cruise missiles, each costing nearly $1 million, have
been fired so far from B-52 bombers and ships at sea. An untold
number of laser-guided bombs, but probably at least 300, have also
been dropped by F-14 and F-18 combat planes flying off the USS
Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Only cruise missiles have so far been used over Baghdad,
reflecting the US commanders' extreme caution in this operation.
Officials Saturday said no planes have yet been downed.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, top US officials have said the goal of
Operation Desert Fox is to ``degrade'' and ``diminish'' Hussein's
ability to threaten his neighbors with chemical, nuclear, or
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen Saturday uttered both of those magic words, saying the
attack has ``substantially degraded'' his warfighting capabilities
and has ``diminished'' his ability to threaten his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   While the secretary declined to declare the mission
accomplished, his words did appear to give his president the option
to make such a declaration if he so desired.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when the air strikes might end, Cohen replied, with almost
circular logic, ``The operation is going to continue until the
president decides it has been completed.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon reveals more about what kinds of targets are
being hit and not hit, Operation Desert Fox is coming to look less
like a comprehensive attack on Saddam Hussein's ability to make
weapons of mass destruction _ and more like an attempt to
destabilize his grip on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the air strikes have been aimed at Hussein's private
security apparatus, the transmitters that let him communicate with
soldiers in the south of Iraq, and his intelligence headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has denied that destabilization is the operation's goal.
However, he acknowledged that would certainly be a ``consequence''
of degrading Hussein's military power.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, key elements of what officials say is the main target
_ Hussein's ability to make chemical, nuclear, and biological
weapons _ are going untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acknowledged Saturday that ``dual-use'' facilities _
plants that produce both chemical weapons and civilian products _
are not being attacked at all, in order to avoid hurting the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally believed dual-use facilities are the only
chemical sites remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Sites that may be producing nuclear and biological weapons are
also absent from the target-list, if they exist at all.
</P>
<P>
   Air strikes have been mounted, however, on sites believed to be
developing and building the missiles that could deliver these
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday morning, the Pentagon claimed to have attacked 11
such sites, inflicting severe damage on one, moderate damage on
five, and light damage on one. The strikes have not destroyed any.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gen. Thomas Wilson, the Joint Staff's intelligence
director, said Saturday that the strikes have set back Iraq's
ability to build long-range missiles by ``at least a year.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that official bomb-damage assessments are ``very
conservative.'' For example, when spy-satellite photos were taken
of the federal building that was blown up in Oklahoma City several
years ago, the assessors deemed the damage to be ``moderate.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Wilson also noted that those facilities can now build
only short-range missiles _ which are allowed by United Nations
resolutions _ and that, even if there were no air strikes, it would
take ``a couple of years'' for the Iraqis to convert them to
long-range weapons. He did emphasize that they seem to have
``plans'' to try and make this conversion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
