<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS-HNS     12-19 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LAMEDUCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRING HOUSE MEMBERS DEPART IN SHOCK ON AN HISTORIC DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Retiring House members were stunned Saturday that
their last day in office would combine an historic vote on
President Clinton's impeachment with the startling announcement by
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston that he was resigning his seat.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day that combined history, chaos and political
risk-taking of a magnitude that most of them had never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., the Rules Committee
chairman who was winding up 10 terms in Congress, said he was
leaving the chamber for the last time ``with very, very mixed
emotions'' and great sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the saddest days in the history of the country _
but one of the most courageous days,'' Solomon told a reporter.
``We did uphold the Constitution and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   He said fledging democracies around the world ``have looked to
us as the beacon of hope. If we ever let that beacon of hope die,
what's it going to lead to?''
</P>
<P>
   After the House voted two articles of impeachment and adjourned,
Solomon lingered on the House floor, talking with colleagues in the
ornate chamber where President Andrew Johnson was impeached in
1868.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying his trademark red cardboard accordion file with the
letters S-O-L-O-M-O-N written in big magic-marker letters on the
side, Solomon headed for his nearby private office and declared his
confidence that House members will rally and pick a good leader to
replace Livingston who gave up his plans to become speaker after
confessing to adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon cited Reps. Dennis J. Hastert, R-Ill., and Christopher
Cox, R-Calif., as possibilities to replace Livingston who had been
slated to succeed Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., when the new 106th Congress
convenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who plans to join a Washington lobbying firm, flashed a
big grin and declared that he will work for the election of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush to the presidency in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., the former head of the Democratic
Caucus who is leaving Congress after his 10th term, said he does
``not want to leave Congress saying there is no hope'' but that he
was ``very aggrieved at the way in which the House has been
portrayed and has behaved'' in impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that I leave the House in this kind of state,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio said it was unfortunate that Livingston, ``the one man who
could heal the institution,'' had resigned. Fazio said he had
personally appealed to Livingston to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place has been badly bruised by the partisan wars that
have swirled around us,'' Fazio said. ``This is a cancer that is
eating away at us. We are flawed human beings and we need to be
tolerant of one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Fazio said House members need to ``gather around those who are
wounded and say, `Don't let this drive you out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fazio said members of Congress should not allow people like
Larry Flynt to influence lawmakers' career decisions. Flynt, the
publisher of Hustler magazine, has offered a $1 million bounty for
proof of extramarital affairs by top government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., who cast his last House vote
Saturday before going to the Senate next month, expressed
disappointment at how his House career ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back on my 18 years with such a feeling of pride and
accomplishment,'' Schumer said. ``To see the House in this kind of
turmoil was not the way I wanted to look back on the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., another retiree, said the
impeachment vote, the attacks on Iraq and Livingston's resignation
``occurring a week before Christmas have had a surreal effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just cast a pall over the chamber to watch the
speaker-designate make such a bombshell announcement,'' Riggs said,
adding that it will take ``months and months'' to heal the
bitterness in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a remarkable ride,'' Riggs said. ``It's certainly
not how I wanted to make my swan song.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul McHale, a three-term Pennsylvania Democrat who also
ended his congressional career with the impeachment vote, said the
process ``has been very draining.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On a personal level, it's a deeply disheartening day in our
nation's history,'' said McHale, a former Clinton supporter who
voted to impeach the president on two articles of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system worked today as the founding fathers intended,''
said McHale, who plans to teach at a Pennsylvania college.
</P>
<P>
   ``A president who acted reprehensibly was impeached ultimately
because of his own conduct. This whole thing started because of
obvious defects in the president's character,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, who finished a 37-year career
in Congress by opposing Clinton's impeachment, said he wasn't
surprised at the high level of rancor in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it should be expected that you would have division on
an issue like this,'' Gonzalez said. ``If there was going to be
such a vote, I'm glad I could be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that a vote on impeachment was wrong. Impeachment
is a measure that shouldn't be based on personal deviation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
