<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1815EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKMAN-EDIT20-COX     12-19 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-EDIT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toss all the rules into the Potomac
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old rules no longer apply. In fact, after this there are no
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Politics doesn't stop at the water's edge any more. You can
indeed impeach a president by a narrow partisan vote. Congress can
not only thumb its nose at the public but also feels free to brag
about it. The job of House speaker, one of the most secure and
stable in Washington, has become a revolving door. By January we
will have had three people in that post in three months, one of
whom never officially had the job.
</P>
<P>
   And in a week in which we go to war and impeach a president, the
stock market rose 130 points.
</P>
<P>
   It is strange _ head-scratching strange. This confluence of
events _ war with Iraq coinciding with a bitter war among ourselves
_ has provided the crowning touch to one of the more bizarre years
in American history. Other eras have been more frightening, more
dangerous, more tragic. But for sheer jaw-dropping melodrama, this
spectacle is hard to top. Someone switched worlds on us when we
weren't looking.
</P>
<P>
   There's no single explanation for all this, no unified theory by
which it can be made rational. But when scientists and
mathematicians see this kind of thing happen _ when a previously
stable system suddenly goes all kablooey _ they suspect what is
called a phase transition, in which the system slides into chaos
before emerging once again into a new form of stability.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the country and the culture are undergoing permanent
change, and the chaos in Washington is both a symptom and a cause
of that change. What shape will those changes take? What will this
country look like if and when we emerge from this nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that the institution of the presidency will be greatly
weakened, pointing out that a series of weak presidents _ Grant,
Hayes, Garfield, Arthur _ filled the office in the wake of the
impeachment of Andrew Johnson in 1868. But that pattern is not
likely to repeat itself. The issues in the Johnson impeachment were
gravely constitutional, involving a struggle for power between the
presidency and Congress. There are no stately balance-of-power
issues in this tawdry personal tragedy, which in itself is an
argument against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   This must, however, have a long-term effect on politics and how
it is conducted. The stunning announcement by Rep. Robert
Livingston on Saturday that he would not accept the job of speaker
makes him just the latest victim of what has become known as ``the
politics of personal destruction.'' And while Clinton's mistakes
are his own responsibility. for which he must pay the consequences,
his impeachment is also a direct product of attack politics. We
must emerge from this mess with a more mature understanding of one
another.
</P>
<P>
   We are all human beings, with human frailties. But given the
intrusiveness and power of modern media, it has become all but
impossible for high-profile people to keep those personal frailties
personal. We have yet to adjust our political standards and
expectations to that new reality.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been considered fair game in politics to use an
opponent's personal weakness as a weapon to disqualify him from
public life and discredit his point of view. But think about that:
If we all have weakness, if all weakness is exposed, and if all
exposed weakness disqualifies a person from office, then none of us
is worthy.
</P>
<P>
   We can wish it weren't so; we can argue that the media ought to
show greater restraint and judgment in covering the frailties of
those in public life. But in a world shared with the likes of Matt
Drudge and Larry Flynt, that's wishful thinking. It's telling that
Livingston's history of infidelity was exposed by Flynt's Hustler
magazine, a publication that exists solely to flout the social
conventions that might bind the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   The only answer is to grow up and accept the fact of each
other's humanity. The personal humiliation of Livingston, Clinton,
Henry Hyde and others might be the cruel but necessary price of
creating that new understanding.
</P>
<P>
   However, in decrying the attack politics of our leaders, we as a
people ought to be honest with ourselves. The cruel partisanship,
the invective and win-at-any-cost mentality that we find so
disgusting in Washington is not some isolated development out of
step with the rest of our culture. The truth is, it reflects our
culture all too accurately.
</P>
<P>
   There's an eerie parallel with what's going on Iraq. Over the
past few days, American sailors and pilots have been firing weapons
at targets that are hundreds of miles from where they sit, targets
they never even see. But here at home we watch on eerie
green-tinted screens as those missiles slam into buildings. It
gives you the sense of war as a video game.
</P>
<P>
   But of course it's not a game. You can't bring the Baghdad dead
back to life by sticking in another quarter and hitting the ``new
game'' button. This business of making war without getting your
hands dirty is dangerous, particularly if it deludes us into
thinking that war can be a tidy undertaking without repercussion or
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   It is not.
</P>
<P>
   Much of modern political warfare has taken on that same
impersonal detachment, the same sense that we can inflict brutal
casualties on our opponents through television ads and radio talk
shows and direct-mail hit pieces without consequence to ourselves.
As leaders of both parties have discovered, it's just not so.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question, the question that really cuts to the core
of all this mess, is why the American public has become so bitter
and angry. Why did roughly a third of Americans thoroughly despise
Clinton long before the name Monica Lewinsky was ever heard?
Conversely, why have Democrats fought so ferociously to save a
president whose behavior even they will not defend? Why can't we
even talk to each other in a civil tone?
</P>
<P>
   The answer must be that the disorder of our politics, the idea
that no rules apply, accurately reflects the disorder of a society
trying to make sense of profound technological, social and economic
change. We're not really fighting over cigars or perjury, or even
the fate of a president. It's much more important than that.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're fighting over what form this new culture will take,
what the new rules are going to be and who gets to sit down at the
table when we write them. For those stakes, we're ready to fight
dirty if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is associate editorial page editor of The Atlanta
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
