<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGSTON-MAIN20-COX     12-19 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-MAIN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Livingston resigns from would-be speaker post, urging Clinton to
do the same
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stunned House Republicans scrambled to select a new
leader Saturday after Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.) shocked Congress
by resigning as the designated new Speaker during during a
passionate plea for President Clinton to leave office himself.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of Livingston's unexpected resigation, names
started ciruclating for his replacement.That list included House
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, the Illinois Republican who presided
over the impeachment inquiry, fellow Illinois Republican Dennis
Hastert and Rep. Christopher Cox (R-Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   But the maneuvering to succeed Livingston paled in comparison to
the drama created by Livingston's speech urging Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You, sir, may resign your post,'' he said speaking from the
well of the House as lawmakers prepared to vote on four articles of
impeachment against the president for the way he concealed an
adulterous affair with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   As Livingston spoke, Democrats, led by Rep. Maxine Waters of
California, raised their fists in the air and began hissing, then
chanting, ``No! No! No!'' Then they yelled ``You resign! You
resign! You resign!''
</P>
<P>
   When Livingston did just that, saying he had hurt his family,
Congress and the country with his own extramarital affairs, a
silence fell then over the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have hurt you deeply,'' said Livingston, who has been
married for 33 years to his wife, Bonnie. ``I must set the example
that I hope President Clinton will follow... I will not stand for
speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having called for his resignation moments before,
Democrats stood with Republicans to applaud Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Bob Livingston's resignation while offered in good
faith was wrong,'' said Rep. Jerry Nadler (D-N.Y.). ``It is a
surrender to a new sexual McCarthyism.''
</P>
<P>
   As Livingston strode off the floor to his Appropriations
Committee offices a few steps from the House floor, Democratic
Reps. Jesse Jackson Jr. of Illinois, David Skaggs of Colorado, and
Elijah Cummings of Maryland ran after him, attempting to convince
him to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston told them firmly, ``It is done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is horrible, we have a real constitutional crisis,'' said
an emotional Jackson, the son of one of the president's staunchest
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of the unexpected resignation, President Clinton
quickly urged Livingston to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president firmly believes the politics of personal
destruction has to come to an end,'' White House Spokesman Joe
Lockhart told reporters outside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   However, Livingston's resignation did little to change Clinton's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to keep on pushing his agenda forward and I think
it would be wrong to give in to this insidious politics of personal
destruction, which seems so pervasive in this town now,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats universally expressed shock and
sadness at Livingston's decision. His resignation sent the House
into pandemonium and the jockeying for his replacement began almost
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert appeared to be the favorite candidate to replace
Livingston, who was chosen last month by the Republican caucus to
replace Rep. Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich resigned last month following the House elections where
Republicans lost five seats to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.) said he urged Rep. Bill Archer
(R-Texas) to consider succeeding Livingston. ``I think that he'd
unify the party,'' Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders included Rep. Chris Cox (R-Calif.), the
chairman of a special committee investigating whether technology
was improperly given to the Chinese as a result of public policy
changes made by Clinton. And Rep. Steve Largent (R-Okla.), who
narrowly lost a bid last month to be majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) said that he was
throwing his support behind Hastert because he ``has the experience
and the character to lead this House.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich watched Livingston on television, telling his press
secretary, Christina Martin, that ``this is a noble, patriotic and
selfless act by speaker-elect Livingston.'' Throughout the day,
Gingrich had little public presence, always traveling with an
entourage and refusing to answer questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom Delay (R-Texas) learned that Livingston
would resign just minutes before the floor debate on impeaching the
president began.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no greater American in my mind, at least today, then
Bob Livingston because he understood what this debate was all
about,'' said Delay, in his speech to lawmakers.''It was about
honor, and decency and integrity and the truth. Everything that we
honor in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Directing his attention to the president, Delay said he hoped
that Clinton would follow the lead of both Gingrich and Livingston
who in his estimation put the good of the country ahead of their
political lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some it's no longer good enough to make a mistake, confess
that mistake and accept the consequences of that mistake and change
the way you live your life and keep moving and make a contribution
to this country,'' Delay said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle expressed concern about how
the private lives of lawmakers were becoming the main entree in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a toxic environment that few are immune from,''
said Rep. Jim Moran (D-Va.), an outspoken critic of the president's
affair with Lewinsky. At this point, he said, the only person who
could possibly pass a vetting process is Rep. Barney Frank
(D-Mass.). And that's because his homosexuality is well know, he
said. ``There is a certain kind of sexual guillotine going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays (R-Conn.) agreed, saying the ``American
Revolution is fast becoming the French Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension was thick throughout the day with Democrats fleeing the
floor to tell reporters that Livingston should remain and
Republicans noting that Livingston did the honorable thing.
</P>
<P>
   The overall sense in the marble hallways of the Capitol was a
House coming unglued at a time when U.S. troops are stationed in
Iraq and the president faced the political fight of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of like a disaster movie scripted by the Marx
Brothers,'' said Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is madness,'' said Rep. Peter King (R-N.Y.) ``We are
spiraling down a path of mutually assured destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Others thought Livingston's resignation was an appropriate
response to end the calamity that has now become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton (R-Texas) joked that candidates in the next
election would be forced to set up several lie detectors.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone caught nearly all members of his party completely
off guard, telling only a small handful of confidants of his
decision to resign before he formally announced in the midst of the
impeachment debate. Livingston said he did not make his decision
until Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gerald Solomon (R-N.Y.), one of those in whom Livingston
confided, said there would undoubtedly be efforts to talk
Livingston into staying, but Livingston's mind was ``made up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party will rally and will make the right
decision,'' said Solomon, who is leaving Congress as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
