<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGSTON-PROFILE20-     12-19 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-PROFILE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Livingston: A hard climb to fall
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice and Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His alcoholic father left home when Bob Livingston was
7 years old, and his mother had to go to work at a shipyard. From
such humble beginnings, the Louisiana Republican had been on the
brink of becoming one of the nation's most powerful politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's resignation announcement Saturday on the floor of
the House of Representatives came just two days after he confessed
that he had affairs while married to his wife of 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest twist in a life that has seen him go from the
bottom rungs of Louisiana social strata to being chosen as speaker
of the next House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had various stages,'' he said in a CNN interview last
month. ``I was a young lawyer and prosecutor for a lot of years,
and congressman now for the last 21 years _ 21-plus years. And in
that time, I think I've learned, through my experiences, that
nothing is like it was before. You've got to move on. You've got to
try to solve new problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving on is something Livingston, 55, knows about.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Colorado, Livingston grew up in an old section of New
Orleans, moving to the suburbs only when district lines were
redrawn to exclude the city. His father's side of the family comes
from an aristocratic line that includes Louisiana's founding
fathers: An early ancestor administered the presidential oath of
office to George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But his family fell on hard times, losing its fortune in the
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've become, I owe not to geneology, but to my mother,''
Livingston told a Louisiana newspaper last year.
</P>
<P>
   After his now-deceased father's desertion, Livingston's mother
worked at Avondale Shipyards and managed to scrape together enough
money to send her son to a Catholic school in the suburb of
Metairie, with the help of a partial scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started working when I was 14 years old shoveling up stuff
from the elephants _ my first affiliation with my party's symbol _
and I've been working virtually every summer until I got out of law
school,'' Livingston told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Navy from 1961-63, Livingston worked his
way through school, selling Fuller brushes and laboring as a welder
at the same shipyards where his mother had toiled.
</P>
<P>
   He married in 1965 and later received his bachelor's and law
degrees from Tulane University. In 1968, he passed the bar. After a
short stint in private practice, Livingston worked as a prosecutor;
as an assistant U.S. attorney from 1970-1973; with the Orleans
Parish district attorney's office from 1974-75; and the Louisiana
attorney general's office in 1975-76.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, he ran for Congress in the New Orleans suburbs and lost
by 3 percentage points. His opponent, however, resigned in the
midst of a voter fraud scandal, and Livingston won the seat in a
special election in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   It's a post he's held since, never facing serious challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a conservative, Livingston supported aid to the
Nicaraguan contras and mandatory sentences for convicted third-time
felons and opposed the ``motor voter'' registration bill, gays in
the military and Voting Rights Act interpretations that permit
gerrymandered black-majority congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Livingston has a legendary temper and has been
known to engage in occasional House floor theatrics, such as
playing the harmonica or wielding an alligator skinning knife to
illustrate how he would cut the budget. He also has a black belt in
tae kwon do.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he surprised many senior members of Congress when House
Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) chose him to become chairman of the
powerful House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Livingston challenged Gingrich for the speakership
after Republicans lost seats in the House in the midtrem elections.
Gingrich resigned, and a few days later Republican members chose
Livingston as their new leader for the term that begins in January.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his rapid climb, Livingston's supporters like to portray
him as a friend to the common man. They point out that when he ran
for Congress, he had just $5,000 in the bank, all of which went
into the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Representing a city renowned for its fine dining, Livingston's
staff is hard-pressed to name his favorite restaurant. They say
he's more likely to eat a Big Mac in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's main residence is outside Washington, but he keeps
a townhouse in Metairie, about 20 minutes from New Orleans. His
three sons live in Louisiana; his daughter, who is adopted, lives
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Louisiana fund-raiser, Livingston's wife, Bonnie,
stood by his side, smiling and patiently answering reporters'
questions. Bonnie Livingston recently went to lunch with Gingrich's
wife, Marianne, to learn what to expect as speaker's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me what was good and what was bad,'' Bonnie
Livingston said. ``She said the unfair criticism was bad. But Bob
comes in without being the person who caused the other party to go
out of office, so he'll have fewer problems, hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
