<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUCKER-EDIT20-COX     12-19 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUCKER-EDIT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scarlet Livingston latest to join Scarlet Letter Club
 &HT;    By Cynthia Tucker
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone with a lick of sense should have been able to see this
coming: The tinderbox of sexual scandal, fueled by the unseemly
tactics of independent counsel Kenneth Starr, has turned into a
raging wildfire, incinerating Democrat and Republican alike.
Alluding to revelations of his extramarital affairs, Rep. Bob
Livingston of Louisiana _ poised to become the next speaker of the
House _ stunned his colleagues on Saturday morning with the
announcement that he intends to resign from Congress in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Apologizing to his colleagues and members of his family _ ``I
have hurt you all deeply and beg your forgiveness'' _ Livingston
said, ``I was prepared to lead our narrow majority as speaker...
but I cannot do that job.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Livingston cast his decision as an honorable sacrifice
_ he also urged President Clinton to resign _ his announcement came
as some of the GOP's staunch conservatives began to question his
fitness to succeed Newt Gingrich as leader of congressional
Republicans. Livingston was forced to disclose his adultery on
Thursday because Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt is planning
an expose.
</P>
<P>
   Though his GOP colleagues initially rallied around him, it is no
surprise that carping and second-guessing broke out later. After
all, it would have been difficult for Livingston to lead a
holier-than-thou crusade after Hustler had outted him.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the problem with this sex-and-lies scandal all
along: Many Republicans cannot meet the standard of morality to
which they wish to hold Clinton. They were foolish to believe they
could seek to oust the president on the flimsiest of foundations _
behavior that stemmed from a sexual affair with a consenting adult
_ and not have that crusade come back to haunt them. They sow the
wind, and reap the whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of that excuses Clinton for conduct that has
been sordid, reckless and grossly selfish. He destroyed his
credibility and moral authority not by having sex (or non-sex, as
the president insists) with Monica Lewinsky but rather through the
casual misuse of aides and associates, repeated lies to them and to
the public and his failure to genuinely take responsibility
(despite carefully staged, heavily scripted, lip-biting public
performances).
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, have been no less reckless in response to
Clinton. They relied on an overzealous independent counsel willing
to trample the Constitution and come close to entrapment; they
published a report on the investigation filled with unnecessarily
graphic sexual detail; they flouted the public will by impeaching
the president. Most surprising under the circumstances, they went
forward _ zealously and self-righteously _ without considering the
skeletons in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   First there was Henry Hyde, the less-than-statesmanlike chairman
of the House Judiciary Committee, who claimed an affair he had when
he was 41 was a ``youthful indiscretion.'' During the Iran-Contra
hearings, Hyde defended the Reagan administration by saying it
didn't make sense to ``label every untruth and every deception an
outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Livingston, whose initial excuse was that, unlike
Clinton, he had not lied under oath or broken any law. Not to put
too fine a point on it, but adultery is against the law in
Louisiana. And does anyone believe that if Livingston had been
blindsided in a deposition in a civil lawsuit _ as Clinton was with
questions about Lewinsky _ that he would have immediately confessed
his serial affairs?
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans such as Georgia's Bob Barr (thrice married;
sued once for child support) are too consumed with their hatred of
Clinton to notice they've set fire to a building from which they
cannot escape. It is up to cooler heads in the Senate, then, to
extinguish this wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   End the impeachment madness. Get us out of the private lives of
public officials.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Tucker is editorial page editor of The Atlanta
Constitution. Her column appears Sunday and Wednesday. She can be
reached at cynthia(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
