<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOOTEN-EDIT20-COX     12-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOOTEN-EDIT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prognostications aside, Senate acquittal far from a done deal
 &HT;    By Jim Wooten
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only the stunning announcement by Speaker-designate Bob
Livingston (R-La.) added drama. Otherwise the national tragedy that
unfolded on cue Saturday was a scripted ritual acted out to the
accompaniment of a national yawn.
</P>
<P>
   This does not bode well for Bill Clinton. The Senate outcome his
defenders and the political prognosticators think certain _ that he
will be acquitted at trial _ is tenuous, a house of hopes and
illusions built on sinking sand.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion is shallow and unstable. Unlike the House, where
districts are drawn with a ideological purity that allows Democrats
and Republicans to snarl invective, to shout partisan viciousness
and to vote with impunity, the Senate is a far different place. The
shallowness, then, of public opinion combined with senators'
freedom from parochialism, makes the trial outcome far from
certain.
</P>
<P>
   This is a remarkable moment in time. The nation is carrying out
acts of war. The president of the United States, the military
commander in chief, invites constant public attention to the
essential job he has of ``running'' the country.
</P>
<P>
   And yet on the first day of war, the stock market rises 85
points and on the first day of impeachment the Dow rises 27 while
the Nasdaq records new highs. Those whose fortunes depend on
stability in the ``running'' of a country are not shaken by the
prospect that this president may be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   At the water cooler, too, the event is ordinary. Opinions, but
little passion. Mark McGwire or Sammy Sosa. Crime in Buckhead. An
event factored into the routine of daily life. And when is Macy's
last one-day sale before Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   A bizarre thing has happened _ and this is what Clinton's
defenders should fear: The nation has discounted the presidency to
its present-day value in people's lives. Like the pre-Christmas
display of bread machines, the presidency is marked down to
clearance prices. Grave as this moment is, people do not feel
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Too much exposure. Too much celebrity. Too much spin. Too many
stories. The presidency, once revered as essential to well-being,
is degraded, marked down. His impeachment affects our choice of
style and policy preferences, not well-being.
</P>
<P>
   With support shallow _ 60 percent of the people didn't want him
impeached, but 59 percent would prefer his resignation rather than
subject the nation to a drawn-out Senate trial _ public opinion can
stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television and the Internet offer reams of information and
misinformation and constant spin, reshaping the channels by which
the nation reaches consensus. During Watergate, the nation came to
consensus slowly and thoroughly. The constant flow of information,
though _ three to five cable shows per night offering spin _ means
people know enough to form an opinion, but not necessarily to
develop conviction. Public opinion, therefore, changes. People
shift and coalesce quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of commitment means that people are forming opinions
based on the options presented them. Article One of the impeachment
resolution can be presented in concise, easy-to-understand terms.
The issue is, did he lie or didn't he? That is the kind of equation
around which consensus quickly forms.
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment now a fact, the rule of law is upheld. No man
is above it. The language of impeachment does not depend for
meaning on any middleman, and is neither strengthened nor weakened
by talk-show chatter or the spin of partisan historians.
</P>
<P>
   If the president will now accept and acknowledge his lies, a
Senate trial can be avoided. The proposal offered by former U.S.
Sen. Bob Dole offers a framework.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the president can continue in office depends on his, and
his defenders', response to impeachment. If the personal attacks on
adversaries are to continue, if the nation is to endure two more
years of partisan vituperation and score-settling, what Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.) calls ``the politics of personal
destruction,'' the country would be better served now by proceeding
to a Senate trial. It need not be drawn-out or salacious. That is
within the purview of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president, too, could hasten reconciliation by resigning, as
Livingston did. ``I must set the example that I hope the president
will follow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next few days are critical. If the president is contrite, if
the gravity of what has just happened does, indeed, cause partisans
to step back from the politics of personal destruction and
incivility, some resolution short of removal from office may indeed
be possible.
</P>
<P>
   The American people are an unpredictable jury. Acquittal in the
Senate is not a slam-dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wooten is editorial page editor of The Atlanta Journal. His
column runs on Wednesday, Friday and Sunday. He can be reached at
jwooten(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
