particularly Nicaragua. Nearly a century after French engineer
Philippe Bunau-Varilla frantically persuaded the United States to
take over a failed French attempt to build a canal in Panama,
Nicaragua's dreams for a canal of its own still haven't died. And
other countries, too, are offering fresh proposals to challenge the
Panama Canal. But whether any of them fly remains to be seen.
