<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SHUSTER-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        SHUSTER BREAKS SILENCE, VOTES TO IMPEACH; MURTHA VOTES
AGAINST   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec 19., -- For the second time in his career in
Congress, Rep. Bud Shuster, found himself supporting the
impeachment of a president.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman member of the House in 1974, Shuster, R-Everett,
would have voted for the impeachment of Republican President
Richard Nixon had he not resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years later, Shuster, who waited until the final
hour to make up his mind, voted Saturday to impeach President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``[This] I believe demonstrates my belief that a constitutional
issue of this gravity should not be decided on a partisan basis,''
Shuster said in a prepared statement. ``
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring the rest of Congress, the Pennsylvania delegation
voted almost squarely along party lines to impeach Clinton for
lying under oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and
obstructing justice. Shuster voted for the articles outlining those
charges, and Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, voted against them.
</P>
<P>
   The articles will be sent to a trial in the Senate, where a
two-thirds majority is needed to convict the president and remove
him from office. Articles accusing Clinton of perjury in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment lawsuit and abuse of power failed on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   The tumultuous day began with Speaker-designate Bob Livingston's
announcement that he would resign following his recent admission of
extra-marital affairs. In a symbolic move, embattled Democrats
walked off the House floor to protest Republican leaders refusal to
allow members to vote for a censure resolution that could have
prevented a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha joined Democrats who streamed off the House floor,
outside the Capitol and in front of a crowd of cheering onlookers,
visitors and television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   An expressionless Murtha and other Democrats re-entered the
building and took their places to vote against the impeachment
articles.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha, evaded reporters after the vote, and said only, ``I have
a plane home to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement released by his office, Murtha denounced
party politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential removal of a President, and the overturning of
the election results which are the very basis of our entire
democracy -- demand unity in Congress and the nation, not
politics,'' it stated.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha also said the impeachment vote would strain the
relationship between Congress and the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges here simply do not rise to that level of
impeachment,'' Murtha said. ``This exercise does not bode well for
hopes in the coming year for a bipartisan approach to dealing with
such vital issues as stabilizing Social Security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
