<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA20-COX     12-19 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: Caught up in a nonstop rush of news
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fall of the house of Nixon pointed out that the
media not only reports on culture, but is part and parcel of it.
Television, tape recordings and two Washington Post reporters had
as much to do with the downfall of his administration as did the
shenanigans of all the president's men.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century later, the Clinton impeachment case is
being played out in a heightened-information environment. These are
the days of hot-off-the-press books by aides and enemies; of
round-the-clock CNN coverage; of Ken Starr culling evidence from
e-mail, taped conversations and answering machine messages; of
Internet flashes that topple the House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   This is the hyper-media age, when _ like a kid overdosed on
sugar _ events move at ``electric speed,'' when the world seems
like ``a growing plant in an enormously accelerated movie.'' Those
phrases are from Marshall McLuhan, a communications scholar whose
mark was made in the 1960s. He believed that speed would lead to
``an understanding of causes.''
</P>
<P>
   But speed can destruct as well as instruct. The recent news has
begotten metaphors for forces beyond our control: impeachment
inevitability becomes a ``snowball rolling downhill.'' Add the
bombing of Iraq or the resignation of House Speaker-to-be Bob
Livingston, and the metaphors take on a nightmare hue.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague compared last week's political crises to being on a
train that is screaming at top speed to who-knows-where. The
breakneck speed was stoked by the media, who now are hanging on for
the ride by their fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   In times like these, journalistic modes of operation shift.
Commentary, that staple of news TV and editorial pages, becomes
less relevant when there's no time or _ in a spin culture _ even no
basis for perspective. All TV can do, some say, is point a camera.
</P>
<P>
   But another apparatus is being pointed: the computer mouse. The
impeachment story has bookmarked this as a watershed year for the
Internet. Matt Drudge pulled the Monica Lewinsky rug out from under
Newsweek when he went online with the story. Salon detailed the
infidelities of House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, and
last week Roll Call revealed Livingston's marital strayings.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reports that Hustler magazine, published by
Larry Flynt, who has offered up to $1 million for information about
the sexual indiscretions of congressional members, may soon make
more online disclosures. Nothing caused as much thunder on the
Internet this year as the Starr Report, which generated a record 32
1/2 million hits for CNN Interactive, according to editor-in-chief
Scott Woelfel. This week's numbers challenged that high, with 25.7
million hits Thursday and 23 1/2 million on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Americans are in disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, the Net can be the most hyper of media, fueling
the frenzy that values breaking a story over getting it right. News
providers who take time to check facts or to consider ramifications
now risk being scooped by the Drudges of the world. The Internet is
jostling journalists and journalism.
</P>
<P>
   And the traditional media's collective finger seems to have
slipped off the public pulse. During election week, when political
pundits misjudged Republican gains and House Speaker Newt Gingrich
resigned, CNN congressional correspondent Bob Franken found himself
explaining to an on-air caller: ``We're supposed to be on top of
things, and we definitely were not then.''
</P>
<P>
   Franken ``then'' implied the state of unpreparedness was
temporary. But it hasn't been. We're all hanging on for the ride,
expecting only the unexpected. As CNN Chairman Tom Johnson said
last week when both Washington and Iraq became crises: ``In my
wildest imagination I could not have predicted you would have the
confluence of these two events.''
</P>
<P>
   And that points to perhaps the greatest irony of the hyper-media
age: Surrounded with 24-hour news channels, our laptops connected
to news sites and wire services, with cell phones and radios in our
cars, we inhabit a gray zone where reality seems inseparable from
spin.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1868, when Andrew Johnson was impeached by the House,
books and newspapers comprised the media. Since then, technology
has reached electric speed, but our understanding of causes, not to
mention effects, remain in pony-express mode.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
