<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV20-COX     12-19 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBS drops the ball with Jets vs. Bills instead of televising the
GOP vs. Bill
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was CBS: On one of the most important days in
U.S. history, for the first impeachment of a president during the
age of television, the network with the longest and noblest
tradition in broadcast news carried a pro football game instead of
the House votes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the day CBS fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of television was there Saturday, all day and all the
way, giving plenty of choices for viewers who wanted to watch the
day's events unfold. CNN and C-SPAN, of course, and ABC, NBC, PBS
and even the wily Fox. But CBS carried the Jets vs. the Bills.
Saturday was a day of history and a day for history, so it's
appropriate to note that CBS was the home of Edward R. Murrow and
Eric Sevareid, the network where former news president Fred
Friendly resigned over a less significant conflict between news and
expediency, the seat of Walter Cronkite, Charles Kuralt, ``60
Minutes'' and Dan Rather.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, at high noon on Saturday, before the House even voted
to impeach President Clinton, CBS broke away to start the pregame
hoopla. (Rather was allowed to break in briefly to announce the
vote results on all four articles of impeachment, then got a few
minutes for a wrap-up when the game broke for halftime).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention was to serve as many viewers as possible,'' CBS
spokeswoman Sandy Genelius explained. ``We had a contractual
obligation to carry the game in its entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, who once stormed off the evening news set when CBS
postponed his newscast to show the conclusion of a tennis match,
was not given to large gestures on Saturday. Maybe somebody at CBS
News needs to make a grand gesture to protest one of the worst
decisions ever made in television news.
</P>
<P>
   When the across-the-board coverage began Saturday morning, TV
anchors and analysts gave the impression that what was to happen
was completely scripted. CNN's Frank Sesno was among those who
explained the planned walk-out by House Democrats shortly before
the impeachment vote. ``It will be, if nothing else, theatrical,''
said ABC's Peter Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Several broadcasters predicted a surprise-free day _ until House
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston (R-La.) announced he was resigning
and ``literally sucked the air out of this chamber,'' as Sesno
vividly put it.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's shocker two days after admitting to extramarital
affairs appeared to suck the air out of the TV pundits as well.
ABC's Cokie Roberts seemed to be shaking after the speech; CNN
correspondent Candy Crowley said she was ``speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is surreal,'' Democratic Minority Whip David Bonior said
from the House floor. ``The scenario reads like the plot of a cheap
paperback thriller.'' But such thrillers can be potent
page-turners, and with Livingston's resignation and the start of a
fourth day of U.S. bombing of Iraq, it was a day when turning off
the set seemed impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Better to keep a thumb on the remote, flipping frantically to
catch Judge Robert Bork on NBC calling Clinton ``the most corrupt
president in history,'' and being challenged by a skeptical Brokaw;
to see Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) trying to bring down the House with
an emotional speech, roaring above the dink-dink-dink of a gavel
reminding him his time was up; to CNN doing split screen between
Christiane Amanpour in Baghdad and the House debate; to Watergate
icon Carl Bernstein on CBS and Tim Russert on NBC, both looking
ahead to the Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' Bob Schieffer pointed out (during halftime) that, given
Congressional timetables, the trial is unlikely to start before
February. When it does, CBS will probably be there. Because
football will be over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
