A8591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-ATTACKS-BOS &LR;      12-19 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ATTACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID MISSILE STRIKES, IRAQIS SEE DIVINE JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ As missiles rumbled outside for the fourth and final
night, Mohammed Naji and his family watched the scrambled reception
of Iraqi TV to see the man commanding the US bombing against them
be impeached by his fellow Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton sent his bombs here to topple Saddam,'' said Naji,
staring while tracers and Iraqi anti-aircraft fire rattled outside
his downtown apartment. ``But your Mr. Clinton has toppled himself.
This is the will of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Through shortwave radios and intermittent Iraqi broadcasts, Naji
and millions of Iraqis saw divine justice in the political blow
delivered to Clinton _ who directed the punishing air strikes at
the heart of Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein's regime.
</P>
<P>
   The dizzying pace of Saturday's news developments _ with the
chaos in Washington, the devastation caused here by US and British
bombing before the end of the offensive Saturday night _ created a
feeling that the political status quo from Washington to Baghdad
was coming unglued.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqis are tuned in to the term ``Wag The Dog'' _ the title of a
political satire of a faked US military attack to protect a
troubled presidency _ and fully conscious of America's questions as
to whether Clinton timed the bombings of Baghdad for the same
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Naji, a 46-year-old printing press operator, along with his wife
and six children, gathered in the living room of their middle-class
apartment while his oldest son adjusted a broken antenna on a 1970s
vintage Sanyo to try to get a picture of American democracy in
action.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi TV reception is severely disrupted since US cruise
missiles have pounded at the government-controlled television and
radio stations' central transmitters near Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   But through the gray static and muffled sound of Iraqi TV and by
tuning into a battered shortwave radio, the family could still get
the picture: that Bill Clinton was the first US president in more
than 130 years to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American and the Iraqi people are the same. The mistakes
are made by the political leaders and the people suffer,'' said
Naji. ``Clinton lies and we are the victims. Tell me, is he bombing
us to save himself?''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set here, Iraq broke the fast of the first day of the
Muslim holy month of Ramadan, hoping that the night skies would be
calm. But before the Najis finished their dinner, the air-raid
sirens wailed. And the distant sound of cruise missiles slamming
into Saddam's military and political infrasctructure from the Iraqi
capital in Baghdad to the southern port city of Basrah.
</P>
<P>
   The Naji family said that despite the bombardment, Saddam would
stand and Iraq would endure. The newscast on Iraqi television was
brief and nearly impossible to follow because of the disruption of
the signal. But strangely, the stock videotaped footage of Saddam
Hussein waving heroically to the Iraqi people under the Arches of
Victory in Baghdad was clear and easy to see. The contrast between
Iraq's access to American democracy at work and the heavy-handed
propaganda of the dictatorship was stark.
</P>
<P>
   Naji and his teenage sons prompted his 2-year-old daughter,
Jasmin, to tell an American vistor to their home who was the man in
the military uniform and the thick black mustache on the
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam. Saddam,'' Jasmin said staring at the television.
</P>
<P>
   In a home with a framed portrait of Saddam on the wall next to a
photograph of the Muslim holy city of Mecca, Naji expressed anger
at the United States for targeting Saddam and was furious that the
atttacks have extended into the Muslim holy month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are bombing on Ramadan,'' said Naji, referring to the
observance of the time when the Muslim holy book, the Koran, was
delivered to the Prophet Mohammed in the 7th Century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only an insult to the Iraqi people, this is an
insult to all Muslims all over the world. And it proves once again
that Clinton is a liar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Clinton announced the decision to bomb Iraq for
preventing UN weapons inspectors from carrying out their work, he
said the United States had to act quickly in part because Ramadan
was approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said on Monday, ``For us to initiate military action
during Ramadan would be profoundly offensive to the Muslim world
and therefore would damage our relations with Arab countries and
the progress we have made in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq interpreted that as a promise that attacks would end at the
start of Ramadan at dawn Saturday. But the US officials insist that
they made no such promise and vowed that the attacks would continue
until all of the targets are destroyed and the mission is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely what that mission is remains unclear. The United
States insists that it is not intending to destabalize Saddam's
regime in its massive air attack, which is accompanied by British
forces. But the ``target list,'' as the Pentagon calls it, has
included the regime's Baath Party headquarters, presidential
palaces, a social services building, and communication centers. The
US claims all of these are suspected sites where Saddam has hidden
Iraq's program for weapons of mass destruction. But the Iraqi
government claims these are attacks on the civilian and political
life of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Saturay night, in the Iraqi Ministry of Information, foreign
correspondents from around the world and Iraqi officials crowded
around a cable-connected television that picks up CNN by satellite.
A cluster of muscle-bound and black-leather-clad Iraqi Mukabarat,
or secret service, agents watched as the US House of
Representatives voted to adopt the First Article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   They looked bored watching American democracy moving in its
slow, grinding pace to impeach the president. One of them yawned
and later asked a fellow Iraqi official in Arabic, ``So what does
this mean? Is he overthrown?''
</P>
<P>
   As the House vote tallies flashed on CNN at 9:15 p.m. local
time, a sudden burst of Iraqi anti-aircraft fire roared outside.
What appeared to be roughly two blocks away, a cruise missile
slammed into another target in downtown Baghdad. Someone yelled,
``Get down!''
</P>
<P>
   And many of the foreign reporters ducked for cover.
</P>
<P>
   After the volley of explosions, Aziz El Herzaji, an official
with the Ministry of Information, pointed to the televised coverage
of the impeachment hearings and said, ``Look at your democracy at
work and look at what it is doing outside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is there behind those buildings across the street,''
added Herzaji, a man in his late 60s, wearing a frayed tweed jacket
and fingering caramel-colored Muslim prayer beeds. ``Clinton? Well,
let him fall. Look at what he is doing to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
