u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-LIONS20-C     12-19 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-LIONS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons shoot for a stress-free win
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ This place is miserable this time of year, and
for that matter it's been miserable for the Falcons just about
forever.
</P>
<P>
   But the Silverdome might seem like heaven's doorstep today if
the Falcons' game with the Lions goes as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (12-2) hasn't played in a game this important since
1980. If the Falcons beat Detroit (5-9) today, coach Dan Reeves
probably will lock up the NFL's coach of the year award without
even coaching.
</P>
<P>
   He's recuperating at his Buckhead home from heart-bypass surgery
on Monday, and he'll have to watch on television as his team tries
to clinch its second NFC West title; the other was in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons win, something they haven't done here since 1986
before losing five in a row, the Falcons will have a bye in the
first round of the playoffs and home game the next weekend. Reeves
could use that time.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose and San Francisco (11-3) wins at New England, the
49ers can clinch the NFC West with a win next week at home against
the Rams, a team that San Francisco has beaten 16 times in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is supposed to avoid any stress. No wonder he said he'll
have team physician Charlie Harrison sitting on the sofa beside
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team will respond,'' free safety Eugene Robinson
said. ``It's going to be paramount that we limit the stress in his
life as much as possible. The way we're going to do that is by
winning this ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   By appearances, the Falcons should roll over the Lions, a bad
team getting worse. They've been steamrolled the past two weeks,
37-22 by Jacksonville and 35-13 at San Francisco, eliminating them
from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   They're losing injured players, too, as an MRI on Friday
revealed rookie quarterback Charlie Batch has a compression
fracture in his back. He's out for the final two games; 14-year
veteran Frank Reich will start.
</P>
<P>
   Also, middle linebacker Stephen Boyd, the team's leading
tackler, and promising rookie receiver Germane Crowell might be
finished for the season because of bad shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The test today is not as much to see if Atlanta can beat Detroit
as it is to see if the systems Reeves has put in place can function
without him.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks is interim head coach.
He will remain in the coaches' box to call defenses and will only
be involved in the offense when there is a critical decision.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, quarterbacks coach Jack Burns will call the plays, but
instead of relaying them through Reeves to quarterback Chris
Chandler, they'll be relayed through backup quarterback Steve
DeBerg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, something like that could have been a huge
distraction,'' said running back Jamal Anderson, the second-leading
rusher in the NFL with 1,596 yards. ``But it's not. One of the
things Dan did was put together a top notch staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident everybody understands their role as defined
for the last two years by coach Reeves,'' he said. ``Unfortunately,
he won't be there to see it fulfilled or fall short. I know that's
one thing he would not want to happen. We have to do it for him,
and for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison drove Reeves to team headquarters in Suwanee on
Saturday, three minutes before the 9 a.m. meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The coach met with players and coaches for 10 minutes and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a lot of fanatical Falcons fans,'' Reeves
said. ``And this week I'll be one of the biggest ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, look for Reeves to return to Suwanee on at least a
part-time basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Dan,'' Anderson said. ``He expects the ship to be
sailing straight ahead when he gets back. We intend to see that it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
