<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-BO     12-19 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP RUSHES TO FILL VOID TO BE LEFT BY LIVINGSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans, stunned by the decision of
Speaker-designate Robert L. Livingston to step aside because he had
been unfaithful to his wife, Saturday scrambled to align behind a
new leader and struggled to draw the lines between public lives and
private morality.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the current House leadership, including Speaker Newt
Gingrich, pressed for a quick endorsement of Representative Dennis
Hastert as speaker for the next Congress. Allies of Hastert, a
former high school wrestling coach and restaurateur, late Saturday
released a list of 80 lawmakers who are supporting him in the Jan.
5 election. It will take 112 votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said Livingston decided to step aside after
being informed Friday that about a dozen conservative Republicans
had reservations about electing him speaker. On Thursday,
Livingston, who is 55 and a father of four grown daughters,
revealed that he had on several occasions ``strayed'' during his
33-year marriage. He said the announcement was prompted by word
that Hustler magazine, which had posted a $1 million bounty for
information about lawmakers' private lives, was preparing a report
on Livingston's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must set the example that I hope President Clinton will
follow,'' Livingston said in a floor speech delivered just hours
before the House voted to impeach the president. ``I will not stand
for speaker of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers of both parties fretted about what Livinsgton's
departure augured for those who serve in public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's next? Go to the video rental store and check out what
videos they were renting? Do we check the 900 lines?'' asked
Representative Richard Baker, a Republican from Livingston's home
state of Louisiana. ``Where in God's name does the public right to
know end and individual rights begin? We have eviscerated that
line.''
</P>
<P>
   After the impeachment votes, Republicans met privately to decide
how to proceed in the wake of their own sex scandal. During the
meeting, aides said Gingrich rose, listed the five characteristics
of a good speaker, and said Hastert was ``the only one man who has
them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Dick Armey has also endorsed Hastert, and
Majority Whip Tom DeLay told reporters: ``He will make a great
speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, 56, now serves as a deputy whip, whose job is to count
votes for the GOP leadership and maintain contacts with Republican
lawmakers. About 15 or 20 members who are part of the whip
organization met in Hastert's office after Livingston's
announcement and by midafternoon had drafted a letter urging
support for Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said in a statement that a ``sense of duty now calls me
to serve our free nation by seeking a position of great
responsibility. ... It is a calling that I have not sought;
however, it is a duty that I cannot ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   It was expected that other candidates might vie for the post,
including Representatives Christopher Cox of California.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Mark Souder, an Indiana Republican who supports
Hastert, said that Hastert was not telegenic but that he could heal
divisions in the House. He described Hastert as ``a teddy bear, a
vote-counter, a peacemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, an architect of the House GOP's impeachment strategy,
told colleagues family obligations kept him from running for
speaker. Some members suggested DeLay was too partisan to repair
the deeply divided House.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was selected by House Republicans on Nov. 18 to
replace Gingrich, who resigned after the November elections. He was
not to take office formally until next month.
</P>
<P>
   It became increasingly clear last week that Livingston had two
predicaments. One was acknowledging his own sexual peccadillos
while leading a party that was impeaching the president for
misconduct related to his. The other was getting the often
unmanageable GOP social conservatives under control next year in
the closely divided House while he was under a moral cloud of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Jerrold Nadler, a New York Democrat, told
Livingston not to give in to the destructive forces that were
pushing honorable people out of public life, and he urged him to
reconsider his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a surrender to a developing sexual McCarthyism,'' Nadler
said to his House colleagues. ``Are we going to have a new test if
someone wants to run for public office: Are you now or have you
ever been an adulterer?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing sight of the distinction between sins, which
ought to be between a person and his family and his God, and
crimes, which are the concern of the state and society as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston told his colleagues he was ``prepared to lead our
narrow majority as speaker, and I believe I had it in me to do a
fine job. But I cannot do that kind of job or be the kind of leader
that I would like to be under current circumstances.'' Livingston
said he would retire from Congress next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Livingston did his fair share in creating this atmosphere
of hatred and hostility by participating in this abuse of the
impeachment process,'' said Kim Gandy, executive vice president of
the National Organization for Women. ``Having helped foul this
pond, now he doesn't want to swim in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gandy, who was among a group of feminists who last week pressed
Livingston to censure rather than impeach Clinton, said she feared
a bad precedent was being set for all public servants. ``If you
require that every politician who cheated on his spouse must
resign, you are going to have some loud echoes in Congress and
state legislatures all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative broadcaster Paul Weyrich, who is closely associated
with the Christian right, said he was stunned by Livingston's
decision but said it was exactly, and refreshingly, the right thing
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, what a terrible thing that morality is having an influence
on politics!'' Weyrich said sarcastically. ``Finally, reality is
catching up with what has been the biggest lie ever perpetrated on
American society: that private actions do not have public
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Republican Representatives Henry Hyde of
Illinois, Dan Burton of Indiana, and Helen Chenowith of Idaho all
confessed to having had extramarital affairs. Weyrich said such
indiscretions that occurred before they entered Congress should not
disqualify members from public service, but some lawmakers said the
atmosphere was still chilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think ... either of them deserved public disclosure,''
Representative Baker said. ``It only caused great harm to their
families and to people who changed their career plans to work with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Nita Lowey, a New York Democrat, said Livingston
had ``no choice'' but to resign in the climate Republicans have
created in pursuing and impeaching the president for misconduct in
his private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The path the Republican leadership has chosen to take us on is
destroying this House,'' Lowey said. ``This is a time for
solemnity, not glee, when you see an individual being destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Frank Luntz said he was ``horrified'' by
what happened to Livingston and predicted the preoccupation with
scandal and private lives could affect the elections in 2000 and
``be an absolute nightmare for the American people, hearing nothing
substantive about politics and everything they don't want to
hear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
