<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-US-COST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST OF WEAPONS MAY BE AROUND $500 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pentagon officials decline to put a dollar figure
on Operation Desert Fox, but the four days probably cost around
$500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tomahawk cruise missiles, fired from B-52 bombers and Navy
ships, cost about $1 million apiece. Roughly 400 were fired _ or
about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's F-14 and F-18 combat planes flew about 200 sorties
over targets outside Baghdad, dropping GBU-15 and GBU-24
laser-guided bombs, which cost about $250,000 and $60,000 apiece,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Officials will not say how many of these bombs were dropped. The
planes can carry between two and four per sortie, so the cost could
run anywhere between $25 million to $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   To replace all these weapons would, therefore, cost between $425
million and $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   This does not include the costs of fuel, repairs, spare parts,
overtime pay and other aspects of basic operations and maintenance,
which are nearly impossible for an outsider _ and very difficult
even for an insider _ to calculate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
