<SLUG> BC-MA-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS MAKE POINT AT POST OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It was an act of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   They knew their packages addressed to Iraq would not be
accepted. Still, the protesters stood in line Saturday at the
Central Square Post Office, along with people buying stamps and
mailing Christmas packages decorated with wreaths and smiling
Santas.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 brown-paper-wrapped packages each bore a label plainly
describing its contents: Children's Aspirin, Medical Journals,
Water, Dried Fruit, Milk, Bandages, School Books, Pens and Pencils.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, each package was rejected by postal clerks, who
politely noted that United Nations economic sanctions prohibit
mailing packages to Iraq that weigh more than 12 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The orderly protesters retrieved the boxes and rerouted them,
some to US Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry, others to
President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeline Albright, with a
request that they be forwarded to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the busy Post Office, some 300 activists decried the
bombing of Iraq and called for an end to the eight-year-old
sanctions that have left the country with shortages of medicine,
clean water, and other basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we think dropping bombs on people and denying them
medicine will make them like the United States?'' asked Jennifer
Horan, 38, a volunteer for the Cambridge-based Campaign for the
Iraqi People. ``If we are so afraid of terrorism, then what better
way to foster it than starve people and deprive them of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The UN imposed economic sanctions on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. A UN Security Council resolution then barred any UN
member country from trading with Iraq. The only exception is the
``oil for food'' deal begun in 1996, which permits Iraq to sell a
small fraction of its oil for food and medicine. The sanctions will
remain in place until Iraq complies fully with UN weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi leaders blame the sanctions for food shortages,
malnutrition, and premature deaths.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF estimates that more than 1 million children under age 5,
nearly one-third of the youngsters that age in Iraq, are
chronically malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   Signe Taylor, 33, who interviewed Iraqi families in 1992 for a
documentary film about the impact of the Persian Gulf War and the
sanctions, said: ``It's tragic. Children are dying from man-made
causes, not from something like a natural disaster. It's something
we can control. And it's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Diener, 34, who carried a sign that read, ``Don't Wag the
Dog,'' said, ``I think Clinton is trying to cover up his abuse of
power in the bedroom by abusing power in the war room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
