<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-FAIL-BOS &LR;      12-19 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-FAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REJECTION OF TWO ARTICLES RAISES DEMOCRAT HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House's rejection Saturday of two of the four
articles of impeachment might provide a glimmer of hope among
Democrats that the case against President Clinton has been weakened
and that a Senate trial could be shortened. But Republicans and
some legal analysts doubted it would make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved two articles of impeachment charging that
Clinton committed perjury before the Whitewater grand jury and
obstructed justice. As expected, the House rejected the abuse of
power article that charged Clinton with supplying false answers to
81 questions submitted by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the House, by a 229-205 vote, rejected the article that
accused Clinton of perjury in his deposition for Paula Jones's
civil suit alleging sexual harassment. Clinton's testimony in that
case, after all, set in motion the chain of events leading to the
president's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in testimony he later called ``legally accurate,''
swore he did not have sexual relations with Monica S. Lewinsky.
Clinton's lawyers argued later that Clinton did not commit perjury
because oral sex was not included in the definition of sexual
relations and because the testimony was not ``material.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an argument that may have helped persuade about two dozen
Republicans to vote against Article II.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan Baron, a former Democratic counsel involved with the
impeachment trials of two federal judges before the Senate in 1988
and 1989, said he did not think it would make much difference that
the House rejected the civil perjury article.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, the Massachusetts Democrat,
said failure to approve the civil perjury article ``significantly
weakens the case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely bizarre to have the House on record saying
the president perjured himself before the grand jury in explaining
his civil deposition testimony, yet at the same time expressly
rejecting an article of impeachment alleging civil deposition
perjury,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8610 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEAKER-ADULTERY20-CO     12-19 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEAKER-ADULTERY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEMBERS WORRY ABOUT ADULTERY 'LITMUS TEST' FOR CONGRESS
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers warned Saturday that a spreading ``sexual
McCarthyism'' may become the new litmus test for public office
following House Speaker-designate Bob Livingston's announcement
that he would resign over adultery charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot be the kind of leader that I would like to be,''
Livingston said. ``So I must set the example.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other Republicans _ Henry Hyde of Illinois, Dan Burton of
Indiana and Helen Chenoweth of Idaho, were re-elected to the House
last month despite recent confessions of extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But as Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt reportedly has
gathered information on a dozen elected or appointed officials with
his $1 million offer for details of extramarital affairs with them,
the decision by Livingston, R-La., seemed likely to reignite the
debate over the boundaries of morality and fitness for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no perfect people and we all make mistakes,'' said
Randy Tate, executive director of the Christian Coalition. ``But
it's unavoidable today that your personal life won't be on display.
And we have always wanted our elected officials to live up to the
highest moral standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans praised Livingston for his difficult decision but
acknowledged that it would raise the bar for those seeking to
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to have to be a thorough vetting process'' for
the next speaker, said Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston ``understood what this debate was all about _ it's
about honor and decency and integrity and the truth, everything we
honor in this country,'' said House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't criticize the president's behavior as being
unacceptable and then not consider this as material, just ignore
this and brush it aside,'' said Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, members from both parties warned that private
behavior was not a proper standard for public service.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., called Livingston's resignation ``a
surrender to a developing sexual McCarthyism.'' He asked, ``Are we
going to have a new test: If someone wants to run for public
office, are you now or have you ever been an adulterer?''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who admitted to an affair decades ago, said Saturday,
``Those of us who are sinners must feel wretched today. Something
is going on repeatedly that has to be stopped, and that is a
confusion between private acts of infidelity and public acts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop destroying imperfect people at the alter of
unattainable morality,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   And after the impeachment vote, nearly the entire Democratic
caucus stood behind President Clinton as he made clear that he
would not resign and declared, ``We must stop the politics of
personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., one of Clinton's most vociferous
defenders, said Livingston's demise may spark a backlash over the
influence that Christian conservatives are having on the Republican
Party. ``This will mark the high point of the religious right,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
