r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-CASSTEVENS-AZ     12-19 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA CLAUS WANTS HIS FAIR SHARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A five-hour meeting in New York between Santa and department
store owners ended today with neither side reporting progress.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an agreement is reached soon, it appears Santa Claus
``won't'' be coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, St. Nick has brought joy to children of all
ages, free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are over.
</P>
<P>
   Santa has turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   According to Santa's agent _ Santa now has an agent _ ``My
client feels he is an integral part of the spirit of Christmas and
is largely responsible for its financial success. I think it is
reasonable to suggest Mr. Claus is as important to the economic
prosperity of Christmas as Michael Jordan is to the NBA or Randy
Johnson to major league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is good.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how to divide $2.6 trillion in holiday season
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Santa reportedly is asking for 58 percent of profits from retail
sales. Negotiators for merchants have called the demands
``outrageous'' and said, ``Santa doesn't understand the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Store owners have offered 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The public already has felt the effects of the four-month-long
labor dispute. Santa has canceled most public appearances. &QL; 
That smile will cost you &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the jolly old man appeared (for a fee) at a Nike
store to promote his new line of athletic shoes _ Air Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Santa signed autographs, for $5 each.
</P>
<P>
   He also charged $4 per ``Ho!'' or three for $10.
</P>
<P>
   Before lifting any child onto his knee and asking, ``And what
would you like for Christmas?'' Santa's agent collected $7.50.
</P>
<P>
   And pocketed $1.94 for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Santa also showed up at last week's Cardinals-Eagles game at
Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   He was booed.
</P>
<P>
   Santa says this isn't about money.
</P>
<P>
   But Claus is profiting during this usually quiet December. He
has appeared on the TV home shopping network three times. A limited
number of Santa collectibles and a new music video featuring Santa
and Pete Rose _ ``Nick &AMP; Pete's White Christmas ''_ sold quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jeff Gordon, Santa has his own Web site: www.jingle.com. &QL; 
Times change &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the elves say Santa seems different since he turned
professional. Even Rudolph has noticed a change.
</P>
<P>
   Santa is taking androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   He ditched the old itchy red outfit. He wears Armani.
</P>
<P>
   Santa favors sunglasses and sports a gold neck chain with a
pendant that says ``Claus No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa has an earring.
</P>
<P>
   The sleigh is out, replaced by a black Mercedes, with
personalized plates.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with Jim Rome, Santa said he is eager to
go to work but won't be railroaded into accepting a bad deal from
``greedy'' store owners.
</P>
<P>
   Santa also told the radio host he is unhappy living in the North
Pole because it's not a major media market.
</P>
<P>
   Santa said he prefers a warm-weather city. Like LA.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   St. Nick and Mike Tyson have become friends.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a percentage of all holiday season profits (the
season defined in the proposed contract as beginning the day after
Thanksgiving and ending the day after the Super Bowl) Santa wants
the use of a private jet on the night before Christmas. He won't
fly commercial. Forget flying coach.
</P>
<P>
   As for home delivery, Santa will not walk on any snow-covered
roofs.
</P>
<P>
   One slip and he could tear a cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Santa won't play hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Santa's agent said that because of legal issues, his client
won't slide down the chimney of any dwelling. He only will enter
and exit the front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hopeful an agreement satisfactory to everyone can
be reached,'' Santa's agent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only want what is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have ruled out postponing Christmas until February.
</P>
<P>
   No new talks are scheduled. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1858EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0257 </DOCNO>
