<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8616 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REAX-HNS &LR;      12-19 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO FIGHT IMPEACHMENT, ASKS RETURN TO CIVILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, pleading for an end to ``the
politics of self destruction,'' vowed Saturday to fight rather than
resign after becoming the first chief executive in 130 years to be
impeached
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is facing a trial in the Senate, appealed for ``a
reasonable, bipartisan and proportionate'' punishment for his
cover-up of a sexual relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic response to his new status as the only elected
president ever to be impeached, Clinton faced reporters and cameras
on the White House lawn just two hours after the House approved two
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   There, under glowering skies and with Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and House Democrats standing by, Clinton
said he would press the Senate for a ``fair means of resolving this
matter in a prompt manner.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been challenged to resign earlier in the day by House
Speaker-apparent Bob Livingston, R-La., who said he would ``set the
example'' by stepping aside himself. Livingston had admitted two
days earlier that he had ``strayed'' from his 33-year-year
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton did not mention the word ``resign'' during his
brief remarks, House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.,
told reporters afterwards that Democratic leaders privately had
urged him not to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard him very clearly say that he will not resign,''
Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the briefing on the South Lawn: ``We must stop the
politics of personal destruction. We must get rid of the poisonous
venom of excessive partisanship, obsessive animosity and
uncontrolled anger. That is not what America deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton silently nodded her agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton portrayed himself as a busy chief executive conducting
the nation's business despite the political backdrop of
congressional Republicans pressing to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   The president left the podium to join a meeting of his national
security advisers to discuss the four-day U.S.-led bombing campaign
against Iraq to punish defiance of U.N.-required weapons
inspection. Clinton emerged two hours later to announce that an end
to the bombing of Iraq because the campaign had achieved its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a career politician who had dreamed of the presidency
since shaking hands with John F. Kennedy in 1963, could barely
disguise his disappointment. He prayed with his religious
counselor, Rev. Tony Campolo, in the Oval Office as the House
approved the first article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Campolo, a friend of Clinton's from the New Year's Renaissance
Weekends in Hilton Head, S.C., and a sociology professor at Eastern
College in St. Davids, Pa., later said that Clinton appeared ``very
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff John Podesta and political adviser
Doug Sosnik entered the Oval Office prayer session to tell the
president that the House had taken action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sober moment, and he reflects it,'' Podesta said
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Podesta and Sosnik then went to Clinton's private study
off the Oval Office to watch televised coverage of House action on
the remaining three articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, closeted in the presidential residence with the
Clintons' daughter Chelsea, was not with her husband as the House
voted. She had visited the Capitol to rally House Democrats shortly
before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces a Senate trial on charges of lying to a federal
grand jury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The last president impeached by the House was Andrew Johnson in
1868 in a political dispute over the harshness of federal
occupation of the defeated Confederacy. Johnson, who succeeded to
the presidency after Abraham Lincoln was assassinated in 1865,
escaped ouster from office by one vote in his Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   President Richard Nixon resigned in 1974 after the House
Judiciary Committee lodged impeachment charges but before final
action in the House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's post-impeachment appearance was rich with symbolism.
About 100 House Democrats who had spent the last two days battling
Clinton's impending impeachment on the House floor encircled him.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady, her arm clutching the president's
elbow, parted the tide of supporters to reach the podium. The
president clutched Mrs. Clinton's hand as Gore declared that ``what
America needs is not resignations but the renewal of civility,
respect for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were already mapping Clinton's defense in
the Senate; if 67 senators vote to convict, Clinton would
automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials hope to cut short the Senate trial by
wooing six moderate GOP senators to join the 45 Democrats in
adopting a bipartisan resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they hope to enlist the help of
former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, a
well-respected centrist who left the Senate in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the GOP's 1996 presidential candidate and a former
Senate GOP leader, proposed last week that Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., introduce a joint congressional resolution to
censure Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, however, has signaled a determination to launch a Senate
trial _ a prospect feared by the White House because the
proceedings might be protracted and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., an early critic of Clinton in
the Senate, said last week that he could not predict the outcome of
a Senate trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
