<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-IRAQ-1220-COX     12-19 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-1220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., BRITAIN CALL OFF AIR STRIKES AGAINST IRAQ -- FOR NOW
 &HT;    With IRAQ-SCENE-1220, IRAQ-PROPAGANDA-1220.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After four days of massive airstrikes against the
soldiers and facilities Saddam Hussein relies upon to retain power
in Iraq, President Clinton ordered an end to the bombing Saturday
and announced a long-term strategy to work with anti-Saddam forces
to topple the dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that the objectives of Operation Desert Fox have been
achieved, Clinton said the United States and its allies would now
``intensify our engagement with the Iraqi opposition groups,
prudently and effectively'' to end Saddam's regime. He said the
United States would help any ``new leadership'' that emerges in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long term, the best way to end the threat that Saddam
poses to his own people and the region is for Iraq to have a
different government,'' Clinton said in a brief announcement at the
White House. ``We hope that we will return Iraq to its rightful
place in the community of nations.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, backing the
president's long-term strategy, addressed himself to the Iraqi
people, saying, ``We have a common enemy in Saddam.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States and its allies will retain a
significant military force in the region that will be used again in
the event that there is evidence of Saddam threatening his
neighbors or resuming efforts to build weapons of mass destruction.
He also said economic sanctions against Iraq would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Although Iraqi officials indicated earlier in the day that they
would no longer allow United Nations weapons inspectors in the
country, Clinton expressed hope that the inspection process could
resume.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq remained defiant, however, as protests and tensions spread
throughout the Arab world, which began observing Ramadan, a holy
Muslim month. Rioters in Damascus attacked the U.S. and British
embassies and broke into the U.S. ambassador's residence in the
Syrian capital. And officials in the United Arab Emirates, Iran and
Egypt called on Clinton to halt the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you that Iraq will continue to defend its land, policy
and dignity . . . We will fight until the last citizen,'' Iraqi
Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan told a news conference in
Baghdad. He also vowed that the mission of the U.N. Special
Commission, known as UNSCOM, is over.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was created at the end of the 1991 Gulf War to
oversee the destruction of banned Iraqi weapons and the means to
produce them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything related to inspections and the Special Commission
is now behind us,'' Ramadan said.
</P>
<P>
   After the president's announcement, Cohen said the four-day,
70-hour operation had successfully hit 100 targets, with a minimum
number of civilian casualties. He said U.S. and British forces in
the conflict had not suffered any casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's attacks, the United States fired nearly 300
Tomahawk cruise missiles from ships in the Persian Gulf or from
B-52 bombers. The missiles carry warheads weighing up to 3,000
pounds
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appeal to anti-Saddam forces in Iraq began earlier
Saturday with a radio address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll strengthen our engagement with Iraqis who want a new
government, one that will respect its citizens and live in peace
with its neighbors,'' he said. ``We must not harbor illusions,
however, that change will come easily or quickly. But we should go
forward and we will with determination, working with opposition
groups, strengthening the global consensus for bringing Iraq a
government worthy of its people.''
</P>
<P>
   This appears to have been a major goal from the beginning of
Operation Desert Fox. Primary targets of the bombings have been the
Republican Guard, the regime's most loyal soldiers, and the
facilities used by the regime for intelligence, propaganda and
security.
</P>
<P>
   The air strikes on Baghdad began much earlier Saturday than the
three previous days of bombing. They came about 6:30 p.m. (Iraq
time), ending hope that the barrages would stop with the beginning
of Ramadan. Witnesses said six Iraqis were injured, one seriously,
when three missiles landed near a welfare office in a residential
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were shown a crater approximately 30 feet wide and 25
feet deep. The blast threw mud, rocks and missile parts over nearby
streets, and the crater remained hot to the touch two hours after
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must ask them why they bombed this place. The children are
crying they are afraid,'' said Saad Aimed, who lives three houses
away from the crater.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the bombed building was a complex for government
benefits. However, they also acknowledged that U.N. weapons
inspectors had come to visit the site at least twice, the last time
two months ago. They said the inspectors were allowed inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a military area. It is not a warehouse for military
things. It is only for the public,'' said Aimed Sibiu, a
32-year-old electrician. ``It takes care of poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   The first day of Ramadan is traditionally a tense and difficult
one as Muslims forego eating, drinking or smoking from sunrise to
sunset. But in Baghdad there seemed to be additional tension caused
by four sleepless nights of missile strikes.
</P>
<P>
   There also appeared to be more than the usual number of militia
from Saddam's Baath Party keeping watch on street corners.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqis awoke Saturday morning to the site of one of the Baath
Party headquarters, a large complex with two 10-story buildings,
apparently gutted and destroyed by repeated missile strikes. The
missiles appeared to have entered from the roof, leaving the walls
intact but hollowing out the inside amid plumes of flames.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second downtown landmark to be destroyed by missiles.
On the first night of bombing, missiles gutted the high-rise
offices of Iraq's military industry.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Iraqis maintained at least a facade of defiance and
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Iraq are more determined to support the
leadership and the central leader, President Saddam Hussein,'' said
Ramadan, the deputy chairman of the Revolutionary Command Council.
</P>
<P>
   On a street in Baghdad, rank-and-file soldiers said they were
equally steadfast.
</P>
<P>
   Near a monument to the Iran-Iraq war, Amar Hamed, a 24-year-old
soldier, showed reporters a handwritten oath of loyalty to Saddam
that he had marked in blood with five of his fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fireworks don't scare us,'' he said. ``We will stay here
against American or Britain or any country for all time and we will
sacrifice ourselves for him (Saddam).''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox National correspondent Scott Shepard reported from
Washington. Cox Middle East correspondent Larry Kaplow reported
from Baghdad.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
