A8629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGSTON-REAX20-COX     12-19 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-REAX20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Livingston decision jolts home district
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COVINGTON, La. _ Residents of suburban New Orleans were stunned
and disappointed by news that Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.) would not
be representing them much longer and would not become speaker of
the House in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't resign _ he's the best congressman we've had in
this state,'' said Ron Komorowski of Covington, across Lake
Pontchartrain from New Orleans. ``Bob Livingston has done so much
for the little people. If you've got a problem, you can talk to him
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who last week admitted to extramarital affairs, is
an extremely popular congressman who has represented suburban New
Orleans for more than 20 years, often running unopposed. Moreover,
he was seen as a scandal-free Louisiana politician, something of an
rarity in a state notorious for crooked politics. Having him rise
to the third-highest position in the country was a source of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been so good for Louisiana's image,'' said Maude Brown,
who was selling Christmas trees in Covington on Saturday. ``If he's
not speaker, fine, but I don't think he should resign his
position.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. David Vitter, a Republican from Livingston's district
who is considered a leading candidate to replace him, said he was
shocked when he saw Livingston on television resigning Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a tremendous loss for the state,'' he said.
``We were going to have a speaker of the House from Louisiana, we
have had years (with Livingston) as the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, and that's made for very good news about
a Louisiana politician. So that is a very sad lost opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's resignation also leaves open the congressional seat
to a possible candidacy by someone reviled on the national
political scene: David Duke. The former Ku Klux Klansman and avowed
white supremacist is head of the St. Tammany Parish Republican
Party in Livingston's district, and probably will run for the
vacant seat.
</P>
<P>
   When Livingston talked of resigning in February, saying he could
make more money if he returned to private law practice, Duke said
he wanted to run for the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Duke could not be reached for comment Saturday. Vitter dismissed
the possibility that Duke could win the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think David Duke's 15 minutes of fame have come and gone,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people said that although they were sorry to lose
Livingston as a representative, they thought he did the honorable
thing in light of his recent confession to extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an honest man _ he probably feels he can't judge the
president and have done the same thing,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson of New Orleans said he liked the fact that Livingston
was setting an example for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton is being arrogant,'' he said. ``He should
resign _ he's got no power, no credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Vitter agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Livingston's stepping down makes a very powerful
argument that Clinton should resign as well and move beyond this
mess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Maginnis, publisher of the Louisiana Political Fax Weekly,
said that in stepping down, Livingston was ``doing what's best for
Livingston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding was that the number of affairs was in the
double digits and more information would have continued to come out
about them,'' he said. ``Livingston would have died by a thousand
cuts, so instead, he fell on his sword for the GOP and has invited
Clinton to join him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Reed, a Republican from Hammond in Livingston's district,
gained some notoriety when he begged Livingston in February at a
town meeting not to resign. Livingston later cited Reed as a factor
in his decision to remain in office. Reed is hoping to get another
chance to speak to Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's not leaving Congress for six months, so maybe I
will get a chance to talk him out of it,'' he said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Scott, who was shopping for a tree with her 2-year-old,
Hannah, and her husband, David, said it was ``ridiculous'' that
Livingston felt forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's trying to show he can take responsibility for his
actions,'' she said. ``But I don't think politics should be about
your marriage. Clinton is being impeached not because of Monica
Lewinsky, but because he lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband felt more strongly that politicians in general are
morally bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton and Bob Livingston have so much power and
yet they can't be trusted to do the right thing,'' David Scott
said. ``If you can't keep your vow to your wife, who can you keep
your vow to? The Republicans are wrapping themselves in this mantle
of morality and here is one of their leaders cheating on his
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Vix, a fire captain in Covington, said neither Livingston
nor Clinton should be in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that nobody is perfect, but those in positions of
such high responsibility have a higher moral standard to live up to
than Joe Blow in the street,'' he said. ``They reflect a much
greater problem in Washington, maybe in the whole country. The
Muslims would say, quite to the point, that we have no God. Why are
we even asking if Clinton and Livingston did something wrong? Isn't
it obvious?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
