<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEAKER20-COX     12-19 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEAKER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDWESTERNER IS EARLY FAVORITE IN NEW SPEAKER RACE
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., quickly emerged
Saturday as the favorite to become speaker of the House when the
new Congress convenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If elected speaker, I will make a particular effort to build
bridges across the aisle,'' Hastert said as became the first
Republican to announce his candidacy for the top House job.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years, Hastert has been the chief deputy to
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Support from DeLay and the party's current top two leaders,
departing Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia and House Majority
Leader Dick Armey of Texas, made Hastert a strong early favorite to
be the next speaker. At a private meeting of House Republicans,
Gingrich argued that as his successor, Hastert would be a
low-profile leader who wouldn't distract attention from the party's
presidential candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert won the leaders' backing even though his first political
mentor was the far less conservative former House Republican
leader, Bob Michel of Illinois. Hastert impressed his colleagues
last month when he refused to cooperate with efforts to draft him
to challenge Armey for majority leader because he had already
promised Armey his support.
</P>
<P>
   Though nominated by party caucuses, House speakers represent the
entire chamber and must be elected by all members. With only a
six-vote margin in the incoming Congress, Hastert's broad appeal is
an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical of higher spending on almost anything except defense,
Hastert is an evangelical Christian whose voting record has been
highly rated by groups of social conservatives and fiscal
conservatives alike.
</P>
<P>
   Among moderates, he earned a reputation in Congress for forging
compromises between the parties and between the Senate and the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not get the highest SAT scores, but he's a real solid
guy _ affable and accessible,'' said a Republican House member who
is supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   He is a former high school wrestling coach with extensive state
legislative experience. Hastert's unbuttoned suitcoats, flopping
tie, pot belly and thick, gray bangs make him look as grandfatherly
as a Democrat who once was speaker, Thomas P. (Tip) O'Neill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who will turn 57 on Jan. 2, is likely to face
opposition from a trimmer, more telegenic Republican _ GOP Policy
Committee Chairman Christopher Cox, 46, of California.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is a Newport Beach attorney who has developed a reputation
as a likeable, brainy champion of the high tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters that he wouldn't announce his candidacy
formally on Saturday because a campaign for the speakership is
``inter-personal among members, and wherever possible it is best to
talk first to the members one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox added, ``If you can imagine, it's the third most significant
post in the government, and (a winning majority of) the electorate
will be only your own vote and 111 other people.''
</P>
<P>
   That assumes that when the 106th Congress convenes on Jan. 6,
all 223 House Republicans would vote for the winner of an
intra-party showdown at a meeting to take place no later than Jan.
5. If they remain united, the 223 GOP votes would be enough to beat
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., who could expect
support from 211 Democrats and one independent.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP unity isn't always guaranteed. In fact, Livingston
withdrew shortly after friends told him that some conservative
Republicans might vote against him next month, because they were
upset by his recent confessions of marital infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quicker we can come to a real consensus, the better off we
are,'' said Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio. ``When you're bleeding, the
first thing you want to do is stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Steve Largent of Oklahoma and Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Bill Archer of Texas were among members to declined to run
after being approached by GOP colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gingrich is leaving and DeLay and Armey are prominent
partisans, their colleagues did not ask them to seek the top job.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
