<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ARRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDITH ARRON, 56, CARNEGIE HALL DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Wash., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judith Arron, the executive and artistic director of
Carnegie Hall since 1986, died on Friday at the University of
Colorado Health Sciences Center in Denver. She was 56 and lived in
Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was breast cancer, Carnegie Hall officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron presided over probably the most momentous years of
Carnegie Hall since its rescue from the wrecking ball in 1960. The
exhaustive $60 million renovation of the hall in 1986 happened on
her watch, as well as the season-long and highly festive centennial
celebration of 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron used the refurbishment of Carnegie Hall's smaller
Weill Recital Hall as an opportunity to transform it from a rental
space to an important venue for events produced by the Hall. They
included debut series, chamber-music events, jazz concerts and a
new music series administered by the Carnegie Hall Composer's
Chair, which is currently held by Ellen Taaffe Zwilich.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ms. Arron, the Hall promoted and extended educational
programs both for the very young and for professionals, with
workshops overseen by musicians like Robert Shaw and Pierre Boulez.
In partnership with the Hall's president, the violinist Isaac
Stern, and its chairman, Sanford Weill, Ms. Arron began a new
endowment campaign in 1995 and had raised $87 million to date.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron came to Carnegie Hall from Cincinnati, where she was
the Cincinnati Symphony's manager and the director of its May
Festival. Her work in developing educational outreach programs
there in 1969 was admired in orchestra circles around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Ms. Arron had worked for the American Symphony
Orchestra League and a government arts program.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron was born in Seattle and graduated from the University
of Puget Sound with a performance degree in cello and piano. Her
husband, Ronald Arron, is a violinist with the Metropolitan Opera
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said Saturday that Ms. Arron's health in the last two
weeks had been ``touch and go'' but that her eight-and-a-half-year
battle with cancer had been ``a miracle'' and a victory of ``will
and heart over doctors and medicine.'' Weill cited her
``extraordinary abilities as an administrator and her keen
understanding of the financial world.''
</P>
<P>
   At her death, Ms. Arron was preparing to bring yet another
performing space to Carnegie Hall, a below-ground area long
occupied by the Carnegie Hall Cinema to be equipped with high-tech
appurtenances and intended for smaller opera productions and
experimental work.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arron is survived, in addition to her husband, by two sons,
Joseph and Edward of New York; her parents, Richard and Berenice
Hagerty of La Quinta, Calif.; a sister, Colleen Fretz of Belize,
and two brothers, Richard Hagerty Jr. of Modesto, Calif., and Dale
Hagerty of La Quinta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1944EST &QL; 
