<HEADLINE>
PREMIER OF NOVA SCOTIA CLEARED IN RAPE TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to correct day of aquittal to Friday from Saturday. No
other changes.)  (jw) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The former premier of Nova Scotia was acquitted Friday
of eight charges of rape, attempted rape and indecent assault
related to incidents that allegedly took place 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The former premier, Gerald Regan, now 70, led the province's
government from 1970 to 1978. He was also a member of the federal
Parliament and a Cabinet minister under Prime Minister Pierre
Trudeau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, long ordeal,'' he said after hearing the
jury's decision. ``We've lived and died with this for the last five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   A jury of six women and four men deliberated about eight hours
before returning the not guilty verdict in a Halifax courtroom
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But it was only after the jury had been sequestered Thursday
night that it became known that besides the three women who had
testified during the trial, 19 other women had told investigators
they had been sexually assaulted or harassed by Regan years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Michael MacDonald, blocked attempts by prosecutors to
allow some of the other alleged victims to testify, and limited
this trial to just the charges brought by three women. The judge
also issued a publication ban, which prevented any information
about the other cases from being reported during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of Regan, a respected public figure in Nova Scotia,
was one of the most sensational proceedings in Canada in recent
years. It brought calls from some quarters for a statute of
limitations on criminal charges. The trial also forced Canadians to
try to reconcile two starkly different images of a man who had
spent most of his adult life in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Regan, a tall, stately man, was always formal and polite as he
marched into and out of the Halifax courthouse. Inside the
courtroom, however, the prosecution and three alleged victims
portrayed him as a brutal rapist and sexual predator who enjoyed
watching his victims cringe in fear.
</P>
<P>
   It came down to Regan's word against the moving testimony of the
alleged victims. The accusers, now middle-aged women, said they
were teen-agers when the attacks took place, often after Regan had
parked his car in an isolated area. The women all said they knew
him then but not intimately.
</P>
<P>
   Regan steadfastly denied making advances to the women.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, his wife, Carole, 62, defended him against
the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The crown prosecutor, Adrian Reid, told the jury that despite
Regan's gentlemanly demeanor and public reputation, he had ``a dark
side'' that led him to prey on young women.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's acquittal was a stinging loss for the prosecution,
which had spent five years on the case. ``If there are grounds for
appeal, we'll consider them,'' Reid told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Regan's lawyer, Edward Greenspan, said that prosecutors had
been off base from the moment the investigation was launched. ``If
he had not been the former premier of this province they would
never have spent millions of dollars pursuing him,'' Greenspan
said. ``It just wouldn't have happened to an ordinary citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Regan's troubles have not ended. He is scheduled to appear in
court again next February as proceedings begin on another sex
complaint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 1951EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON20-COX     12-19 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON LAUNCHES FIGHT TO SAVE HIS PRESIDENCY
 &HT;    840&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hours after becoming the only president in this
century to be impeached, President Clinton launched the next phase
of his fight for political survival Saturday, vowing he would not
be hounded from office and calling for a censure deal in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring a stunning challenge by House Speaker-designate Bob
Livingston to follow his example and resign, Clinton pledged to
remain in the White House ''until the last hour of the last day of
my term.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a dramatic appeal from the White House lawn, Clinton
asked all Americans to mend the tears which a year of scandal and
bitter partisanship have ripped in the fabric of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must stop the politics of personal destruction,'' Clinton
declared.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must get rid of the poisonous venom of excessive
partisanship, obsessive animosity, and uncontrolled anger,'' he
said. ''That is not what America deserves. That is not what America
is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by his wife, Vice President Al Gore, and 101 of his
staunchest House Democratic supporters, Clinton was visibly
stricken by conflicting emotions in a setting that mixed some of
the somberness of a wake with much of the rhetorical energy of a
campaign rally.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton struggled to fend off tears as Gore hailed him as ''one
of our greatest presidents,'' praising Clinton's efforts through
six years of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton appeared more determined than wounded as he pledged
to ignore calls for his resignation and press on to complete his
second term.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want the American people to know today that I am still
committed to working with people of good faith and good will of
both parties to do what's best for our country, to bring our nation
together, to lift our people up, to move us all forward together,''
Clinton said. ''It's what I've tried to do for six years. It's what
I intend to do for two more, until the last hour of the last day of
my term.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the point, Clinton donned the mantle of
commander-in-chief, going directly into a meeting with his national
security team to assess the impact of four days of U.S. and British
attacks on Iraqi military and communications sites.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have achieved our mission,'' Clinton said in an address to
the nation after the meeting, at which he decided to declare
victory and end air strikes against Iraq after 70 punishing hours.
''I want to give my thanks to our men and women in uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of Clinton's attention, however, was the battle he's
waging on Capitol Hill, where the House voted to impeach him on two
charges _ perjury before a grand jury and obstruction of justice _
in connection with his attempts to cover up an intimate
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's House action, the first since Andrew Johnson's
impeachment in 1868, moves the issue to the Senate, which is
expected to hold a trial to determine whether to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction on either charge would require a two-thirds
majority vote in the Senate and would result in Clinton's immediate
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of House Republicans, however, have urged Clinton to
head off a Senate inquiry by resigning.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, a Republican from Louisiana, said he would forego
the chance to become speaker of the House and step down from
Congress in six months as political penance for repeated instances
of adultery he admitted to several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   He then challenged Clinton to step down, saying, ``I must set
the example that I hope President Clinton will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   In his South Lawn address, Clinton made no mention of
Livingston's challenge, but White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
''the president's wish is that Representative Livingston would
reconsider the decision he announced on the floor today.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the Senate impeachment fight, Clinton said he would
try to achieve in the Senate what he was unable to win from the
House _ an agreement to drop the impeachment charges and instead
approve a resolution of censure condemning him for his conduct in
the Lewinsky matter but ending the constitutional process that
threatens his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have accepted responsibility for what I did wrong in my
personal life, and I have invited members of Congress to work with
us to find a reasonable, bipartisan, and proportionate response,''
said Clinton. ''That approach was rejected today by Republicans in
the House, but I hope it will be embraced in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   With his personal attorney Gregory Craig looking on, Clinton
said ''I hope there will be a constitutional and fair means of
resolving this matter in a prompt manner.''
</P>
<P>
   With opinion polls showing that about 65 percent of Americans
believe Clinton is doing a good job as president, he made clear
that part of his Senate strategy will be to continue to plead his
case to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask the American people to move with me, to go on from here,
to rise above the rancor,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Even as he was surrounded by political allies, though, Clinton
found himself a lonely historical figure _ only the second American
president ever to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the darkest moment of his political career, Clinton
declined to watch the first House vote to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton closeted himself in the Oval Office, where tiny
white lights flickered on a large Christmas tree. With him was the
Rev. Tony Campolo, an old friend and one of a group of spiritual
advisers Clinton to whom he has turned since his admission last
August that he had an ``inappropriate'' relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   After the first vote, Clinton moved into a nearby study with his
chief of staff, John Podesta, and one of his closest policy aides,
Douglas Sosnik. Together, the group watched the House approve one
additional article of impeachment against him and vote down two
more.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Clinton strode out of the Oval Office, through a
glass door on which hung a large green Christmas wreath with a
broad red bow, to address reporters. First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton was at his side, her right arm tucked over his left.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath steely gray skies and the twisted limbs of barren trees,
staff members took deep breaths and exchanged quick grasps of
hands, as if to gird themselves for a moment as solemn as the
winter afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a sad day for the presidency, the constitution and the
country,'' said one aide. ''But there's also a sense of relief that
it's moved out of the House, where it's been so partisan and
bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton let others do the public criticizing of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., lambasted House
Republicans for managing what he called ''a partisan vote that was
a disgrace to our country and our Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me say simply, the president has acknowledged that what he
did was wrong,'' said Gore. ''But we must all acknowledge that
invoking the solemn power of impeachment in the cause of partisan
politics is wrong. Wrong for our Constitution, wrong for the United
States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   With those attacks out of the way, Clinton was free to take the
high road, calling for national reconciliation in the wake of the
most bitterly partisan political year in at least a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Out in the country people are pulling together,'' Clinton
said. ''But, just as America is coming together, it must look, from
the country's point of view, like Washington is coming apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have some atmosphere of decency and civility,'' he
said, ``some presumption of good faith, some sense of
proportionality and balance in bringing judgment against those who
are in different parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Following his appearance at the edge of the Rose Garden, Clinton
ignored a couple of questions shouted at him from reporters.
Instead, he strode among his Democratic supporters as if presiding
over a memorial service, shaking hands, patting backs and
expressing his gratitude for their support.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thanks,'' Clinton said to Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., the former
civil rights leader who has been among Clinton's sturdiest
defenders over a long a scandal-stained year.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton leaned over the broad shoulders of the congressman,
locked him in a long embrace with both arms and slapped him on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
