<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-LIVINGSTON-HNS &LR;      12-19 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LIVINGSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON'S DRAMATIC RESIGNATION STUNS LAWMAKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Capping one of the craziest weeks in House history,
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston, who admitted to adultery earlier
in the week, shocked colleagues Saturday by giving up his post and
promising to resign his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., a former wrestling coach first
elected to Congress in 1986, quickly emerged as the frontrunner for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The latest setback hit as House Republicans were reeling from an
array of problems, including internal bickering between moderates
and conservatives, plummeting popularity with voters, and
increasing partisan tensions with Democrats. Members of both
parties said they feared Livingston had become the latest casualty
of a ``sexual McCarthyism'' spreading in Washington, whereby
private lives were being exposed for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   While he had been informally chosen by his party last month to
be speaker, Livingston still faced an official election by new
House members next month. His confession alienated some
conservative members who indicated they might reconsider their
support.
</P>
<P>
   He was to replace Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who quit the post after
November midterm elections went poorly for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Livingston's announcement could not have been more
dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing colleagues gathered in the House chamber for a
historic presidential impeachment vote, Livingston called on
President Clinton to resign, prompting Democrats to boo and chant
that the incoming speaker was the one who should resign.
</P>
<P>
   Before they could finish taunting him, the lanky Louisianan
dropped the bombshell that he would do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my colleagues, my friends, and most especially my wife and
family, I have hurt you all deeply and I beg your forgiveness,'' he
said to a suddenly hushed chamber. ``I was prepared to lead our
narrow majority as speaker and I believed I had it in me to do a
fine job. But I cannot do that job or be that kind of leader I
would like to be under the current circumstances,'' he said. `` So
I must set the example that I hope President Clinton will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would resign from the House in six months.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his statement, lawmakers of both parties, some of
them tearful, gave Livingston a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats expressed disbelief at Livingston's
decision, with a number urging him to reconsider. They complained
that the episode further indicated a deterioration of civility and
respect for privacy in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're eating ourselves,'' bemoaned Texas Democratic Rep. Nick
Lampson.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., one of the few Republicans arguing
against impeachment, said that events of the last week should serve
as a ``wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are destroying and consuming ourselves with hatred,'' he
said. ``There will be more dead bodies along the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, citing Republican sources, reported that
Livingston's wife, Bonnie, had asked him to step down.
</P>
<P>
   The latest drama began unfolding Thursday evening when
Livingston disclosed to colleagues that he occasionally had
extramarital affairs during his 33-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston revealed the affairs to pre-empt an investigation by
media, including Larry Flynt's Hustler Magazine. A story about his
adultery had been posted on the Internet site operated by the
Washington newspaper, Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
   While most Republicans continued to back Livingston, it became
apparent that a number of conservatives were unhappy with the
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   In the newly elected House where the GOP holds a six-vote
majority, Livingston could not afford a defection of even a
handful.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., said Friday that about a dozen
conservatives were unhappy with Livingston's conduct. Wamp said he
relayed those concerns to Livingston on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Wamp said Livingston was aware of his eroding support. ``He
looked at me and said, `You need to find a new leader.'''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston emerged as party leader last month after House
Republicans became increasingly disgruntled with Gingrich in the
aftermath of the party's showing in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich decided to resign rather than face a challenge by
Livingston, who had amassed considerable clout as chairman of the
appropriations committee.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Livingston has come under increasing criticism,
particularly from Democrats angry that he delegated to House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the task of overseeing the
impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Many believed that DeLay was pressuring moderate Republicans
into voting for impeachment by ruling out the possibility that the
House might consider censure as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats became even more furious with Livingston when he sided
with DeLay on the censure issue.
</P>
<P>
   However, DeLay is likely to amass even more power if Hastert is
elected speaker. The Illinois lawmaker has served as DeLay's top
deputy in his whip operation.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Livingston's announcement, DeLay had endorsed
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will make a great speaker,'' said DeLay, whose office also
sent out a list of 80 lawmakers backing Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's standing was bolstered by the backing of other
powerful allies including Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and
Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to his wife, Hastert announced his intention to
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``After searching my heart and discussing it with my family and
closest friends, my sense of duty now calls me to serve our free
nation by seeking a position of great responsibility _ that of
speaker of the United States House of Representatives,'' he said in
a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Cox, R-Calif. also said he would consider running for
the post. Another potential candidate, Texas Republican Rep. Bill
Archer quickly ruled himself out.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were hoping that either DeLay or Armey, combative
conservatives who alienate liberals, might run for speaker so they
could have someone to run against in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, the liberal Democrat from Massachusetts,
joked that ``there's a great fear in the Democratic caucus that Tom
Delay would not be speaker. If he needed money for his campaign we
would raise it.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and Armey said they would not run for speaker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
