</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-SAMGASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP BILLING: GASH BOWLS 'EM OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several of his teammates came up to Sam Gash Wednesday to give
him the good news, but for Gash seeing was believing. So in this
Age of the Computer, Gash's Buffalo Bills teammates did what they
must in such a circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   They downloaded the proof for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys were looking on the internet and they saw I'd been
picked for the Pro Bowl,'' the former Patriots fullback said last
week. ``I said, `Stop bulljiving me.' So they copied it and brought
it to me. I was amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as amazed as the host of the Pro Bowl announcement show that
night on ESPN, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, they didn't really know what to say about my
position,'' Gash joked. ``When they came to the NFC fullback they
said, `Mike Alstott has 697 yards rushing and five touchdowns.'
Then they go, `In the AFC, Sam Gash has 186 yards total (31 rushing
on 10 carries). That dude is sorry, man. He musta got in on a
humbug.' It was funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have your peers vote you in for the kind of stuff I do _
block, block, block _ is the highest honor I've ever received
because I'm hard to find. Unless you're playing against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently that was the Patriots' problem last offseason. The
people running the place had never had to pry Sam Gash off the
front of their helmet and thus forgot what he brings to a team when
his knee is right and his coach believes in him and he's free to
knock people's socks off. In such a circumstance, Gash was twice
named a first alternate to the Pro Bowl and this year became the
AFC's starting fullback for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But just a year ago, under far less positive circumstances, Gash
was called a whiner. He was called injury prone. He was called
unable to realize his worth. He was also called at home one day and
told he wasn't wanted anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Gash was being replaced, it was said, by a younger, faster,
stronger, less injury prone, cheaper, softer-handed guy named Tony
Carter, who had just been told he was no longer wanted in Chicago.
That is no reflection on either guy because that's the way things
go in the NFL these days. What is a reflection is what you do after
you leave.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Sam Gash did.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Gash has only 31 yards rushing. It is 10 times the
production New England has received from Carter, who has 3 yards
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Carter has 17 pass receptions for 155 yards and no
touchdowns. Gash has 17 pass receptions for 155 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Gash has not missed a game, playing in all 14 and
leading the blocking for 1,000-yard rusher Antowain Smith. Carter
has already missed four games with injury and will sit out again
Sunday against the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Gash is aware of all this but will say nothing against the
man who replaced him because ``Tony is a very good fullback, and
that's coming from one fullback to another,'' Gash said. ``I just
felt given a fair opportunity I could play, too. They didn't see
that, or they didn't want to see that. Fine. They obviously felt I
wasn't their kind of player. I understand that's just business. I
thank them now for letting me go, because I got to come to a place
where they believe in me. They believed I was a good football
player here from the day they signed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up here believing I had to prove to them I could play,
but they had the attitude that I could and that never wavered. From
the first day they put me in position to succeed. I was amazed at
that after what happened in New England. So it doesn't bother me
that they didn't want to re-sign me. It's the way they did things
that bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Patriots did things was for some in the organization
to whisper that Gash was damaged goods while others were assuring
him they would find a way to re-sign him. Some claimed they tried
to reach him by phone repeatedly without success while he insists
no such calls came. Instead, they spoke once with his agent and
decided his contract demands were ridiculous and that was the end
of it.
</P>
<P>
   There was no negotiation, they now acknowledge, but say Gash's
people left no room for it. Perhaps, but they willingly paid more
than $2 million a year to Max Lane and ended up benching him a
month ago and handed over a $500,000 signing bonus to a receiver
named Brian Stablein, who had never taken a snap for them and was
cut in August without ever playing a game in New England.
</P>
<P>
   As happy as Sam Gash is, it is not easy for him to forget what
he was put through last year.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you play the game the way Gash does. There is nothing
fancy about his approach. It is a street fight every down, so if
you want to attack him, you had best bring your lunch pail because
it will be a long day for you.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, Gash is going to the Pro Bowl in February, his
running mate is over 1,000 yards with two games to go, his team is
happy with him, and he is a leader in their locker room. In other
words, he has done for the Bills what he did for the Patriots until
somebody decided he was an overpriced, broken-down piece of
machinery instead of what he really was _ a darned good football
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I was injury prone,'' Gash recalled. ``I found that
funny. The only time I ever missed was when I hurt my knee (late in
the 1996 run to the Super Bowl). I played with busted ribs and a
bad wrist, so for them to say I was injury prone was a slap in my
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to blast them. They got a good fullback and I
was out. I just wish they told me they didn't want me and that was
the end of it, but one guy tells you one thing there and the other
tells you something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, I hate the Patriots organization. I would
never want to be associated with them again. I'm loyal to the end,
but when the end comes, I'm done if you slight me. I give a team my
all, but you slap me in the face and I can't forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played them this year, I felt we were the better team
both times. I didn't see the team I should have seen (in New
England). They dismantled a team that went to the Super Bowl in two
years. I have a lot of friends there, but I (couldn't) care less
about their organization because of what they tried to do to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up here I'm happy. I'm happy to go to work and beat my body
down for these people because they had faith in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not once, Gash insisted, did his faith in himself waver during
his season of trial. Not when he was battling back from his knee
injury or when his season started slowly. Not when it became clear
coach Pete Carroll had decided to play Keith Byars ahead of him and
not even at the end, when Gash insists Bobby Grier said he would
work things out with his agent at the same time Carroll was
courting Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never at that point,'' Gash said when asked if he ever
questioned his ability to come back from his knee problems. ``Not
with the staff they had. If I had talked to Coach Parcells and he
said `You just can't hit it anymore like you used to,' I might have
reevaluated things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the little whispers from their staff how I couldn't do
it in New England anymore, but I knew I could play somewhere in the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   All season his bosses knew he could play in Buffalo. Come Feb.
7, the whole football world is going to know he can play in the Pro
Bowl, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great tribute to Sam,'' Parcells said when he learned
of Gash's selection this week. ``I love that kid. He's a special
guy. I think everybody in the league knows that now, what kind of
player and person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   A year too late, a few more people know it in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gash acknowledged he and his teammates had their doubts when
they first heard the Bills had signed  &UR; Doug Flutie &LR; . &UR;  &LR;  Then Flutie
came to camp and their doubts were relieved. ``When we saw how
strong his arm was and the decisions he made, we knew we were all
right,'' Gash said. ``You see the fire in him and you want to do
all you can for him. The decisions he'd make to bail us out when
we'd miss a block. Just in practice you could see he was a very
wise quarterback who made good decisions. I understand now why they
talked about him the way they did in Boston. He wins games. He'll
pass, he'll run, he'll go downfield and throw a block. He's a
complete quarterback. And he brings out the best in the people
around him. If you haven't played with him, you look at him and
just see his size, but if you play with him, you begin to see why
he's always won everywhere he's been.''... There are an assortment
of reasons why  &UR; Ty Law's  &LR; game has risen to Pro Bowl level, but one
that may go unnoticed is the power in his lower legs and the
quickness of his feet. ``Ty has phenomenal lower-body strength,''
secondary coach  &UR; Ron Lynn  &LR; said. ``He can get his body contorted in
some positions and he doesn't have to take a step or two to get his
balance back. He has real good total body strength and nice feet.
His body control is exceptional too. He's just a real good
athlete.'' ... Speaking of Law, he said that as happy as he was to
be selected to the Pro Bowl ``the most important thing is winning,
and the fact that we haven't takes a lot of the joy from this. All
it is is an individual accolade. I'd trade my Pro Bowl spot for a
trip back to the Super Bowl. There's nothing like playing in the
Super Bowl. When you retire no one's going to ask, `Did you play in
the Pro Bowl?' They're gonna ask, `Do you have a ring?''' ... 49ers
wide receiver  &UR; Jerry Rice  &LR; is on one of the worst four-game
stretches of his career. The 12-time Pro Bowl receiver has produced
fewer yards the last four games (114) than he had in their game
with the Falcons five weeks ago (169). But do not think Rice is
slipping. He leads the NFC with 73 catches and is fifth in
receiving yardage with 993 ... Denver quarterback  &UR; John Elway  &LR; said
this week winning the Super Bowl last season has taken far more of
a burden off his shoulders than he realized he was carrying. ``I
know  &UR; Dan  &LR; ( &UR; Marino &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whom he will oppose Monday night and who has
yet to win a Super Bowl) gets tired of answering those questions
and no matter what he does, that is going to be the thing that
everybody goes back to because that is what happened to me after we
lost the Super Bowl in '89,'' he said during a national conference
call. ``No matter what you do numbers-wise or anything else, it
still goes back as a quarterback to how many Super Bowls you've
won. By us winning last year, I no longer had to answer all those
questions. That's a big burden, and to remove that asterisk behind
my name was bigger than I would have thought. There was only one
win or loss that counted. That was winning the Super Bowl. That is
a great deal of pressure to get off your shoulders. So I have a
great deal of empathy for him with the career he's had and for what
he's done for the NFL. As unfair as it is, that's the way of
life.'' ... Amazing fact. In 16 NFL seasons, Elway and Marino have
faced each other only once ... Asked about the season in which
Marino threw 48 touchdown passes, Elway said simply, ``That second
year he had will go down in history as probably the greatest year a
quarterback has ever had. I think that '84 year is the most amazing
thing. Didn't he throw for 5,000 (yards)?'' As a matter of fact, he
did ... Speaking of Marino, he was asked at midweek if he had grown
frustrated at the restraints thrown on him and the passing game by
coach  &UR; Jimmy Johnson  &LR; the last two years. ``I was pretty lucky
early on because I had a great group of receivers and a coach that
was very willing to open things up, and it showed,'' Marino said.
``I think it really did. It showed. We're running an offense now
that we're trying to be a little bit more controlled because of
maybe the personnel that we have and wanting to run the ball more
and be more consistent running it. So things have changed some, but
to say it frustrates me, no. I'm the quarterback of this team. I'm
going to do whatever is asked to try and help this team win. Last
week, we threw 57 times. We haven't done that in a long time and we
lost. So, you look at it and say, `Maybe we need to run the ball
more.''' ... How do you figure the Pro Bowl voting? Baltimore is
5-9 and had five players voted onto the AFC team while Miami is 9-5
with the third-rated defense in the NFL, one that has allowed 40
points fewer than any other team (206), yet placed only defensive
lineman  &UR; Tim Bowens  &LR; on the team. How cornerbacks  &UR; Terrell Buckley
 &LR; (eight interceptions) and  &UR; Sam Madison  &LR; (seven) both missed is
difficult to fathom. Together they have more interceptions than any
starting cornerback tandem in the NFL. Two years ago, the Patriots
passed over Madison to select Chris Canty on the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Lions coach  &UR; Bobby Ross  &LR; lost it last week before his
team went out to play the 49ers on Monday night, telling them,
according to a source in the locker room, that he could no longer
motivate them. Ross claimed he knew he was a good coach and the
reason the Lions were losing was that they were not good players.
Several nights later, the same source said, Pro Bowl running back
 &UR; Barry Sanders  &LR; came out of the 49ers game because he said he had a
headache. ``Nobody else would have gotten away with that but
there's different rules for Barry,'' the source said. Something
tells me there's a headache waiting for Bobby Ross by the end of
this dismal season ... The Jets hold an option on quarterback
 &UR; Vinny Testaverde  &LR; for next season but are close to finalizing a
cap-friendly long-term deal that could take him through the end of
his career, at least as a starter ... Central Florida quarterback
 &UR; Dante Culpepper  &LR; has his eyes on the prize. Culpepper, who is the
second-rated quarterback in next year's draft, hired agent  &UR; Mason
Ashe  &LR; following a meeting with him on the day he was supposed to be
at a season-ending team meeting. Culpepper probably figured he'd
done all he could for Central Florida after throwing for 3,690
yards and 28 touchdowns in a 9-2 season ... The Broncos may have
had the most talked-about streak in the NFL broken last Sunday in
New York, but it's not the longest one. Vikings kicker  &UR; Gary
Anderson  &LR; needs two more successful field goals to break the NFL
record for most consecutive kicks in NFL history, a record held by
former Viking Fuad Reveiz (1994-95). The 39-year-old Anderson has
kicked 29 straight, dating back to the 15th game of last season.
He's 23 for 23 with another perfect 51 for 51 on extra points, and
has made 82 straight kicks of one type or the other dating back to
last season. No kicker has ever gone a full season without missing
a kick of any type (The Rams' Tony Zendejas missed one extra point
in 1991). While the Vikings need 62 more points to set an NFL
scoring record, Anderson is only 5 points shy of having outscored
the Philadelphia Eagles, who have racked up a dismal 125 points.
Fifteen more in their final three games and the Eagles will have
done the opposite of the Vikings, setting a rec-ord for lack of
productivity. The 1992 Seattle Seahawks hold the rec-ord for
offensive futility ... If Anderson breaks Reveiz's record, he'll
have one of the same guys to thank that Reveiz had.  &UR; Mike Morris
 &LR; has been the long snapper for both ... If the 6-8 New Orleans
Saints somehow make the playoffs, it will be because of their
defense, which has outscored the offense in three of the last five
games ... Indianapolis running back  &UR; Marshall Faulk  &LR; is trying to
join Roger Craig as the only back in history to rush for 1,000
yards and also have 1,000 receiving yards. Faulk is second in the
AFC to Davis with 1,228 yards rushing and is second in the AFC with
78 receptions for 862 yards. He needs 268 yards to break Sanders's
single-season total offense record of 2,358 ... Falcons team
physician  &UR; Charles Harrison  &LR; said he believes a new factor in heart
disease should be added after attending to Atlanta coach  &UR; Dan
Reeves &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who underwent quadruple bypass earlier this week. ``We
know the risk factors for heart disease,'' Harrison said.
``Cholesterol, diabetes, high blood pressure, family history, and
cigarette smoking. I'm going to add another one _ NFL coaching.''
Reeves is the third Falcons coach in two years to suffer a heart
attack.
</P>
