<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO STAY IN OFFICE DESPITE IMPEACHMENT VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton vowed Saturday to remain in
office ``until the last hour of the last day of my term,'' after
the House approved two articles of impeachment against him.
</P>
<P>
   Aides began work immediately to blunt Republican calls for his
resignation after he became the first president to be impeached by
the House in 130 years. They also turned their attention to the
Senate, where a trial likely will begin in January to decide
whether to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the American people to know today that I am still
committed to working with people of good faith and good will of
both parties to do what's best for our country, to bring our nation
together, to lift our people up, to move us all forward together,''
Clinton said, flanked by scores of congressional Democrats on the
White House lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I've tried to do for six years. It's what I intend
to do for two more until the last hour of the last day of my
term,'' he declared. With first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton at his
side, he thanked the Democrats and the few Republicans who opposed
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/Time Magazine poll found 48 percent of those polled
favored no trial but a censure of Clinton; 31 percent favored no
trial but Clinton's resignation and 16 percent favored a Senate
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could take cold comfort in the fact that President
Andrew Johnson was impeached by his political opponents in 1868
only to be acquitted in the Senate by one vote. Johnson completed
his term.
</P>
<P>
   The House, divided mostly along party lines, voted two articles
of impeachment against Clinton, accusing him of perjury and
obstruction of justice for lying about and trying to cover up his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Two other
articles of impeachment failed.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the final House vote, two buses left the Capitol
building for a short drive down Pennsylvania Avenue to the White
House where more than 70 Democrats met with the president, the
first lady and Vice President Al Gore in the White House residence.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said Clinton
began the meeting with an apology to the members.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said at the top of the meeting how saddened this has made
him and how sorry he is that we all had to go through this. He has
apologized to us in a very sincere way on a number of occasions,
but today was as somber and as genuine and as meaningful as
anything that we have heard,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Democrats told him ``in clear terms that he cannot and
he must not resign. And I heard him very clearly say that he will
not resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, a Waco Democrat and one of several Texans who
joined Democrats on the South Lawn, said, ``The president is not
going to resign period. End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to resign would be a slap in the face of 47 million
Americans and to let a partisan impeachment process force the
resignation of a duly elected president would set a terrible
precedent for the future and make impeachment an annual event,''
Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   It would take 67 votes in the 100-member Senate to remove
Clinton from office, a margin that would appear unlikely because
there are 45 Democrats. But White House officials intend to take
nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lewis, Clinton's communications chief, said the White House,
through a series of conference calls and talking points, had sent
information to Clinton's supporters across the nation outlining how
they can become active in the president's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The message: the House vote was a partisan act by a lame-duck
Congress, and now the Senate should find a bipartisan solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our folks are now so energized,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another White House aide said, ``The mood is pretty sober but
there's also a sense of relief that this is moving out of the House
and into the Senate where hopefully there will be less rancor and
less partisanship and a little more fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats braced for an expected rash of calls for Clinton's
resignation, especially after the stunning announcement by House
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston, R-La., that he would resign his
seat within six months following his disclosure of extramarital
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic statement on the House floor, Livingston called
for Clinton's resignation, generating catcalls from Democrats, but
then hushed the House by saying he intended to take his own advice.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton issued a statement asking Livingston
to reconsider his resignation and deploring the situation that
brought it about.
</P>
<P>
   Later on the South Lawn, Clinton bemoaned the atmosphere in the
nation's capital, suggesting that to most Americans it must look as
though Washington was coming apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must stop the politics of personal destruction,'' Clinton
said. ``We must get rid of the poisonous venom of excessive
partisanship, obsessive animosity and uncontrolled anger. That is
not what America deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time the House took its first vote, Clinton was in the
Oval Office with Tony Campolo, an evangelical minister from
Philadelphia who has emerged as a spiritual adviser to the
president. Campolo later told CNN the two were praying.
</P>
<P>
   There is no television in the Oval Office. Chief of Staff John
Podesta and Senior Adviser Doug Sosnik interrupted Clinton's
meeting with Campolo to tell him the House had approved the first
article of impeachment. Clinton and his aides walked to the
adjacent study where they watched the vote on the other three
articles.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ricchetti, a deputy chief of staff, also came to the
study, telling the president that Republican leaders had been
lobbying members to vote in favor of the first and third articles,
both of which passed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
