u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     12-19 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPIONING CAUSE: WHIPPLE'S TEAM BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ The University of Massachusetts has the
best football team in the country. That is not my opinion. It was
not determined by a writers' poll, a computer's whims or a
corporate sponsor's desire for a lovely matchup in the Insight.com
Bowl, Hotmail Bowl or AOL Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There was a legitimate championship game played at Finley
Stadium Saturday and the Minutemen won it. It was not the Tostitos
Fiesta Bowl, which is supposed to be the Bowl Championship Series
title game for Division 1-A teams. Please. Show me any championship
game that is not played on the field and I'll show you a rotisserie
league showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen didn't have to deal with that. They turned into
Southern tourists the past few weeks, making two trips to Louisiana
and one here. They were the 11th seed out of 16 teams in the
Division 1-AA playoffs, came to a city that is only a few miles
north of the Georgia line, and scored 55 points on a previously
undefeated team from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was a neutral-site field,'' UMass linebacker
Khari Samuel said. ``We knew that it wasn't. Their fans had
something like 13,000 tickets and we had less than a thousand. But
that's OK. I like that. I wouldn't have liked it if this game had
been played in New England because I think it would have made us
think we had an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is that I hope you found time to watch this team
during the season. I hope UMass athletic director Bob Marcum has
the state's checkbook open so he can retain Mark Whipple as head
coach. I hope the NCAA can see the beauty of having a true title
game for all levels of football. And, please, I hope you do not
think I am gloating when I say this: I cannot believe I was paid to
watch this game.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is that you are not supposed to cheer in pressboxes. It
is unprofessional. Everyone was reminded of that before UMass and
Georgia Southern produced their 55-43 gem. I wish I could have seen
the people who made that announcement. I wish I could have seen if
they were cheering. If they weren't? Well, I'm convinced that they
are other-worldly extras from ``Star Trek'' or Area 51 experiments
who left Roswell, N.M., to see how crazy earthlings play football.
But I could not see them because I was fixed on this game. You know
how you are afraid to get up from a basketball game because you
think you might miss something? This game was like that.
</P>
<P>
   UMass scored on its first possession, had 21 points in the first
quarter, and 38 points by halftime. They opened the game with an
outrageous five-receiver set, a formation they appropriately call,
``Chattanooga.'' They faked a fourth-down punt and ran for a first
down, tried a fullback option, and threatened to drop an onside
kick when they were up by 17 points. They did that all in one half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told someone earlier in the week that it definitely was not
going to be a 10-9 game,'' Whipple said. The coach went on to say
that he thought ``45 (points) would be enough to get it done.'' He
did not smile when he said that. Think about it: It's one thing to
say that your team needs 45 points to win. It's quite another to
have confidence that your team has the ability to score 45.
</P>
<P>
   That's only one reason why Marcum should be a little nervous
this morning. Whipple took a team that was 2-9 last season and
turned it into the best group in the country. In only one year. He
tinkered with his quarterback, got a 100-meter champion from
Florida, and added a few other players, but he basically took the
core from a last-place team and produced 12 wins. Big-time programs
pay attention to stories like that. Don't be surprised in a couple
weeks when Whipple's name pops up as someone's coaching candidate
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen, though, can think about that later. Saturday,
they were out to prove their worth to a region. Everywhere you
looked downtown you saw Georgia Southern fans. They screamed out
school chants and songs 90 minutes before the game. One fan paraded
outside the stadium with a sign that read, ``If I went to UMass,
I'd kill myself.'' Once the game started, the Minutemen weren't
getting much respect from the Southern players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying, `We ain't gonna let no Yankees come down
here and beat us,''' Samuel recalled. ``I just said, `I'm going to
keep my mouth shut and play the game.' I didn't want to be jumping
around or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing the players didn't jump around because they
would have been too tired to do anything on the field. This was a
game that required stamina. Once the Eagles made it a 38-33 game,
it was obvious that Whipple's team would need that 45 and even
more.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great game to watch. It made you wonder if the players
enjoyed it, even if they were on the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, 55 is more than 43,'' Georgia Southern coach Paul
Johnson said. ``It could have been 6-3. It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The final score was not 6-3. It was 55-43. UMass had the most
points. The Minutemen are the best team in the country. It's not an
opinion. If you don't believe me, you can go to Amherst. The
players have game mementos _ including a trophy _ to prove it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
