<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTE-RANDYGORD     12-19 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTE-RANDYGORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYING HUGE PRICE, GORDON SELLS HIS SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a man can want something just a little too much.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a man can love his sport just a little too much.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a man can crave a return to the big-time just a little
too much.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Gordon has become such a man.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is a former head of the New York State Athletic
Commission, a former television boxing analyst, a former editor of
Ring magazine, a former director of boxing at Foxwoods Casino, a
former lot of things in boxing. The problem is not his past. The
problem is his present.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, 1983, a fighter named Billy Collins came to Madison
Square Garden as a promising junior middleweight with an undefeated
rec-ord. He left a broken man, half blind from being hit in the
face by the loaded gloves of a kid named Luis Resto, who always
claimed he didn't know a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did Resto's chief second, well-known trainer Panama
Lewis. In the end, Resto and Lewis did jail time after being
convicted of tampering with those gloves, gloves that not only beat
Collins out of boxing but beat the life out of him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after that fight a drunken Collins, no longer able
to fight or work because of those eyes, drove his 1972 Oldsmobile
into a hackberry tree at 68 miles per hour on a road where he used
to run every day and died. His parents believe he aimed at that
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Resto and Lewis have denied for 15 years any involvement in the
removal of half the horsehair padding from inside those killer
gloves that night. Just happened, they say. Somebody else cut the
quarter-size hole in the palm and emptied them, they say. Maybe
cornermen Artie Curry, who's dead now and can't speak for himself,
they say, or Pedro Alvarado, who along with Lewis and Resto was
banned from boxing for his involvement in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but Lewis was always considered a shadowy figure in
boxing, a guy who would do all he could to give his man an edge.
That night, Resto had a big edge on a kid from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   When Collins died, Ring magazine wrote an editorial headlined
``Murder, Plain and Simple.'' That editorial was written by Randy
Gordon and it led to a 15-year feud with Lewis, one that only
heated further after Gordon became director of the New York
commission and made clear there would be no reinstatement of Panama
Lewis's license to train boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then things have changed. Gordon fell into and out of
boxing after leaving the commission in 1995, presently working in
real estate and teaching boxing to guys in suits who wear rep ties
for a living. Lewis, meanwhile, served 2 1/2 years in jail as a
result of the Collins incident and since has trained fighters in
gyms that still allow him to work, but he has not entered a ring in
15 years because no state has agreed to re-license him.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Lewis is training Frans Botha, who will challenge
Mike Tyson Jan. 16 on a show that will be watched by millions.
Botha's manager, Sterling MacPherson, is a friend of Gordon's and
solicited his help in preparing Botha, but to do it Gordon had to
agree to work with Lewis. After much soul-searching, he did and is
presently in Las Vegas with all of them. He says he has shed many
tears over this decision, one that came after long talks with his
family, his rabbi, and a priest of his acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   He says he went back years after the incident and read the trial
transcript and talked with as many of the people involved as he
could and slowly came to the conclusion that although Lewis was
convicted and sent to jail, the evidence proved nothing but that
someone loaded the gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon says he is no longer sure it was Lewis, although he
admits he doesn't know that it wasn't and concedes something
happened in that locker room that night, and Lewis knows what it
was.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon says he told Lewis during a tear-stained meeting between
the two longtime enemies that he needed to know if he had done it
or not. Lewis, Gordon claims, showed deep remorse for what had
happened to Collins but said over and over, ``What does it matter?
He's gone and he shouldn't be gone.'' In other words, he told
Gordon nothing but what he knew Gordon wanted to hear ... which was
just enough sobbing to convince him it was all right to accept the
job and turn his back on his principles.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon says Lewis told him he was just in the wrong place at the
wrong time, adding, ``I'm not a monster.'' Well, it seems to me the
only person in the wrong place at the wrong time is dead now. His
name is not Panama Lewis. It's Billy Collins, and Gordon knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's sorry,'' Gordon said Friday night from his
hotel room in Las Vegas when asked to explain how on earth he could
have agreed to work with a man he once called party to a murder.
``I don't know if he did it or not, but I believe he's sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gordon really does believe that, but it's more likely
he's doing what people do when they love too strong or want
something too badly. He's blinding himself to the facts, and the
facts are that Panama Lewis was in charge of those gloves that
night. He was responsible for what happened to them and what
happened was that half the padding was removed and a boy was, for
all intents and purposes, beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I have spent time in the house of Billy Collins's
broken family. I have been to the spot where he died and to the
graveyard where he is buried. I have stood in a New York gym with
Resto and Lewis and asked them both what happened and listened to
their denials and got answers that didn't fit the questions being
asked.
</P>
<P>
   I have come to believe in my heart that Panama Lewis is
responsible for what happened to Billy Collins and more than likely
is the one who did the deed, although that is difficult to prove
beyond a shadow of a doubt because too many people who were there
that night are dead or too old to remember or not inclinded to
reveal what they know.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that Lewis was the one who refused to glove
up Resto when a commission inspector ordered him to. When he
didn't, the inspector left to get his superior. He was gone for 15
minutes. When he got back, Resto was gloved up and no one could
tell the gloves had been altered.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon knows inspectors came back later and found horsehair
traces on the floor of a bathroom stall in Resto's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   He knows Lewis has said time and again how he learned the little
things about getting an edge from the great trainer Ray Arcel and
that sometimes you just think you're being smart when maybe you're
being something else.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon knows these things, yet he is in Las Vegas with Botha and
his head trainer because it's a big fight and he wants to be part
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, I believe what changed his mind was not new evidence. It
was that he had been out of boxing's mainstream too long and sold
himself out to get back in.
</P>
<P>
   That is a sad thing to say because I have known Gordon a long
time and know how much he loves the sport. It is why I spoke with
him at great length about his decision. I heard him cry trying to
explain it. I heard him talk of Lewis's remorse and the doubt
created by the trial transcript and his belief now that he is not
sure what Lewis did or what he knew at the time.
</P>
<P>
   I also heard him say: ``I love the sport and I want to be part
of it. When all is said and done, if you believe he's sorry,
there's no correcting it, so I decided to do this. I knew I'd be
called the biggest hypocrite who ever lived. I'll live with it. My
personal battle over this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 minutes later, he was in tears on the telephone
trying to justify it. If he's honest with himself, he knows why the
tears came.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he is not willing to be part of the effort to get
Lewis his license back in New York, a move that if granted would
also allow him to work in other states where he is presently banned
because of a reciprocal agreement to honor suspensions by all state
commissions. Somehow he has convinced himself this washes his hands
of a dirty saga. It does not.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow he has convinced himself that blind love for a sport or
a blind desire to get back into a big fight's intoxicating action
can justify what his tears on Friday night made clear to me he
knows is wrong. It cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very strange situation,'' Gordon acknowledged.
``Nobody knows the torment I'm going through. Do I have to turn a
gig down in the sport I love because I'm with a guy two hours a day
who may or may not have emptied those gloves?''
</P>
<P>
   To that I say, yes, you do. Remorse and repentance are wonderful
things. So are second chances. We all need them. But that won't
bring Billy Collins back to his family and it shouldn't bring
Panama Lewis back his license to work in a boxing ring. It should
not have brought Randy Gordon back to Lewis's side either, no
matter how big the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he has little to do with Lewis outside preparing
Botha. He said they break no bread together. He said he asks him
almost daily if he did what he was convicted of and insists he will
know before fight night.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when I asked what he will do if Lewis says yes, he did load
the gloves of Luis Resto, Gordon says he's not sure. Sadly, I am.
</P>
<P>
   He will go to the arena and do his job with Botha and act as if
he hadn't heard what he'd heard. He'll do it because he loves his
sport too much and craves the action too much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
