<HEADLINE>
NINERS QB PLAYING BETTER THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ If the Patriots still had any starting players
left, the news that Antonio Langham just might be back in the
49ers' defensive backfield Sunday would have been cause for New
Englanders kicking their heels in glee. Langham has been lit up
more this season than any switchboard in any Congressional office
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, even if all the Patriots were healthy and Drew Bledsoe
could have sent Terry Glenn time and again deep downfield to torch
Langham, New England still would have a difficult game against the
49ers. That's because San Francisco has one player _ no, not Jerry
Rice _ who is well-nigh indispensable, if not unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the ball in my hands that much,'' Young said of
his outgaining Detroit's Barry Sanders by more than a 2-to-1 margin
last Monday. ``I'd rather put it in someone else's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Truly, though, any time the ball is in Young's hands, only good
seems to happen to the 49ers' offense. It has been that way for
years and years, but now Young is 37, and, if anything, he seems
better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as we can be right now,'' said Young of that
rarity in San Francisco, an offense that is a threat both on the
ground and in the air. ``But we've got to be able to do it week in
and week out.''
</P>
<P>
   Young still delivers those so-familiar slant passes of San
Francisco's West Coast offense as well as ever, always seeming to
find Jerry Rice or J.J. Stokes or Terrell Owens. But what is more
fascinating is that Young seems more mobile than ever, and running
better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the prime of his career,'' said 49ers coach Steve
Mariucci, ``and he's enjoying having some weapons around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Young has rushed for 437 yards this season, the second-highest
total in his career. The quarterback still has a chance to top his
all-time mark on the ground, 537 yards in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The intrigue of all this is that all know what Young will do _
particularly on a key down _ and that is to tuck the ball under his
arm if he's under pressure, sidestep one or two of those lumbering
offensive linemen, raise the ball over his head as if he's to pass
when a linebacker confronts him near the line of scrimmage and then
scamper 10 or 15 or 20 yards downfield before he hook-slides to a
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's playing very smart football,'' said Mariucci.
``He's making good decisions on passing downs and running when he
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Lions, there was a classic Young play when San
Francisco had a third down at the Detroit 9-yard line. The
quarterback dropped back to pass, was flushed over toward the
sideline, and suddenly reversed direction. He raised the ball over
his head when a Detroit linebacker approached near the line of
scrimmage and then easily scampered into a corner of the end zone _
the corner of the end zone at the opposite sideline along which he
was first trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every possession is so important,'' said Young, explaining his
philosophy of quarterbacking. ``You never want to waste a
possession.''
</P>
<P>
   Young explained why those third-and-9s that he seems to convert
so effortlessly, either with a pass to Rice or a scramble from the
pocket, are so important. ``Our theory is to be aggressive, to do
something every possession we have,'' he said. ``You have to take
advantage of every chance you have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Niners now have Garrison Hearst to gouge out huge chunks on
the ground and, as Young put it, ``every time I turn around and
hand off the ball, I look around and Garrison Hearst is 8 or 10 or
12 or 30 or 40 yards downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 49ers also have three receivers with large egos and
Young acknowledged, candidly, ``the wide receivers will be chomping
at the bit (against the Patriots) to have more balls thrown to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, with Hearst running the way he is running, with the
49ers offensive line blocking the way it has been blocking, and
with Young still so deft in finding his receivers, opposing
defenses have a true dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions chose to double-team Rice often and ``if opposing
defenses continue to play coverage on our receivers like that,
we've got to be able to run the football,'' said Mariucci. And now
it seems to be almost a matter of choice for the 49ers: Throw the
ball for 300 yards? Or run the ball for 200 yards?
</P>
<P>
   And the man making the choices, the quarterback deciding what to
do, is a man truly in his prime _ Steve Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
