<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PRESIDENTSCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP LOSS UPSETTING, BUT NOT AN UPSET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ease with which the International Team defeated the United
States at last week's Presidents Cup was, indeed, a surprise. But
don't call it an upset because the only stunner is this: People
still can't believe the US should lose one of these team events.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that the International Team's top five players (Nick
Price, Greg Norman, Ernie Els, Vijay Singh, and Steve Elkington)
had won nine majors among them. No matter that Frank Nobilo, Stuart
Appleby, and Craig Parry had justly earned world-class status with
outstanding play on the American PGA Tour. Or that Royal Melbourne
was a hard, fast golf course, the type of which the Americans
rarely play. No matter that in the 1996 Presidents Cup, the US
barely won on its home soil, 16 1/2-15 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   What seemed to be the only factor mentioned was the presence of
Tiger Woods, David Duval, Mark O'Meara, and Davis Love _ ranked
1-2-3-4 in the world _ in the US lineup. Conveniently overlooked
was that Woods, O'Meara, and Love were also in Spain a year ago
when the US lost to Europe in the Ryder Cup. That was a loss
chalked up to the quirkiness of a Valderrama layout and the magical
touch of coach Seve Balle-steros. The loss Down Under? Many pointed
to incredible good fortune (Nobilo's 40-foot birdie putt on the
18th hole of the opening match) and plain old luck (Parry's chip
shot at the same hole the next day). Again, conveniently overlooked
was the fact that Woods, Duval, O'Meara, and Love _ as well as Fred
Couples, Jim Furyk, and Justin Leonard _ all missed short putts
that could have turned around their matches in the early going when
the International Team was building momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago Bobby Jones explained that there was golf and then
there was tournament golf. Anyone who has tried to take his or her
game into competition knows exactly why Jones was saying the two
have nothing in common. Going a step further, there is tournament
golf and then there is team competition and for reasons hard to
explain, great players don't always make for a great team. That, of
course, won't stop people from making a US team led by Woods,
Duval, O'Meara, and Love the big favorite in next September's Ryder
Cup matches at The Country Club. By then, memories of Melbourne and
Valderrama will have faded, but not this reality: The ``underdog''
Europeans are 4-2-1 in the last seven Ryder Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ben Crenshaw  &LR; could not have been too happy with the way his
American colleagues played in Melbourne, but if there is a bright
side to the 20 1/2-11 1/2 defeat, it could be a more determined
effort in the Ryder Cup. Which is something Crenshaw, the US
captain, would welcome. He hopes US players who figure to be on the
team would take advantage of opportunities to play The Country Club
and get familiar with the course, something they did not do at
Valderrama or Oak Hill in Rochester, N.Y., in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw figures to have a busy 1999, but has already agreed to
take part in the 50th anniversary of the Francis Ouimet Scholarship
Fund. He will be the guest speaker and honoree March 11 as the
distinguished organization puts on a gala event at the Westin
Copley Plaza. It is a nice coup for the folks at the Ouimet and a
perfect match, too. No one in golf embraces the sport's history
quite like Crenshaw, and the Ouimet Scholarship Fund keeps alive
the memory of arguably the most important person in the history of
American golf.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the dinner are available by calling 781-891-6400.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of campus visits and serious thought,  &UR; Brent Wanner
 &LR; has committed to Wake Forest. ``It's strange,'' said Wanner, a
senior at Nauset Regional on Cape Cod, ``to know I'm going there
already when there's still a lot of (high) school left.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wanner, one of the bright young golf talents in
the country, said he was relieved to have the process behind him as
he opted for  &UR; Arnold Palmer's  &LR; alma mater over Georgia Tech,
Vanderbilt, and Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Wanner's busy summer included impressive performances in the US
Junior Amateur and the Ouimet Memorial, which he led through 36
holes before being overtaken by  &UR; Frank Vana Jr. &LR;  in the final round
at Woodland Golf Club. At the recent Polo Junior Classic at Disney
World, Wanner opened with a 67 and easily marched into match play,
where he lost in the first round. His friends from Dennis
Pines/Highlands _  &UR; Kenny Lewis  &LR; and  &UR; Michael Carbone  &LR; _ did
slightly better in that prestigious American Junior Golf
Association event, both of them making it to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Carbone will be playing his college golf at the University of
Rhode Island, while Lewis is only a junior at Dennis-Yarmouth, so
the collegiate recruiters will have to put their chase on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Another URI signee is  &UR; Justin Goodhue  &LR; of Glastonbury, Conn.,
who summers on the Cape and has been the club champion at Cranberry
Valley in Harwich.  &UR; Kristy &LR;   &UR; Howard  &LR; of Newton will attend the
University of Louisville, while  &UR; Abby Spector  &LR; of Waterville,
Maine, has signed with North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As he fights to regain world-class status,  &UR; Nick Faldo  &LR; has
entered the upcoming South African Open. A stated goal of Faldo's
is to earn his way on to the Ryder Cup team, and playing in South
Africa (a European Tour stop) is part of his strategy. No doubt he
is ready to tee it up, having played well in the recent Australian
Open. After an opening 77 Down Under, Faldo brushed past reporters
and marched to the range, though he did take a break from his
practice to talk with  &UR; Norman Von Nida &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a legend in Australian
golf. At 87, Von Nida is legally blind, but his feel for the game
is not lost; he talked putting with Faldo, who apparently
benefited, for he came back with a 69 and was in the hunt before
losing out to  &UR; Greg Chalmers  &LR; ... Great story out of South Africa
where a former gas station attendant,  &UR; Solly Sepeng &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 58, won a
senior event for the biggest paycheck of his 26-year professional
career. For years, apartheid laws prevented Sepeng from playing at
various clubs in his nation. His two-shot win over  &UR; Simon Hobday
 &LR; was his first in a PGA-sanctioned tour and earned him a free plane
ticket to take part in either a European or American senior event
in 1999.  &UR; Gary Player &LR; , &UR; Lee Trevino &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; John Jacobs  &LR; were among
those in the field ... If you had any lingering doubt that golf is
truly a world sport, consider that the top four finishers in the
girls' division at the AJGA Polo Junior Classic were from Germany,
Spain, California, and Paraguay ... The pressures of tour
qualifying have been well documented, but for one European pro,
just getting there proved a hardship.  &UR; Darren Parker &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a
30-year-old Englishman, was a passenger in a car driven by fellow
player  &UR; Robert Coles &LR;  that crashed on the way to the course in
Sotogrande, Spain. Parker came away with a broken arm, 42 stitches
in his head, and no hopes for a 1999 European Tour card. Coles was
uninjured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
