<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GUTHRIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX SIGN RELIEVER GUTHRIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every now and then the Red Sox get lucky. Since the offseason
began, they have been looking for quality pitching. And free agent
lefthander Mark Guthrie was out there all along, eager to return to
his baseball roots.
</P>
<P>
   So you can understand why the parties came together with the
signing of a two-year, $3.2 million contract Saturday. Guthrie, 33,
has been a reliever for most of his major league career, which
began in 1989. He was born in Buffalo, but grew up in Scituate,
where his family still resides.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie has been with the Minnesota Twins and Los Angeles
Dodgers. He spent his first 6 1/2 big league seasons with the Twins
and was a member of Minnesota's 1991 World Series championship
team. His last 3 1/2 seasons have been spent in Los Angeles, mainly
in a middle relief/setup role. Last season, Guthrie appeared in 53
games, third most on the Dodgers staff, with a 2-1 record and 3.50
ERA in 54 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking for a long time,'' said Guthrie. ``I knew I
wasn't going back to the Dodgers. I wanted to go back to the East
Coast, where I'd lived until I was in the sixth grade. The East
Coast is more dynamic and there is more happening there. When I was
in the American League I always enjoyed pitching at Fenway Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie will give the Red Sox bullpen depth and experience in
the wake of Dennis Eckersley's retirement. Guthrie becomes the 20th
pitcher on the team's 40-man roster but only the fifth lefthander.
The others are are Joel Adamson, Brian Barkley, Ron Mahay, and
Robert Ramsay.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie will take outfielder Darren Bragg's place on the roster.
The team decided Friday night not to tender Bragg a contract for
next season. Guthrie becomes the third free agent signed by Boston,
joining infielder Jose Offerman (from Kansas City) and righthander
Mark Portugal (from Philadelphia).
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five seasons, Guthrie has a 14-14 record with a
3.90 ERA and 247 strikeouts in 304 2/3 innings. On natural grass,
Guthrie has been even better, with a 2.86 ERA and 176 strikeouts in
224 innings over the last five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie is sure to be a favorite of Red Sox pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan. Last year, Guthrie prevented nearly 77 percent of
inherited runners (23 of 30) from scoring and retired the first
batter he faced in 36 of 53 outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get much publicity in this role,'' said Guthrie,
``but I enjoy it. In the American League you pitch more and that's
what I'd like to do. You get a lot of responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
