<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-SCENE-1220-COX     12-19 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SCENE-1220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEITHER BOMBS NOR SANCTIONS DETER IRAQIS FROM STAYING IN THEIR
COUNTRY
 &HT;    With US-IRAQ-1220.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ When the bombing started, Hilmi Al-Jarrah took just a
small bag and his family dog, Rocky, and hit the road. But they did
not flee, they headed straight to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Jarrah, an Iraqi, lives in Amman, Jordan, but his wife and
four children were in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to stay there because they love their country. They
sent for their father and their shaggy miniature sheep dog.
</P>
<P>
   By the time U.S. officials called off the air strikes after four
days, it was already early Sunday morning in Iraq. But to Iraqis
like this family, the sleepless nights of bombing were another in
along line of traumas for them and their country.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, the Al-Jarrahs sat in their large home looking
like any upper-middle class family in the United States. Alhamzed,
12, passes the time with computer games. Nadine, 19, reads Gabriel
Garcia-Marques' ``Love in the time of Cholera,'' and keeps a diary
thinking she might not make it through the week.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the stress of living under airstrikes and the
demoralizing state of their country, nostalgic for the good
schools, medical centers and oil-boom economy of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, their days have been idle. Bombings have closed the
schools. They government's television transmitters have been badly
damaged, leaving just one channel limping along for entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, tension seemed to be increasing on Iraqi streets. Major
downtown landmarks, such as the headquarters for President Saddam
Hussein's Baath Party and the offices of the government's military
industries, have been gutted by missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There were slightly more soldiers patrolling Baghdad's streets
and the start of the holy month of Ramadan, with its daily ritual
of fasting, made observers irritable as it does in even the best of
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Iraqi leaders sounded the predictably defiant chords,
urging their people to resist American aggression and fight to the
last man.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Al-Jarrahs and other families, the battle is trying
to cope with the munitions that fell practically unseen from the
skies. They sidestep questions about politics, but illustrate just
how sad it can be when people are caught in the middle of a violent
political battle that makes a country with a grand past bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky, a cream-colored shaggy thing about a foot high, sat up
and gave some yappy barks at the bombs that fell Saturday evening.
The Al-Jarrahs live near the Iraqi Ministry of Defense, a likely
target in the assault.
</P>
<P>
   At times, they have slept with relatives in a nearby house or in
the same room to support each other when the attacks create flashes
across the sky and rattle the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives are measured between the ``first war, second war or
third war,'' -- meaning the war against Iran in the 1980s, the Gulf
War in 1991 and now this.
</P>
<P>
   Hilmi Al-Jarrah, 49, used to be a commercial airline pilot until
the United Nations-imposed ``no-fly zone'' in southern Iraq shut
down Iraqi Airways in 1990. Then, he tried to open an import
business, but economic sanctions sank that venture.
</P>
<P>
   Now he deals in real estate in Jordan. The family lived there
for several years and could have stayed, but they came back. Nadine
studies architecture and says her college is excellent. She likes
the warm Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents love the secular openness of Iraq, compared to other
neighboring countries. It does not matter here that Hilmi is a
Sunni Muslim, and his wife a Shiite, or that they have many
Christian friends, or that they usually keep a Christmas tree. They
say this is where they belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be far away from our country when our country
is at war,'' Hilmi Al-Jarrah said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he talked about how hard things are now after the eight
years of economic sanctions Iraq has faced since invading Kuwait in
1990. They cannot travel anywhere without making the 11-hour drive
to Amman. Farouz Al-Jarrah is a dentist, but she has stopped
practicing because there is little dental medicine.
</P>
<P>
   They know a college professor struggling to get by on his
$12-per-month salary. And they do not barbecue anymore because some
neighbors cannot afford meat. Even before this recent bombing,
their electricity shut off for four hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   They take solace in being together, and check on relatives when
there are no airstrikes. They play with Rocky. And, they hope for a
future that is more like Iraq's good old days. It's what keep them
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not all of their life,'' Hilmi Al-Jarrah said,
gesturing toward his children. ``It might be all of my life, but I
have to worry about their futures. They have to return Baghdad to
the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
