<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOPLA MISSING WITH BC, HOLY CROSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not as if there weren't tempting options. It was, after
all, the last shopping Saturday before Christmas, and television
offered the University of Massachusetts winning a Division 1-AA
national championship, Jets-Bills, and the first presidential
impeachment vote in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps that's why only 2,811 quiet souls (a papered house,
at that) turned out for Boston College's 61-45 victory over Holy
Cross at Conte Forum Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   You know it's a tough draw when WEEI's Ted Sarandis stands beind
the press table _ a maitre d' with a microphone _ shaking hands and
telling patrons, ``Thanks for coming. Did you get enough to eat?''
</P>
<P>
   Boston College is out of session for the holidays. Students had
to evacuate by 5 p.m. Friday. This meant that an already-shrinking
fan base was reduced to player relatives, some Mass. Pikers from
Worcester, and a few folks who remember when any BC-HC game
mattered.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Boston College and Holy Cross grads held
seats of power in the Greater Boston community, and Eagle-Crusader
games were a source of considerable fun and occasional wagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to today's game I gave a 20-minute talk to our players
about what this game is,'' said Holy Cross coach Bill Raynor, a
Boston native. ``They started playing this game in 1906. It's been
a tremendous, spirited rivalry with some great players. And I
remember being here in 1990 when Holy Cross last won this game and
that was something special. Now even though we're in different
leagues and the level of basketball is different, there is interest
still felt by former players and fans.''
</P>
<P>
   There are still BC and HC grads all over our region, but there
aren't many bragging rights at stake. The schools don't play one
another in football anymore. A century-long rivalry that once
featured a Holy Cross Orange Bowl team and BC teams bound for Sugar
and Cotton Bowls was terminated in 1987 when it became clear that
Holy Cross should no longer play a Division 1 power.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball rivalry never approximated the intensity of the
Jesuit grid joust. For the better part of the century, it was all
Holy Cross as Bob Cousy, Tom Heinsohn, Ron Perry Sr., and a host of
All-Americans led the Crusaders to NCAA and NIT tourney titles. HC
remains the only New England school to win the NCAA basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   BC's hoop program turned the corner when Cousy took over as
coach. In recent years the Eagles have upended No. 1-ranked teams,
won the Big East Tournament, and twice advanced to the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   But the Glory Days of hoop are in the rearview mirror for both
schools. HC's last NCAA tournament appearance was a 30-point
blowout loss to Arkansas in 1993. BC was atop the Big East just two
years ago, and coach Jim O'Brien had a raft of recruits ready to
keep the Eagles in the hunt well into the next century. But
everything dissolved when the BC administration undercut O'Brien in
a fit of sanctimonious scrutiny, and experts predict the 1998-99
Eagles may go winless in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   And so you had a 3-7 BC team facing a 2-6 Crusader team
Saturday. The Eagles lost to Harvard and carried a four-game losing
streak into the game. Holy Cross was without starting point guard
Ryan Serravalle (stress fracture), and came into the game with a
three-game losing streak. This was the 101st basketball game
between the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The head coaches are rivals. Raynor and Skinner faced each other
a couple of times when Raynor was a freshman at Dartmouth and
Skinner was in his first year at UMass. Those were the days of
freshman teams. Skinner's frosh team had a guard named Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we beat them,'' recalled Skinner. ``I think I had 35
and Billy scored 35.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really remember,'' said Raynor. ``But I'm gonna say we
won. We had a good freshman team that year. I probably had a good
game because Al or Rick was guarding me.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said he did not guard Raynor. ``You're gonna have to ask
Rick about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by sophomore forward Jared Curry of Braintree, Raynor's
Crusaders Saturday bolted to a 9-2 lead and still held a 23-13
margin with 5:30 left in the first half. But the Eagles had success
with a full-court zone trap and cut it to 3 by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   It was all BC after intermission. The Crusaders couldn't crack
the press and scored only 5 points in the first 16 minutes of the
second half. Eagles sophomore sub forward Jonathan Beerbohm ripped
off 9 consecutive inside points as BC built a 49-36 lead with 4:33
left in the quiet arena. A yo-mama alley-oop dunk by freshman Kenny
Walls served as the exclamation point in BC's win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no sense of rivalry with anybody,'' said Skinner.
``We're not at that level yet. Our players are still trying to find
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' next home game is Jan. 6 against (gulp) top-ranked
Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
