<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-NEELYGRO     12-19 1847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-NEELYGROSEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST OF NEELY INSPIRATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cam Neely's comeback didn't go according to Hollywood script _
put away your double-runners and drop that stick, Sylvester
Stallone _ but his legacy does continue in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Michal Grosek, who has blossomed into Buffalo's leading scorer
this season, sits down before every Sabres home game and watches
videotaped highlights of Neely, once the game's premier power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Neely's agent, Boston-based Jay Fee, is also Grosek's agent. Fee
introduced the two last season and, according to Fee, the Czech
left winger asked if Fee could send him some tapes of the former
Bruins star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I sent them, Michal said to me, `He was a pretty good
player, wasn't he?''' said Fee. ``And I said, `Yeah, Michal, he was
one of the best ... and you could play like him, you've got the
skill, and you've got the size.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2-inch, 210-pound Grosek went into weekend action
with 9 goals and 19 points in 25 games, tops among all Sabres. It
doesn't appear he's about to run away with the Art Ross Trophy as
the game's top scorer, at least not this season, but he is way
ahead of his career pace (81 points in 199 games).
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Grosek began tuning in on Cam's film festival
during last season's playoff, about the same time Sabres coach
Lindy Ruff told him that his sagging play might keep him from
suiting up in the postseason. A little bit of kick-in-the-can
catalyst and a little bit of Cam have gone a long way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I want to play,'' Grosek said in an interview in
Pro Hockey EuroReport. ``Play physical games, score goals.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Grosek's career is reminiscent of how Neely
developed into the game's best blend of strength, finesse, and
ferocity at right wing. Selected 145th overall by the Jets in '93,
Grosek got only brief looks (total 28 games) over three seasons
with the Jets before being swapped with Darryl Shannon to the
Sabres in February 1996 for Craig Muni. He immediately became a
Sabres regular, though never showing a real tenaciousness around
the net until the '98 playoffs (6-4_10 in 15 games).
</P>
<P>
   Neely, of course, was a much higher pick (ninth overall by
Vancouver in '83), but never caught the eye of management in his
three seasons with the Canucks. He arrived in Boston in the summer
of '86, the day of his 21st birthday, and went on to score 36 goals
that season and 344 for the Bruins, three times breaking the
50-goal plateau in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Neely and Grosek have talked just the one time, but Fee said
they'll probably meet up again next month around the All-Star
break. Given the impact of the Neely tape, which runs about 30
minutes, Fee might want to consider distributing a few more among
his clients, or sending them out to would-be clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, but if I do that, Cam might start charging me,'' said
Fee. ``Hmm, Cam charging me, that would be a switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sabres general manager Darcy Regier sees some of
Neely in Grosek's game, but says a direct comparision is premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cam Neely was a phenomenal player,'' said Regier. ``You can
see similarities between the two, their skating, and their
strength. But Cam's quick release and that mean streak of his _
boy, he could be mean _ were something that really set him apart.
Michal has the potential to become a power forward, just by virtue
of his sheer strength from the top of the circles, but I don't
think he's quite there with Cam yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Former BU defenseman  &UR; Tom Poti &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now a regular as a rookie on
the Oilers' blue line, had to reach deep into his pocket in Miami
Wednesday night when the Edmonton rookies hosted a team dinner at
Shula's steak house. Poti,  &UR; Craig Millar &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Fred Lindquist
 &LR; divvied up a tab of $12,500. ``It's amazing when you see those
kind of numbers,'' said Poti. ``But, every rookie's got to do do
it.'' Poti had filet mignon, which ended up costing him about $420
an ounce ... Gee, if the Hurricanes keep this up, do you suppose
all those daddywarbucks in Hartford will try to woo back the
Forever .500s with enough governmental givebacks that they could
return and deal for  &UR; Pavel Bure &LR; ? And who would have thought the
Hurricanes could have reshaped the product so significantly with
 &UR; Ron Francis  &LR; ranking no better than seventh in team scoring as of
last week? ... Another one of Fee's clients, Toronto netminder
 &UR; Felix Potvin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; remains home in Montreal, waiting for the Leafs to
deal him _ something that can't happen now until the holiday trade
freeze expires at midnight, Dec. 27. ``I feel the Leafs have
overplayed their hand,'' said Fee. ``Whatever they've been offered,
it never seems that it's quite enough.'' Clubs believed to have
interest: Chicago, Montreal, Florida, and the Islanders ... Red
Wing power forward  &UR; Brendan Shanahan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; here at the Fleet last
night, said he has grown tired of ``all the chicken littles'' who
constantly want to tinker with the game's rules. Shanahan: ``I've
only been in the game 12 years, so I'm not the oldest veteran or
the youngest guy. Now one of the latest cries is that the game
isn't producing enough skilled players. Heck, in Canada there was a
government inquiry _ why don't we have skilled players? _ when we
couldn't beat the Czechs in a shootout (at the Olympics). Hey, when
the Czechs shut out the Russians, there was no government inquiry
in Russia why they couldn't score a goal against 'em.'' ... The
Sabres watched the Rangers pluck young defenseman  &UR; Rumun Ndur  &LR; off
their roster Friday, claiming the 23-year-old Czech off the waiver
wire. Rangers coach  &UR; John Muckler  &LR; was the Sabres GM when Buffalo
drafted Ndur in '94. ``There will always be that risk there for us,
because of John,'' acknowledged Regier. On Friday, Regier dealt
disgruntled forward  &UR; Donald Audette &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the 29-year-old right winger
whose career has been diminished slightly by a series of knee
injuries and operations, to Los Angeles for a second-round draft
pick in '99. Audette has sat out all season in a contract dispute
as agent  &UR; Gilles Lupien  &LR; has been unable to strike a deal.
According to Audette, the Kings have offered him a two-year deal
worth $3.6 million ... Former Boston College star  &UR; Marty McInnis
 &LR; is finally showing the scoring touch he had in his days at the
Heights. Swapped to Anaheim this season, (for a fourth-round draft
pick in 2000 immediately after the Blackhawks obtained him from
Calgary), McInnis has eight goals, four of them game-winners, with
the Ducks. He suffered a cracked cheekbone late last week but
hasn't left the lineup ...  &UR; Ziggy Palffy's  &LR; deal with the
Islanders, agreed to Thursday, works out to $33 million over six
years, provided the Isles pick up the $7 million option in year No.
6. He'll make a pro-rated $3 million for the rest of this season
(about $1.8 million). If he keeps improving as a sniper, Palffy
could look woefully underpaid by the summer of 2000 ...  &UR; Bob
Goodenow &LR; , &UR;  &LR; head of the Players' Association, wouldn't offer an
opinion as to when he thinks the NHL will see its first $100
million contract (a la the Dodgers'  &UR; Kevin Brown &LR; ). ``Oh, that's
impossible to say,'' said Goodenow. ``I suppose it will be when
there's a player available that another team believes is worth that
kind of money.'' In other words, what's your house worth? What
someone's willing to pay for it? Look for that first $100 million
deal on or before July 1, 2000 (annual free agency date), which
will give the NHL about 18 months to catch up to the salary curve.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman  &LR; cautions those who might be
overly eager to see 19-year-old  &UR; Joe Thornton  &LR; step in and do the
job now for the Bruins. ``Look at  &UR; Guy Lafleur &LR; ,'' said Bowman.
``As good as he was _ and remember, he was drafted just before his
20th birthday _ it took him a few years to get established.''
Bowman arrived in Montreal with Lafleur in the fall of '71 and
recalls watching him struggle mightily at center, especially
against Boston. ``He was no match for ( &UR; Phil &LR; )  &UR; Esposito. &LR;  The
Bruins had that size, with Esposito and  &UR; Ken Hodge  &LR; and  &UR; Wayne
Cashman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and Lafleur was just overmatched. He didn't have the
confidence. Remember, he was drafted No. 1 and he was supposed to
replace ( &UR; Jean &LR; )  &UR; Beliveau,  &LR; but put him out there against a great
player, and he couldn't win a faceoff. No way did I think he'd be a
superstar.'' In his fourth season, switched to right wing, Lafleur
fired in 53 goals _ the first of his six straight 50-plus seasons
... Planet Warning. Planet Warning.  &UR; Rick Curran &LR; , &UR;  &LR; agent for  &UR; Al
Iafrate &LR; , &UR;  &LR; reports that his client should be ready to attempt an
NHL comeback ``within a month or so.'' The former Bruins defenseman
opted to retire during the offseason, eschewing the contract he had
in hand from the Hurricanes, not wanting to take the money if he
didn't feel his knees could withstand game pressure. According to
Curran, Iafrate has been rehabbing on his own in Michigan, feels
good again, and, if all goes right, will report to the 'Canes next
month. ``The deal's been in place the whole time,'' said Curran.
``But Al didn't feel right about taking the money if he didn't feel
he could play, which is why he retired. But he's been working at
his own pace, feels much better, and he looks like he's ready to
go.'' ...  &UR; Paul Coffey  &LR; is finally getting some ice time in
Chicago. The Hall-of-Famer-to-be has been out almost all season
because of nerve damage in his back, which doctors told him was
caused by a steroid epidural he received earlier this year that was
meant to ease back pain. When the pain crept down to his leg and
into his right foot, he sought another opinion, and that's when
doctors at the Mayo Clinic diagnosed the nerve damage ... Detroit's
 &UR; Doug Brown &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a former BC Eagle, on the superior core of NHL
defensemen who still keep playing well into their 30s _ guys such
as Coffey,  &UR; Ray Bourque &LR; , &UR; Larry Murphy &LR; , &UR; Chris Chelios &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Al
MacInnis &LR; : ``Maybe these guys all grew up watching  &UR; Bobby Orr &LR; .''
And where will the next group come from? ``I think we're seeing
them now,'' said Brown. ``There's  &UR; Rob Blake  &LR; in Los Angeles and
 &UR; Ed Jovanovski  &LR; in Florida _ it's the group that watched all these
guys who are still playing.''... Perhaps the best hockey read of
the season:  &UR; David Salter's  &LR; feature on  &UR; Steve Durbano &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ex-tough
guy of the Blues, Penguins, Scouts, and Rockies, in the Dec. 18
Hockey News. Durbano, now 47, lives in Yellowknife, Northwest
Territories, where he sells cleaning goods and shampoos carpets and
rugs. When he did time in an Ontario prison in the '80s for drug
trafficking, only one former teammate came to visit him: ex-Bruin
 &UR; Ken Linseman &LR; . Durbano on his new life: ``I give myself a year of
real hard work, a lot of promotion, pounding the streets handing
out flyers, knocking (on) doors, introducing myself, not as Steve
Durbano the ex-hockey player, but Steve Durbano with
Electrolux/Electroclean. I'm not Bobby Orr in this town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
