<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PROBOWL-TYLAW-BOS     12-19 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PROBOWL-TYLAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' SECONDARY FIRST RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH _ The old saying is that figures lie and liars
figure, but how do you figure this?
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the annual Pro Bowl team was announced and the
26th-ranked pass defense in the National Football League placed two
members on the AFC team and a third as an alternate. That meant
three of the four members of the secondary of the New England
Patriots had been voted among the league's elite by their peers
despite the fact many of those peers had riddled them with pass
completions, if you choose to believe the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the numbers, the Patriots have allowed 3,186 yards
through the air this season, an average of 227.6 a game. The
statistics say the Patriots have allowed 58.1 percent of the 515
throws against them to be completed, and there can be no arguing
the fact that 19 of the 27 touchdowns scored on New England have
been produced by receivers catching balls either over, behind or
through that secondary.
</P>
<P>
   So how did Ty Law become a first-team Pro Bowl cornerback,
strong safety Lawyer Milloy become the third safety on the AFC
all-star team, and free safety Willie Clay be selected as an
alternate?
</P>
<P>
   Patriots secondary coach Ron Lynn believes he knows the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those statistics are deceptive,'' said Lynn. ``We feel the
true barometers are yards per attempt and touchdowns per attempt,
and we're very good in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people realized we have good players back there that
have been playing well with a hobbled pass rush in front of them.
With Willie (McGinest) out so much and Chris Slade bothered by his
ankle and knee most of the year, we haven't got the kind of
pressure on opposing quarterbacks we'd hoped for, and that has to
affect your secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to pass defense, it's all connected. With our
(overall) ranking, it is surprising to some extent that people
looked past those numbers and realized how well Ty and Lawyer and
Willie have played, but it makes you feel good that they did
because it was important to them.''
</P>
<P>
   To no one more so than Law, who many felt a year ago deserved
such an accolade but failed to gain it, and who this season is tied
with Miami cornerback Terrell Buckley for the NFL lead in
interceptions (8) yet knows that number could have been
overshadowed by the negative ones against his secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley and teammate Sam Madison learned the hard way this week
that no number guarantees anything when Pro Bowl ballots are filled
out. They have more interceptions (15) than any starting cornerback
tandem in the league and they play on the NFL's sixth-rated pass
defense, yet neither will make the trip to Hawaii in February. Such
are the vagaries of a selection process Law needed four years to
crack but doesn't yet fully understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times it's a popularity contest,'' Law said of the
oft-criticized Pro Bowl balloting. ``Terrell deserved to go as much
as I did. How does anyone justify that? He got my top vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still think it says something about the way we've played
here this year to be selected when you're ranked 26th in the NFL in
pass defense. I'm glad people didn't just look at our numbers and
judge us on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers can be deceiving. We've given up a lot of yards but
that's not because we couldn't play individually. Look at our run
defense. No one can hardly run on us (89.1 yards a game), so teams
have to try and throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the numbers of balls they had to throw (515) to get
that yardage (6.1 yards per attempt). Teams have had to throw 40
(36 to be precise) times a game to make their yardage. And me,
personally, I've got eight interceptions and 32 passes defended, so
I think that's saying something, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the voters who elected Law along with the Jets' Aaron
Glenn over Buckley and Madison and added Seattle's Shawn Springs,
whose seven interceptions were enough to make him the third corner
picked.
</P>
<P>
   While Law leads the NFL in interceptions overall, Milloy leads
all AFC safeties with five and is the Patriots' second leading
tackler with 124. Although Lynn acknowledges the latter stat is not
necessarily a good sign for his defensive unit as a whole, it has
been for Milloy, whom Lynn feels caught the attention of his peers
by the knockout shots he has delivered both at the line of
scrimmage and in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyer is a legitimate tough guy,'' Lynn said. ``He's a
throwback in that regard. He's fearless as a competitor, and people
notice that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a passion for the game. The fact is there are guys
who are bigger and there are guys who are faster and there are guys
who are stronger at that position, but there's not many who will
play it with the fire and commitment he brings to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very aggressive. I think that's a by-product of his
toughness and his love of the game, and you see it when he hits
somebody. He tackles guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he does, hitting them the way Denver's Steve Atwater has,
which has put Atwater in the Pro Bowl for the eighth time in his 10
NFL seasons. Why Milloy plays this way may be a combination of
things, but one factor surely is that football helped save him from
a troubled youth, which included a period in which he did not know
where his mother was.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she would return and his family would be reborn, but
in her absence it was sports _ and the most violent of sports in
particular _ that held him together.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be rewarded out of respect for your progression over the
years is a great feeling,'' the three-year veteran said of his Pro
Bowl selection. ``I thought I'd been progressing, and this helps
reinforce that feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I've been a consistent tackler and consistently played
my position. I think it's been my best year, so if I hadn't gotten
it I would have been disappointed for a day or two, but you know
how hard it is to push some of those (Pro Bowl) veterans out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've all been helped by having so many games on
national TV. We've gotten pretty good coverage, and got a lot of
situations where people were talking and writing good about us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But being picked isn't about going to Hawaii. It's about
earning and maintaining that respect around the league.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own way, Clay has managed to do that during a season of
trial in which he has often been forced to sacrifice his own
obsession with making plays for the good of a secondary that has
struggled to find a solid corner to go with Law.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the year, Clay has been rolled over the top of the
other corner, playing a game of reinforcement rather than one of a
truly free safety, which has often taken away opportunities for
interceptions and fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Clay has only two interceptions and one fumble recovery and has,
at times, been the subject of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   But, while the uneducated may have had little idea what Clay's
role was this season, Lynn knows it well. Instead of playing the
role of ``Big Play'' Clay that led him to a multi-million-dollar
free agent contract several years ago when he came to New England,
he became best supporting actor, an often frustrating role but one
that has not gone unnoticed by his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie just does so much for our football team that the public
doesn't understand,'' said Lynn. ``But all our players know.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands the `whys' of what we're doing on defense, not
just the hows. He helps every guy out there. I told Ty and Lawyer
that they deserved (to be selected) but that both of them should go
to Willie and thank him for putting them in position to make those
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Law and Milloy did more than that this week when they asked Clay
to be their guest in Hawaii if he isn't moved from alternate status
to the Pro Bowl roster. Explained Milloy, ``Willie's the reason we
were in position to make the plays we did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He does so many things for this team it isn't funny,'' Lunn
added. ``You can't tell him that enough because of all the emphasis
on stats in this culture, but it's true. I know this: I have to
make no apologies for him being mentioned on that (Pro Bowl)
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor for Law or Milloy, two guys who may play on the 26th- rated
pass defense Sunday but will be part of the AFC's best one come
Feb. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
