<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8693 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-19 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO KEEP THIS WINDOW OPEN, COWBOYS MUST BEAT EAGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It made perfect sense then. It is reality now. Harsh reality.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1994, Troy Aikman began talking about the Valley
Ranch ``window of opportunity that was closing.'' The Cowboys had
reached dynasty status, but free agency, the salary cap and normal
football attrition was chipping away at the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we were too good to waste what we had,'' Aikman
said last week. ``We had won two Super Bowls. I thought we could
win two or three more before the window closed. That's what I kept
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning two or three more didn't happen. If anything, the world
championship of '95 was a surprise, considering the internal
turmoil that engulfed the Cowboys in December of that year. After
that, the slide south became an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   And now ...
</P>
<P>
   The window has slammed shut.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowls are strictly memories for these Cowboys. Today at
Texas Stadium will be just another Sunday of attempted playoff
survival. Even the Eagles are scary.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, of course, will not admit the dream has died. It's the
``team thing'' that prevents such a confession, but evidence over
the past three weeks is hard to deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our window has closed,'' he said, ``but instead,
it's now more a case of us looking out a different window.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reinvent ourselves. The cast of players is so
different, there is no way we can be compared to where we were four
and five years ago. Different team, different window.''
</P>
<P>
   But what they see is a rather parched landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-November, the view was different. The Cowboys had risen
to borderline NFC championship contender. But the ground was shaky.
When injuries hit, the ground caved in.
</P>
<P>
   Until he was gone, no one realized how important Ernie Mills was
to the offense. Mills' numbers and production were outstanding, but
he still was easy to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   While Michael Irvin struggled, and still struggles, to grasp a
new offense, he became only a receiving shadow of his former self.
Irvin, however, maintained immense respect from opposing defensive
units and a veteran like Mills pounced on that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   With Mills gone, however, the experience factor at receiver went
to nil. Billy Davis became more of a marked man, and that showed.
Strangely, it's been Patrick Jeffers, No. 6 out of six receivers on
the roster a month ago, who has responded best.
</P>
<P>
   The David LaFleur injury took out a blocking tight end, hurting
the ground game. Plus, LaFleur was a receiver who had to be
accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us considered a Mills and a LaFleur such vital
components? Only the offensive failures of the past two weeks have
emphasized that.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the middle of the offensive line began to show
both green-ness and old age. Center Mike Kiselak and guard Flozell
Adams are rookies. Guard Nate Newton is ancient. None are playing
well at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Bet me on this:
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' first draft pick in April will be a center. Chan
Gailey is a stickler for running the ball, which makes him no
different from most coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Cowboys were smoke and mirrors to begin with.
But when Nine-Toed Deion took his hike, it changed so much about
defensive strategy. This demonstrates the existing fundamental
weakness of the defense, that a cornerback could have a major
impact on the system. It's not supposed to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman parrots Gailey when it comes to the injuries. ``They
can't be used as an excuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But they are an excuse. A legitimate excuse. To be competitive,
the Cowboys have to have health. Over the course of an NFL season,
that is hard to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say,'' added Aikman, ``we wouldn't be in the position
we are in right now if we'd had a bit more luck on injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   With six losses this season, all can be accounted for, save for
the disgusting display in New Orleans. Otherwise:
</P>
<P>
   Denver _ not good enough. Oakland _ scored 12 points without
Aikman. Chicago _ scored 12 points without Aikman. Minnesota _
bombs away on a Deion-less secondary. Kansas City _ too many
injuries and a loss of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who will say beating Philadelphia today would
prove nothing. Wrong. The Cowboys, by winning a game again, will
accomplish plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``To return to the right mindset, the Eagles are our most
important game of the season,'' said owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out the old window, you couldn't see it that way. But
without question, this is a different window that is also closing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
