<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., BRITAIN END BOMBARDMENT OF IRAQI TARGETS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ended four days of air attacks on
Iraq Saturday, saying he was confident ``significant damage'' had
been inflicted on Saddam Hussein's command structures.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after becoming only the second president ever to be
impeached, Clinton made a national television appearance to assure
Americans that the strikes had reduced Iraq's ability to produce
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But the president warned that he was ready to order further
military action if Iraq continues to produce and use chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would welcome the return of (the United Nations weapons
inspection team) back into Iraq,'' Clinton said. ``But ... if not
allowed to resume its work on a regular basis, we will remain
vigilant and prepared to use force if we see that Iraq is
rebuilding its weapons programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced his decision to end U.S.-British attacks,
dubbed Operation Desert Fox, following a meeting at the White House
with his top national security advisers and a telephone
conversation with British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That operation is now complete,'' Clinton said, revealing that
the Desert Fox mission was scheduled to last only 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Blair noted that all British and U.S. forces involved
had returned safely to their ships and land bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objectives have been achieved. We set out to degrade
Saddam's military and weapons capability, and we have done so,''
Blair told reporters. He said that severe damage had been done to
many of the elite Republican Guard units responsible for propping
up Saddam's regime and hiding his weapons programs from U.N.
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing at the Pentagon, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said the air strikes had inflicted ``substantial damage'' on seven
categories of targets, including industrial facilities and oil
refineries, military command centers, and missile sites.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen estimated the strikes had set back Saddam's ``war fighting
capability'' by ``at least a year,'' including his ability to make
and deliver weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have selected those targets which pose the greatest risk to
the region _ chemical, biological, and indeed even potentially
nuclear capability and the means to deliver them,'' the secretary
said. ``We believe that we have inflicted substantial damage upon
his capability to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   After calling off the strikes, Clinton stressed that the threat
of renewed force would play an important role in a strategy he
wants to devise with U.S. allies to contain Saddam and possibly
force him from power.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy, he said, would include maintaining a strong U.S.
presence in the Persian Gulf region to enforce the no-fly zones
over Iraq, maintaining extensive sanctions against Iraq, and
providing renewed assistance to Iraqi opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long term, the best way to end the threat that Saddam
poses to his own people in the region is for Iraq to have a
different government. We will intensify our engagement with the
Iraqi opposition groups, prudently and effectively,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the United States stands ``ready to help a new
leadership in Baghdad that abides by its international commitments
and respects the rights of its own people.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton called off the attacks, U.S. and British forces
continued to bomb and fire cruise missiles at large concentrations
of Saddam's Republican Guard troops and sites believed to house
elements of his chemical and biological weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's forces responded with ineffective anti-aircraft fire,
which has been the only Iraqi military response during the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missiles fired from U.S. ships in the Persian Gulf and
laser-guided bombs apparently destroyed a good portion of Iraq's
air defense system. As a result, said one Pentagon official, ``we
have been able to fly ``into Iraq and not been successfully engaged
by any of the ... air defense systems.``
</P>
<P>
   One Pentagon official said the bombing and missile attacks on
key army installations were meant to ``eliminate'' as many of
Saddam's elite troops as possible. He said Saddam's most loyal
security forces were targeted in an effort to increase the
possibility of a rebellion against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Guard was a key target,'' the official said.
``They not only guard Saddam, they also keep his weapons hidden
from inspectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acknowledged that the attacks on the Republican Guard
locations could have a destabilizing effect on Saddam's regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that we attack those forces who are in charge
and help him either conceal, move, transport and maintain these
weapons of mass destruction programs, then that can have the
consequence of degrading his forces and his stability,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary added that only military-related targets were hit
in an effort to reduce the chance of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
stressed that the damage to Iraqi targets was apparently more
``significant'' than initial assessments of the missile and bomb
strikes had indicated. He said that some 100 targets had been hit
one or more times during the operation. Although he declined to
give a precise number of cruise missiles and bombs used in the
strikes, he told reporters that more than 400 would be ``in the
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is being executed with precision and success,''
Shelton said, using satellite photographs and videotape from U.S.
warplanes to illustrate how many of the targets had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Before he called off the operation, Clinton offered an
explanation for the continued bombing in a videotaped message to
the Arab world as it was beginning to observe the holy month of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Saddam as a vicious dictator responsible for a
``reign of terror against own people,'' Clinton said the Iraqi
leader was a threat to all ``Muslims and non-Muslims alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing Saddam's refusal to go along with U.N. inspections,
Clinton said, ``We had to act. Saddam simply must not be allowed to
threaten his neighbors or the world with nuclear arms, poison gas
or biological weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
