<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-RDP-1STLD-WRITET     12-19 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: years ago. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those Iraqi targets that received little or no damage were
struck again, while new military and industrial sites were targeted
in Saturday's raids, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even by the Pentagon's definitions, 18 of the 74 analyzed
targets received little or no damage.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign ended with no U.S. or British casualties or planes
shot down, a testament to the use of unmanned cruise missiles and
relatively little resistance from Iraq's air defenses other than
ineffective anti-aircraft artillery. Iraq has said that at least 68
civilians have died, but there has not yet been a clear accounting
of casualties there.
</P>
<P>
   A second aircraft carrier, the Carl Vinson, entered the Persian
Gulf and moved into position to take part in a fourth day of
strikes, joining the carrier Enterprise, whose F-14, F-18/A and
EA-6B jets had pounded Iraq for three days. Accompanying the Carl
Vinson were six cruisers and destroyers able to fire Tomahawk
cruise missiles, but officials said they did not launch them,
saving them, significantly, for any future strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's attack included strikes by F-16 and F-15 fighters, as
well as British Tornado fighters, based in Kuwait and supported by
aerial tankers and AWACS communication jets flying out of Saudi
Arabia. B-1 bombers, based in Oman, also flew into Iraq on their
first combat missions after a troubled, three-decade development.
</P>
<P>
   A focus of the assault was the barracks and headquarters of four
divisions of the Republican Guard. U.S. missiles also hit seven or
eight of Saddam's presidential palaces and the headquarters of
Saddam's Baath Party in Baghdad, badly damaging it, Pentagon and
British officials said. Iraq's refusal to allow U.N. weapons
inspectors to inspect that building was one of the reasons the
United States and Britain cited it for targeting.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, signs of destruction were everywhere after the third
night of the attack unleashed the most punishing strikes yet in
Baghdad. Saddam's forces said they had shot down 23 of 60 cruise
missiles fired into Baghdad overnight, a claim the Pentagon
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the diplomatic sensitivities of attacking during
Ramadan, Clinton prepared a videotaped address to be broadcast in
the Arab world Saturday, explaining the American rationale for
striking Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's address came amid a swelling anger in the region.
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, one of the closest American
allies in the Arab world, called for an immediate halt to the
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has spent the last few months trying to revive the
Middle East peace effort and just last week played the role of
mediator between the Israelis and Palestinians, declared in his
radio address the ``most profound admiration for Islam.'' And he
sought to distinguish the assault on Saddam, saying the Iraqi
leader had disregarded the United Nations, other Arab states and
his own people.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decision to use force is easy, especially at a time when
I'm working so hard to build peace in the Middle East and to
strengthen our own relations with the Arab world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the days ahead, I hope all Muslims will consider America's
sincere desire to work with all people in the Middle East to build
peace,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In London, George Robertson, Britain's defense secretary, said
the attacks had hit 100 military and industrial targets and had
caused ``substantial damage.''
</P>
<P>
   While the overthrow of Saddam was not the stated objective,
Robertson made it clear that the strikes on the Republican Guard
were meant to weaken Saddam's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republican Guard ceases to support Saddam, his brutal
regime is under immediate threat,'' Robertson said. ``We want the
Republican Guard to know that the cozy life they have led under
Saddam is under attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair said he could not guarantee that the air assault would
topple Saddam. But he added, ``It would be wonderful if Saddam
could be removed from power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
