<HEADER>
A8704 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-1STL     12-19 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT IS ONLY LATEST BATTLE IN `CULTURAL WAR' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: subs 6th graf to correct to ``situational'' sted of
``situation'') 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The last time the House impeached a president, it
was a direct result of the Civil War. This time, the historic act
was an indirect result of a cultural war.
</P>
<P>
   President Andrew Johnson was impeached in 1868 primarily because
he rejected radical Reconstruction plans for the South. He was
spared removal from office by a single vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was impeached Saturday by a narrow, almost
strictly party-line vote on two articles, claiming perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   In that debate, Republicans may have contended that the case
against Clinton hinged on lying under oath and other official
misdeeds, while Democrats argued it was all about sex. But not far
beneath the surface of the historic political drama loomed a
broader, more transcendent issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is in the dock now, in part, because of a nasty national
battle over values that has waxed and waned for almost 30 years. In
many ways, House consideration of impeaching Clinton was the 1960s
coming home to roost.
</P>
<P>
   To many Republicans in the House and beyond, Clinton is a
classic ``if it feels good, do it'' baby boomer. To the social
conservatives who now hold sway in the GOP, Clinton is situational
ethics and moral relativism incarnate, be the issue the current
dispute about sex and lying or his older controversial actions _
draft evasion, anti-war activism and smoking marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   To many Democrats, the Republican majority _ and independent
counsel Kenneth Starr _ are direct descendants of the late Arizona
Sen. Barry Goldwater dictum that ``extremism in the defense of
liberty is no vice.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri even hinted at
the earlier ugly phenomenon of McCarthyism when he spoke of
``inquisition'' and demanded that the politics of ``smear and slash
and burn must end.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the impeachment vote neared Saturday, the split arose
sharply as House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, characterized the House
debate as ``relativism vs. absolute truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., rose to counter that the
House was ``losing sight of the distinction between sins, which
ought to be between a person and his family and his God, and
crimes, which are the concern of the state and of society as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of the cultural divide echoed earlier in the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   When a Democrat, Rep. Tom Lantos of California, said that
impeachment for lying about sex violated ``the principle of
proportionality,'' a Republican, Rep. Merrill Cook of Utah, replied
that ``a lie is a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook derided the idea that Clinton's oath before his January
deposition or his August grand jury testimony committed him only to
``the truth that's convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans don't think much of attempts to make bank shots
about deeper cultural divisions off the impeachment debate. They
are quick _ and correct _ to point out that were it not for
Clinton's smarmy White House dalliances with former intern Monica
Lewinsky and his attempts to conceal them, the president would not
be caught up in the first impeachment debate in the full House in
130 years.
</P>
<P>
   But experienced social commentators believe the additional
social perspectives present in the debate are unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just an easy theory, it is absolutely part of our
times. It's playing out right now, every day, before our eyes,''
said Haynes B. Johnson, the former Washington Post reporter who
chronicled the mood of the last decade in his ``Sleepwalking
through History: America in the Reagan Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more than just this moment. It's much more than just
Bill Clinton,'' Johnson said. The ``cultural war'' spoken of by
conservative commentator Pat Buchanan ``is really true.''
</P>
<P>
   George Shipley, an international corporate strategist and
Democratic adviser based in Austin, Texas, said the two sides of
the impeachment debate broadly represent the classic dichotomy from
the 1960s: ``Those people who expressed a liberated lifestyle and
those who were repelled from it.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, 30 years later, Shipley said, the parameters of that
debate have shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moral corset worn in public by these Republicans is not
very attractive,'' Shipley said, and could result in a backlash.
``The American people have sent them a message: Get off the
president's back. They haven't heard that message. It cost them the
(Newt Gingrich) speakership, and it may well cost them the Congress
in the 2000 election.``
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rasky, former chief congressional correspondent of the New
York Times and now a journalism professor at the University of
California at Berkeley who studies cultural developments, called
the current impeachment debate ``the other bookend of the cultural
revolution'' that rocked the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, she said, is ``the poster boy of everything that
(Republicans and conservatives) found hateful'' about the era. ``He
is the embodiment of everything that began to go wrong with the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than producing a generation tempered by world war and the
Depression _ the 1960s sent forth a generation ``tempered by
nothing except prosperity,'' Rasky said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she observed, the GOP right, which is
controlling the impeachment process, is ``the indigestible lump of
Republicanism,'' which makes the party unacceptable to a broad
swath of America.
</P>
<P>
   The animosity of conservative Republicans against Clinton has a
historic grounding, several social analysts agreed, going back to
the 1964 presidential election and the drubbing of Republican
nominee Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a transcendent moment for liberalism in America,''
Haynes Johnson said. Looking at the House Republicans, he observed:
``These are Goldwater boys and girls in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   But the political landscape quickly began to shift, beginning
with the election of Ronald Reagan as governor of California in
1966. Reagan took on the college demonstrators and what he saw as
permissive educators. Incumbent Democratic Gov. Pat Brown's attempt
to label Reagan an extremist failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Goldwater they tasted defeat,'' Rasky said of
conservatives, ``but with Reagan they found out how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Quickly the phenomenon took on national implications. Richard
Nixon played on similar cultural themes in the national election of
1968 and rallied ``the silent majority'' shocked by the antiwar
protests and other civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   Even that era echoed in the House debate Friday, as a Vietnam
veteran, Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, rose to speak in favor of
impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you serve in the Vietnam War?'' Hyde asked Johnson,
drawing the unspoken comparison with Clinton, who resisted military
service in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Johnson said, and earlier in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much time did you spend in a prison camp in Hanoi?'' Hyde
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly seven years,'' Johnson answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're qualified to talk about the military service,''
said Hyde, his broader, deeper meaning lost on almost no one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
