u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-PENTAGON-1STLEDE     12-19 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-PENTAGON-1ST </SLUG>
 LEDE-WRITETHRU-BOS  
 (w and i coding)  
 CLINTON CITES SUCCESS, HALTS AIR WAR
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hours after being impeached by the House of
Representatives Saturday, President Clinton declared victory in his
air war on Iraq and brought his bombing-campaign to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident we have achieved our mission,'' Clinton
proclaimed, adding that the attacks ``inflicted significant
damage'' on Saddam Hussein's ability to threaten his neighbors with
nuclear, chemical, or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president emphasized, ``We will remain vigilant . .
. prepared to use force'' again if it seems Hussein resumes
aggressive activities. He said that sanctions, which have deprived
Iraq of $120 billion so far, would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hoped Hussein would allow United Nations
inspectors to reenter Iraq, but said he would continue to encourage
Iraqi opposition factions that seek to overthrow Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference a few hours before Clinton's announcement,
the Pentagon sharply upgraded its estimate of how much damage the
airstrikes had inflicted on Hussein's military power. The new
assessment clearly gave Clinton an opening to stop the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, over three nights of airstrikes, many targets _
including those related to Hussein's nuclear, chemical, and
biological weapons program _ remained only lightly damaged, and
several others were not attacked at all.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his decision after his national security advisers
briefed him on these results late Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As the fourth night of bombing got under way, Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen said the attacks have ``substantially degraded''
the Iraqi leader's ability to wage war.
</P>
<P>
   General Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
declared himself ``very pleased with the results'' and reported
``significant success.'' The upbeat words were explicitly meant to
reverse the glum impression of Friday's news briefing, when Cohen
said he was merely ``satisfied'' and Shelton allowed that ``not
all'' the strikes had ``gone according to plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the brighter picture, other officers said, was due to
the results of Friday night's ferocious barrage of bombs and cruise
missiles, some of which struck targets that they had missed or just
lightly damaged before.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was also due to revisions by intelligence analysts,
who, the day before, had not had time to examine satellite photos
of all the targets.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday morning, US and British bombs and missiles had
attacked 97 targets and done at least some damage to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   This marked an advance over the day before, when 89 targets had
been attacked, of which 12 received no damage.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 cruise missiles, each costing nearly $1 million, were
fired from B-52 bombers and ships at sea. An untold number of
laser-guided bombs, but probably at least 300, were dropped by F-14
and F-18 combat planes flying off the USS Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Only cruise missiles were used over Baghdad, reflecting the US
commanders' extreme caution in this operation. Officials Saturday
said no planes were shot down.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, top US officials said the goal of Operation
Desert Fox was to ``degrade'' and ``diminish'' Hussein's ability to
threaten his neighbors with chemical, nuclear, or biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen Saturday uttered both of those magic words, saying the
attack ``substantially degraded'' his military capabilities and
``diminished'' his ability to threaten his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   These words gave the president the option to declare the war
over.
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon revealed more about what kinds of targets were
being hit and not hit, Operation Desert Fox came to look less like
a comprehensive attack on Hussein's ability to make weapons of mass
destruction, and more like an attempt to destabilize his grip on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the airstrikes were aimed at Hussein's private security
apparatus, the transmitters that let him communicate with soldiers
in the south of Iraq, and his intelligence headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has denied that destabilization was the operation's goal.
However, he acknowledged that would certainly be a ``consequence''
of degrading Hussein's military power.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, key elements of what officials said was the main
target _ Hussein's ability to make chemical, nuclear, and
biological weapons _ went untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acknowledged Saturday that ``dual-use'' facilities _
plants that produce both chemical weapons and civilian products _
were not attacked at all, in order to avoid hurting the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally believed dual-use facilities are the only
chemical sites remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Sites that may be producing nuclear and biological weapons were
also untargeted, if such things exist.
</P>
<P>
   Airstrikes were mounted, however, on sites believed to be
developing and building the missiles that could deliver these
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday morning, the Pentagon said forces attacked 11
such sites, inflicting severe damage on one, moderate damage on
five, and light damage on one. The strikes did not fully destroy
any.
</P>
<P>
   However, General Thomas Wilson, the Joint Chiefs' intelligence
director, said Saturday that the strikes have set back Iraq's
ability to build long-range missiles by ``at least a year.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Wilson also noted that those facilities can now build
only short-range missiles _ which are allowed by United Nations
resolutions _ and that, even if there were no airstrikes, it would
take ``a couple of years'' for the Iraqis to convert them to
long-range weapons. He did emphasize that they seem to have
``plans'' to try to make this conversion.
</P>
</TEXT>
