<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAPSULE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS-EAGLES CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COWBOYS (8-6) Can the Cowboys repeat their 34-0 drubbing of the
Eagles on Nov. 2?
</P>
<P>
   A shutout of any team is highly unlikely, even of the Eagles,
who are averaging 10.1 points per game. The Cowboys held the Eagles
to 200 yards of total offense the last time. They had three sacks
and two interceptions in their most dominating performance of the
season. But that was a long time ago. In the midst of a three-game
losing streak, the Cowboys have yielded 100 yards rushing in each
game. They have forced only three turnovers. And they have only
three sacks. The Cowboys don't need to create a whole lot of mayhem
to beat the lowly Eagles. But they will certainly need to make a
big play early to keep the Eagles from gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
   What are the Cowboys going to do at cornerback?
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on whether Deion Sanders can play. He missed most
of the past week nursing the most famous sprained big toe in the
Fort Worth-Dallas area. Regardless of whether Sanders can play or
not, Kevin Mathis is expected to start at left cornerback. Kevin
Smith, who has returned from a back injury, has normally been the
left cornerback, but the club moved him to right cornerback during
practice last week. Of course, that position is owned by Sanders.
If Sanders plays, he'll line up next to Mathis. If Sanders can't
play, it probably will be Smith at right cornerback and Mathis at
left.
</P>
<P>
   What should we expect from the running game?
</P>
<P>
   This is the one aspect of the Cowboys that has puzzled coach
Chan Gailey. The Cowboys have rushed for 188, 168, 224, 151, 162
and 173 yards this season. They've also had totals of 68, 58, 8 and
51. The latter three totals came in the past three games, so the
Cowboys are definitely on the downside of a trend. In the last
outing against the Eagles, Emmitt Smith had 23 carries for 101
yards. Even though the Cowboys are struggling, it would be an upset
if Smith did not get close to 100 again today. He has rushed for
more yards against the Eagles than any other NFL team.
EAGLES (3-11) How different is the Eagles' offense than the one
that didn't score in the first game against the Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   The club made Koy Detmer the starter at quarterback in Week 13
and the team is averaging 16.7 points per game. They had averaged
8.4 points per game in the first 11 weeks under Rodney Peete and
Bobby Hoying. Duce Staley replaced Charlie Garner as the starting
running back the week after the Cowboys game and has averaged 80.5
yards per game in his six starts since. Staley, in fact, has become
the club's most consistent offensive weapon. He leads the team in
rushing (901) and receptions (49). The only change the club has
made on the offensive line is replacing left guard Jermane Mayberry
with former Cowboy George Hegamin.
</P>
<P>
   Is Koy Detmer the answer at quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles are trying to find out. The former Mission High
School star has started the past three games, throwing five
touchdowns and two interceptions. He has been sacked twice. His
inspired play at Green Bay nearly led the Eagles to an upset
victory. In 11 games, Rodney Peete and Bobby Hoying combined for
two touchdown passes (both by Peete) and 13 interceptions. They
were sacked 52 times. But Eagles coach Ray Rhodes is cautioning
against getting too giddy about Detmer. ``Let's not get too
antsy,'' Rhodes said. ``Let's let him play the season out.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it for the Eagles?
</P>
<P>
   At 3-11, the Eagles have their worst record at this point in the
season since they were 2-11-1 in 1972. They have been shutout three
times, 38-0 against Seattle, 34-0 against Dallas and 20-0 against
the Giants. The losses to the Cowboys and Seahawks represented the
first time in NFL history a team suffered two home shutout losses
of at least 30 points or more. The Eagles have scored more than 20
points only once, in a 24-21 loss against Kansas City. The last
time they went a full season without scoring 20 points at least
twice was in 1956.
ONES TO STOP COWBOYS DEFENSIVE TACKLE LEON LETT
</P>
<P>
   He's playing his first full season since 1994 and was selected
to his second Pro Bowl. He has plenty of notches on his belt this
season. In the last game against the Eagles, he had four tackles
and five quarterback pressures. He has tied his career-high with
four sacks this season, seven tackles for loss, and 17 quarterback
pressures. EAGLES WIDE RECEIVER IRVING FRYAR
</P>
<P>
   Fryar is the NFL's seventh all-time leading receiver with 776
receptions, but has struggled this year. The 15-year veteran has
only 40 receptions for 459 yards. But he has scored a touchdown in
each of his past two games, and you can bet he'll want to test a
Cowboys secondary that may include Kevin Mathis and Charlie
Williams.
EDGE COWBOYS RUN OFFENSE 121.8 yards per game
</P>
<P>
   VS. EAGLES RUN DEFENSE 146.7 ypg
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Cowboys have averaged 39 yards rushing per game the
past three weeks. Yet Emmitt Smith leads an attack that has put up
more than 150 yards rushing six times. The Eagles' past three
opponents have rushed for an average of 154.7 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOYS RUN DEFENSE 101.0 ypg
</P>
<P>
   VS. EAGLES RUN OFFENSE 109.1 ypg
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Even
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Cowboys have allowed their past three opponents to
rush for at least 100 yards. Their past two opponents held the ball
in excess of 34 minutes. Philadelphia running back Duce Staley had
a career-high 141 yards rushing last week.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOYS PASS OFFENSE 222.8 ypg
</P>
<P>
   VS. EAGLES PASS DEFENSE 178.2 ypg
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Eagles
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Michael Irvin has only one 100-yard receiving day since
Oct. 18. Troy Aikman has been held under 200 yards passing in each
of the past two games. The Eagles have allowed only one passing
touchdown the past two weeks. Defensive end Hugh Douglas is fifth
in the NFC with 12.5 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOYS PASS DEFENSE 221.6 ypg
</P>
<P>
   VS. EAGLES PASS OFFENSE 145.8 ypg
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Cowboys could get Deion Sanders back today. Even if
they don't, the Cowboys cornerbacks played well against the Chiefs
last week (five pass breakups). The Eagles have averaged only 153.5
yards per game since they last played Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Comment: New kick returner Tyrone Hughes had a 35-yard punt
return and a 35-yard kickoff return last week. The Eagles rank near
the middle of the NFC in kickoff return and kickoff coverage.
</P>
<P>
   COACHING
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Chan Gailey has been calm in the first three-game
losing streak of his 14-game pro coaching career. He has been
careful not to point fingers or let his players do the same. The
Eagles' Ray Rhodes is probably in his last season with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS Mike Fisher NFL beat writer
</P>
<P>
   Key Cowboys including Troy Aikman and Daryl Johnston are taking
the lead this week, strongly insisting that no matter what
outsiders think this year's winter freeze on victories is
completely unrelated to last year's winter freeze on victories. OK.
Here's the chance to prove it. A month ago, the Cowboys were 8-3,
with Minnesota next up. Figure a loss there, and then a four-game
season's end featuring have-nots New Orleans, Kansas City,
Philadelphia and Washington. Give the Saints a little credit? Fine.
Give the Chiefs a little credit? Fine. Give the lowly Eagles a
chance to win this game? Better not. Cowboys 24, Eagles 13
Kevin Lyons Cowboys beat writer
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely no way the Cowboys can lose today. Of
course, I felt the same way about the Cowboys in New Orleans and
Kansas City. But this is different, isn't it? The Cowboys are at
home. They are playing another woeful NFC East opponent. And for
the first time in the Chan Gailey era, they are desperate for a
victory. Yeah, they've got injuries. But sometimes, you have to win
because you are the better team. Period. The Cowboys, by far, have
the better team. Cowboys 23, Eagles 3
Clarence E. Hill Jr. Cowboys beat writer
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, the Cowboys beat the Eagles 34-0 the last time. The
Eagles are playing better and the Cowboys are playing worse. Deion
Sanders probably won't play. But the Eagles have nothing to play
for and their coach, Ray Rhodes, is telling everyone that he
deserves to be fired. The NFC East title is on the line for the
Cowboys, who are also motivated to play better because they want to
make a playoff run. Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys 24, Eagles 14
COLUMNISTS' PICKS: Randy Galloway: Cowboys 20, Eagles 14
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
