<HEADLINE>
BLUES LOSS IS COYOTES' LOSS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - St. Louis defenseman Chris Pronger's two-handed slash
to the head of Coyotes assistant captain Jeremy Roenick in the
Blues' 3-2 win Thursday night has proven costly.
</P>
<P>
   But so did a calculated gamble by the Coyotes, as they prepared
to host the New York Islanders today at 1 p.m. in America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who will try to shake the effects of their first
two-game losing streak of the season against the Islanders, tried
to slip young defenseman Bryan Helmer through waivers for the
purpose of reassigning him to Las Vegas of the IHL, but St. Louis
claimed him on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell, NHL vice president and director of hockey
operations, leveled a four-game suspension on Pronger Saturday for
his slash, which fortunately didn't cause serious damage to
Roenick. In addition to a $1,000 fine, Pronger will lose $66,145.83
in salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Pronger swung his stick in an extremely reckless and
dangerous manner, and his stick made contact with the Phoenix
player's head,'' said Campbell, explaining the penalty.
``Deliberate blows to the head will not be tolerated under any
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the 6-foot-6, 220-pound Pronger decided to use the 6-0,
200-pound Roenick's head for a T-ball remains a question. Roenick
claims he did nothing to incite Pronger, but speculated Pronger
might have grown frustrated by physical play by the Coyotes.
Pronger has refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger's loss coupled with that of defenseman Chris McAlphine
to injury against the Coyotes, left the Blues thin at the blueline
when Helmer became available.
</P>
<P>
   Helmer, scoreless in 11 games with Phoenix, was thought a
promising prospect when Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith signed
him as a free agent from the defense-rich New Jersey Devils in
July.
</P>
<P>
   His brief career here was a rollercoaster. He was twice
reassigned to Las Vegas only to be recalled before he ever reached
airport, and once was sent to Las Vegas and recalled the following
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we acquired Bryan we knew he would be up and down all
year,'' Smith said. ``To guarantee we would have him we would have
had to keep him with us all year, which we weren't willing to do.
St. Louis claimed him and that's the way it goes. We didn't want to
lose him. It's a chance you have to take sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our top five defensemen (Teppo Numminen, Jyrki Lumme,
Keith Carney, Oleg Tverdovsky and Gerald Diduck), and with Deron
Quint and Jason Doig, we feel we have to young players who can give
us a sixth defenseman and an excellent defensive corps.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are merely dropping by home today for a game against
a suddenly redhot opponent and a change of clothes. After today's
game, they play their next three on the road at Detroit, Chicago
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They have played eight of their last nine games on the road,
going 3-3-2 away from America West, and were noticeably leg weary
when their Eastern Canadian road swing ended in St. Louis Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's was a tiring and hard road trip,'' Smith said. ``We
didn't play as well as we have at other parts of the season. We
missed our jump in the first periods, even in the win at Ottawa. We
were fortunate Nikolai Khabibulin played an excellent game there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to get it back again. It might be we're
paying a price right now for the earlier part of our season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes two straight losses have come with Captain Keith
Tkachuk sidelined with a groin straight. Tkachuk was on the ice for
Saturday's light workout at the Ice Den and thinks he will play
against the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   But to cover his bases, Smith recalled left wing Louie DeBrusk
Saturday from Las Vegas, where he registered three goals and nine
points and a staggering 153 penalty minutes in 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders are trying to complete their four-game road trip
unbeaten. They whipped San Jose 1-0 and the Los Angeles King 5-4 in
overtime, then battled to an overtime tie with Anaheim Friday
night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
