<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENTS MIGHT HAVE TO LOWER SIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sentiment is growing around the NHL that player salaries
actually may stay at a semi-reasonable plateau when this summer's
batch of unrestricted free agents searches for gold.
</P>
<P>
   Too many clubs are reporting huge financial losses and simply
won't be able to keep raising the salary bar every year. Only the
handful of market-rich teams, led by the free-spending New York
Rangers, will continue to make gluttons of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That can't be good news for free agents such as Calgary's
 &UR; Theo Fleury, the Rangers'  &UR; Brian Leetch, Colorado's  &UR; Patrick Roy
and Montreal's  &UR; Vincent Damphousse. Or for the next talent tier of
players such as the Coyotes' hard-working  &UR; Bob Corkum, a Selke
Trophy candidate this season as the league's top defensive forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the offers are going to be less and fewer this
summer,'' Carolina Hurricanes General Manager  &UR; Jim Rutherford said,
``because we're all at the point where our payrolls are out of
whack.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at what has happened in Anaheim, where the
Disney-owned Mighty Ducks are expected to lose money _ probably
about $8 million _ for the first time in their history. Their
payroll has increased to $31.5 million from $25.5 million a year
ago and $16.5 million in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an industry, our revenues are not catching up the inflation
of salaries to the point where most teams, the great majority of
teams, are losing significant amounts of money, and we are now one
of them,'' said  &UR; Pierre Gauthier, Ducks president and general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Glen Sather, general manager for the financially burdened
Edmonton Oilers, said last week's trade sending  &UR; Chris Gratton, who
received a $9 million signing bonus, from Philadelphia back to
Tampa Bay is an example of what may come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hope this changes things,'' Sather said. ``These guys
blow their brains out on a long shot and every time there's a
signing like this, everyone in the league suffers.'' &QL; 
The Ironmen &QL; 
Coyotes defenseman  &UR; Teppo Numminen said he was sad to see
 &UR; Mark &UR; Recchi's iron man streak end this past weekend. After playing
in 570 consecutive games, which had been the longest active streak
in the NHL, Recchi sat out his second straight game Monday against
the Coyotes because of lingering effects from pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game. The healthier you can be and the less
games you miss, the better you are,'' said Numminen, who will play
in his 242nd straight regular season game today against the
visiting New York Islanders. ``It's too bad his streak had to end,
but sooner or later, it happens to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Numminen, who hasn't missed a game since the 1995-96 season,
doesn't think anyone will catch Recchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. To go through that long with nothing
happening?'' Numminen said. ``It's really great. I don't think
that's going to happen again for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's  &UR; Rod Brind-Amour is the new leader with 433
consecutive games.  &UR; Doug Jarvis, now an assistant coach with the
Dallas Stars, holds the NHL record with 964 straight games. Former
Roadrunners Coach  &UR; Garry Unger, the former record holder, is second
with 914.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's mistake &QL; 
Imagine  &UR; Rob Blake's disappointment after drawing a three-game
suspension for slashing Vancouver's  &UR; Harry York last week in his
first game back from missing a month because of a broken foot.
Blake called the suspension ``a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to whack his stick and at the last second, he reached
out for the puck,'' Blake said. ``I don't think it was that bad,
but he went down like he was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   York suffered a minor bruise, but that's all. Blake, meanwhile,
was forced to forfeit $82,304 of his $5.3 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to say it was a baseball swing,'' Kings Coach
 &UR; Larry Robinson said. ``If that's a baseball swing, he must be
hitting singles.'' &QL; 
Goalie for hire &QL; 
The Calgary Flames have been battling a war of attrition with their
netminders. Veteran  &UR; Ken Wregget has been out for two months
because of back spasms. Last weekend, rookie No. 1  &UR; Tyler Moss went
down because of a groin injury. Their top goalie in the minors,
 &UR; Igor Karpenko, also is hurt.
</P>
<P>
   That left them with youngster  &UR; Jean-Sebastien Giguere, a rookie
who routinely gets dehydrated and vomits before and sometimes
``during'' games. Such was the case last Saturday in Florida, when
Giguere got sick during the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Brian Sutter, who recalled another rookie, 20-year-old
 &UR; Tyron Garner, all the way from Oshawa in the juniors as an
emergency backup, was seeing red. He purposely kept trainer  &UR; Terry
Kane from running out on the ice to check on Giguere, who was
doubled over in the crease. But he finally relented, albeit with a
message for Kane to deliver to Giguere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told TK, `First of all, leave him in there. And second of
all, tell him to suck it up and do something about it,' '' Sutter
said. ``The greatest goalie that ever played the game,  &UR; Glenn Hall,
used to get sick before every game, every night, every period.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
