<HEADLINE>
BASS TOURNAMENTS CAN BE HARMFUL TO FISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Bass fishing tournaments create their own problems
during the winter and summer months.
</P>
<P>
   The tournaments are no-kill operations; the goal is to release
the bass back into the lakes. Catch bass, weigh them in and return
them to the lake. It's an admirable goal, but it often doesn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter, bass go deep. They often are caught in 60 feet of
water. When they are brought up, their float or swim bladders _ the
things that help them stabilize and operate in the water _ fill
with air from the rapid rise from the depths. They float on the
surface, belly up, and often die. It's something like nitrogen
narcosis, or the bends, which affects humans when they are brought
to the surface from great depths without decompression.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, when night tournaments are prevalent, the bass
sometimes die from lack of oxygen in faulty live wells. The live
wells in bass boats pump air into the water but sometimes don't
inject enough to keep fish alive. Stress kills the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Fish brought from great depths are a problem addressed by
tournament sponsors. Hypodermic needles are used to penetrate their
swim bladders and release the air, supposedly allowing the bass to
adjust to the rapid rise in depth.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Jim Warnecke, fish program manager for the
Arizona Game and Fish Department in the Mesa region, the swollen
bladders are only one of many problems bass suffer when brought up
quickly from deep water.
</P>
<P>
   Warnecke cited an article in ``In-Fisherman'' magazine that
quoted a study by two researchers from California Polytechnic State
University who tested bass in a simulator in depths from 30, 60 and
90 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   The fish suffered from expanded bladders, external hemorrhaging
and ruptured stomach tissues at all three simulated depths. Fish
tested at 60 to 90 feet also bled internally, and some suffered
from popped-out eyes and everted stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   When raised from 30 feet, about 25 percent of the bass died
after a delay of one or two days. When raised from 60 to 90 feet,
more than 40 percent died within a few hours. Hemorrhaging and gas
bubbles in the blood apparently were more dangerous than bladder
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Bass under 10 inches were more likely to die than larger fish.
</P>
<P>
   Warnecke said the study proved that bass caught at depths
greater than 60 feet shouldn't be released because of a poor
survival rate. Internal damage kills the fish.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the fish caught in 35-40 feet can be released
successfully, although a hypodermic needle might not be the best
method of releasing air from the bladder; it could puncture organs
and vessels. That method also does nothing to reduce the gas
bubbles in the blood that can cause blockages in the heart and
other organs.
</P>
<P>
   Warnecke wrote that the preferred alternative is to recompress
bass by lowering them to at least 33 feet without puncturing the
swim bladder. This reduces the size of the bladder by half and
squeezes the air bubbles from the blood.
</P>
<P>
   The method is to use an inverted metal or weighted plastic milk
crate at the end of a 40-foot rope. Take the fish to 40 feet or
more of water and place three to five floating bass in the crate.
Lower the fish to at least 33 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Don't puncture the bladder. It's not necessary. The fish will
right themselves at that depth and swim out of the crate. The bass
will have a greater chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't science wonderful? &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
