<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS OPEN DOOR FOR CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Thanks to an assist from the Washington Redskins, the
Cardinals are a third of the way home to ending the NFL's longest
playoff drought.
</P>
<P>
   They will clinch their first playoff berth since moving to
Arizona and first since 1982 if they beat the New Orleans Saints
today at Sun Devil Stadium and if the Kansas City Chiefs beat or
tie the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins' 20-16, come-from-behind victory over Tampa Bay
gives the Cardinals (7-7) a half-game lead over the Buccaneers
(7-8) for the NFC's third and last wild card playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great the Skins won, but we have to handle our
business,'' offensive tackle James Dexter said. ``We've just got to
go out and win. We beat the Saints and take care of the Chargers
next week, that's it. We don't have to worry about anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's victory left the Giants (6-8) still in the playoff
hunt. They would win any tiebreaker over the Cardinals because they
swept the season series.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints (6-8) also remain in the race. They would earn a
berth by winning their final two games. They would have victories
over the Cardinals and Buccaneers and a better NFC record than the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's playoff hopes are slim as the result of the loss.
The Buccaneers need to win, to have the Cardinals lose twice or to
have the winner of today's Cards-Saints game to lose its regular
season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's victory Saturday clinched NFC playoff berths for
Dallas (8-6) and Green Bay (9-5). The Cowboys need to win one of
their final two games to clinch the NFC East title. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
