<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8723 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-MENTALITY-A     12-19 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MENTALITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF MENTALITY: NEW ADDITIONS GIVE CARDS NEW ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Larry Centers has seen all manner of mug, pug and
thug parade through the locker room. Many, he believed, had no
business wearing Cardinals red.
</P>
<P>
   Centers, a fullback in his ninth Cardinals season who became the
team's all-time pass receiving leader last week, was not crushed to
see them go. He is among the few who has stayed, or been allowed to
stay, through a succession of deeply depressing seasons to the
brink of hope.
</P>
<P>
   A Cardinals win today over New Orleans and a New York Giants
loss or tie will put the Cardinals into the playoffs for the first
time in a non-strike season since 1975, ending the longest drought
in the NFL. If the Cardinals win today but don't clinch a playoff
spot, the Cardinals will secure a berth with another victory at
home next Sunday over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   That's new ground for this young team. Forty-five players on the
53-man roster have been acquired during the past three years.
Twenty-eight were not yet in the league when Vince Tobin became
coach in 1996. And 12 players have some sort of playoff experience.
Those players know what it takes to have a playoff mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Centers is at once grateful that the newcomers have put the
playoffs finally within reach and bitter that it took so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can definitely blame them,'' Centers said of some Cardinals
players past. ``We're paid to give 100 percent. When you see
someone fail to give it, you have to question if they're
professional. It's a cancer on your team. It eats at the fiber of
your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody on the roster has appeared in a postseason game as a
Cardinal, and only 12 have been there with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think experience is overrated,'' said
receiver/return specialist Eric Metcalf, who as a rookie in 1989
returned a kickoff for a touchdown that lifted the Cleveland Browns
to a playoff win over Buffalo. ``Even if you've been there, you
still have to make plays, and we have lots of guys on this team who
can do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation reminds me of my rookie year because we had to
win out to go to the playoffs. We just got prepared to play and we
played. That's all we have to do here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has grown up quickly, Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mental approach is more mature,'' Tobin said. ``Each
time that you are in a situation where you have to win, you mature
a bit. Really, it was the same stakes last week at Philadelphia.
This game is every bit as important to New Orleans as is to us.
We'll both be playing extremely hard to get that last playoff
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints (6-8) are out of the race if they lose. If they win,
their record will be the same as the Cardinals (7-7) going into the
final week. The Saints would hold the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been here eight years,'' said Aeneas Williams, the
five-time Cardinals Pro Bowl cornerback, ``I don't know if I could
express what it means to me in terms of our opportunity this
weekend. It's overwhelming. We realize we have the opportunity to
do something this team hasn't done since I've been here. Our motto
this week can't be `We want it,' but `We have to have it.' This is
an opportunity we can't afford to let slip by.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if New Orleans is big-game proven, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a young football team, and probably by design,'' Saints
Coach Mike Ditka said. ``I'd rather be young and rambunctious and
take my chances. I have coaches even on my staff who say we need
more experience. You get experience by playing. You can't say
you'll draft a kid and he will be ready in two years. He won't be
ready in two years unless he plays. He may make mistakes, but
talent and enthusiasm can overcome experience.''
</P>
<P>
   That thought was echoed by Terry Bradshaw, a Fox TV analyst who
quarterbacked Pittsburgh to four Super Bowl titles in the 1970s.
Bradshaw suffered through a 5-9 record as a rookie in 1970 and 6-8
his second season. In his third, Bradshaw and a strong defensive
front took the Steelers to the AFC championship game with an 11-3
mark. Two years later, the Steelers won the first of their four
Super Bowls during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were young, but so what?'' Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw said the young guys became believers when they opened
1972 with a win over Oakland, followed at midseason by another big
one over Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be an established team to beat one,''
Bradshaw said. ``But once you do, then you get everybody believing,
and that's the point the Cardinals need to get to next.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals aren't to be confused with the Steelers at the
dawning of their championship era. The only similarity so far is
that the group has struggled through its initial two seasons
together. None of the Cardinals' seven victories this year is over
a winning team. And their foe today isn't to be confused with the
Raiders or Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   But in scale, the stakes for the Cardinals approximate those
described by Bradshaw that put the Steelers over the hump. Like the
Steelers, the Cardinals are built around a promising young
quarterback, Jake Plummer, and a potentially dominating defensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everybody is focusing and getting ready to move
on to the next level,'' said Lomas Brown, the seven-time Pro Bowl
left tackle who went to the playoffs while with Detroit. ``I think
they're handling it well considering it's a group of guys that has
never been in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was going through it the first time, the most
eye-opening thing to me was the tempo and the intensity that guys
play with. It's now at the point where they look at it as it's
either you or me. That's the attitude they take out there with
them. You see a lot more cutting.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals backup middle linebacker Mark Maddox, who was on three
Super Bowl teams with Buffalo, said he is encouraged by the change
he has seen in the locker room since training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters is not the age of the players, but that we have
played 14 games together and we have grown,'' Maddox said. ``When
you look at where we are compared with where we started, we have
come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Devlin, who played with Maddox in the Super Bowl at
Buffalo, said this team has one vital characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hungry,'' Devlin said. ``If you've never been there and
you don't have a lot of guys who've been there, the one thing
you've got to be is hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Devlin said his teammates should relish this opportunity. He
recalls his in the Super Bowl as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember trying to take in every little thing because I
didn't know if it was ever going to happen again _ knowing
everybody's watching, the excitement, being one of the first guys
out there on the kickoff return team,'' Devlin said. ``I was on the
wedge. The ball was in the air, and I didn't even hear a thing it
was so loud. Just little things like that, if you never experience
it, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we can get there, then it's going to have a snowball
effect. To me, that's why this game so pivotal. This is like a
playoff game. That game we played against Dallas was sort of like
that. To me, this should be 10 times better than that. This is the
kind of game that turns around franchises. This is the kind of game
that gets teams on that 10-year streak, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   While some teammates know the feeling, Centers and other
Cardinals long-timers can only imagine it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words really can't explain how good the feeling would be once
the playoff berth becomes a reality,'' Centers said. ``We don't
have enough time to tell you what it would mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ups and downs, the ins and outs around here, the
disappointing days. Weeks. Months. Years. After all those, going to
the playoffs would be the most special thing in my career. In
reality, the final three weeks of our season have been playoff
time, and we have gained the mentality that we need to carry us
over the hump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
