<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH20-COX     12-19 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton impeached; Senate to decide final fate
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives, riven with partisan
anger and stunned by the sudden resignation Speaker-elect Bob
Livingston (R-La.), impeached President Clinton Saturday for ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton became only the second president in the nation's history
to be impeached, setting the stage for a Senate trial that the
country has not seen in 130 years. Clinton's fate now rests with
the 100 members of the Senate who can convict the president and
expel him from office with a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no signs of giving up, Clinton stood shoulder to
shoulder with Democrats at the White House following the vote and
vowed to continue his work as commander in chief until ``the last
hour of the last day'' of his presidency. He later announced the
the bombing in Iraq was over.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Democratic leaders continued to press for a
punishment short of impeachment, such as censure. But Senate
majority leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) signaled the Senate would take
the initial step of swearing Senators under oath to ``do impartial
justice according the Constitution,'' the first step of an
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing (of a trial) will depend greatly on the president
and lawyers,'' Lott said in a statement following the House's
historic vote. Lott pledged to attend to the ``people's business''
during the prelude to any impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's vote unfolded in an atmosphere drama, bitterness and
solemnity. Livingston shocked colleagues by announcing his
resignation only days after admitting to extramarital affairs, and
challenged Clinton to follow his example.
</P>
<P>
   Minority leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.) pleaded one last time for
a House vote on censuring the president and called for an end to
the ``politics of personal destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop destroying imperfect people at the alter of an
unattainable morality,'' Gephardt said. ``We are now rapidly
descending into a politics where life imitates farce, fratricide
dominates our public debate and America is held hostage to the
tactics of smear and fear.''
</P>
<P>
   But Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) warned members not to
confuse ``private acts of infidelity'' with public acts of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the chief executive trivializes the oath, justice is
wounded, you are wounded and our children are wounded,'' said Hyde,
moments before the House proceeded toward the vote. ``Follow your
conscience and you will have served your country.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans defeated a procedural motion that would have forced
vote on censure, prompting Democrats to stage a brief walk out,
before proceeding to a vote of the four articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Voting almost entirely on party lines, the Republican-controlled
House voted to impeach Clinton on two separate counts for lying to
a federal grand jury and obstructing justice in independent counsel
Ken Starr's investigation of Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The House defeated two other articles charging that Clinton
perjured himself in Paula Jones's sexual harassment lawsuit and
lied to Congress in his written response to questions about his
testimony. Article two was defeated 229 to 205. Article four was
defeated 285 to 148.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the House completed voting, Hyde and other
Republican leaders carried the two approved articles from the House
side of the Capitol to the secretary of the Senate, there to await
action by the Senate in early January.
</P>
<P>
   The articles were written on parchment and tucked inside two
blue binders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad day, but it shows our Democratic process
works,'' Hyde said just before the procession to the Senate began.
``And I think we are strong enough to handle the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost simultaneously, House Democrats traveled en masse up
Pennsylvania Avenue to attend a rally at the White House and stand
shoulder to shoulder with Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared outside the White House after the vote, looking
haggard but showing no signs that he will heed GOP calls to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the American people to know today that I am still
committed to working with people of good faith and good will of
both parties to do what's best for our country, to bring our nation
together, to lift our people up, to move us all forward together,''
Clinton said. ``It's what I've tried to do for six years. It's what
I intend to do for two more until the last hour of the last day of
my term.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the final votes were tallied, Democrats and
Republicans began arguing the outcome of a potential Senate trial.
Democrats argued that the defeat of the second impeachment article,
alleging Clinton lied in his Jones deposition, weakened the overall
case against the president because the evidence that Clinton lied
was strongest in the second article.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of article two puts a big hole in the case,'' said
Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.), a member of the Judiciary Committee.
``That is very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still, however, must contend with seven allegations that
he obstructed justice by influencing the testimony of his personal
secretary and trying to silence Lewinsky with help in securing her
a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is overwhelming and substantial,'' said Rep.
Steve Buyer (R-Ind.), who along with Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) will
serve as House prosecutors in the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, Buyer and the 11 ``floor managers,'' or prosecutors, said
they will push the Senate hard to conduct a trial and not drop the
impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats, meanwhile, signaled that they will pursue the
censure alternative. Republicans outnumber Democrats in the Senate
55 to 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be several points early in the Senate proceedings
when the Senate could choose to substitute a strong censure
resolution,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.). ``If that does not
happen, we are headed for a difficult and lengthy trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority leader Tom Daschle (D-S.D.) said Clinton's
actions merited ``serious punishment,'' but said the president
should not resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot allow any president, Republican or Democrat, to be
forced from office by a party line vote in the House,'' Daschle
said. ``In America, the president serves at the will of the people,
not the pleasure of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Three House members _ Reps. Charles Schumer (D-N.Y.), Jim
Bunning (R-Ky.) and Mike Crapo (R-Idaho) _ will have the
opportunity to also vote in the Senate, having been elected
senators of their respective states. Schumer voted against all four
articles, while Bunning and Crapo both voted for.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only five Democrats _ all but four from the South _
broke ranks to vote for the two articles of impeachment ultimately
adopted by the House. The Democrats were Reps. Ralph Hall and
Charlie Stenholm of Texas, Gene Taylor of Mississippi, Virgil Goode
of Virginia and Paul McHale of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   On the article dealing with grand jury perjury, which passed 228
to 206, only five Republicans voted against impeachment:
Christopher Shays of Connecticut, Peter King and Amo Houghton of
New York, Connie Morella of Maryland and Mark Souder of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   On the article dealing with obstruction of justice, 12
Republicans voted no. That article passed with only a five-vote
majority, 221-212, meaning that it would have failed if no
Democrats had defected.
</P>
<P>
   President Andrew Johnson was the first and only other president
ever impeached in 1868. He was acquitted in the Senate when
Senators failed by one vote to convict him with the necessary
two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   President Nixon resigned before articles of impeachment voted by
the House Judiciary Committee reached the full House for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Although they fought bitterly over the fairness of the House
proceeding and the ultimate votes, Democrats and Republicans
appeared to share many of the same feelings of sadness and
solemnity that accompanied the historic vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no cheers when the 218 was hit,'' said Rep. Jim
Leach (R-Iowa), referring to the point at which the first
impeachment article officially carried. ``I don't think there is a
single member who didn't understand the solemnity of this event.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.), from Clinton's home state of
Arkansas, said he took ``a deep breath'' before he cast his first
vote to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not respectful of our Constitution,'' said Rep. Bill
Delahunt (D-Mass.), a judiciary committee member, after the vote.
``History will look with disdain on what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day,'' said Rep. Henry Waxman (D-Calif.) ``It's a
day of idiocy. I've never seen a deliberative body act in such a
bizarre way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
