<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-19 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SETS UP SENATE TRIAL WITH IMPEACHMENT OF CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled House of Representatives
impeached President Clinton on Saturday, setting the stage for a
trial in the Senate for only the second time since the nation's
founding.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of votes largely along party lines, the House
approved two articles of impeachment formally accusing Clinton of
lying to a grand jury and of obstructing justice in trying to
conceal an affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Two other articles, one accusing Clinton of perjury in a civil
lawsuit, the other alleging abuse of power, were rejected when
moderate Republicans sided with Democrats to vote against the
allegations, drawn up by some of the GOP's most conservative
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not label lawlessness, our children cannot recognize
it. And if we do not punish lawlessness, our children will not
believe it. How can we tell our children that honesty is the best
policy if we do not demand honesty as a policy,'' J.C. Watts,
R-Okla., told the House before the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Voting on the four articles _ each required a separate roll call
of House members _ began at 1:09 p.m. EST. In a little over an
hour, the voting on each of the articles had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who were rocked by leadership tumult Saturday,
immediately delivered the impeachment documents to the Senate,
whose members could end Clinton's presidency after a trial. To do
so, however, would require a two-thirds majority vote _ 67
senators.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton vowed to fight to remain in office
``until the last hour of the last day'' of his term, which ends in
Jan. 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by dozens of congressional Democrats who for weeks have
fought the Republican impeachment juggernaut, Clinton rejected
calls for his resignation and urged an easing of partisan tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must stop the politics of personal destruction,'' Clinton
said. ``We must get rid of the poisonous venom of excessive
partisanship, obsessive animosity and uncontrolled anger.''
</P>
<P>
   The president pledged to work with the Senate to find a
``reasonable, bipartisan and proportionate'' resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a deal is reached, the Senate would begin a trial with
the 55 Republican and 45 Democratic senators sitting as jurors, and
Chief Justice William Rehnquist presiding. It would be the first
impeachment trial of a president since Andrew Johnson in 1868.
Johnson's Senate trial lasted 74 days and ended with acquittal, by
one vote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the House Judiciary Committee recommended articles of
impeachment against President Nixon. He resigned before a vote in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has said that any
trial would be ``governed both by the Constitution and by our rules
and precedents.'' He cautioned senators to ``be judicious in any
discussions'' of the House action and impending trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, hundreds of people packed the visitors galleries to
witness the debate, which at times reached lofty tones and at
others bogged in parliamentary minutiae. Outside, thousands
gathered on the lawn east of the Capitol chanting, ``Witch hunt!
Witch hunt!'' and waving signs saying, ``Shame on Congress'' and
``Impeach the Liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, as the impeachment debate neared full throat, members
were stunned into silence, some shedding tears, when Rep. Bob
Livingston, R-La., announced that he would not accept the
speakership when the new Congress convenes in 2 1/2 weeks and would
quit the House in six months. He was selected in November after
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., announced he was leaving the House.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Livingston, who only two days earlier confirmed
his own marital infidelities to the chagrin of some conservatives
in his party, was known in advance by only by a handful of close
allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only challenge you in such fashion if I am willing to
heed my own words,'' Livingston said in seeking the president's
impeachment. ``So I must set an example that I hope President
Clinton will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans were visibly distraught.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, fought tears. Rep. John Mica,
R-Fla., wiped his eyes, then walked off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a driving force behind the impeachment process as
Livingston took a back seat, rose a few minutes later and said
Livingston's decision proved the House was on the right course in
seeking to oust Clinton. Livingston ``understood what this debate
was all about _ honor and decency and integrity and the truth,''
DeLay said. ``It was also a debate about relativism versus absolute
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats compared Livingston's situation to Clinton's troubles
and urged Republicans to bring the national nightmare to an end by
dropping impeachment and instead supporting a resolution rebuking
the president's behavior. The request was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the case to impeach Clinton, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
cautioned colleagues to avoid confusion between what he called
``private acts of infidelity and public acts'' involving a
government official who lies when under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when you have a serial violator of the oath who is the
chief law enforcement officer of the country, who appoints the
judges and the Supreme Court, the attorney general, we have a
problem,'' said Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But House Democratic leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri said:
``We are on the brink of the abyss. The only way we stop the
insanity is through the force of our own will, ... for all of us to
finally say, `Enough.'
</P>
<P>
   ``May God have mercy on this Congress and may Congress have the
wisdom and the goodness to save itself today.''
</P>
<P>
   Likening impeachment to a peaceful coup d'etat, some Democrats
spiced their defense of Clinton with warnings of political
recriminations against Republicans from a scandal-weary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Spanish phrase for a coup, ``golpe de estado,'' Rep.
Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., told of growing up in the public housing
projects of the South Bronx. ``I know a bunch of bullies when I see
them,'' Serrano said, turning to the Republican side of the
chamber. ``The bullies get theirs, and you're going to get yours,
too. The people are going to rise up, from California to New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   When voting began, Democratic House members staged a brief
walkout to protest the refusal of Republicans to allow a vote on
censure as an alternative to impeachment. All but one of the
Democratic members left the chamber, and about half left the
building, then returned less than 10 minutes later to vote against
each article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're offended by this process,'' said Gephardt, who led his
Democratic colleagues down the Capitol steps. ``They have
disregarded the clear will of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The first article of impeachment, which accused Clinton of lying
to a federal grand jury investigating his affair and efforts to
hide it, was approved 228-206, with five Democrats voting for
impeachment and five Republicans voting against.
</P>
<P>
   The article accusing Clinton of obstruction of justice passed
221-212. This article alleges that he tried to cover up his affair
with Lewinsky by inducing her and others to lie. Twelve
Republicans, less persuaded by the evidence on this charge, voted
no but five Democrats again voted yes.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Saturday ``a bizarre day in the House,'' Rep. Ken
Bentsen, D-Texas, said when Americans look at what happened ``they
will think we're nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen called the partisan rancor over Clinton's impeachment
``a culmination of the viciousness of American politics'' that
began more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before adjourning, the House selected 13 Republican members to
act as managers, or prosecutors, when Clinton's case goes to trial
in the Senate. The managers are led by Hyde and include other
members of the Judiciary Committee: Reps. Bob Barr of Georgia; Ed
Bryant, Tennessee; Steve Buyer, Indiana; Charles Canady, Florida;
Chris Cannon, Utah; Steve Chabot, Ohio; George Gekas, Pennsylvania;
Lindsey Graham, South Carolina; Asa Hutchinson, Arkansas; Bill
McCollum, Florida; James Rogan, California; and James
Sensenbrenner, Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
