<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton impeachment no vindication: For Barr, it's about
`upholding the law'
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just a year ago, Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) was the lone
``impeacher'' in Congress, urging the removal of President Clinton
months before the nation even heard the name Monica.
</P>
<P>
   With the House's decision Saturday to impeach the president for
perjury and concealing his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky, Barr is now suddenly part of a chorus of
impeachers. And it looks like the conservative Georgian's role will
only expand in the 106th Congress with his appointment to be one of
13 floor managers running the Senate trial of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's call for impeachment last year may have been about
alleged fund-raising abuses, not perjury, but in the world
according to Bob Barr, that is a mere detail.
</P>
<P>
   To Barr, the end game is the same: The president has been
publicly shamed and humiliated in becoming the second president in
the history of the nation to be impeached by the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very sad day,'' said Barr, during the vote to impeach
the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Barr's detractors say he has perhaps never looked so
energized as he did striding across the U.S. Capitol with Judiciary
Commitee Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) to deliver two articles of
impeachment against Clinton to the office of the Secretary of the
Senate for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton faces an uncertain future, Barr's political position
appears to be rising. After just two terms in Congress, Barr has
become a fixture on the national stage as one of the more outspoken
members of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   During the panel's four-month impeachment inquiry, Barr was a
regular on the likes of CNN, trotting out to tell audience after
audience why the president should be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we accept that this inquiry is merely about sex and
politics, we have already failed in our constitutional
responsibility,'' said Barr, during one of his numerous floor
statements on impeaching the president. ``This is about the rule of
law. It is about accountability. It is about American citizens
being free from fear that a high government official can tap them
on the shoulder, escort them into a room, force them to succumb to
the official's wishes and then obstruct that citizen's right to
seek justice in our courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But how much impact that recognition will have on Barr's career
long term remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Staff aides on both sides of the aisle note that Barr has toned
down his arguments, presenting cogent, albeit fiercely partisan,
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientists deliver a more mixed reaction to Barr's
polemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the leading spokesperson for the hardest of the hard
right,'' said Norm Ornstein, a scholar at the American Enterprise
Institute in Washington. While Barr's push for impeachment has won
him national recognition, Ornstein questions what it means from a
public policy perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that there are lots of people saying he has been
vindicated as he moves from the wilderness to national prominence,
but he won't have an impact on policy,'' Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   William Connelly, professor at Washington &AMP; Lee University in
Virginia has documented the GOP takeover of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, Barr overplayed his hand on the impeachment
committee by calling for impeachment before the facts handed over
by independent counsel Kenneth Starr were proven. He would have
been wiser, Connolly said, to have taken a more centrist position
like that of fellow Republican Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr has been an attack dog for impeachment from the
beginning,'' Connelly said. ``Barr has always been on the fringe,
chomping on the bit to remove the president. I don't think his
performance on the committee was particularly enlightening.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Barr's gain will be among the fringe, not among the
two-thirds of America who do not want the president impeached,
Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr has had his 15 minutes of fame and I think we've seen
him for what he is: a man of moderate talents who caters to the
right wing conservatives,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's crusade for impeachment has certainly spawned the wrath
of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   One Atlanta-based group _ called the Committee to Dis-Barr
Georgia _ has created a Web site casting Barr as a ``white
racist,'' a violator of campaign fund-raising laws and philanderer
who has failed to pay child support.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site serves up the latest news about Barr's own personal
life. For example, on July 8, 1998 is an item about potential
marital discord. Another one posted on January 1, 1998 describes a
well-known event some years ago where Barr was seen licking whipped
cream off the chest of a woman during a Leukemia Society
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think he's a hypocrite,'' said Steve Anthony,
executive director of the Georgia Democratic Party, who has known
Barr since their days as competing party chairmen in Cobb County,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   In the same turn, Barr is often approached by citizens and
commended for his stern view of Clinton's actions. ``You are doing
God's work,'' one woman said to him at a recent Judiciary Committee
hearing on impeachment. ``We are so glad that you are here.''
</P>
<P>
   But a look at Barr's background does reveal a puzzle of
contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Barr talks about racial equality, but he spoke to
the Council of Conservative Citizens, a group that believes
interracial marriage results in a white genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Barr espouses a conservative family values agenda, but has been
married three times.
</P>
<P>
   As a Reagan-appointed U.S. Attorney, he upset the leaders of his
own party by going after former Rep. Pat Swindall on perjury
charges.
</P>
<P>
   It is a list that Barr openly shrugs at. His enemies in the
White House are out to get him with ``another one of their smear
campaigns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's attack on the White House has brought him few friends
among members of the opposite party.
</P>
<P>
   Where Barr is an ardent foe of Clinton, Democratic Rep. John
Lewis is an ardent supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's good or healthy for American leaders to be
appearing before separatist groups or racist groups,'' said Lewis,
a former Civil Rights leader whose district abuts Barr's. ``We
should send the strongest possible message that we believe in
bringing people together, not dividing them along racial lines.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Barr denied knowing about the group's views until
he arrived at their convention in Charleston, S.C. on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ludicrous to think that I would believe that,'' Barr said
of the group's views on racial matters.
</P>
<P>
   But the next day, the group's chief executive officer said Barr
was given copies of the group's magazine in advance. Most of the
magazine's issues espouse the racist attitudes of the group. Once
again, Barr denied knowing about the group's beliefs, handing
reporters copies of what he had received.
</P>
<P>
   The material mentioned conservative causes, such as opposing
school busing, but it did not overtly outline the group's belief
that whites are supreme over blacks. Barr said he did not find out
about the group's beliefs until he arrived to deliver his speech on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, who has spoken before the ultra-conservative John Birch
Society several times in the past, said he did not walk out because
if he walked out of every group that he disagreed with he'd never
be on a panel.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the impeachment vote, Barr delivered an address
invoking the words of former President John F. Kennedy during the
civil rights movement. In that speech Kennedy said the rule of law
should be used to enforce the integration of blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Barr use his uncle's words, Rep. Patrick Kennedy
(D-R.I.) shouted at Barr in front of a group of reporters. Later he
called Barr a ``racist and a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr responded by pointing out that as a former U.S. Attorney in
Atlanta he persecuted White supremacists. He called Kennedy a
``young punk.''
</P>
<P>
   For a member of Congress to appear before this group and say
they didn't know about it is impossible,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of people who admire Barr's politics,
respecting him for the way he has been firm on the conservative
agenda. He fought hard against the federal recognition of same sex
marriages and to limit the reach of the federal law enforcement
during the 104th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During the 105th Congress, Barr spent much of his time on the
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee investigating the
campaign fund-raising abuses of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted some to ask about what he has done on local
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But issues such as transportation and education are the
responsibility of local, not federal government, said Matthew
Glavin, president of the Southeast Legal Foundation, where Barr
once worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barr is a person with very deep convictions,'' Glavin said.
``He is someone willing to lead, rather than be followed. He was
out in front of this parade. Now, the president seems to be in deep
trouble and all the plans that the White House has have unraveled
and we can look at Bob Barr and say: You were right.''
</P>
<P>
   That is clearly not what William Waldrop thinks. As the chairman
of the Cobb County Democratic Party, Waldrop is in charge of
running candidates to run against Barr.
</P>
<P>
   In November's election, an insurance agent won 45 percent of the
vote against Barr with less than $13,000. Waldrop says it is
because Barr has ignored the issues of the 7th district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Barr is truly an embarrassment to our district,'' he said.
``All he does is attack the president over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking it all in stride is the way Barr works. He often sleeps
on the floor of his office, commuting home each weekend to see his
wife, Jeri.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office on the day that Clinton ordered air
strikes in Iraq, Barr seemed concerned that the Republican
leadership might postpone the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly know how to snatch defeat from the jaws of
victory,'' Barr said, almost depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Why does he dislike Clinton so? Where does that come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dislike him, I just believe in the Constitution and
everything it stands for,'' he said. And that means making sure
that the president is not ``above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been grueling fight, a long battle. Does he feel
vindicated?
</P>
<P>
   No, he says. ``It's all about upholding the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
