<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO PREGAME, CBS SHOULD PUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks into the season, a CBS Sports executive begged for
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give our NFL pregame show some time,'' he said, ``and you'll
see the results.''
</P>
<P>
   We've seen the results: It's not worth our time.
</P>
<P>
   Just when NFL teams are gearing up to be at their best, the NFL
pregame shows should be doing the same. Yet CBS' ``NFL Today'' is
by far the worst of the group, and it is not getting better. As a
connoisseur of the genre, I submit that _ considering its lack of
lively debate, humor, entertainment and information _ it's the
worst NFL pregame show ever.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese factor is huge on all three of the big Sunday morning
shows: ESPN's Chris Berman is a carnival barker, but he's made
cornball seem cool; the fraudulent canned-laugh exchanges between
Fox's Terry Bradshaw and James Brown are painful, but at least
they're sometimes funny.
</P>
<P>
   But the CBS team of Jim Nantz, Marcus Allen, Brent Jones and
George Seifert? The latter three are ex-jocks and rookie
broadcasters, and Jones is the only one with a track record of even
having a sense of humor. Seifert is somnolent. Nantz is nothing
more than a handsome game-show host. In person, Allen's demeanor is
classy, but here he's a blank slate.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm on the Fox and ESPN shows is too often fake. The
``So-and-so told me exclusively'' stuff is grating. And, given the
resources _ remember, the three networks each spent a fortune to be
part of the $2.2 billion bid for the NFL on TV _ shouldn't these
shows have the same humor, warmth, polish and professionalism of a
``Seinfeld'' or a ``Drew Carey Show''?
</P>
<P>
   CBS' offering lacks all of it. There is no enthusiasm, save for
Jones' ramblings. There is no real reporting, with the quirky
exception of the recent addition of ex-Browns exec Mike Lombardi,
who had been a behind-the-scenes info guy but now bumps Seifert
from the set. And there is a decidedly ``who cares'' atmosphere, as
if the boys running this morgue-like show know nobody's watching,
so what's the point?
</P>
<P>
   So CBS continues its fight for ratings with a tiny stick,
battling with ESPN's ideal combination of outspokenness in Sterling
Sharpe, analysis in Tom Jackson, reporting in Chris Mortensen and
showbiz in Chris Berman. (I can't figure out what Jim Kelly
offers.) And battling Fox' appealing-to-the-masses team of
Bradshaw, Brown, Howie Long (who has more true star quality than
all the rest of all these guys combined) and Cris Collinsworth. (I
can't figure out what he offers, either.)
</P>
<P>
   Some advice: You know what the best football show in TV is? It's
ESPN's ``Prime Time'', the postgame wrapup. It's trim, sleek,
funny, insightful. It's Berman and Jackson, by themselves, putting
the whole league _ every team, every score, every game _ in one
neat package.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: On the other network shows, I have a tough time
getting scoring updates; on ESPN's postgame coverage, I get
ad-libbed analysis of everything.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what I want in my pregame show: Everything.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MAN'S PRO BOWL BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to say which players should've been on the Pro Bowl
teams. It's tougher to say it and then follow up by selecting which
players should've been removed. Example: An ESPN analyst this week
said Miami inside linebacker Zach Thomas got robbed by not making
it, and in the next breath said how deserving San Diego's Junior
Seau and Baltimore's Ray Lewis are as they made it. Huh? Here's a
few of my ins and outs:
</P>
<P>
   Remove San Francisco receiver Jerry Rice. Replace him with San
Francisco receiver Terrell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   Remove Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski. Replace him with
Denver linebacker John Mobley.
</P>
<P>
   Remove New Orleans defensive end Joe Jackson. Replace him with
St. Louis defensive end Kevin Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Remove Dallas guard Nate Newton. Replace with, oh, all sorts of
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   And now, one man's Pro Bowl ballot: NFC
QB _ Steve Young, San Francisco RB _ Jamal Anderson, Atlanta; Barry
Sanders, Detroit WR _ Randy Moss, Minnesota; Antonio Freeman, Green
Bay TE _ Mark Chmura, Green Bay OT _ Larry Allen, Dallas; Todd
Steussie, Minnesota OG _ Randall McDaniel, Minnesota; Kevin Gogan,
San Francisco C _ Jeff Christy, Minnesota DE _ Reggie White, Green
Bay; Michael Strahan, Giants DT _ John Randle, Minnesota; Bryant
Young, San Francisco OLB _ Kevin Greene, Carolina; Derrick Brooks,
Tampa Bay ILB _ Jessie Tuggle, Atlanta CB _ Deion Sanders, Dallas;
Ray Buchanan, Atlanta S _ Leroy Butler, Green Bay; Robert Griffith,
Minnesota Specialists: P Brad Maynard, Giants; K Gary Anderson,
Minnesota; KR Glyn Milburn, Chicago. AFC QB _ Doug Flutie, Buffalo
RB _ Terrell Davis, Denver; Marshall Faulk, Indianapolis WR _ Jimmy
Smith, Jacksonville; Eric Moulds, Buffalo TE _ Shannon Sharpe,
Denver OT _ Tony Boselli, Jacksonville; Tony Jones, Denver OG _
Ruben Brown, Buffalo; Bruce Matthews, Tennessee C _ Dermontti
Dawson, Pittsburgh DE _ Bruce Smith, Buffalo; Michael Sinclair,
Seattle DT _ Darrell Russell, Oakland; Ted Washington, Buffalo OLB
_ Mo Lewis, Jets; John Mobley, Denver ILB _ Ray Lewis, Baltimore CB
_ Ty Law, New England; Aaron Glenn, Jets S _ Rodney Harrison, San
Diego; Lawyer Milloy, New England Specialists: P Craig Hentrich,
Tennessee; K Jason Elam, Denver; KR Jermaine Lewis, Baltimore.
NUMBERS GAME 21 _ Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre, the winner of
the past three MVP awards, leads the NFC with 21 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   268 _ Indianapolis running back Marshall Faulk needs 268 yards
to break the NFL single-season record for yards from scrimmage.
TRIVIAL PURSUIT Six quarterbacks, three from each conference, were
voted into the Pro Bowl: Denver's John Elway, the New York Jets'
Vinny Testaverde, Buffalo's Doug Flutie, San Francisco's Steve
Young, Minnesota's Randall Cunningham and Atlanta's Chris Chandler.
How many of them are with their original teams?
</P>
<P>
   None.
QUOTABLE Minnesota receivers coach Hubbard Alexander knows he
caught heat in Dallas for not developing receivers. Now does he
deserve some credit for Randy Moss? ``I've got six championship
rings in my lifetime, three from Super Bowls with the Cowboys,''
Alexander said. ``I don't have to apologize to anybody. \RIn
Dallas\S, they're making me the scapegoat.''
CHECK OUT ... The concept of ``refereeplay'' for the playoffs,
thankfully dead. But give commissioner Paul Tagliabue high grades
for P.R. spin here. The owners were squawking, the coaches were
squawking, the players were squawking, the media was squawking, the
fans were squawking. So with owners possibly ready to put the
needed 24 votes where their mouths were, here comes the Competition
Committee needing to first approve sending it to the owners. The
movement loses, 7-1. So no vote is legal _ and the commissioner can
at least say he tried.
NFC BUZZ Look deeper inside Carolina linebacker Kevin Greene's
sideline attack on assistant coach Kevin Steele last week, and
Greene's action seems even more the work of a selfish player. There
are indications the dispute had something to do with Carolina's
wishes that Greene _ Pro Bowl-bound because of his sack prowess _
focus more on stopping the run. ... By the way, does anybody else
find it strange that grabbing a coach earns Greene a one-game
suspension, the same suspension given to Panthers running back Fred
Lane after he made an obscene gesture in the end zone? Should
grabbing one's coach be handled the same as grabbing one's crotch?
... The Rams have four wins, three of them against AFC East
contenders New England, Buffalo and the Jets. ... The Redskins have
won five of seven as Norv Turner pushes to save his job. ... Coach
Mike Holmgren has a $4 million-a-year invitation to stay with the
Packers, but logic says he will wait until he hears other offers
before he even considers remaining. ... Carolina rumor: Coach Dom
Capers is out, Florida's Steve Spurrier is in. Good one, except
there are indications Spurrier hasn't even been contacted yet. ...
Look for the Bears to offer Todd Sauerbrun a new contract that will
allow him to join the Oilers' Craig Hentrich as the sport's only $1
million punters. ... No, the Packers say, they still aren't giving
up the ship. ``I'm not a statistical person,'' says Packers GM Ron
Wolf. ``But I believe the best defense in the NFC belongs to the
Green Bay Packers. That gives you a chance.'' ... Some Rams players
are using Isaac Bruce's hamstring injury _ so bad it caused him to
miss all but five games this year and now has him on the injured
reserve list _ as evidence that coach Dick Vermeil's practices are
too grueling. ... Philadelphia at Dallas: The Eagles have lost 16
consecutive road games. ... In four of 12 games, the Saints'
defense has outscored its offense. ... Detroit would like to give
as much work as possible to rookie QB Charlie Batch, but his back
problems may alter their plans. ... San Francisco QB Steve Young
needs four TD passes in the final two weeks for a career-high total
of 36. Young had 35 in 1994. ... Update on the Not Ready For The
Big-Time Players: Arizona has won consecutive games only once this
season, and has yet to beat a team with a winning record. ... Tampa
Bay at Washington: Two teams on three-game win streaks, both riding
hot Trents. Tampa Bay's Trent Dilfer has 13 TD passes in his past
seven games; Washington's Trent Green has thrown 14 TDs to only two
interceptions. ... Vikings receiver Randy Moss is the only rookie
voted to the Pro Bowl.
AFC BUZZ Kordell Stewart has created an awkward situation for
himself by his tears. You can cry when you're in pain. You can cry
after you lose. You can cry when you talk to the media about a
family tragedy. But _ it's an unwritten rule in the macho world of
professional football _ you cannot cry because you've been taken
out of a game. ``It happened, so be a man about it,'' Stewart said,
explaining his emotional outburst after being pulled during a 16-3
loss at Tampa Bay. ``I told \Rmy teammates\S) I'm still Kordell,
I'm still a fighter and not a loser.'' But ask Steelers insiders
about the aftershock of Stewart's sideline breakdown last Sunday.
They'll tell you that Stewart's future as a top-notch quarterback
is an uphill battle; his six interceptions in his past three starts
has fueled speculation that Mike Tomczak might get another chance
at QB with Stewart reprising his old ``Slash'' role as a
passer/runner/receiver. And they'll also tell you Stewart's days as
a leader are over. ... The Jets beat good teams. They're 7-1
against teams with winning records. ... Oakland at San Diego: The
No. 2- vs. No. 1-ranked defenses in the NFL, but the Raiders are
slumping, with one win in their past six games after a 6-2 start.
... Baltimore receiver Floyd Turner caught only 10 passes for 166
yards and one touchdown in his first 10 games. In his past three
games, Turner has 297 yards and four scores. ... Indianapolis at
Seattle: The Colts have allowed only 15 sacks; the Seahawks lead
the NFL with 49 sacks. ... Jets coach Bill Parcells is upset with
``Sports Illustrated'' because he thought he had a deal with them
to not put his picture on the cover. ``Yeah, I requested purposely
not to be on that cover,'' said Parcells of the edition released
before the Jets-Miami matchup. ``I said I really didn't want to do
the article if it was going to be on the cover. As recently as last
week I took a photo for them with a guarantee that it would not be
on the cover.'' A ``Sports Illustrated'' spokesman said it would
never enter into such an agreement. Conclusion: Control freak
Parcells overstepped his bounds. ... Odd situation for the
Chargers, who must motivate themselves while playing under a
lame-duck head coach in June Jones, who has taken a job at the
University of Hawaii. ... Seattle's 12 touchdowns by return
(fumbles, interceptions and special teams) is an NFL record. ...
Buffalo is poised to become only the fourth team in NFL history to
make the playoffs after starting 0-3. ... In addition to Detroit's
Scott Mitchell, mark down Kansas City's Elvis Grbac as a guy who
might end up as Cleveland's starting QB in 1999. Grbac, however,
might get playing time in the final two weeks although Rich Gannon
has led Kansas City to 30 points or more in three consecutive
games.
THE PLAYOFF PICTURE The Jacksonville Jaguars have a chance to
continue their march toward ``model franchise'' status tonight, as
they travel to Minnesota (13-1). The Jaguars are 10-4 and in charge
of the AFC Central. The title is theirs with a win or a tie in
Minnesota and a Tennessee loss or a tie (the Oilers are at Green
Bay). While Jacksonville's expansion partner, Carolina, has
experienced the highs and lows of the NFL (an NFC title game
appearance two years ago and 2-12 this season), Jacksonville
figures to be the most formidable AFC playoff obstacle facing
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Other key games include:
</P>
<P>
   Jets (10-4) at Buffalo (9-5): A New York victory gives the Jets
their first division title since 1969. New York won the earlier
meeting, 34-12, in Week 10.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (11-3) at New England (8-6): The Patriots will
play without QB Drew Bledsoe, but have a chance to clinch a playoff
spot with a win and a Tennessee loss. The 49ers still trail Atlanta
(12-2) in the NFC West. Atlanta is at Detroit, where a victory
gives the Falcons a division title for only the second time in the
franchise's 33-year history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
