<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERN FIGHTS TO SAVE NBA EMPIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Recite David Stern's successes, and the list
starts to sound almost cliche.
</P>
<P>
   The storied rise of the NBA with Stern as commissioner is so
well-documented, so oft-cited, the average fan could play
word-association games with Stern's resume and without hesitation
complete the following sentences:
</P>
<P>
   Before Stern took over, the NBA played ... to half-empty arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Before Stern took over, the NBA Finals were broadcast ... on
tape delay.
</P>
<P>
   Before Stern took over, the league was viewed as ... a
collection of drug users and thugs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Stern became NBA commissioner in 1984, it would
have seemed fantasy to suggest the league would one day wilt under
the immense weight of its prosperity, as opposed to crumbling under
the weight of its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is the state of the NBA today _ a league too successful
for its own good, its incredible fortunes having begotten the most
damaging labor war in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, players and owners, who just 14 years ago forged a
partnership that gradually burgeoned into a multibillion-dollar
global enterprise, have shut down their money machine because they
cannot agree on how to divide the $2 billion annual fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's nearly six-month-old lockout threatens to wipe out the
entire 1998-99 season. Stern himself will have to make that fateful
decision _ probably within the next 14 days if no progress is made.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the lockout has badly tarnished the NBA's reputation
and threatens to destroy everything Stern helped create. Yet you
would hardly know it by listening to Stern's detached assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an economic model that needs some remodeling,'' he
says flatly, almost comically underplaying the crisis that has
wiped out 300-plus games and counting. ``Successful companies have
labor problems at one time or another.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the voice of ``Easy Dave,'' as he dubbed himself during
the 1995 labor negotiations. The commissioner is renowned for
profanity-laced tirades behind closed doors but in public it's all
statesman and salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the NBA has canceled games over labor issues for
the first time in history, or that it may become the first pro
sports league to cancel a season.
</P>
<P>
   Easy Dave's sales pitch right now is this: lockout or no, things
could be far worse. He knows. He's been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest crisis this league faced was ... in the late '70s
and early '80s (when Stern was NBA general counsel). We were a
league that had very little following, and predictions of our
demise were widespread,'' Stern said during a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were viewed as having too many African-American players, we
were viewed as the only place in the country where drugs was an
issue and where players earned too much money _ about $200,000
apiece.... The only time we ever made the evening news was if a
player got hit by another player, or a story on race or empty
arenas or drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the last year has brought the NBA more bad publicity
for drug abuse (Allen Iverson, Isaiah Rider) and violence (Latrell
Sprewell). But it took the lockout, imposed by owners July 1, to
really smear the league's image and close the book on a decade and
a half of unbridled growth.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that, for the 1983-84 season, average attendance was
10,620 per game, ticket sales were about 10 million and arenas were
filled to about 60 percent of capacity. In 1997-98, attendance
averaged 17,135, ticket sales reached close to 20 million and
arenas were filled past 90 percent capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum salary was $272,500, the median was about $1.3
million, and the top players commanded $10 to $20 million a year.
Coaches too are prospering _ all but four cleared $1 million last
year _ and Stern himself reportedly makes about $7 million (though
he is declining paychecks during the lockout).
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, the commissioner's paycheck has grown with the
value of the sport he governs. Stern himself grew up with the NBA,
beginning in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-born Stern was 24 when he landed a $7,800-a-year
job with the law firm that handled the league's legal matters. By
1978 he rose to general counsel for the league under Commissioner
Larry O'Brien and six years later succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   The ascension did not exactly come as a surprise to those who
watched him grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Suns owner Jerry Colangelo recalls, ``I came into the NBA in
1966 with the startup of the Chicago Bulls. David joined the NBA as
in-house counsel a year later, so I have seen him grow and develop
over those 31 years. I recognized early on that he was very bright,
articulate and was an excellent lawyer and saw him develop other
skills, like becoming very adept at a marketing sense and how to
sell a product, which was new ground for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it has been Stern's business and sales acumen as much as
his lawyer skills that has characterized the era. Creation of
subsidiaries, NBA Properties and NBA Entertainment, gave the league
a marketing machine and television production company. Stern also
planted seeds of the league around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   He played a role in the 1976 settlement that brought free agency
to the NBA, helped create the salary cap system that possibly saved
the league and instituted pro sports' first drug policy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Stern didn't turn a flailing league into a
multibillion-dollar corporation on his own. For that, he owes much
to Magic, Larry and Michael. But Stern helped channel all that
charisma, skill and drama into an entertainment dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8756 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-STERN-2nd-take-LA     12-19 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: entertainment dynasty. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of how these negotiations turn out, Stern's place in
sports history is cemented in the same bracket as the NFL's Pete
Rozelle.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Stern, I think, is one of the most brilliant sports
executives in the history of modern-day sports,'' said Steve Wood,
a player agent and professor of sports business at Clark Atlanta
University.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the lockout nears the six-month mark and polls show
increasing disdain and disinterest in the league, the intertwined
fortunes of the league and its esteemed leader are in peril.
</P>
<P>
   Is the presumed genius of Stern finally failing? Not exactly. In
fact, quite possibly the opposite. Some observers, including
agents, say he's never been more effective than during this
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   He planned ahead by securing a four-year, $2.6 billion
television contract that provided the league income even without
games being played. He's strategically refused to set a drop-dead
date for saving the season to keep his adversary off kilter.
</P>
<P>
   And he has done his best to undermine the union by playing off
the lower- and middle-income players against the superstars, whose
salaries he wants to cap. Late last week he took that approach to
the extreme, directly mailing a nine-page proposal, aimed at the
middle class, to all 430 players, circumventing union leadership.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part the players have stood firm, but in recent
weeks, having missed three paychecks, several have broken ranks
with the union. In a union conference call, numerous agents lobbied
union head Billy Hunter to compromise and settle.
</P>
<P>
   And while Stern continues to publicly posture about how far
apart the two sides are, it is the players' association that has
arguably made the most concessions to date _ among them, a cap on
some superstar salaries, a decrease from 20 percent to 10 percent
on annual pay raises and longer rookie contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's strategy is long term, and the lesson here is the NBA is
trying to avoid the fate of other pro sports leagues, notably Major
League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball owners lost their fight for salary controls during the
1994 strike, and the result is the current spending spree that's
created a huge competitive chasm between rich teams and poor teams.
The current hand-wringing among baseball owners could portend a
labor battle for the ages in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Stern is trying to avoid the same Band-Aid approach baseball
took, only to have things get worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll spend his days watching the league he
resurrected take daily beatings from media and fans, knowing the
damage could be permanent if his gambit doesn't get the desired
results.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's success is the league's success, and likewise the
league's failings will be tied to the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Stern's image) is already tarnished,'' said agent
Marc Fleisher. ``I don't think David could ever get back to where
he was prior to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Colangelo: ``Is his stomach churning over this whole state
of events? Sure it is. As is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Stern lets it show.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I took it personally, I wouldn't be able to do it,'' he
says. ``I've been doing this since 1967, and we've been in some
real donnybrooks. This is one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So says Easy Dave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
