<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-SEASON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS STILL SEE GREATNESS AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks before last Sunday's loss to the New York Giants, a
team of reporters asked the Denver Broncos about their chance of
becoming just the second team in modern NFL history to go
undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play like we can,'' linebacker Bill Romanowski was
saying back then, ``nobody out there can beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think we line up every week as the better team,''
backup quarterback Bubby Brister was saying back then, ``which
gives us a great shot at going unbeaten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to not only go 16-0, but to get into the playoffs,
then through the Super Bowl, and go 19-0,'' cornerback Ray Crockett
was saying back then. ``That'd make us the greatest team ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Shy, reticent types, these Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, they're so reluctant to talk about greatness that now,
even after the loss, they're still talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Says Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe: ``I'll take an 18-1
record \Rregular season and postseason combined\S and we're still
better than the '72 Dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   Them's fightin' words in Miami, where the Broncos play for win
No. 14 tomorrow night. But they shouldn't come as a shock, because
the Broncos' plan remains the same: Denver, 13-1 after the Giants
loss, can still forge a season that allows it to rank with ``the
greatest teams ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a bigger picture now,'' Crockett said.
``Combine what we've done before with what we have a chance to do
now, and history will still remember us as something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Because even NFL historians have short memories _ pro football
may be the ultimate ``What have you done for me lately?'' business
_ it takes a moment to recall how strange it is that this
collection of NFLers would be the team that threatened immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway, 38, considered retirement before this
season and has been banged up enough that backup Brister might as
well be considered Denver's co-starter. The offensive line lost
Brian Habib to free agency and Gary Zimmerman to retirement, two
good reasons to figure running back Terrell Davis wouldn't be as
good as he was in 1996 or '97, when he rushed for 1,117 and 1,750
yards, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, Sharpe has caught at least 53 passes per season. But
the starters at wide receiver, Rod Smith and Ed McCaffrey, don't
have that kind of pedigree. Smith was not drafted out of college.
McCaffrey was picked up off waivers. The debate rages in Denver
whether their present success is a product of their talent or of
teaming with Elway in coach Mike Shanahan's system.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, linebacker John Mobley and lineman Trevor Pryce are
future stars, and safety Steve Atwater and end Neil Smith are
backside-of-their-career stars. But otherwise, Romanowski's
well-orchestrated campaign to be known as a Butkus-like linebacking
monster notwithstanding, it's hardly a celebrity-studded group.
</P>
<P>
   So, entering this year _ though it required study beyond just
press clippings _ there were legitimate questions about how good
this team was, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all that with the normal challenge of following a Super
Bowl title season with a similarly charged effort, and America
should be more surprised at the Broncos' excellence than it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the result of what Mike Shanahan does,'' Crockett said.
``He's the guy who sets the tone of being low-key but having high
expectations. We expect to be great, so we handle winning pretty
matter-of-factly.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, privately, some of the Broncos simply assume their trip
to Miami will result in another victory as they march toward the
inevitable. The presence of coach Jimmy Johnson and quarterback Dan
Marino on the opposition add some luster to the battle, to be sure.
But. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's how you do it,'' said Sharpe, mockingly helping any
team attempting to repeat what the Giants did. ``Somehow stop
Terrell Davis. Then you hope John Elway has a cold and Bubby
Brister's on vacation. It's your only hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants proved that boast incorrect. But the Broncos do win
most on-paper battles with the Dolphins. Then comes the Week 16
meeting with Seattle. And then the postseason, where the Jaguars
and the Broncos have become each other's nemesis. Could the likely
showdown be a great matchup? Sure. But the game will be at Mile
High Stadium, in January, when the Broncos increase their
psychological edge. Oh, and by the way: Denver already played the
potent Jags once this year, and beat them, 37-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've felt the same way for a long time around here,'' Sharpe
said. ``We're a team destined to do something special. We're a team
with a purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
