<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN COWBOYS' GROUNDHOG PEEKS, HE MAY SEE MUSHROOM CLOUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In keeping with local custom, sometime around dusk today the
official Valley Ranch groundhog, Punxatawney Jerry, will emerge
from his luxury burrow and survey the surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   If the sun is setting on his beloved Cowboys, you know what that
means:
</P>
<P>
   Two more weeks of the NFL season. Tops.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they'll probably beat the Philadelphia Eagles today. It'll
amount to a mercy killing, judging from the way that Philly coach
Ray Rhodes has been talking.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles are 3-11 and scorching the end zone at the rate of 10
points per game, which sounds like a misprint but isn't.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether rumors of his coaching demise have been
exaggerated, Rhodes answered last week, ``Let's be realistic. We've
had a terrible season. What do you expect is going to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles learned the other day that, for the first time in 27
years, the franchise would not have a representative in the NFL's
Pro Bowl. However, six former Eagles have been selected to play,
representing their new teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' seasonlong plunge has not stopped Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones from declaring today's scrimmage ``as big a game as
we've had here at Texas Stadium in the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jones is no stranger to hyperbole, but maybe he simply
sees the train coming from the other end of the tunnel. It's been
that kind of month.
</P>
<P>
   A more intriguing assessment figures to come in January,
whenever the (a) mushroom cloud or (b) hand of the Almighty
disappears from above the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys aren't a Super Bowl team, if they don't even get
to the game's threshold, what does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   Will the new generation of Cowboys fans accept it? Better still,
will the brain trust at Cowboys, Inc.?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. The last time that a major reconstruction took place
at Valley Ranch, they began by firing Tom Landry. So that's out.
</P>
<P>
   They traded Herschel Walker. Can't pull that scam again.
</P>
<P>
   And they drafted Troy Aikman. Eureka _ a lifeboat.
</P>
<P>
   Except that Cowboys diehards refuse to accept the notion that
this team needs a major retooling. They point to the injuries of
this season _ who knew Aikman and Deion Sanders would each miss
five or more games? They point to the twin 13-12 defeats at the
hands of Oakland and Chicago. They point to new blood like Flozell
Adams and Michael Myers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what they're pointing at, though. Are they saying
the current Cowboys are better than 8-6, or that the future already
appears brighter?
</P>
<P>
   It's much too early to proclaim the latter. And the former
point, let me suggest, doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   This is a trophy kind of town, and there is no jewelry that
comes with losing in the second round of the NFC playoffs. Cowboys
apologists can say that the Super Bowl was never the prize, that
all along this was only to be a season of healing from the Switzer
era, but how convenient.
</P>
<P>
   No, the common chant being heard in September at Valley Ranch
was that, armed with a new coach, the Cowboys possessed playoff
talent that, by December, would be deemed artful enough to make
their familiar Super Bowl run.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't heard that one in weeks, however.
</P>
<P>
   So now what?
</P>
<P>
   Around the league, writers are calling the Cowboys old and
saddlesore. That's not entirely correct. Guard Nate Newton is 37
and qualifies as old. He has had a lackluster month.
</P>
<P>
   But you'd think there should be an earnest playoff sweat left in
Aikman, who is 32, and in Michael Irvin (32), Daryl Johnston (32),
Sanders (31), Smith (29) and Leon Lett (30).
</P>
<P>
   Next year they will all be a year older, with no replacements in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey can't afford to make the mistakes (see the 1995
draft) that the former regime made. The Cowboys will need help just
to get this far in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, it's only Ray Rhodes and the already
plucked-and-basted Eagles making a Christmas visit this time.
</P>
<P>
   A big game? Well, if the owner insists.
</P>
<P>
   But come back in two weeks and see the mushroom cloud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
