<SLUG> BC-BKN-HUNTER-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTER HAS KEPT HIS TROOPS IN LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Billy Hunter can spew obtuse phrases like ``escrow
tax,'' and ``BRI'' with the best of them. And he does. But scrape
away all the lawyer-speak and finance mechanism double-talk, and
the director of the NBA players' union is, at his core, the one
thing his clients needed most:
</P>
<P>
   A politician.
</P>
<P>
   History will show Hunter failed in his lone foray into
professional politics _ an unsuccessful attempt in 1990 to unseat
Oakland Congressman Ron Dellums. But as the appointed figurehead of
430 NBA players, Hunter has proven to be an adept leader of a
complex constituency.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old former U.S. attorney has done exactly what his
opponent, NBA Commissioner David Stern, presumed couldn't be done:
maintained the unity of his troops _ from the superstars to the
scrubs, the $33 million franchise player down to the $272,000 12th
man.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Hunter has so far protected the financial gains of
NBA players _ and protracted the league's lockout. How you judge
those results depends on your point of view.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain: season or no season, good deal or bad,
Hunter has become a force equal to Stern in the basketball
marketplace and has justified his rank as the 40th most powerful
person in sports in a recent magazine poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has great political skills, the players respect him, he's
an ex-athlete, he's quite eloquent, he's tough, he's a no-nonsense
kind of guy,'' says agent Marc Fleisher. ``The vibe I'm getting
from players is they're willing to stand shoulder to shoulder with
him and fight the fight, which is something a number of us were not
sure of early on.''
</P>
<P>
   That shoulder-to-shoulder stance is the players' greatest
leverage in this $2 billion standoff. United they profit; divided,
they'd settle for less.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter knew this when he took the job in 1996. A battle-tested
lawyer who once represented the tobacco industry, Hunter was a
newcomer to labor negotiations. But as a one-time agent to former
rap stars Hammer and Bobby Brown, he knew the power held by the
paid talent.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the talent was a group of 400-plus athletes, so he
began his term by logging frequent-flier miles. Like any
politician, he needed to kiss some babies to win support.
</P>
<P>
   So Hunter visited all 28 NBA cities to meet with players, many
of whom felt burned by former director Simon Gourdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent two years developing trust among my players and
proving that I could do the job in a competent and professional
manner,'' Hunter says. ``My only agenda was to demonstrate that I
was available to them.... When I go into a locker room, I talk to
every guy. I don't just go to the superstars. Everybody is
important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years and one lockout ago, things were different.
Superstars fought union leaders, powerful agents like David Falk
led a drive to decertify the players' association. Gourdine, a
former NBA attorney, was viewed with distrust by players.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the deal signed by players and owners under that
cloud in 1995 proved just as problematic as many feared. Top player
salaries skyrocketed _ Shaquille O'Neal got $121 over seven years,
unproven Kevin Garnett got $126 million, Michael Jordan began
signing one-year deals in excess of $30 million per season _ but
the middle class disappeared as one-fourth of the union's members
signed minimum-salary deals.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's job, then, combined impossible elements: protect the
gains of the superstars and restore the middle class at the same
time, all the while somehow meeting the concerns of NBA owners, who
were spending themselves into a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tall order for someone negotiating his first collective
bargaining agreement, but Hunter has never shied away from a
challenge. Or an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager growing up in Cherry Hill, N.J., Hunter attended
a school with fewer than 20 other African-Americans and a handful
of Jews. His circle of friends included both, and that coalition of
minorities was sometimes forced to protect its honor the
old-fashioned way _ in fistfights with less-progressive white
students.
</P>
<P>
   In his professional life, Hunter proved just as aggressive. He
prosecuted surviving members of the Jim Jones cult 20 years ago and
helped convince President Jimmy Carter to pardon Patricia Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in private practice in Oakland, Hunter represented R.J.
Reynolds and Philip Morris as a member of the tobacco industry's
litigation team.
</P>
<P>
   But he also donated his time to friends and neighbors and sought
out public service, traveling around the world on trade missions
for the Oakland Port Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I'm an eclectic person,'' Hunter says with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing, it would seem, could sufficiently prepare Hunter
for his next career move, leaving private practice to become the
figurehead for perhaps the richest labor union in the known
universe.
</P>
<P>
   But as in the past, Hunter has been tireless in pursuit of his
clients' interests. That has meant seven-day work weeks, heading
home at 11 p.m. some nights, traveling a week or two each month to
visit players and no vacation in 2{ years, save the occasional long
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing short of that would suffice, though. Unlike Stern, whose
clientele is limited to 29 owners, Hunter's employer has 430
mouths. Add several dozen agents on top of that, all with opinions
and interests of their own, and you wonder if Hunter's reported
$675,000 salary is perhaps insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
