A8985 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     12-19 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTCARDS FROM THE LEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ricky Williams in the house and Roger Clemens maybe on the way.
What next, a change in the Rangers colors to say, burnt orange? A
hook-'em-Horns banner across Home Run Porch?
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't gotten that drastic, although it began to look
that way last week when the Rangers risked losing a utility
infielder who could very well make their 25-man roster next spring
in order to acquire University of Texas' Heisman Trophy winner
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And who spent last weekend schmoozing and celebrating with
Williams after he won the Heisman in New York? Rangers' owner/UT
mover-and-shaker Tom Hicks, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance certainly was that Hicks had pulled off the
biggest act of cronyism by a Rangers' owner since Brad Corbett
ordered general manager Eddie Robinson to protect his buddy John
Ellis, who was rehabbing from a badly broken ankle, in the 1977
expansion draft and lost promising right-hander Jim Clancy to
Toronto instead.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says general manager Doug Melvin. It's just a case of a
GM knowing what might please his owner and acting on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all my idea,'' Melvin claims. ``I'd tried to work a
trade with Philadelphia to get him and couldn't do it. This
\Rgetting Williams from Montreal for $100,000 cash after the Expos
took him in the Rule V draft last week at the winter meetings\S was
better because it didn't cost us any players.''
</P>
<P>
   It almost did. The Rangers had to bump shortstop Scott Sheldon _
who hit 29 home runs at Triple A last year and is expected to
battle for a job as backup to Royce Clayton this spring _ off the
40-man roster and place him on waivers, meaning Sheldon could have
been claimed by another team. Fortunately, the Rangers found out
yesterday that he had cleared waivers and assigned him to the
Oklahoma roster. It would have been a crime if Sheldon had been
lost because of this move.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, expected to be one of the top two or three picks in
the NFL draft next April, has struggled in his two brief stints in
the Phillies' farm system since being selected in the eighth round
in June of '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good bat speed and he can run,'' Melvin said, ``plus
I'm a character guy. When we asked him who his favorite football
player was growing up, he didn't have one. But when we asked him
about baseball, he immediately said Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was only a mediocre football player, I think he'd be
playing baseball, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when Melvin told Hicks that he was getting Williams,
the Rangers' owner was delighted.
</P>
<P>
   You could call it brown-nosing, but burnt-orange nosing might be
more accurate. ...
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Williams will get an invitation to spring training. Too bad
Will Clark won't be there to address the subject of Ricky's
dreadlocks in ``The Thrill's'' inimitable way. ...
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Manager Johnny Oates made it to Austin for the big PR
bonanza at the Williams' announcement, but couldn't stick around an
extra day for a little Christmas cheer at the team's annual holiday
luncheon with the media. What, we eat one too many Bloomin' Onions
or something?. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's the skinny on the holdup on the Clemens deal with the
Rangers, according to someone who should know: If the Rangers
refuse to give up Ivan Rodriguez, Rusty Greer or Ruben Mateo, then
the Blue Jays want the pitcher they get back in the trade to be
upgraded to 20-game winner Rick Helling. The Rangers, so far, have
stuck to offering Esteban Loaiza. ...
</P>
<P>
   Agent Jeff Moorad (Steve Young, Troy Aikman, Pudge Rodriguez,
Clark, et al) has sent out beautiful cards featuring photos of
himself, his wife and two great-looking kids. On his desk are of a
couple of props for the photo, including a very readable plaque
that says: ``Show Me The Money!'' And you thought it might say
something seasonal like, ``Peace on Earth, Good Will Toward
Men?''...
</P>
<P>
   One reason to worry about the Frogs against Southern Cal at the
Sun Bowl: The Trojans put nine men on the line against Notre Dame,
dared the Irish to pass the ball, and stuffed their running game.
TCU threw for two touchdowns all season and starting quarterback
Patrick Batteaux didn't get his first until the final game against
winless UNLV. ...
</P>
<P>
   Ted Davis, the former Mavs' radio play-by-play man? His bio in
the Milwaukee Bucks' media guide also lists him as a former ``radio
voice of the Texas Rangers.'' He did once spell the late Mark Holtz
for a week when Alice was ill, but we're a little sensitive about
who gets to be called ``voice of the Rangers'' and Teddy, while a
nice guy, isn't one of them. ...
</P>
<P>
   Remember minor-league second baseman Warren Morris, who went to
Pittsburgh for Loaiza? He just hit .307 (fifth) in the Arizona Fall
League with 8 home runs (tied for second) and 27 runs batted in
(fifth) and impressed his manager, Reds coach Ken Griffey Sr.
``He's a flat-out, bona fide hitter,'' Griffey said. ``I don't see
any problems with his game.'' The Pirates will start Morris at
Triple A this season and hope he'll be their starting second
baseman in 2000. ...
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on this: Jim Bronner, agent for Rangers outfielder
and A.L. MVP Juan Gonzalez, isn't exactly beating down Melvin's
door, trying to get a contract extension for his client. ``He's not
pushing it at all,'' Melvin says, which could mean Bronner intends
to prod Gonzalez toward free agency and a move-over-Kevin Brown
contract....
</P>
<P>
   And a very merry Christmas to my new hero, Mavs forward Chris
Anstey, who had a quote in this section last week that bears
repeating: ``What's the difference if you make $10 million a year
or $9 million a year?'' Anstey told our Dwain Price. ``How much
difference does it make to your lifestyle? It's going to be more
than most people see in a lifetime anyway. Everyone should just be
thankful for what they've got and play the game they love.''
</P>
<P>
   A tip of the egg nog glass to Chris and the happiest of holidays
to you and and yours.
REVO'S RIMSHOTS Based on Kevin Greene's choke hold on a Panthers
assistant coach last weekend, he'll definitely have post-football
career opportunities in politics. Maybe even as Jesse ``The Body''
Ventura's running mate in a future tag-team assault on the White
House. Let's see somebody talk impeachment then.
</P>
<P>
   Nate Newton selected to the Pro Bowl? It's the punch line to a
Jay Leno joke, right? Obviously the votes must have been taken
before the Cowboys' past two games.
</P>
<P>
   So how Will Clark, Albert Belle and Cal Jr. co-exist in that
surly Baltimore clubhouse? Clark and Belle are both from Louisiana
but that doesn't mean they'll like each other. And if Will tries
his ``Sheriff'' act on Ripken, he's liable to get his badge taken
away.
</P>
<P>
   So Jerry Jones would like to bring back instant replay, and the
sooner the better. Maybe the call he'd most like to see under
review is the one he made when he hired You-Know-Who back in '94.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
