<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENNESSEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE PATIENCE PAID OFF IN VICTORIES  
 VOLUNTEERS GREW INTO THEIR NO. 1 RANKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The early road to Tempe was filled with
caution signs and construction zones. But by the midway point,
Tennessee went full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about a team that sent eight players to the NFL in the
off-season prompted the Volunteers to play it safe in the early
going. They limited what new quarterback Tee Martin was allowed to
do, and they waited patiently as an inexperienced defense matured.
</P>
<P>
   It was a winning formula. Tennessee capped an undefeated season
with a No. 1 ranking and a spot in the Fiesta Bowl. The 12
victories include six over ranked teams, and the last three were by
a combined 89 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the season, nobody thought we'd be at the point we
are now,'' linebacker Eric Westmoreland said. ``People were
second-guessing us because of all the players we lost, including a
starting quarterback, to the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight who advanced to the pros, three were first-round
picks: quarterback Peyton Manning, wide receiver Marcus Nash and
defensive back Terry Fair, a South Mountain High School product.
</P>
<P>
   Most preseason polls had Tennessee ranked near 10th, but Coach
Phillip Fulmer believed his team could finish higher if three goals
were met:
</P>
<P>
   Run the football well enough to lead the Southeastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Improve turnover ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Lead the league in scoring defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers led the SEC in rushing with a 211.3 yards
average. They wound up with a plus-16 turnover margin (sixth in the
nation) after ranking 10th in the league a season ago. And they
allowed 14.4 points a game, just three-tenths short of SEC leader
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seniors, I really challenged them, personally and
publicly,'' Fulmer said. ``They bought into the approach. Then we
started answering all the `ifs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest ifs involved Martin, who had never started, and a
defense that lost seven starters, including three in the
secondary. &QL; 
Tee time &QL; 
Early in the season, Tennessee took an ultra-conservative approach
with Martin, a junior who had attempted only 12 passes as Manning's
backup last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to ask you to win games for us,'' Fulmer told
him early. ``I'm going to ask you not to lose any.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first four games, Martin completed 35 of 79 passes for
509 yards. The 44 percent effort was the lowest passing percentage
at Tennessee in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers kept the game plan simple. And as Martin's
confidence grew, their conservativeness drove him crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating. I felt like I was being held back by my
own coaches,'' he said, smiling. ``It was like jail.''
</P>
<P>
   By Game 5, the coaching staff's confidence in Martin matched the
quarterback's. He completed 16 of 26 passes against Georgia and 10
of 14 vs. Alabama. Against South Carolina, he connected on an
NCAA-record 23 straight passes before missing his final attempt and
finishing 23 of 24.
</P>
<P>
   In the Volunteers' final seven games, Martin passed for 1,499
yards, 10 touchdowns and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become a real field general,'' cornerback Steve Johnson
said. ``He's got a lot of confidence. It wasn't like that the first
couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said, ``I think I've exceeded my expectations. I came in
wanting to be the most fundamental quarterback, play smart football
and not lose any games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that came and more. We had a dream of being undefeated and
competing for a national championship. We got it all. Now here I am
on the Number 1 team in the nation.'' &QL; 
Give me a `D' &QL; 
The Volunteers' defensive concerns included a secondary with three
new starters and a front with questionable health.
</P>
<P>
   The backfield worried the staff most. Cornerback Dwayne Goodrich
was the only one with starting experience. Safety Fred White and
cornerback Steve Johnson had played but were in few big-game
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, senior linebacker Al Wilson said, ``They're
going to have to grow up immediately, and I expect them to grow up
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right,'' White said. ``We didn't have any respect. We
didn't have any big-game experience. We had to come out and show
people that we were going to fight as hard as we had the years
before. And we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a fast, hard-hitting defense that
specializes in big plays.
</P>
<P>
   There was a four-down, goal-line stand after a turnover against
Georgia. A 90-yard interception return for a touchdown by defensive
end Shaun Ellis against Auburn. And Wilson's 12-tackle performance
vs. Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Defensive coordinator John Chavis) came into this season
knowing we were great athletes but not knowing what kind of team we
were going to be,'' Johnson said. ``He wanted to give us our own
identity. He met with us before the season and said, `We're going
to be a very aggressive defense. If you don't like to be in the
quarterback's face, then you better transfer.'' &QL; 
Odds and ends &QL; 
Fulmer emphasized that the 12-0 record is a product of a team
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Few have been as exciting as wide receiver Peerless Price, who
caught 10 touchdown passes and surpassed 100 yards in three of the
Volunteers' final six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peerless is doing as much with the football as anyone we
have,'' Fulmer said. ``He makes as much happen, per touch, as any
receiver we've had here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Volunteers endured without tailback Jamal Lewis, who was
lost for the season after suffering a knee injury against Auburn on
Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   If one thing defined Tennessee in 1998, it was resilience. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
