<HEADLINE>
LOSS TO N.C. STATE TURNS FLORIDA STATE'S SEASON AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The Bobby Bowden most people know is jovial,
quick-witted and slow to anger. But the Florida State coach was not
in a funny, ha-ha mood Sept. 14, two days after the Seminoles had
been upset, 24-7, at North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked into the team meeting that day, players sat up
straight and listened. Florida State had not lost more than two
games in a season since 1986 and had finished the previous 11
seasons ranked no lower than fourth. Bowden bluntly laid out what
was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us plain and simple, `If you guys don't raise your
level of play, this program is going down,' '' said cornerback
Mario Edwards. ``That right there was enough to open every sleeping
ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, who keeps notes of every speech to his team, couldn't
recall exactly what he said without searching through his files.
But he remembers the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about living off previous team's reputations,'' he
said. ``That was the keynote. (I said) `The reason we were
preseason Number 2 and Number 3 or whatever is because of what last
year's team did. It ain't nothing y'all did. You didn't contribute
anything.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That day seems far away now to the 11-1, second-ranked
Seminoles, who will play No. 1 Tennessee on Jan. 4 in the Fiesta
Bowl. But it was on that Monday when they renewed their commitment
to remaining one of the elite programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   That day, they looked at each other and vowed not to be
responsible for the beginning of a fall from grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose a game like that, little things creep into the
back of your mind,'' offensive guard Jason Whitaker said. ``Is this
the year the dynasty will fall? It was always in the back of my
mind. I did not want to be here when the dynasty fell, if it is
going to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles are usually national championship contenders, but
Bowden thought his team might be a year away from its best shot at
winning one.
</P>
<P>
   His top quarterback, Dan Kendra, had blown out a knee in the
spring game and was lost for the year. The backup, sophomore Chris
Weinke, had thrown only 13 passes the year before.
</P>
<P>
   There were only four seniors starting on defense and two on
offense. There was immense talent in the freshman and sophomore
classes, and it was thought they wouldn't mature fully for another
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' confidence grew when they beat Texas A&AMP;M in the
opener. But when North Carolina State, an average team, upset
Florida State, Bowden decided changes needed to be made,
commitments renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Practices were tougher. Players were told that if they didn't
practice, they didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you'll do this as a coach,'' Bowden said.
``Things will be going good for you and you're afraid somebody will
get hurt, so you start slacking off. So they have to wake up by
getting beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that game, our philosophy changed. We were going to go
out and do what it takes, not matter if all of them got hurt. We
worked a little bit harder, and we haven't backed down a day since
either.''
</P>
<P>
   There were questions, however, that tougher practices could not
answer. Most of the doubts centered around Weinke, who was
intercepted six times against North Carolina State, a school
record.
</P>
<P>
   All the work in the world wouldn't overcome a quarterback who
didn't play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris had such a bad day that that was the big question
mark,'' Bowden said. ``Have you got the wrong quarterback? Have you
spent all this time getting this young man ready and he simply
can't play well on Saturday? Those are things going through your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, however, responded. He did not throw an interception in
the next eight games, as the Seminoles proved their loss to North
Carolina State was a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   The young defense, meanwhile, developed beyond anyone's
expectations. It's first in the country in total and passing
efficiency defense and second in scoring and rushing defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to make some decisions about how important winning was
to us and how being better than average, how much that meant to
us,'' defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews said. ``I think we had
some guys who grew up, seniors that accepted more responsibility
and some juniors that acted like seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   There were difficulties along the way. The biggest came in the
10th game, when Weinke suffered a neck injury shortly before
halftime against Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced by sophomore Marcus Outzen, who became the
full-time starter when Weinke underwent surgery and was lost for
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden continued to preach that a national championship was
still a possibility, a theme he had repeated even after the North
Carolina State game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down, we were thinking, `yeah, right,' '' said receiver
Peter Warrick, the team's most dangerous offensive threat. ``Then
Weinke goes down and we're thinking it's really over now. But
everything happens for a reason, and we're back where we needed to
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
