<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUTGERS-TEMPLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG SCARLET KNIGHTS DONE IN BY VETERAN OWLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ They have won back their raucous fans who
have long made this corner of New Jersey one of the coziest,
craziest basketball bastions in the Northeast. They've won seven
games, two of them in the Big East Conference. But the Scarlet
Knights of Rutgers showed they are still a young team in need of
baby steps, crumbling 56-38 Saturday to a seasoned Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Those here in the noisy, sold-out Louis Brown Athletic Center,
however, left assured that Coach Kevin Bannon, in his second year
at Rutgers, has put together a program that is much further along
than Rutgers' surprising football team of 1998 and perhaps worthy
of the same respect that Vivian Stringer's women's team commands.
This team is better than the one that was 14-15, (6-12 Big East)
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights play tough defense and they have two budding
stars in the freshmen Dahntay Jones and Rashod Kent. But it was a
dreadful shooting collapse in the first 11 minutes of the second
half that turned an exciting, back-and-forth game into a Temple
blowout. In a span where everything from dunks to free throws
caromed off the rims, Rutgers shot two of 17.
</P>
<P>
   It was all a crafty bunch of struggling Owls needed to stretch a
three- point game into a 15-point lead and, finally, an 18-point
rout. Temple's 6-10 center, Lamont Barnes, knocked in 14 and senior
guard Rasheed Brokenborough scored 23. But it was the Owls'
intricate matchup zone that limited Rutgers to just 29 percent
shooting and kept the Scarlet Knights nearly 30 points below their
season scoring average.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rutgers and Temple needed a victory, but for very different
reasons. The Scarlet Knights wanted to prove their 7-1 start wasn't
a fluke. The team, picked by the Big East's coaches to finish
eighth, had a five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls (5-4) needed to reassert themselves after an early
stretch of hard luck that may have demoralized a team many had
thought was one of Coach John Chaney's best in years. After winning
its first four games, Temple dropped four of the next five by a
combined total of 12 points _ including one-point losses at Indiana
and Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Temple also lost sophomore guard Lynn Greer, who was averaging
10 points, when he caught an elbow in the eye against Penn State.
That injury, which required surgery early this month, will keep him
out until late February.
</P>
<P>
   Kent and Jones kept Rutgers as close as three points, 25-22, in
a deliberately played first half. Kent, 6-feet-6, 265 pounds,
knocked around Barnes and 6-9 Kevin Lyde as if they were willows.
Kent came into the game averaging 10.9 points on 82 percent
shooting from the field, and he showed how: He's never more than
two feet from the goal.
</P>
<P>
   His two offensive put-backs and bruising defense cleared the
floor for Jones, a 6-5 slasher, to score nine points on a variety
of lane splitting drives. He also had two steals and frustrated the
Owls' veteran back court of Brokenborough and Pepe Sanchez. The two
were six of 13 from the field in the first half and turned the ball
over three times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Temple managed to shoot better than Rutgers by 38 percent
to 32 percent and make all of its free throws, - including two by
Brokenborough with no time left at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
