<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SPAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEVILLE, REAL BETIS REBUILDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ For nearly two years, the cathedral bell tower
La Giralda, the symbol of this Andalusian city, has been covered in
scaffolding. The large bronze statue that serves as a weather vane
and has been perched on top since the 1500s has been removed, a
victim of the elements and the centuries. Its much-debated
replacement is not scheduled to be put in place until late
December.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giralda is not the only municipal monument in Seville in
need of scaffolding. The Real Betis soccer club is under
renovation, as well, and soccer meaning what it does in Spain, the
pace of change is much faster.
</P>
<P>
   After paying the world-record sum of $35 million to Sao Paolo FC
for the Brazilian striker Denilson _ outbidding would-be rivals
Real Madrid and FC Barcelona _ Betis finds itself in 14th place in
the 20-team Spanish first division after 14 league matches.
</P>
<P>
   Seven games ago, the club hired its fourth and most recognizable
coach of the young season: Javier Clemente, the pugnacious Basque
who coached the Spanish national team for six years until he was
forced out last month in the wake of Spain's fiasco of a World Cup
and subsequent loss to Cyprus in qualifying for Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be pushed out of the national team affected me a lot
because it was unfair,'' Clemente, who reported to work in Seville
on Wednesday, said. ``The idea of going a whole year without
coaching was something I didn't like, and it was something I liked
even less after what happened to me. I hope I can turn things
around at Betis.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had some success so far, bringing Betis up from last
place. Really, though, there was only one direction to go on the
banks of the Guadalquivir. In its first seven matches, ``Beti,'' as
the s-dropping locals here call it, surrendered a league-high 13
goals and scored only 4. In the game before Clemente was hired, it
was beaten, 5-1, on the road in Valencia, which prompted not only
the resignation but the retirement of the Chilean coach, Vicente
Cantatore.
</P>
<P>
   Cantatore was not the first Betis coach to retire in the last
three months. On July 27, the widely respected Luis Aragones, the
man who was supposed to guide Betis' multibillion-peseta lineup to
new heights resigned for what he said were personal reasons, one of
which reportedly was his resistance to meddling from the club
president, Manuel Ruiz de Lopera. Aragones was replaced by Antonio
Luis Alves de Oliveira, the former coach of Porto, who lasted only
a few weeks and resigned shortly before the season began. Enter and
exit Cantatore, Betis' third coach of the preseason, which was
certainly not what the ambitious Lopera had in mind when he
approved a budget of $80 million for player acquisitions and
salaries this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not asking to be champions but for him to remove the
team from the situation it is in and put us in the top six, where
we belong,'' Lopera said after negotiating a one-year deal with
Clemente in a hurry on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately half of Lopera's budget was spent on Denilson, the
21-year-old who has played in seven league matches and two UEFA Cup
matches and has yet to score a goal or score many points with those
who appreciate value for money. Denilson is clearly a gifted
technician, but his flashy and not always effectual or generous
play has begun to make clear why Brazilian Coach Mario Zagallo
decided to use him only as a substitute during the World Cup this
summer. In a loss to Celta, he was replaced after 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The leap from South American soccer to Europe is seldom
straightforward, however, and the club's avid fans are still more
thankful than resentful that Denilson deemed their team and city
worthy enough to sign on the dotted line. It remains to be seen how
long he stays in favor with Clemente, who made a habit of
emphasizing unity over individual artistry during his tenure with
the Spanish national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't interest me how much he cost,'' Clemente said.
``What interests me is how he plays. If he cost a lot and plays
well, great. Denilson showed in his country that he was one of the
best players in Brazil and the world. What he needs to do now is
show the same thing but with Betis.''
</P>
<P>
   Having healthy teammates would not hurt. The star striker
Alfonso missed most of the early season with a knee injury that
turned out to be more serious than first thought. Other key players
have also missed games, and losing the Croatian star Robert Jarni
to Real Madrid this summer has not helped either.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been a continuing legal battle between the club
and a construction firm over delays in the renovation and expansion
of its stadium. A Sevillan who made his fortune in real estate
development, Lopera has been the strong and soccer-savvy
personality behind Betis' revival in the 1990's. When Lopera took
over the club, it was in the second division: no isolated
occurrence for an outfit that has long been in the shadow both on
and off the field of its rival, FC Sevilla, from which it split in
the early 20th century. The year after Lopera arrived, the club was
promoted under the direction of Lorenzo Serra Ferrer, and it has
qualified for European competition ever since. Meanwhile, FC
Sevilla was relegated after the 1995-96 season, which was good for
the morale of long-suffering Betis supporters, whose club had
suddenly become fashionable, but bad for the revenue and interest
that the heated intracity rivalry generates.
</P>
<P>
   If Clemente does not continue to improve morale and
performances, Seville, one of the most passionate soccer cities in
Europe and the fourth-largest city in Spain, may again have its
local rivalry: in the second division. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
