<HEADLINE>
STEPHENVILLE WINS CLASS 4A DIVISION II TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The best pass-catch combination in Texas high
school football history now has the state records and trophy to
prove it.
</P>
<P>
   If any doubt remained as to whether Stephenville featured
attractions other than quarterback Kelan Luker and receiver Cody
Cardwell, its defense buried that notion.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville (15-1) shredded the vaunted defense of La Marque
(13-1) and held the Cougars to a season-low scoring output, winning
the Class 4A Division II state championship, 34-7, yesterday at
Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   La Marque's sixth consecutive state title appearance ended
bitterly after victories the past three seasons. The Cougars are
0-3 in title games against Stephenville, having also lost to the
Yellow Jackets in 1993 and '94.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville scored 34 unanswered points after trailing, 7-0, in
the first quarter. La Marque's previous high for points allowed was
16.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville also snapped La Marque's 20-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   With 286 yards passing, Luker set state records for passing
yards in a season (4,697) and a career (8,294).
</P>
<P>
   Cardwell (107 catches in 1998) iced his already established
state records for season and career receiving yards, finishing with
2,422 and 4,343 yards, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so proud of a group of players in my life,''
Stephenville coach Art Briles said. ``We've got unselfish players
who care about each other and that's how you win a state
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 7-0 first-quarter lead on Tim Parker's 3-yard
run, La Marque went 17 minutes, 17 seconds without a first down.
Stephenville linebacker Jack Hodges, who prowled the line of
scrimmage, led a stunning defensive effort with 10 tackles (four
for losses), a sack and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew all we had to do was execute our defense,'' defensive
end Cal Jillson (two sacks) said. ``Our coaches were putting us in
the right spot. We were confident, even when we were losing.''
</P>
<P>
   While the defense held La Marque's running game (89 yards) well
below its season average (213), Stephenville's offense scored on
five consecutive drives to take a 27-7 lead. It began with a tight,
18-yard scoring toss by Luker to T.J. Douglas for a 7-7 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker J.W. Boren's 28-yard field goal and a 33-yard touchdown
pass to Chris Evatt (five catches, 104 yards) by Luker gave
Stephenville a 17-7 halftime lead. The 17 points before the half
came within 6 minutes, 49 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still felt like we could win at halftime,'' La Marque coach
Larry Walker said. ``But we had some breakdowns and didn't
execute.''
</P>
<P>
   From Stephenville's first score until game's end, defenders
Hodges, Jillson, Clayton Harmon, B.J. Mercer, Clark Boone, Craig
Parks (blocked punt), Keith McCormick and Brady Gunn put a clamp on
La Marque that the Cougars won't soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville's first two second-half drives resulted in a Boren
44-yard field goal for 20-7 lead. The bottom later fell out of La
Marque's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Luker converted a third-down pass to Cardwell for 10 yards and
then had all day to hit Evatt for 39 yards to the La Marque 5-yard
line. Running back Jimmy Ferrazas ran it in to give the Yellow
Jackets a 27-7 third-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a real good defense,'' Cardwell said. ``We knew our
offense was a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Luker said knowing he could throw on La Marque by halftime was a
comfort. With 4:53 to play, he was celebrating on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone works their butt off for so long,'' Luker said. ``If
you get here and don't win it, you get your heart broken. You want
it to be worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
