<HEADER>
A9015 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAROUK-AZR &LR;      12-19 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAROUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQI NATIVE A U.S. CITIZEN AND CRITIC OF BOTH NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Farouk Al-Hashimi, native of Baghdad and citizen of the United
States, is condemned as a betrayer by his Iraqi family, and perhaps
by some of his fellow Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As bombs and famine ravage the cradle of Islam, relatives see
Farouk as a brainwashed Westerner who defends the U.S. system and
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a traitor in their eyes,'' he admits sadly. ``You know
why? Because I have food. I have a car and a home. I am an enemy
because I don't feel what they feel. I don't suffer what they
suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 58-year-old Muslim may also be vilified by some
Americans because he is a bitter critic of American military and
economic strategies which, he claims, subjected his family to bombs
and hunger for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is playing games,'' Farouk says. ``America's
policy in the Middle East is ruled by two things. Oil, No. 1. And
Israel, No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The unemployed banker and Islamic Sunday school teacher has
straddled this unsteady fence between nations, cultures and faiths
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is American,'' Farouk noted. ``Her nephews fought with
American troops in Kuwait. My nephews fought for the Iraqi army in
Basra.''
</P>
<P>
   In a voice tinged with pride, humility and nostalgia, he
recounts the personal saga that led from the Arabian desert to the
Sonoran.
</P>
<P>
   Farouk said he is one of 11 children born into a Sunni family
that traces its Baghdad history 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   After enrolling at the University of Baghdad, he spent two years
reporting for a progressive Iraqi newspaper, ``The People,'' then
gained an economics degree in 1963. He was drafted into the army,
rose to the level of first lieutenant, and planned a military
career.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1968, however, Saddam Hussein and his Baath Socialist
Party came to power. Farouk fled to the United States and enrolled
at Detroit's Wayne State University, where he met Sally Eperjesy.
</P>
<P>
   A Hungarian-American Catholic woman. An Islamic Arab immigrant.
Worlds collided, merged into marriage and moved to Phoenix for a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been a good example of how Christians and Muslims
should live together in peace and understanding,'' Farouk says.
</P>
<P>
   He attended the American Institute of Banking. Two siblings also
moved to Phoenix. But there is another family 7,600 miles away.
Farouk said he tried to reach his oldest brother before this week's
missile attacks, but could not get through.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier letters and phone calls, he added, they have told of
conditions in Baghdad. Farouk said the bread is so stale and stiff
that it cannot be chewed unless it is first dampened and warmed. He
said a niece wheezes from asthma because there is no medicine, and
his brother's high blood pressure led to a stroke for the same
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say I am the most brainwashed American,'' Farouk added.
``They don't understand anymore what I say because of their
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Iraqis hate Saddam, Farouk added. The dictator has executed
those who plot rebellion, including soldiers and two
brothers-in-law. He has tortured and killed imams. Farouk says
Saddam would not receive 1 percent of the vote if Iraq held open
elections.
</P>
<P>
   But starving people are more concerned with survival than
rebellion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot lift a finger if you don't have food in your
stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the Iraqis also despise an American government
that has blockaded supplies and bombarded cities, Farouk said.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment is true through much of the Arab world, even among
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Farouk said Muslims see the United States as an ``arrogant
bully'' not just becaL &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
