<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENDERS SOFTENING THE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditionally, the relationship between borrowers and lenders
has been defined by two assumptions, both seemingly
self-contradictory: One was that to obtain credit, a person had to
establish a good credit history. The second was that lenders
generally preferred to make loans to those who didn't need them.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the traditional rules for lending have
softened significantly _ particularly with respect to mortgages and
home equity loans. Now, credit experts say, borrowers who are
already in debt are often welcome to borrow more. And those whose
track records have been less than perfect _ even abysmal _ are
often given another chance to prove themselves good bets as
borrowers. ``Basically, you can get a mortgage today even if you've
been through bankruptcy,'' said Gerri Detweiler, education adviser
for Debt Counselors of America, a consumer advocacy organization
based in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Detweiler said that while there had always been lenders
willing to lend money to those with less than perfect credit, such
loans were typically short-term and at relatively high interest.
Now, however, it is possible for those who have had credit problems
to get long-term mortgages or home equity loans from lenders who in
the past would have rejected such borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   And while those with blemishes on their credit histories are
still likely to pay higher interest rates, she said, those rates
can usually be renegotiated if the borrower re-establishes a good
payment record. ``The bottom line is that there are lots of
opportunities out there for borrowers,'' Ms. Detweiler said. ``Even
borrowers with bad credit.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the less-than-perfect credit market is increasing so
significantly that Intuit, the Mountain View, Calif., company that
markets Quicken software and sponsors an Internet site for those
seeking home mortgages (www.quickenmortgage.com), recently added
lenders who specialize in so-called ``subprime'' loans to its Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``These borrowers represent from 15 to 20 percent of the
market,'' said Alison Berkley, group product manager for the
company. Ms. Berkley said borrowers who visit the Quicken Mortgage
site and whose credit history is ``less than perfect'' would be
referred to one of four new lenders affiliated with the site. ``We
have a product called the `Back on Track Loan,' '' said Shelly
Porges, executive vice president of new business initiatives for
The Money Store, a home equity lender based in Sacramento, Calif.,
that is now a participating lender on the Quicken Mortgage Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that with the new program, homeowners who have had
problems paying off high-interest credit-card debt could get a
home-equity loan to consolidate that debt. And while the interest
rate on the loan is generally higher than the rate for those with
good credit histories _ from one to several percentage points more,
depending on the severity of past credit problems _ it is typically
lower than rates charged on credit cards. Also, Ms. Porges said,
the interest rate on the loan will be steadily decreased after each
year of on-time payments.
</P>
<P>
   She added that while most conventional lenders relied upon
mathematical formulas and credit scoring to determine a borrower's
eligibility, her company, which specializes in the ``subprime''
market, also takes into consideration a borrower's personal
explanation for past credit problems. ``We often call our loans
`story loans' because we listen to the borrower's story and try to
understand the circumstances,'' she said. ``And that allows us to
be more flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   But even conventional lenders seem to be increasingly willing to
offer ``subprime'' borrowers an understanding ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human element is unquestionably a factor in underwriting
today,'' said Oded Ben-Ami, senior loan officer for Sterling
National Mortgage, based in Great Neck, N.Y. Mr. Ben-Ami said that
while most lenders use traditional underwriting factors like
income, credit history and loan-to-value ratios to determine
whether a particular loan is acceptable, they have become more
flexible when weighing those factors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, credit-reporting bureaus usually provide
lenders a credit score for a prospective borrower. That score,
Ben-Ami said, is typically based upon a variety of factors,
including the frequency and severity of late payments, the total
amount of debt outstanding, the number of credit lines open and the
proportion of debt that is outstanding to credit available in the
form of unused credit limits on credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every factor has its own weight,'' he said, pointing out that
the last-mentioned factor _ the proportion of debt outstanding to
credit available _ is deemed quite important. ``People who are
maxed out on their credit cards are statistically regarded as
default, foreclosure or bankruptcy risks,'' Ben-Ami said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, even those who have significant
amounts of outstanding debt could be considered reasonable credit
risks if their payment history is good and their income is high
enough to allow them to continue making payments on outstanding
debt even with the additional expense of the new loan.
</P>
<P>
   And while late payments generally have a negative effect on a
borrower's credit rating, Ben-Ami said, not all late payments are
accorded the same weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're applying for a mortgage, a late mortgage payment
is the worst late payment of all,'' he said, explaining that
generally speaking, car loans and boat loans are next on the
late-payment-impact hierarchy followed by bank credit cards,
revolving charge accounts, student loans and gas credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ben-Ami said, the weight accorded to late payments can
be minimized if a reasonable explanation is provided. While every
negative item on a credit report will have a detrimental impact, he
said, explanations are always entertained.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the underwriter wants is an exculpatory explanation,''
Ben-Ami said. ``They want to hear that the problem wasn't the
borrower's fault or that it was the result of extenuating
circumstances _ like sickness or a temporary job loss _ that are no
longer a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that any items listed on a credit report as being
in collection or in ``charge-off'' status _ meaning that the lender
has either sent the matter to a collection agency or has given up
trying to collect the debt _ must be satisfied and removed from the
credit report before another lender will make a new loan.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, neither bankruptcy nor even a prior
foreclosure are absolute bars to borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standard underwriting guidelines allow for mortgages to be
approved when there's been a bankruptcy that has been discharged
for at least three years,'' he said. Foreclosures, he said,
generally require four to five years' passage, and then only with a
very good explanation. ``Foreclosure is a mortgage lender's
nightmare,'' he said. ``There is no explanation that will be
accepted without some suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ben-Ami said, the mortgage-lending market is so
competitive _ particularly in the area of ``subprime'' lending _
that given sufficient income and equity in the property being
mortgaged, along with a willingness to pay anywhere from 2 to 8
percentage points more in interest _ even borrowers with horrible
credit histories can find a lender willing to make a loan. ``There
can be a reasonable explanation for almost anything,'' Ben-Ami
said. ``And time heals all wounds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
