<HEADLINE>
PUNDITS OFTEN STUMBLE IN SEARCHING FOR MARKETS' LOGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the questionable reasons given for the stock market's
gyrations, the impeachment angle is the most specious.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's 126-point swoon by the Dow Jones Industrial
Average, a key theme developed by drive-time radio pundits
attributed the market's weakness to investor anxiety about the
impeachment vote. The prospect of a presidential ouster made
marketeers fearful, they opined.
</P>
<P>
   When the market rebounded Tuesday and the Dow recouped its
Monday loss despite intensifying momentum for impeachment, guess
what? The impeachment angle wasn't a subject for discussion when
drive-time commentators were explaining the market's resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday a reporter from The Wall Street Journal described
how the fears about impeachment ``promise to add more uncertainty
to an already volatile stock market.'' The reporter sought out four
Wall Street worthies willing to say, well ... yes ... maybe ... now
that you mention it ... impeachment might be a worrisome thing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the market had more than impeachment to worry about.
The administration decided to bomb Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here for stock market players is to keep your eye on
the ball. Even if markets move for no apparent reason, talking
heads always feel compelled to offer a reason. Nobody ever came on
the evening news to announce, ``The stock market did what it did
today for no good reason whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite bit of related humor is a cartoon with a TV anchor
saying, ``Technology stocks fluctuated wildly on rumors that
technology stocks would fluctuate wildly.''
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting is how the hot-button issues affect
explanations. Those sympathetic to the president's problems, for
instance, seem to think they can help his situation by convincing
investors that impeachment is against their best interests.
</P>
<P>
   That's just not the way the world works, however. Although the
stock market tanked the last time we had an impeachment effort,
there were about a dozen good economic reasons that explained the
market's problems better than the political troubles besetting
America.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's changed since the Nixon imbroglio. Stock prices in
normal times are mostly driven by corporate earnings. This is true
to some extent today, but with profits eroding, the market
continues to climb. Why? The Federal Reserve has taken it upon
itself to do what it must to make markets happy.
</P>
<P>
   With so much of the world in economic distress, U.S. officials
feel it's in the best interest of Americans to pursue policies that
enhance prosperity both at home and abroad. The Fed is doing its
part by tamping interest rates. This not only helps business and
consumers, but also sustains demand for stocks by making other
investments less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, though, investors will demand higher earnings
before they bid stock prices higher. Easy money is doing the job
it's supposed to do but can take the stock market only so far.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what happens in Washington will be a sideshow. While
it's true markets don't like uncertainty, impeachment concerns
don't necessarily translate into uncertainty. A Gore presidency
probably wouldn't be all that much different from a Clinton
presidency between now and 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
