<SLUG> BC-DOG-HOMECOMING-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Lost dog returns home, fulfills family's Christmas wishes  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to a 10-year-old to never give up hope at
Christmastime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to her dog to never let her down. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks Tiffany Brown wore a locket containing a picture
of her runaway dog, Sami, a female mixed breed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany had owned the dog for a little more than a year when
Sami ran away from home _ her father's Raytown house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany has lived in Overland Park with her mother, Laura Brown,
since her parents divorced. Until three months ago the dog lived
there, too, even when Tiffany left for weekends with her father,
Ray Brown. But after escaping the Overland Park yard one too many
times, Sami was taken to Raytown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the three weeks Sami was missing, Tiffany said, she never
stopped thinking: What if? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her mother and grandmother told her stories of dogs traveling
hundreds of miles to get home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany prayed each day and cried more than her share of tears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ray Brown scoured his neighborhood, put up posters, took out a
classified ad, offered a reward and called shelters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, Sami ran away from home looking for home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Laura Brown went for the paper Friday morning, Sami
scampered from the bushes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened the door and said, `Sami's home.' She came running
down crying, and even the dog was crying,'' Laura Brown said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sami spent most of the day sleeping and could barely stay awake
during a bath. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dog's journey started in northern Raytown, south of the
Truman Sports Complex, and ended near 91st Street and Antioch Road,
about a mile northeast of Oak Park Mall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been in my car riding back and forth before, but I
would never in a million years have thought this,'' Ray Brown
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using the most direct route, Sami would have traveled about 15
miles, crossing Interstate 435, State Line Road, Metcalf Avenue and
the Blue River, among other obstacles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany called Sami's return her ``best Christmas present.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the dog's new home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna keep her,'' Laura Brown said. ``She went to all
that trouble to come home. We're going to keep her.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-98 2311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981219.0357 </DOCNO>
