r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMBAT-FILM-KAN &LR;      12-19 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMBAT-FILM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ALL DUE RESPECT TO PRIVATE RYAN, FILMS CAN'T REVEAL TRUE
HORRORS OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this year, director Steven Spielberg's movie ``Saving
Private Ryan'' overran box offices, conquered critics, and was
hailed by many as ``the most realistic war film ever made.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amid the onslaught of publicity, however, Richard Snow, the
editor of American Heritage magazine, took a deep breath and
decided that the whole phenomenon was worth a closer look. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we should publish something that carefully examined
both the reaction to `Ryan' and the sudden return of World War II
movies,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a qualified writer, Snow called one of his magazine's
contributing editors, Roger J. Spiller, the George C. Marshall
Professor of Military History at Fort Leavenworth's Command and
General Staff College. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger has thought longer and more intelligently about war than
anyone I know,'' said Snow. ``So I asked him to write an essay
placing `Ryan' in some perspective. At first, though, Roger was
bridling at the idea.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Spiller said recently, he had no desire to see the film
at all. He had been ``thoroughly chilled'' by the pre-release
publicity campaign that claimed ``Ryan'' had accomplished what no
movie had done before _ that in its first 30 minutes alone, it had
captured the true nature of combat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The combat experience is a problem I've been studying for 20
years,'' Spiller said, ``and I didn't want to see it trivialized
yet again. Too many Americans already confuse Hollywood films with
reality. Most of the critics who cheered `Private Ryan,' based
their appraisals on other war movies. I didn't want to be part of
that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow, however, wouldn't be put off. ``I really hectored Roger
until he acquiesced,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost unspoken between the two men was the assumption that
although the article's ``hook'' would be an assessment of ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' Spiller's essay would range far beyond that
critique. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it as a chance to say something substantial about combat
and the popular misconceptions that surround it,'' Spiller said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I began studying war because it is the greatest curse mankind
experiences. And combat is the /{sine qua non/} of warfare _ its
dark, essential heart. It is a subject that has not been
particularly well-handled by either military historians or movie
makers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spiller, 54, a soft-spoken, courtly man, began the task of
examining ``Ryan'' knowing that any significant criticism he made
of the film would be controversial. But he is no stranger to
intellectual conflict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, for example, in a special issue of /{American
Heritage/}, Spiller literally invited controversy by asserting that
the most overrated of all American generals was Robert E. Lee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate commander, he wrote, may have epitomized
gentlemanly style and conduct, but he ``was also a traitor to his
countrywho led his side from calamity to calamity.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The furious reaction to Spiller's essay surprised even a
seasoned editor like Snow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God,'' he said recently, ``it produced the most mail of
anything we've ever done. The only way we could surpass that
response would be to print an essay on the most overrated
Savior.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the enraged letter writers shared a common set of
assumptions about Spiller. He was, they stated, a wimpy, elitist,
Northeastern, pot-smoking weirdo who knew nothing about war and had
never heard a shot fired in anger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spiller, a connoisseur of misconception, quietly savored the
irony. For he is a native Texan, the son of a Texas Ranger. And he
is an Air Force veteran who has indeed heard shots ``fired in
anger.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He earned his doctorate at Louisiana State University, where he
studied military history under Pulitzer-prize winning historian T.
Harry Williams (author of /{Lincoln and his Generals/}). And in
addition to teaching at the Army's command college, he has also
served as ``personal historian'' to the chief of staff of the U.S.
Army. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lee controversy didn't ruffle him. That dispute was a mere
squall compared to the far more substantive storm Spiller created
in 1988 when he attacked a vaunted theory first propounded by Brig.
Gen. S.L.A. ``Slam'' Marshall, one of the Army's most revered
historians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's 1947 treatise /{Men Against Fire/} contained the
alarming claim that during World War II, no more than 25 percent of
the U.S. infantrymen engaged in combat actually fired their
weapons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's data, or so he stated, had been obtained while
debriefing hundreds of combat infantry units. And his shocking
conclusion, neatly cocooned in the phrase ``ratio of fire,'' was
quickly accepted by the military. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then along came Spiller, who in 1988 published a
myth-shattering essay in the London-based /{Journal of the Royal
United Services Institute/}, considered by many the most
prestigious military-affairs publication in the English-speaking
world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it succinctly,'' Spiller said recently, ``I wrote that
Marshall `cooked' his numbers. I could find no evidence that he did
any real field work on the subject at all. I think he believed his
assertion, but he didn't have the data so he simply made it up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spiller's discovery, reported on the front page of the /{New
York Times/}, knocked the theory on its ear, and further convinced
Spiller himself that the combat experience was tragically
misunderstood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With that background, Spiller approached his assessment of
``Saving Private Ryan.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In some ways he was surprised. ``I thought it was a good film,''
he said. ``Not hands-down the best war film ever made, not even the
best film about World War II, but a good film made with honorable
intent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His reservations about Hollywood's depiction of combat, however,
remained unchanged. And those feelings are clearly reflected in his
essay, ``War in the Dark,'' slated for publication in the February
issue of /{American Heritage/}. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The essay's ironic title refers not to night combat but to the
curious assumption that war can be understood by someone seated in
the darkened comfort of a movie theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``An impossibility,'' Spiller said. ``A movie can't tell you
what it smelled like or sounded like or really felt like at Omaha
Beach. And it can't begin to convey the fear and despair
experienced by combat soldiers who come to believe their daily hell
is endless.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conversation, Spiller cited a similar conclusion
reached by movie director Samuel Fuller, a combat veteran who
landed at Omaha Beach on D-Day with the 1st Infantry Division.
Fuller later made an acclaimed film titled ``The Big Red One''
based on his unit's experience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the kind of publicity drummed up to promote
``Saving Private Ryan,'' though, Fuller was unusually candid about
the inherent shortcomings of any war movie, including his own. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``To do it right,'' he told Time magazine in 1984, ``you'd have
to blind the audience with smoke, deafen them with noise, then
shoot one of them in the shoulder to scare the rest of them to
death.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between real war and the Hollywood version was
starkly illustrated, said Spiller, by the experience of hundreds of
combat photographers who risked their lives throughout World War II
trying to capture the essence of combat on film. They discovered
that true battlefield scenes bore no resemblance to the way
Hollywood depicted them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So a question worth asking,'' Spiller writes in his upcoming
essay, ``is how we came to think we know more about war than we
actually do?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer, he writes, is that we believe what we see in the
movies. And that disturbs him, for such misconceptions have
consequences. To illustrate, Spiller cites the remarkable impact
World War II films had on their audiences. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, when young Marines were queried about their reasons for
enlisting, fully 50 percent said it was because of their respect
for John Wayne in ``The Sands of Iwo Jima.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the Vietnam War, one veteran told a researcher: ``I saw
them World War II movies. I thought war was glorious, I thought it
was glamorous. Why didn't someone tell us different? Why didn't
someone tell?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And that yawning gulf between ``Disneyfied combat'' and the real
thing gnaws at Spiller. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What readers will find in Roger's essay,'' said American
Heritage editor Snow, ``is his passionate belief that combat is a
profound and terrible human mystery, and you can't presume to learn
much about it by suffering through the first half hour of a
Hollywood film.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
