<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-SOUNDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDS OF SPORTS READILY IDENTIFIABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen.
</P>
<P>
   Close your eyes, and concentrate. There's a game going on. Which
sport is it? Just listen. The ears will supply the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The staccato pop-pop-pop-pop of plastic on plastic in several
small, violent collisions? It must be a football game.
</P>
<P>
   The high-pitched squeak of rubber on wood, repeated in quick,
irregular intervals? It must be a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   The crunch of steel cutting into ice? Hockey.
</P>
<P>
   The loud, reverberating crack of wood striking cowhide?
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The thwack of club striking ball? Golf. The strum of strings
striking ball? Tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Each sport has its own unique sounds that instantly identify the
game. Each sport has sounds that when you close your eyes, you can
tell what game is being played.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a visceral level, sound is very important,'' said Dr. Phil
Anthony, a Fort Worth otologist, a specialist in medicine dealing
with the ear and its disorders. ``The pop of the pads tells you a
whole lot more what happened from the stands than seeing there was
a tackle made. I wouldn't hesitate to say that sound is a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Put a blindfold on athletes and coaches, and play the games.
They can tell you what's going on just by the sounds of sport.
Football: The hits parade The sound of pro football is the sound of
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pads and helmets colliding against each other,''
Cowboys safety Omar Stoutmire said. ``You hear that, you know
there's a football game going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Those noises occur every time the ball is snapped, along with
the guttural sounds of large men trying to outmuscle each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear that, and you know what sport it is,'' Cowboys
receiver Patrick Jeffers said. ``That's a distinct sound, all the
grunting and groaning between the big meat up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Less common, but just as distinctive, is the sound of a
linebacker leveling a running back or a safety smacking a receiver
coming over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hollow, helmet-to-helmet collision that you hear every so
often,'' Cowboys fullback Daryl Johnston said. ``You know that
somebody's just experienced a big hit. It's a very definite sound.
You usually get a lot of oohs from the crowd, and it'll get the
players to turn their heads to see and make sure everybody's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Punter Toby Gowin's ears are attuned to the sound of foot
striking leather.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell if there's a good pop on the ball,'' he said.
``If they don't hit it clean you can't hear it. It's a kind of a
slap. When you hear the thump, you know that someone's hit the ball
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also more subtle sounds, such as a receiver gathering in
a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the sound of a Troy Aikman bullet hitting you in the
shoulder pads and knocking the wind out of you, and the sound when
you catch a ball clean,'' Jeffers said. ``You can hardly hear it;
it's just that little thunk sound. As a receiver, you love to hear
that sound when you just pick it clean.'' Hockey: Ooohh Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock waxes poetic when talking about the sounds of his
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you hear is the swoosh of the skates, the
cutting of steel blades to fresh ice,'' he said. ``That sound is
unmistakable.''
</P>
<P>
   Every hockey player makes that sound when striding up the ice.
But those who really know the sport can recognize differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really hear powerful skaters,'' said Hitchcock, who
includes Mike Modano in that group. ``They have a sound to their
skating that's really recognizable. They have a different sound
than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruising defenseman Derian Hatcher also has a favorite noise,
but it has nothing to do with skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like hearing it when you hit someone and you hear them
grunt, or you hear them go `ooohh,''' Hatcher said. ``I like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Only those close to the hit can hear the grunt, but there are
other sounds that tell the tale of a physical game, sounds like
bodies crashing into the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the whole building shakes,'' Hitchcock said. ``The
most dynamic hitting sounds are the mid-ice collisions. They are
sounds that just wake up both teams.'' Baseball: Pillow talk
America's pastime offers a feast for the auditory sense.
</P>
<P>
   On the field there's the sharp crack of the bat at the
professional level, or the ugly ding of metal at the amateur level.
There's the pop of a fastball into the catcher's mitt, the calls of
the umpires, the chatter of the infielders.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates notices the sound of bat hitting
ball more during batting practice than during games, and he notices
the sound of a Juan Gonzalez drive more than that of Mark
McLemore's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You notice the difference,'' Oates said. ``Even when they both
hit it well, there's a different sound of a power hitter as opposed
to a line-drive type guy. When Juan hits the ball you know it's
going to go farther. The impact, his strength, you know it's a
totally different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The pop of the ball into the catcher's mitt has something to do
with the velocity the pitcher puts on it, but more to do with the
type of glove used.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old-time mitts with no break, you can't make it make a
sound,'' said Oates, a former catcher. ``It's like catching with a
pillow. But when Pudge \RIvan Rodriguez\S catches the ball, you can
just toss it and he can make it pop.'' Basketball: Squeaking havoc
There is basketball being played at the Landry Center, where the
Mavericks would be practicing if there was no lockout. It might be
a pickup game, but it's still basketball.
</P>
<P>
   How can Mavericks forward Samaki Walker tell?
</P>
<P>
   ``The squeaking of the shoes and the bouncing of the ball,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The high-pitched squeaking is unmistakable as players stop and
start on the hardwood floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks guard Steve Nash can close his eyes and tell the
quality of the game by the sound of the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hear all the shoes on the floor squeaking, you know
it's a serious game,'' he said. ``If you just hear a couple, it's
probably half-hearted.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other sounds. The rhythmic pounding of the ball in the
hands of a guard, the soft swish of a jumper hitting nothing but
net, the ball kissing the backboard on a bank shot, and the
rim-rattling force of a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``A power dunk is definitely a hard, quick sound,'' Walker said.
``It sounds like power. A soft dunk is not as hard. It may be
pretty, but it's not as hard.'' Auto racing: Good vibrations A
full-throated, racing engine is an assault on the ears. It's pure
power. It sounds like speed. It sounds, well, incredibly loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound is something that's always there,'' said former
Indy-car driving star Johnny Rutherford. ``It's part of the action.
It's part of what the fans like. The sound not only pierces the
ears, but it's a resonance on the body. That's part of what fans
like particularly about stock cars because they are so loud. It
almost vibrates inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Within that noise, though, there are subtleties. An expert like
Rutherford can distinguish between a Winston Cup stock car and the
open-wheeled cars of the Indy Racing League and Championship Auto
Racing Teams series just by the sound of the engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have their different characteristics,'' he said.
``The Cup car is a throaty, V-8 sound. It's a thump. You can tell
listening to it at speed what it is. The CART cars are
turbo-charged and turn a lot more RPMs, so they've got the
high-pitched whine to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are other, not-so-pleasant sounds associated with
auto racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are the bone-chilling sounds of the tires squealing in a
slide,'' Rutherford said. ``It's not common, but when you hear it,
it's scary. Or when you're listening to a car run and suddenly it
goes silent and then you hear the thump. You know exactly what
happened.'' Tennis: String music A tightly strung racket hitting a
felt-covered ball sounds like a symphony to Tut Bartzen, who has
heard that form of music going on 50 years. And the retiredTCU
coach and current director of the Mary Potishman Lard tennis center
in Fort Worth can tell the variances in the game via the sounds of
his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two baseliners playing, you're going to hear longer
intervals between hits,'' Bartzen said. ``It's going to be very
much like a metronome. It's going to be very predictable when the
contact with the ball is, because the players strive to get the
same interval between the bounce and the contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hear a different tempo, where the intervals are much
shorter, you've got one guy coming in behind the serve or the
return of serve. And in doubles, you're going to have rapid-fire,
and without looking you could tell there's more than two guys out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound won't just tell when the ball is hit, but what kind of
a shot it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you hear that ball hit, you definitely know if it's
a finesse stroke, or a medium-pace ball or a very hard ball,''
Bartzen said. ``It would also indicate how much spin there is on
the ball by the sound of it. A ball that's spinning doesn't have a
clean impact. It's more of a brushing the strings across the ball.
It's a whole different sound.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also different sounds associated with different
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``On grass you have almost no sound,'' Barzten said. ``Hard
court, you definitely hear it. On carpet indoors, it's like
bouncing it on a rug. You don't hear as much. On clay, you
definitely hear the ball hitting because it tends to skid on the
dirt.'' Golf: Heavy metal Brian Mahon is the head professional at
the Hank Haney Golf Center at City Place, near downtown Dallas. He
hears the sound of clubs striking balls again and again, day after
day.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to be looking to know the quality of the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solid shots have kind of a sharper, crisper sound to them,''
he said. ``Off-center hits tend to have a bit of a clunky sound to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That sound has been basic to the sport since Scots invented the
game. But as technology has changed the clubs, so has it altered
the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanium definitely has a different sound than the original
steel heads did,'' Mahon said. ``That was a tremendous difference
in sound going from the old wooden heads to steel. Now a wooden
head sounds strange, because everybody uses steel or titanium.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to tournament golf there's another sound, that of
the gallery. And those sounds differ depending on the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the major championships have a different sound to
them,'' Mahon said. ``The Masters is such a hallowed ground, and
the crowd size is limited somewhat. The people are more respectful,
just glad to be there. They don't necessarily roar as loudly as
they do at other tournaments. The U.S. Open and PGA don't limit
ticket sales as much, and all kinds of people tend to go. You've
got a loud, raucous crowd. The British Open is very polite, very
traditional. You get more of a polite clap and not as much of a
loud roar.''
</P>
<P>
   There are unique sounds associated with other sports. The
thundering hoofbeats of horses straining for the finish line. The
furious splashing of swimmers. The thud of a gymnast's feet landing
after a dismount. The crash of pins after being struck by a bowling
ball. The violent thump of foot striking leather in soccer. The
rapid-fire clack of paddles hitting plastic in table tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Close your eyes. Listen.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds of sport will tell the tale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
