<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARIZ-OFFICE-REAL-650(     12-19 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-OFFICE-REAL-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $500-MILLION MIXED PROJECT FOR PHOENIX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla. )  (js) 
 By STEVE BERGSMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Construction has begun on the first new office
building in eight years in downtown Phoenix, the initial phase of a
$500-million mixed-use complex with 1.5 million square feet of
office space.
</P>
<P>
   The building will rise on land acquired as the result of an
exchange with the federal government two years ago of 108,000 acres
in Florida for 106 acres here once occupied by a school for Indian
children.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix site was acquired in 1996 by Barron Collier Co. of
Naples, Fla., which traded to the government South Florida wetlands
and scrub-pine property that it had owned since the early 1900s for
the old Phoenix Indian School property in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   It then traded 75 acres of that property to the city for 7.4
acres downtown; Barron Collier retained 15 acres, and donated the
rest to the Veterans Hospital adjoining the site. The city will
create a park with its land and the government will add the South
Florida acreage to the Big Cypress National Preserve adjacent to
the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed-use Collier Center is a joint venture of Barron
Collier and Opus West Corp. of Phoenix, a regional developer.
Barron Collier is a family-owned holding company primarily involved
in real estate development, oil and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The project, whose first phase is expected to be completed in
2001, will include three 500,000-square-foot office towers and, in
a separate building, a major convention hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase includes a 1,500-space, three-level, below-grade
parking garage in a 520,000-square-foot office tower anchored by
Bank of America, as well as a two-story complex offering 85,000
rentable square feet of retail and restaurant space.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America will take 200,000 square feet for its
Arizona-Nevada headquarters and Quarles &AMP; Brady, a Phoenix law
firm, will move to downtown from midtown and lease 40,000 square
feet in the building. The office space is 45 percent preleased,
said Thomas Roberts, president of Opus West, with retail 60 percent
preleased. Palomino, a West Coast restaurant chain, will be among
the tenants moving into the retail space, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a core base of law firms, banks and accounting firms
that occupy space downtown, and potentially a lot of midtown
tenants could move back downtown over the next five years,'' said
Roberts, who is also managing partner of Opus Collier, a joint
venture developer. In the '80s, many companies migrated to midtown,
where a rash of new buildings rose in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Opus West, the project's general contractor, has built more than
16 million square feet of office, industrial and retail space
throughout the West. The center was designed through a joint effort
of Opus Architects &AMP; Engineers, Jerde Partnership of Venice,
Calif., and Langdon Wilson Architecture of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Collier Center development was supposed to have started this
summer on the heels of the opening of downtown's Bank One Ballpark,
the new home of the Arizona Diamondbacks, but commercial lending
tightened. The developers scrambled through the summer to find
financing and eventually secured a $115 million construction loan
from Bank of America. Finally, on Nov. 10, ground was turned
marking the beginning of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Turmoil in the capital markets also caused problems with the
Collier Center's attempt to attract a third major convention hotel
to downtown Phoenix. Westin Hotels had signed a letter of intent to
move into the complex in the first phase, but Westin has not yet
secured its financing. ``If we can't come to terms with Westin, we
will be looking at other hotel companies,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Collier Center is a welcome addition to the ongoing
``renaissance of downtown Phoenix,'' said Jerry Colangelo,
president of the Arizona Diamondbacks baseball and Phoenix Suns
basketball teams, who was an architect of the so-called
renaissance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Colangelo opened the first downtown sports venue, the
$90 million America West Arena, to house his original sports
franchise, the Phoenix Suns. The arena, along with an office-retail
complex called the Arizona Center designed by Rouse Co. that opened
in 1990, are considered the two original pillars of this city's
downtown revitalization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The area had been devoid of cultural, entertainment and shopping
activities until these projects came along. To make matters worse,
office tenants had been drifting toward midtown and the trendier
Camelback Corridor to the northeast. Downtown was also in danger of
losing one of its biggest companies, Arizona Public Service, the
state's largest utility.
</P>
<P>
   ``If APS decided to move out of downtown, any plans of
revitalization would have been shot,'' says James B. Fijan, a
senior vice president with CB Richard Ellis in Phoenix. ``But they
decided to stay and go over to the Arizona Center and that kicked
off that whole project'' _ two office buildings and 120,000 square
feet of retail built around a park-like setting.
</P>
<P>
   While there's still a lot of retail at the Arizona Center, most
of the space has been turned over to restaurants and pubs. It has
been a night and weekend draw since it opened. That complex was
capped off this year with the opening of an AMC 24-screen movie
theater, the first theaters in downtown in over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   America West Arena was the second building block for downtown
revitalization. Not only has it become home to the Phoenix Suns,
but it is also residence to the Phoenix Coyotes professional hockey
team, the Arizona Rattlers indoor football team and the Phoenix
Mercury of the Women's National Basketball Association, plus
countless concerts and special events. The arena was home to 219
event nights in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown revitalization is like fitting together pieces of a
puzzle,'' says Margaret Mullen, executive director of the Downtown
Phoenix Partnership, a business improvement district. ``If you have
pieces missing, the picture is never complete. We could have had a
revitalization without the ballpark or the arena, but we needed one
or the other. We needed one major sports venue downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Ballpark attracted 3.6 million baseball fans into
downtown over the course of the Diamondbacks' inaugural season this
year. New pubs and restaurants are opening near the stadium, which
also happened when the America West Arena began operations. From
1989 to 1997, licenses to bars, restaurants, hotels and retail
jumped from 154 to 248, while downtown taxable revenues leaped from
$56.8 million to $127.4 million, according to the Downtown Phoenix
Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Symphony Hall, downtown now has three other
theaters and auditoriums for plays and concerts, including a new
Herberger Theater and the restored Orpheum and Union Hall. The $48
million Arizona Science Center, which includes a planetarium,
opened last year.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown office vacancy through the third quarter ran 12.7
percent, reports Grubb &AMP; Ellis in Phoenix. Most of that was Class C
property. Class A property carries a healthy 5.29 percent vacancy
rate and Class B, 12.78 percent. Net absorption in downtown totaled
70,584 square feet in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown boasts 4.8 million square feet of space out of 43.3
million in the whole metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Residential development may become another phase of downtown
growth. BRE Properties, a San Francisco real estate investment
trust, announced earlier this year that it would begin renovating
the old Title &AMP; Trust Building into apartments. First constructed
in 1931, the seven-story building is now the only vacant historic
structure in downtown, but a $13 million renovation is to turn it
into 90 apartments, including a 2,100-square-foot penthouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
