<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-JONSSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEAD INJURY SENDS JONSSON HOME FOR EXAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kenny Jonsson, the Islanders' top defenseman
and best all-round player, sustained what appeared to be his second
concussion in a month during Friday night's 2-2 tie with the
Anaheim Mighty Ducks when Travis Green clipped him on the head with
a flying elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson, who was making his fourth appearance after missing
eight games with post-concussion syndrome, was retrieving the puck
from behind the Islanders' goal in the first period when Green
charged toward him, his elbow up. Green's arm collided with
Jonsson's head, immediately dropping the defenseman to the ice.
Jonsson lay motionless as several of his teammates rushed Green, a
former Islander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a headache right away,'' said Jonsson, who returned to
Long Island Saturday. ``That was the only symptom I had. We were
concerned because I just came off of a concussion.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, there was some confusion as to the extent of
Jonsson's injury. Early reports from the locker room were that
Jonsson, who had been examined by a Mighty Ducks doctor, had
sustained another concussion. But more than an hour later, an
Islanders spokesman said Jonsson merely had a headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with Kenny during the second period,'' Dr. Eliot
Pellman, the Islanders' director of medical services, said from
Long Island. ``He suffered a headache as a result of the hit. We do
not have enough information to determine whether Kenny suffered a
concussion or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who played six seasons for the Islanders before being
traded to the Ducks late last season, was not penalized for the
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travis took advantage of someone who was against the ropes,''
Mike Milbury, the Islanders' coach and general manager, said. ``I
don't know what day they come to Long Island, but it's going to be
interesting. It was a cheap shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbury added: ``He's gutless. That's why he's not wearing an
Islander uniform anymore. He got overpaid, and that's my own
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbury planned to send a videotape of the incident to Colin
Campbell, the National Hockey League disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing Mike says surprises me,'' said Green, who angered
Milbury by holding out for two straight years when he played for
the Islanders. ``I'm not going to stoop to Mike's level. I'm not
out there trying to hurt guys. It was a clean hit. He had his head
down and I was coming to finish my check. What am I going to do,
stop?''
</P>
<P>
   The sight of Jonsson laying on the ice, his hands on his head,
was what everyone feared. Because the Islanders have yet to prove
they can compete without Jonsson, who logs more ice time than any
other Islander and is a stabilizing force on the blue line, the
power play and the penalty kill. Of the eight games Jonsson missed
with the first concussion, by no coincidence, the Islanders lost
seven.
</P>
<P>
   And by no coincidence, the game turned nasty after Jonsson's
injury. Many Islanders took exception to Green's elbow, which
appeared to have been thrown late and when Jonsson's head was down.
Rich Pilon, the Islanders' toughest defenseman, took special
exception. For the remainder of the game, Pilon zeroed in on the
Ducks' star players, Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne. Pilon drilled
Kariya, who missed most of last season with post-concussion
syndrome several times and hit Selanne so hard his helmet came off
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a hard check,'' Pilon said. ``Kenny
definitely was not in a position to protect himself. When he was
out there, I was definitely looking for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilon added: ``Green is not an Islander anymore. Kenny is.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Jonsson spoiled any satisfaction the Islanders may
have received from getting their fifth point in three games on
their West Coast swing, which concludes Sunday afternoon at Phoenix
against the Coyotes.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
