<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CHARITY-GAME-NYT &LR;      12-19 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CHARITY-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3-POINTERS, PREDICTIONS AND BOREDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. &UR;  &LR; _ Patrick Ewing and Charles Barkley played
a casual game of one-on-one, trading taunts and missed jump shots.
Glen Rice threw up errant &UR;  &LR; 3-pointers a few feet from midcourt,
trying to guide the shots in with body English. Sitting on the
sideline, Dan Majerle and Karl Malone looked bored.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that locked-out National Basketball Association players
do indeed have a lot of free time on their hands, 16 of the game's
current and former stars showed up for the morning shoot-around
Saturday &UR;  &LR; at the Atlantic City Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Their charity game at 9 Saturday night on Showtime was the first
organized basketball many of them had played in more than six
months. Amid the usual hype for such an event was the specter of a
lost season approaching quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern had just made some more strong comments
about that possibility, but none of the players seemed concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to do it, do it,'' Gary Payton said. ``If he
cancels the season, he cancels the season. He's going to hurt
himself and he's going to hurt us and the fans will be hurt, so
that would be crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said: ``Everyone wants to make it seem like a false sense
of security on the players' behalf. I think it will end in the next
week. Sometimes when it's Christmas, you're in a giving mood. We've
been doing it all summer; maybe it's their turn now.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice before the game drew fewer than 100 fans to the
12,500-seat auditorium. One middle-age woman, seated five rows from
the court, took the opportunity to nap.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of fewer than 7,000 was in the building before the
tip-off, including hundreds of children who had received free
tickets. Game organizers said hours before the game that 8,000
tickets had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   The small turnout at the morning practice made it easy for
Barkley to hold court again. As is his custom, he sounded off on a
variety of subjects, from the lockout to Michael Jordan's possible
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about a lot of money,'' Barkley said. ``The owners are
greedy and the players are greedy. I can sympathize with both. I
don't care about either one of them. I just want it to get resolved
because it's not good for the game of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Jordan, he said: ``Michael is done. He doesn't want to give
anyone mixed messages. I've been telling you guys for three months
that he's not playing. He's had enough. He's done everything. He
made his last shot to win the world championship. What more do you
need? Let the man enjoy the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did not attend the game, though it was co-promoted by his
agent, David Falk. Jordan, who has promised not to decide whether
to retire until after the lockout is over, was playing in a golf
tournament in La Quinta, Calif. His failure to attend hurt the
proceeds of Saturday night's game, which was to benefit Unicef,
Save the Children and a group of Philadelphia-based charities.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets were sold for between $25 and $500. Because Atlantic
City traditionally slows down between Thanksgiving and Christmas,
it was unclear how much interest the game had actually generated.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people can afford $500 around Christmas?'' Barkley
said. ``This is obviously not a big basketball market, so we should
have tried to lower the ticket prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, each player was well received during pre-game
introductions, but only a few players appeared to be in game shape.
As to the quality of basketball that would be played with no NBA
training camp for any of the players, expectations were not high.
Shawn Kemp showed up perhaps 30 pounds over his playing weight,
looking like a bookend forward instead of a svelte, skywalking
All-Star. And Ewing also needed to shed a few pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller, though, has not put on an ounce. He has boasted
that he will show the rest of the league's marksmen who the best
shooter is. Whether he would get that chance in a few weeks was
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   With no negotiations planned, the only sure thing anyone could
take solace in was Barkley's talking and campaigning for another
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks are a team I would consider,'' he said, admitting
that he had illegally contacted teams during the lockout. ``I like
the Knicks. I would love to play with Patrick and Allan Houston.
The addition of Marcus Camby is going to really help. The Knicks
are solid. I think there are five or six teams that could win the
championship. Unfortunately for me, all six want me.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
