<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--ANDERSON-HNS &LR;      12-19 2084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ANDERSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Anderson's drug arrest demonstrates dangers of letting down guard
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Suddenly everything was clear. Everything Greg ``Cadillac''
Anderson should have seen long before, every question he should
have asked, every ``no'' he now knew he should have said had become
clear in a flash as if the triggers surrounding him had been
pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Epiphany came in the form of an FBI pistol pressed to the side
of his head, his hands pulled behind his back. And as Anderson,
just a few weeks removed from his 10th NBA season stretched out on
the hotel room floor, his face pressed against the carpet, he never
felt so foolish, so beaten, so alone.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had let himself be drawn into a drug deal. For no
reason other than as a favor, he gambled everything he had worked
for and lost. He never saw the risk, never realized when friendship
turned to setup and finally to disaster. He never considered the
potential for prison that now is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 20, Anderson and three others pleaded guilty to
possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, an offense that
could bring a maximum penalty of 40 years in prison. Federal
sentencing guidelines in Anderson's case call for 37 to 46 months
in prison and there is reason to hope for less time. But prison is
virtually certain. There is no chance for parole in a federal drug
case.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson pleaded guilty because he said there was no denying
that he was. His crime, he said, was his fault. His fate, he
accepts, is now out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like, if you did it, you did it,'' Anderson said.
``They caught me red-handed. I could have said `no.' I could have
stopped this. But I didn't. I'm not in a state of thinking, Why did
this happen? I should have been saying that before it happened. I
should have said a lot of things before it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There was a time Anderson blamed someone else. He was prone on
the casino hotel room floor filled with drug money, the room
crowded with FBI agents, his body shaking when he turned toward the
man he had considered a friend who had turned from drug dealer to
government informant and asked, ``Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you do this to me,'' Anderson pleaded. ``What have you
gotten me into.''
</P>
<P>
   When it all began, Anderson, 34, had no intention of getting
into anything. A former Worthing High School and University of
Houston star who played for the Atlanta Hawks last season, Anderson
was used to being approached by fans who would try to become his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson went out by himself on a Friday night to Atlanta Live,
a popular nightclub in the Buckhead section of Atlanta. That night
early in 1998, he met Howard Hill, a drug dealer from Biloxi,
Miss., and Anthony Bates, an FBI informant apparently assigned to
investigate Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody goes there, a lot of the pro athletes and people who
come to town,'' Anderson said. ``I was sitting there having a cold
beer. They knew who I was. We were laughing, joking, teasing
people. They seemed pretty cool. They told me they were from out of
town so I invited the guys to the game on Sunday. I invited a lot
of people to games and gave them tickets. But one thing led to
another. They came back again and wanted to hang out. We exchanged
phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hung around. We laughed, talked, cracked jokes. If you're
a pro athlete, you're either going to go out with a lot of friends,
or you're going to go out and probably meet a lot of friends.
Normally when you meet people out like that, somebody may want to
buy you a beer and then go about their way. It was a strange
introduction. They kind of hung around I guess to see what females
they could pick up around me or see what other stars they could
meet. At that time of the evening, nothing else dawned on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates and Hill returned to Atlanta throughout March and April.
Anderson invited them to shootarounds and games, introduced them to
teammates Tyrone Corbin and Anthony Miller.
</P>
<P>
   They went out to eat after practices, and to the clubs at night.
When Anderson did wonder about what sort of jobs could allow Bates
and Hill time to hang around Atlanta and money to spend with an NBA
veteran, an answer was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got kind of curious and asked what kind of work they did,''
Anderson said. ``One of the guys said they were offshore. I know
people who go offshore for two weeks, and are home for two weeks,
so it didn't dawn on me they were doing anything illegal. I know
people here (in Houston) and in Louisiana that go offshore 14 days
at a time, and will be off the same amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson does not know if he was targeted. Hill could have been
seeking a drug connection in Houston, or even entry to the circles
of an NBA veteran. Because he also pleaded guilty and did not have
a trial, that information is not available in public records.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Hawks lost to Charlotte in the first round of the
NBA playoffs, Anderson and Miller stopped in Biloxi on the way to
Houston to see Bates and Hill on May 5. After Miller left the
group, with Anderson's confidence long since assured, Bates and
Hill told Anderson they sold drugs in Mississippi and began asking
if Anderson could introduce them to a cocaine supplier in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started asking me if I knew people,'' Anderson said.
``They told me they do this and do that and I told them it's not my
type of life. But where I grew up, I've seen it. I've never been
involved in it before, but I've seen it. They asked me if I knew
any people back home. But they kept asking me and asking me if I
knew somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when Anderson arrived in Houston, his estranged
wife had moved out, taking their four children and most of their
possessions. A week later, Hill and Bates arrived in Houston and
Anderson introduced them to Kevin Blackmon, an acquaintance he had
assumed could be a drug connection for his friends from
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back home, my family was gone,'' Anderson said.
``I came back home to a house that wasn't like I left it.
Everything just moved too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I introduced them to a guy I knew, Kevin Blackmon. We liked
cars, drag racing. We all had the same cars (Chevrolet Impala SS).
We were friends since growing up. He was a good guy. I hate that I
got him involved. I hate that I got myself involved. If I knew
these guys better, it wouldn't have happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't really know each other. They knew me from hanging
out in Atlanta. Kevin knew me from hanging out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he introduced a drug buyer to a seller, Anderson _ offered
no more than a $1,000 finder's fee for his role in the scheme _ was
likely guilty of conspiracy to distribute a controlled substance.
Blackmon sold a kilo of cocaine to Hill, who left his car in
Anderson's driveway in Houston as collateral, further involving
Anderson in a drug transaction.
</P>
<P>
   When Hill and an associate, Kevin Porter, brought the drugs to
Mississippi, agents arrested them, in possession of 16 bags of
cocaine, at a traffic stop set up by Bates and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hill agreed to work with the FBI to further implicate Anderson,
and began calling him daily to come to Biloxi to pick up Blackmon's
money, saying his son was diabetic and in the hospital and that he
couldn't leave Mississippi. By then, every phone conversation with
Hill was recorded to further implicate Anderson, but a drug deal
was set up in a Mississippi hotel, the Grand Casino Bayview where
the FBI set up surveillance equipment and waited for Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Hill picked up Anderson at the airport, and brought him to the
hotel. Once there, in the room and scenario set up by the FBI, he
gave Anderson the $26,000 and told him someone would join them in
the room to buy the last few ounces of cocaine. Anderson said he
protested. But with one last chance to refuse, to show he knew
better, he didn't. Within seconds, officers crashed into the room,
Anderson holding $26,000 in drug money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Get on the ground with your face down,''' Anderson
said. ``With guns in your face, you don't have any choice. It was a
legitimate rush. It was scary. I never had anybody come in on me
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared. Here I am in Biloxi, Miss. I know nobody but
Hill. And something like this happens. I try not to (think about
it). That was the worst night of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He waived his right to an attorney, rapidly admitting his
involvement in the drug deal. He agreed to implicate Blackmon, just
as Hill had implicated him. When he did hire an attorney, Tim
Johnson of Houston, a case for entrapment was considered, but ruled
out because Anderson had so willingly introduced a drug buyer to a
seller to traffic in drugs, and because he so thoroughly had
admitted his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson pleaded guilty sure he would go to prison.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Anderson doesn't know why he did not even consider the peril to
which he so rapidly thrust himself. He has no prior drug arrests,
insists he has no financial problems having made roughly $7 million
in his NBA career, $272,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up working,'' Anderson said. ``Since I was 7 years old,
I had yards to cut. My dad and my mom instilled that in me and in
all my sisters and brothers. I had my bicycle with a string
attached to a mower. I was always independent. I used to fix my own
bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time went on, I always worked and had my own car. When I
was in the ninth grade I had a car the old guy down the street sold
me for a dollar. It wasn't anything but a fuel pump. Once I got to
high school, I worked to have my own car, a Delta 88, '71. All
through college I worked in the offseason because I knew in order
to have what you want, you have to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony that he had fallen into the shortcut he had always
avoided, and never needed, was unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows,'' he said, ``anybody can make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, he will become an NBA cautionary tale, a name
used as warning. He said he is comfortable with that, believing,
``To people who know me, I'm still known for what I did (in
basketball). For those who look at me for what happened on the bad
side, may God bless them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing was originally scheduled for Feb. 9, but Anderson was
granted a motion to continue sentencing to May 19 to allow him to
play this basketball season in the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   But that deal fell through and the judge in the case, Walter J.
Gex III, could choose to go ahead with the sentencing Feb. 9 when
Hill, Porter and Blackmon are scheduled to be sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Anderson has prepared. He said he spends little time
thinking about the sentence he might receive or his likely time in
prison. He said friends and former teammates have been unfailingly
supportive.
</P>
<P>
   But before Thanksgiving, he told his four children, Greg Jr. 11,
Gabriel, 9, Geia 8, and Geremy 3. It was, he said, the toughest day
since his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't scare them. I just told them, `Daddy did a bad
thing,''' Anderson said. ``How do you tell kids? It was a mistake I
don't want them to make in their lives. It was hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love me as their daddy, Greg Anderson Sr., they look at
me as their father, whether I'm in the NBA or a truck driver.
They're understanding kids. They're Christian kids. They know it
was a mistake, something I did wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson admits that. Accepting responsibility is one of the
considerations in the federal sentencing guidelines. But Anderson
contends there is no use denying his ``mistakes,'' confident what
he did is not who he is. He also will not spend his time thinking
about the transgressions of his past or agonizing about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a state of thinking, Why did this happen?''
Anderson said. ``I should have been saying that before it happened.
Sometimes you don't know what the outcome is going to be. I think
about that. But I don't let that drag me down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have people asking, `Are you all right, are you
OK?' I'm OK. A lot of people are surprised. One of my friends I
hadn't talked to since everything happened called. He said, `Man,
you sound all right, like you ain't worried.' I said, `What's to
worry about?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever will happen will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows there were chances to prevent what happened, chances he
ignored. As he knew from the moment he was pushed to that floor in
Biloxi, it's now far too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
