<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-19 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--NBA-HNS &LR;      12-19 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--NBA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hope for NBA settlement slips away
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NBA stars, barred from their profession and unwilling to accept
deals to bring them back, played their exhibition in Atlantic City
on Saturday night, billing it as more than ``the game of the
year,'' but perhaps the ``only game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from the only ``game' this week. And the week
full of NBA owners' and players' thrust and parry made the
possibility that the season's games could be lost an increasing
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern prepared for his Aspen, Colo.,
vacation Friday by repeating his contention the cancellation of the
season was ``virtually inevitable.'' National Basketball Players
Association director Billy Hunter countered that Stern's prediction
is no more than a threat designed to shake the players' resolve.
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, the sides were arguing about who initiated the
successful talks of the previous week. By Thursday, Stern had sent
a letter to the players detailing the owners' proposal, only to
have Hunter send a memo to players disputing the worthiness of
every Stern contention.
</P>
<P>
   And by Saturday's made-for-cable exhibition, the steps taken
eight days earlier seemed wasted, replaced by new levels of rancor
and anger, and mistrust. Falling hard from the giddy, hopeful
moments taken from the secret bargaining sessions the week before,
both sides reacted sharply, emotionally after negotiations broke
off after 30 minutes. And the rhetoric that has followed has grown
uglier.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of arguing the unworthiness of the owners' proposals,
the players and their leadership have moved to challenge the
veracity of the owners' _ and Stern's _ motives. Even Hakeem
Olajuwon, who has been careful to chastise both sides evenly,
described Stern's vacation as a ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just reverse psychology,'' Olajuwon said. ``It's not
going to work. (A split within the union membership) is what the
owners are counting on. The players are not going to break. The
union is too strong for any player to want to break.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern has increased his predictions that the season has become
likely lost, even beginning his letter to the players with ``As the
1998-99 season slips away from us '' and charging that by
considering the owners' offer a bad deal ``you would prefer to lose
the entire season.''
</P>
<P>
   The players have countered that Stern is making empty threats as
negotiating ploys to rattle their resolve and inspire them to
accept an unfavorable agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be finished once they decide they want it done,''
Rockets guard Brent Price said. ``I really believe Stern holds the
power to this thing. They control the tempo. We've already
indicated we're willing to make concessions. We're the ones that
really want to get a deal. I think (Stern's vacation) is another
move on his part to show he's in control, that he's not concerned.
But he's responsible for the whole league. I have faith he's not
going to let the whole season end. That would be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's war of words, rather than move the players closer
to accepting an agreement, seems to have allowed Hunter the
opportunity to refute Stern's contentions and solidify his support.
</P>
<P>
   Both documents prove NBA players are and would be incredibly
well-paid, on the average better-paid than in any other U.S. team
sport, but Hunter countered that would not be enough because of the
sport's profitability. Hunter does not dispute the projections,
only that they would not be a ``fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have seemed increasingly steeled by the position that
only they have made real concessions in the negotiations, citing
the position to which Hunter repeatedly alludes in his memo that
owners' concessions have been from earlier proposals while the
players' capitulation has been from the previous
collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get concessions from us,'' Hunter wrote, ``they eventually
agree to come off of their demand, and thus give the appearance
that they are making a concession.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's response refers to Stern positions as a ``neat trick,''
warns ``don't be fooled,'' and concludes Stern's vacation is a
``stunt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
