<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CANADIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOAL PRODUCTION IS SCARCE AS THE DEVILS SALVAGE A TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Jacques Lemaire, the Devils' former coach, was
watching the Devils from the stands here Saturday night, and it
might have had something to do with the team's offensive
production. The Devils, who had scored 28 goals in five games
before Friday night, scored just one goal Saturday, but it was
enough for a 1-1 tie against the Montreal Canadiens, who have gone
without a victory for nine games, their longest such streak in six
years.
</P>
<P>
   Vadim Sharifijanov scored the goal for the Devils, who played
low-scoring games under Lemaire but have been scoring much more
under Coach Robbie Ftorek. But the Devils now have just three goals
in their last two games after scoring five or more in five straight
games before the loss to Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty killers and Martin Brodeur earned the tie for the
Devils (18-8-4). The penalty killers were perfect in seven manpower
advantages for the Canadiens, and Brodeur had another inspiring
performance in goal, this time with 22 saves, one in the overtime.
Brodeur's only blemish was Turner Stevenson's second goal of the
season, which tied the score with 6 minutes 14 seconds left in
regulation at the Molson Center.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was rested in a loss to Calgary the previous night at
Continental Arena, and he was sharp when he had to be in the first
two periods Saturday night. He has always been sharp against the
Canadiens, the team he idolized when he was growing up in Montreal.
Brodeur entered the game having allowed just one goal in two starts
against the Canadiens this season, a 3-0 victory and a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-1 tie on Dec. 4 was the last game before the Devils went
on a scoring binge, building an undefeated streak of eight games
before the 5-2 loss to Calgary on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring just twice against the Flames, the Devils had
trouble scoring again Saturday. Several times they found themselves
in good scoring positions, only to have their shots sail wide or
over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were extremely cautious on defense for the most part,
but the Devils created more opportunities in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in his 14th game, Sharifijanov scored his second goal of
the season 8 minutes 17 seconds into the middle period after a pass
from Brendan Morrison. His blistering shot from the top of the
right circle hit the top of the net behind Jeff Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Sharifijanov is a skillful player, and in the few games he has
played Ftorek has used him with players such as Sasha Lakovic, who
is primarily a fighter. Lakovic drew an assist on Sharifijanov's
goal, for his first point of the season and the second in his
28-game National Hockey League career.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were presented with a marvelous opportunity a minute
later, when two Canadiens were sent to the penalty box, giving the
Devils a two-man advantage. But the advantage disappeared over a
minute later when Bobby Holik was penalized for roughing.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils played without Bob Carpenter for the second game in a
row. Carpenter's bruised right foot must be really bruised, because
he was left home Friday night after the loss to Calgary. His place
was again taken by Denis Pederson, who centered for Jay Pandolfo
and Brian Rolston. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman KEVIN DEAN returned after missing six games with a
groin injury that he had aggravated the last time the Devils met
the Canadiens. . . . BRENDAN MORRISON was back in the lineup after
he was a healthy scratch against Calgary.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
